the ``sharpeville six,'' a group of blacks whose murder convictions have drawn protest at home and abroad, are scheduled to be hanged friday, one of their lawyers said monday
attorney prakash diar said an appeal for clemency was denied and the five men and one woman were notified they will be executed friday morning
the six were convicted in connection with the killing of black township councilor jacob dlamini in sharpeville, about 40 miles south of johannesburg, on sept. 3, 1984
evidence at their trial showed the six were not among those who actually hacked and burned dlamini to death
they were convicted under the doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which holds they were responsible for the killing by being part of the mob that gathered outside dlamini's home with the intent to kill him
human rights groups and government officials, both in south africa and internationally, have called for clemency
theresa ramashamola, 26, is the only woman on death row in south africa for what activists consider a politically motivated offense
britain's conservative party government expressed hope monday night that south africa will call off the hangings
lynda chalker, minister of state at the foreign office, told the house of commons, ``even at this late stage we sincerely and earnestly hope that the south african government will heed the united call of everyone for clemency in these cases.''
she said britain backed a united nations security council call for the sentences to be commuted
about 100 lawmakers of britain's opposition labor party signed a statement expressing ``total condemnation'' of the planned executions
amnesty international, the london-based human rights organization, appealed to south african president p.w. botha to spare the lives of the six
dlamini's killing came during riots which began a two-year outbreak of nationwide anti-apartheid protests that left more than 2,000 blacks dead
black activists frequently targeted black township councilors, considering them collaborators with the white-led government
the media workers association of south africa appealed to the government monday to ``demonstrate good will to the people of south africa in particular and mankind at large by sparing the lives of the sharpeville six.''
the scheduled execution date is three days before the anniversary of the sharpeville riots of march 21, 1960
sixty-nine blacks were killed when police fired on peaceful protesters demonstrating against the pass laws, which required blacks to carry identification documents while in white areas. the laws have since been repealed
the 1960 shootings raised an international storm of protest
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. sted spokeswoman; subs 25th graf pvs, an abc, with tracking poll in tuesday's washington post</note>
bob dole declared monday ``it's not over'' for his republican presidential campaign despite indications of a big illinois victory for george bush, but democrat paul simon admitted ``i have no plans beyond tomorrow'' and the home-state primary he needs to win
with five presidential candidates racing around the state in a final day of campaigning, jesse jackson was buoyed by a poll suggesting he may have pulled even with fellow favorite son simon
on the eve of a significant breakthrough ... with your help, we the people can win illinois,'' jackson told a cheering crowd of about 1,800 in carbondale, ill. ``i tell you, we the people will win.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, lying third, sought a good enough showing to keep up some momentum from super tuesday. over and over on monday, dukakis hammered at simon's contention that the democratic convention will be deadlocked
it ``would be a disaster'' for the democrats to end the primary process without a nominee-to-be, dukakis said, with ``negotiating, dealing, people behind closed doors trying to decide who the nominee ought to be.''
dukakis apparently wasn't the only democrat wanting to avoid a brokered convention. democratic chairman paul kirk suggested monday he would try to rally uncommitted delegates behind whichever candidate is leading the field at the end of the primary season, if none has a lock on the nomination
kirk said in a telephone interview from new york that he didn't want to ``leave the impression that kirk's going to be the broker'' but said he would be ``in the middle'' of efforts to avoid hurting the nominee with a battle just before or during the convention
the problem for dole was much more immediate than the conventions, months away in the summer. the kansas republican was looking for a way to keep his campaign alive in the face of a string of bush victories
it's not over for bob dole,'' he told the executives club of chicago
later, at a news conference, dole repeated his determination to continue beyond tuesday: ``i've made a judgment that illinois, whatever happens, we're going to keep going.''
the kansas senator said he had ``made some inroads'' against bush in illinois, but that there had not been enough time to stop bush's surge after a 16-state win last tuesday
you want to elect momentum or elect the better candidate?'' he asked the executives club audience. ``maybe it's going to take a couple of weeks for everything to sort of slow down.''
but the illinois outlook for dole was not good
a chicago tribune poll said bush was the choice of 62 percent of the likely gop voters in illinois, with only 28 percent for dole
such a strong showing could give bush a big chunk of the 82 republican delegates at stake in illinois. added to his current total of 705 delegates, it could give him more than 60 percent of the 1,139 needed to win the nomination at the gop national convention in new orleans in august. dole has 165
despite the numbers, bush told a reporter that suggestions he has locked up the nomination are premature
i feel the speculation has gotten ahead of the story,'' bush said as he flew on air force two from chicago to springfield, ill. however, when asked if he were surprised that dole was staying in the race, he replied: ``i'm not sure i understand what he's doing.''
on the democratic side, simon was facing the reality that he has to win the illinois primary to keep even his stripped-down campaign alive until the democratic national convention in july
i have no plans beyond tomorrow,'' he said in chicago. ``i have to win and i will win. but obviously michigan and wisconsin come next.''
and second place isn't good enough
a strong second isn't very strong,'' simon told a reporter. if he does end up in second place in either delegates or the popular vote in illinois, he said, ``i'd have to reevaluate.''
one poll published monday in the chicago tribune suggested simon faces the possibility of a second-place finish
the survey, conducted friday and saturday, said 32 percent of likely democratic voters supported jackson, 29 percent backed simon and 20 percent said they would vote for dukakis. rep. richard gephardt of missouri was the choice of 5 percent and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee had the backing of 4 percent
the poll, conducted by peter hart research associates, interviewed 500 people and had a potential margin of error of 5 percentage points
an abc news-washington post tracking poll published in tuesday's editions of the post gave simon the lead with 39 percent support to jackson's 34 percent among very likely democratic voters. dukakis had 17 percent with gore and gephardt far behind. the potential sampling error in the survey, conducted saturday and sunday, was plus or minus 6 percentage points
going into the illinois primary, dukakis held the lead in the associated press delegate count, with 463 to 424 for jackson. gore had 353 and simon just 36
a total of 173 delegates are at stake on the democratic side in illinois
one dukakis goal is to win some of those delegates, a difficult task given the complicated nature of the state's ballot. voters not only cast ballots for presidential candidates, they also vote directly for delegate candidates. thus, a vote for dukakis in the ``beauty contest'' portion does not necessarily mean a vote for him in the delegate selection process
another goal, dukakis aides said privately, is to narrow the democratic field. mentioning the polls showing dukakis drawing his last-minute support from simon's voters, the governor's aides said they would be delighted to see jackson beat simon, believing it would drive the senator from the race
republican pat robertson was to be in washington on primary day, where he planned to meet with the visiting israeli prime minister, yitzhak shamir. the robertson campaign characterized it as a meeting of ``two old friends.'' 3rd graf pvs, `she felt ...'</note>
katharine hepburn, whose outspoken suppport of women's reproductive rights is a family tradition, made a rare public appearance monday night when planned parenthood honored her and her late mother at a gala affair
the 79-year-old miss hepburn received a standing ovation from 1,100 guests at the waldorf-astoria hotel for the black-tie event, titled ``celebrating two generations of individual courage
it's a frightfully important subject,'' the actress said of women's rights to abortion and birth control. ``and i'm damn lucky to have had a mother who waked me up at an early age'' to the importance of ``doing things for other people.''
attired in a black pantsuit, miss hepburn said, ```when a girl becomes pregnant should she be forced by law to have this baby? she's 13. she doesn't want it. she can't support it. her family doesn't want it. it would seem to me that she should be allowed to have an abortion.''
miss hepburn was ``enthusiastic'' about the party, said winston forrest, vice president of planned parenthood federation of america
she felt her mother deserved the honoring,'' he said
the black-tie event is to benefit a planned parenthood fund to honor miss hepburn's mother, katharine houghton hepburn
proceeds from the dinner, priced at $500 to $1,000 a ticket, will be dedicated to miss hepburn's three priorities: keeping abortion safe and legal, preventing teen-age pregnancies and preserving family planning for the poor
her mother, an early supporter of birth control, worked alongside planned parenthood founder margaret sanger more than 70 years ago
mrs. hepburn, a member of the houghton family that founded corning glass, testified before the u.s. senate in the 1930s on the need for birth control, particularly for poor women, forrest said
she maintained that ``a rich woman could get the information and access to birth control but the poor woman could not,'' he said
she died in 1951 at the age of 73
miss hepburn became involved in planned parenthood in 1981. the group's president, faye wattleton, recruited the actress ``to take on the legacy her mother had established by volunteering to write letters and be spokesperson for reproductive rights and abortion rights for women,'' forrest said
he said her involvement has brought the organization an additonal 200,000 donors and supporters
more than 50 handicapped people demonstrated outside the department of transportation on monday to protest what they said are federal policies that result in inadequate mass transit services for disabled people
some protestors chained themselves to the doors of the dot headquarters and vowed to stay until officials agree to improve bus service for handicapped people
members of americans disabled for accessible transportation (adapt) gathered from around the country to protest the department's decision to appeal a january ruling that transit agencies must provide services to the handicapped regardless of cost
in the ruling, u.s. district judge marvin katz in philadelphia struck down a transportation department regulation requiring the nation's transit authorities to spend no more than 3 percent of their budgets on the disabled
the demonstrators timed their protest to coincide with a three-day meeting of the american public transit association, which represents local agencies that provide bus and subway service
timothy cook, a philadelphia attorney who represented adapt in the lawsuit, said the present system of allowing transit agencies to decide what services to provide to the handicapped ``gives individual states the option to discriminate.''
cook said that in philadelphia, handicapped residents must phone five to seven days in advance to get an accessible bus to pick them up
they should be able to use the next bus coming along,'' cook said. ``many transit authorities simply don't want funny-looking people on the bus with normal people.''
transportation secretary jim burnley said monday the department is ``fully committed to providing mass transportation to people with disabilities.''
the panama canal, still one of the hemisphere's most important pieces of real estate, has allowed ships to move between the atlantic and pacific without interruption through nine months of political unrest
nearly 13,000 vessels a year avoid the long voyage around cape horn, the southern tip of south america, by traveling 50 miles from sea to sea through the ``big ditch'' that opened in 1914. more than 140 million tons of cargo move through it every year
the panama canal treaties signed in 1977 commit the united states to turn over complete control of the canal and military installations to panama by midnight dec. 31, 1999
gen. manuel antonio noriega, commander of the defense forces and the man in charge in panama, claims washington wants to renege on the treaties and continue ``occupying'' the canal indefinitely
he says the reagan administration is waging a smear campaign to try to replace him with an administration it can manipulate. noriega was indicted in florida last month on charges of involvement in smuggling colombian cocaine into the united states
although the canal remains an emotional topic of debate, its strategic importance has declined in the past 30 years
dennis mcauliffe, administrator of the panama canal commission, says that is because the united states has improved and extended its military forces
during and after world war ii, through the 1950s, the major port system was new york and sealift through the canal was about the only way to reinforce presence in the pacific, but now there are major u.s. naval forces in both oceans and major ports on the west coast,'' he said
there is less of a need to transport capital ships through the canal, and airlift capacity has increased tremendously.''
traffic through the canal brings the commission about $320 million a year in tolls
supertankers and the largest bulk carriers are too big for the three sets of locks that raise and lower vessels 85 feet, but 93 percent of the world's ships can get through, said richard wainio, chief of the commission's economic and marketing division
the panamax is still the world's most popular cargo shipbuilding design,'' he said, referring to the largest vessel the canal can handle. a panamax vessel has a beam width of 106 feet. the locks are 110 feet wide
nor is the canal concept outdated. the united states, japan and panama began a study last year of the feasibility of building another. its conclusions are expected in 1992 at the earliest
for the united states, the strategic value of what used to be the panama canal zone is enhanced by the presence of the southern command, involving about 10,000 american soldiers and 20,000 dependents, which is responsible for u.s. military operations in latin america
it operates half a dozen bases along the canal and has its headquarters in quarry heights, adjacent to balboa
during their long tenure, the americans built replicas of their own towns. communities of white wooden houses on tree-lined streets named in english still can be found in the 10-mile-wide area that had been the canal zone
mcauliffe said this week that day-to-day coordination between his commission and panamanian port authorities is ``easy, fluid and very effective.''
this month, there had been several bomb threats, which he called ``an irritant,'' and the commision flew in large quantities of cash because of panama's banking crisis to cover the paychecks of canal employees. the latest checks were handed out monday
under sanctions imposed last week, the reagan administration is withholding monthly payments to panama of about $6.6 million for canal operations and putting the money in escrow
fifty years after the nazis closed the world's first museum of jewish art in vienna, a private exhibit of jewish ritual objects has been drawing large crowds of visitors
some 800 items displayed at the ``judentum in wien'' (``jews in vienna'') exhibit housed by the museum of the history of vienna are all loans from a private judaica collection, regarded by art historians as one the most important private collections of jewish life
according to max berger, owner of the collection, most of the drawings, paintings, sculptures, medals, coins, manuscripts and handicraft on show were in danger of being destroyed or lost after austria's annexation by nazi germany in 1938
berger, a viennese businessman who survived a nazi concentration camp, pieced together his collection over years and this is the first time it has been shown in public
the exhibit displays mementoes of jewish life from the early 18th century until present, focusing on vienna as an important center in the history of european jewry. museum officials said it is the first step toward opening a permanent jewish museum here in the next two or three years
about 6,000 jews live in vienna today, compared with 200,000 who helped make this city a capital of science, culture and the arts before world war ii. they included sigmund freud, gustav mahler, stefan zweig, arnold schoenberg and hundreds of others
some 65,000 austrian jews perished in nazi concentration and death camps during the war
the exhibit is divided into eight sections, including ritual objects and hebrew writings, the jewish year and life, the history of the viennese jews, zionism, anti-semitism and persecution and jewish contributions to art and culture
it's the first time that the most important private judaica collection in europe is displayed for the austrian public after the war,'' karl-albrecht weinberger, a curator who helped set up the display, said in an interview
by march 3, the exhibit had been visited by some 30,000 people
on saturdays and sundays we have up to 500 visitors a day,'' weinberger said, adding that recently austrian school authorities advised schools to come and see the exhibit as part of their history classes
more young austrians gradually have been educated about the nazi past and the holocaust in the two years since the first disclosures that president kurt waldheim had covered up his wartime past as a german army lieutenant in the balkans
weinberger said the exhibit was planned before waldheim became president
the most valuable objects displayed are a silver-and-gold torah crown made in austria in 1810 and a torah plaque made in 1806 of gold-covered silver
the oldest display is a torah curtain made around 1700 of red velvet laced with silver threads
weinberger said the first jewish museum in the world opened in vienna in 1895, with a very big collection of jewish art
the nazis dismantled it in 1938. while some items were lost or destroyed, others were taken by the germans to prague where they planned to open a big anti-semitic jewish museum. the museum never materialized but some objects have remained in the prague jewish museum which opened after the war
asked if the austrians ever asked the czechs to return the items held by the vienna museum, weinberger said they never did
it's difficult to prove what objects belonged to the jewish vienna museum as all catalog were destroyed during the war,'' he said
a cracked fuel line threw a metric wrench into a plan by honda to become the first japanese automaker to transport its u.s.-built cars back to japan for sale
the auto carrier green bay, built in japan last year, was examined by repair crews monday, a day after it slipped quietly back into port here with its cargo of 540 u.s.-built accords and 100 honda motorcyles
the ship's owner, central gulf lines of new orleans, declined to comment, but honda spokesman shin tanaka in detroit said a fuel line crack forced the ship's return
he said honda motor co. ltd. was postponing from march 22 to april 8 a gala reception to welcome the vessel at narashino port, east of tokyo. if necessary, he said, the cargo will be moved to another ship from the green bay, which has made several successful trips for honda since it was completed oct. 29 by mitsui engineering &amp; shipbuilding ltd
the ship departed march 7 with much fanfare, after tetsuo chino, president of honda north america inc., drove the first car on board and held a news conference with sen. bob packwood, r-ore
francois l. elmealeh of the port of portland's marine marketing department said the problems with the ship didn't threaten the cargo or crew
i think it's an embarrassment more than anything,'' elmealeh said. to update with washington post-abc news poll showing simon with strong lead; picks up 10th graf pvs bgng, `i would'</note>
sen. paul simon shrugged off new poll results suggesting his lead in his home state had diminished to a tie with jesse jackson, but conceded sunday that his democratic campaign was hampered by not having the money to buy television ads in illinois
obviously, not to have paid media hampers me in illinois,'' simon said as he campaigned in the city's chinatown neighborhood. ``but the only way i could have paid media would be to use up the resources and obligate the matching funds that are coming.''
that would have left simon unable to afford television advertising in wisconsin, new york and other states with contests upcoming, he said
frankly, i'm not in it just for illinois _ otherwise i'd go on paid media. ... i want to win the nomination _ not buy the nomination,'' he added
but the results of a chicago tribune poll to be published in monday's editions suggested simon's campaign was faltering in illinois, despite his record as a state representative and u.s. senator
the poll of 500 registered democrats indicated 32 percent supported jackson, 29 percent backed simon and 20 percent favored massachusetts gov. michael dukakis. however, the poll, taken for the tribune by peter d. hart and associates, has a margin of error of plus or minus five percentage points, making the race a dead heat
the poll, taken friday and saturday, updates one taken earlier last week that showed simon leading with 35 percent, followed by jackson with 30 percent and dukakis with 18 percent
simon still insisted he would carry his home state on tuesday, saying, ``i think the people of illinois are going to make a sound decision.''
and his optimism appeared to be supported by a poll for the washington post and abc news which was published in monday's editions of the newspaper
that poll showed simon holding a strong lead with 42 percent, jackson 33 percent, dukakis 14 percent, sen. gore of tennessee 4 percent, rep. richard gephardt of missouri 3 percent and others and undecided, 4 percent. the poll was based on telephone interviews friday night and saturday with 287 illinois democratic voters who were likely to cast ballots. the margin of error was 6 percent
i would add that four years ago there wasn't a single poll that showed me ahead and i won,'' simon said, referring to his upset victory in a u.s. senate race against republican incumbent charles percy
meanwhile, dukakis, who has assaulted simon's campaign with a blitz of last-minute television advertising, accused simon of ``doing a disservice to the democratic party'' by talking up the likelihood of a brokered presidential convention in atlanta
i think the notion of a brokered convention would be an absolute disaster,'' dukakis said sunday
the reality is we're not going to have a first-ballot nominee,'' simon countered. ``and those brokered conventions have produced candidates ... like franklin roosevelt, harry truman and john f. kennedy, and it turned out quite well for the american people.''
it's been nearly three years since a toddler's visit to a doctor sparked what has become the marathon trial of margaret kelly michaels, a former day-care teacher accused of sexually abusing her students
ms. michaels, 26, resigned from the wee care day nursery in maplewood in april 1985 after working for six months. a few days later, a boy, now 7, told a nurse taking his temperature rectally that ms. michaels did the same to him
the school was closed soon afterward, and by december 1985, ms. michaels had been indicted on 235 counts of sexually abusing 31 3-to 5-year-old students
the charges have since been reduced to 20 students. closing arguments in the trial, which began nine months ago in superior court in newark, are expected to begin tuesday
the prosecution contends ms. michaels performed sexual acts on the children, forced them to perform sexual acts on her, engaged them in nude sex play and threatened further harm if they told of the abuse
ms. michaels, who once aspired to be an actress, has been free on $25,000 bail and living with her family in pittsburgh since january 1986
all but 128 charges of abuse have been dropped because of lack of evidence and recent higher court rulings that clarified what testimony is admissible in child sex abuse cases
we'll all be glad when it's over,'' ms. michaels' attorney, harvey meltzer, said last week. ``we are very, very optimistic she'll be acquitted on all charges.''
assistant prosecutor glenn d. goldberg said, ``we feel there is no reason to disbelieve the children's testimony about what happened.''
the boy who went to the doctor three years ago testified via closed-circuit television last june that ms. michaels once took his temperature and that of two friends using a rectal thermometer
the boy's mother testified earlier he told her in april 1985 that ms. michaels used a rectal thermometer daily on children
the mother and son were among about 120 prosecution witnesses. in all, 19 children testified via closed-circuit television from judge william f. harth's chambers. ms. michaels took the stand earlier this month, and was one of 22 defense witnesses
the defense has argued there was not ``the time, space or opportunity'' in the bustling environment of the school for ms. michaels to commit the alleged offenses
but the prosecution said ms. michaels, whose duties included supervising napping children, created opportunities. they contend she sometimes took children, without permission, to a remote music room and played the piano during sex games
the defense also says the children were prompted in their allegations by investigators, psychologists and prosecutors. experts for the prosecution testified children cannot be ``brainwashed'' and could not have made up the stories
the prosecution also said ms. michaels' presented a false image of herself
as a four-year drama student, a lot of what she was doing on the witness stand was an attempt to appear spontaneous when in fact it was not spontaneous,'' goldberg said
but metzler said: ``what we have is a very, very large jigsaw puzzle that the jury must complete. ... we are going to show there are pieces missing from the puzzle. then it's up to the jury to determine if the missing pieces amount to a reasonable doubt.''
after 15 years of entertaining readers around the world, humorist russell baker says he has written his last ``sunday observer'' column
i did it for 15 years. that's a long time to write a column with three weeks' lead time,'' baker said sunday. ``columnists tend to hang on too long. i wanted to call it quits before that.''
baker, who announced his decision in a farewell column in the new york times magazine, plans to continue his weekday column for the times and work on a book
baker's daily and sunday columns are distributed to about 400 newspapers across the united states and about 100 foreign papers, according to kevin delaney of the new york times news service. the weekday column appears twice a week
i'll still be doing the daily column, probably longer than i should,'' baker said. ``i'm 62 years old. you begin to run out of steam.''
