jimmy carter has vowed to support nigeria's drive to eradicate guinea worm, a debilitating parasite that permanently disables 12,000 nigerians annually
the former u.s. president, who arrived sunday on an overnight visit to this west african nation, pledged the support of global 2000, a private, non-profit institution founded during his 1977-81 presidency. the atlanta-based organization funds health and agriculture projects in the developing world
nigeria is the most heavily afflicted country in africa. if we can succeed here we can reach our goal to totally eradicate guinea worm'' by 1995, carter said during a meeting with the nation's health minister, dr. olikoye ransome-kuti
it is estimated that 2.5 million nigerians contract the disease each year through contaminated drinking water
eunice kennedy shriver has been selected to receive the 1988 laetare medal, one of the most prestigious awards given to american catholics, the university of notre dame announced
the university's president, the rev. edward a. malloy, said recently mrs. shriver will be honored for her work as founder and chairwoman of special olympics international
inscribed on each laetare medal is the slogan, `truth is mighty and will prevail,' '' malloy said. ``last summer, while hosting the international special olympics games, the notre dame community saw anew an ancient christian truth: christ comes most often in the stranger's guise.''
mrs. shriver, a native of brookline, mass., is the fifth of the nine children of joseph p. and rose fitzgerald kennedy, and the sister of the late president john f. kennedy
the directors guild of america has honored bernardo bertolucci with his second directing award for ``the last emperor,'' in what could bode a triple-crown award season for the italian movie director
bertolucci, who in january won a golden globe for directing ``the last emperor,'' picked up the dga award saturday night in ceremonies held jointly at the beverly hilton hotel and in new york
an academy award next month would make it a bertolucci sweep. only three times in the 40-year history of the dga award has it failed to coincide with the academy award winner for best director
the last time was in 1985, when steven spielberg's directorial colleagues gave him the nod for ``the color purple,'' while the academy of motion picture arts and sciences didn't even nominate him. the oscar went instead to sydney pollack for ``out of africa.''
other top dga winners saturday were will mackenzie, who received the tv comedy directing award for an episode of nbc-tv's ``family ties'' called ```a' my name is alex''; and marshall herskovitz, who won the nighttime dramatic series award for his pilot for abc-tv's ``thirtysomething.''
bernard rudofsky, an architect and social commentator, has died at age 82
rudofsky died of cancer saturday at new york university hospital
he wrote on a variety of subjects, ranging from the relationship between the body and clothes to how streets are used in cities
rudofsky's books and museum exhibitions influenced not only architecture but fashion, interior design, urban planning and food
he was our most perceptive and outspoken critic of human habits and habitations,'' said the chief editor of interior design magazine, stanley abercrombie
rudofsky first made waves in 1944 with an exhibition at the museum of modern art entitled ``are clothes modern?''
the exhibition, which examined the incompatibility of the human body and clothing, showed one of his contributions to fashion, the ``bernardo sandal,'' a curved piece of leather with straps
twenty years later, rudofsky had an exhibit at the museum of modern art called ``architecture without architects'' on vernacular architecture _ the design of buildings built in societies, sometimes ancient or primitive, that he believed were without pretensions
rudofsky, who was born and educated in vienna, received a master's degree in architecture and engineering and a doctorate in technical sciences at the technical university. he practiced architecture for several years in italy
he has lived in new york since 1935
his books included ``streets for people,'' in which he examined how streets are used in cities around the world, and ``the unfashionable human body,'' which looked at the relationship between the body and clothing
rudofsky taught at yale university, the massachusetts institute of technology, the royal academy of fine arts in copenhagen and waseda university in tokyo
he is survived by his wife, berta. taylor's role in evening's events, picking up 5th graf pvs, `as the...'.</note>
amid the glitter and glamour of elizabeth taylor and a parade of other celebrities, a gala benefit sunday raised $2 million for aids, which organizers said made it the largest private fund-raiser for the disease ever
that's so much money ... i mean that's so incredibly much money, and the things that money will do!'' said ms. taylor. ``we're talking about living or dying. and it's getting closer and closer to all of us. ... we want to do something about it
the government can help to a certain point. dollars can help to a certain point,'' she said
the evening's total was about $2 million, said james figetakis, an associate of ms. taylor's publicist, chen sam
ms. taylor chairs the american foundation for aids research, which will receive part of the funds. she served as hostess and chief drawing card at the gala
as the finale swung into full force sunday night, a steady stream of stars in sparkling jewels and dresses began arriving at the fontainebleau hilton hotel here. they expressed gratitude they could contribute in the battle against aids
it's really an honor for me to be here,'' actor matt dillon said. ``it's a real problem everywhere, not just in america, but all over the world. anything i can do to help is why i'm here.''
i think it's about time south florida got involved in the fight against aids,'' said miami vice star saundra santiago. ``i'm very happy to be here to support this.''
other stars on hand included lauren hutton, cheryl tiegs, ben vereen, marlee matlin, donna summers, grace jones, margaux hemingway, eddie albert, susan anton and van johnson. organizers say they hope the benefit will serve as a model for similar fund-raising efforts elsewhere
we've had the most private funds raised (for acquired immune deficiency syndrome) at this one function than any other place in the country,'' said event spokesman charles cinnamon. ``we want it to be the prototype for the rest of the country.''
despite a lack of corporate sponsorships, which had been expected to raise some $500,000 of the initial $3 million goal, tickets to the ``grand finale'' at the hotel here sold out and private donations were giving the fund drive an added boost, organizers said
stars and guests were invited sunday to attend about a dozen black-tie parties from miami to palm beach, being held at the homes of local celebrities and prominent community leaders for $2,500 a plate, before converging in miami beach for the finale
the aids benefit was spearheaded by the community alliance against aids, a fund-raising arm of the university of miami school of medicine. proceeds from the event were being split between the university's aids programs and the american foundation for aids research, a non-profit group chaired by ms. taylor, which supports research and education
in palm beach, celia lipton farris raised at least $137,000 in advance ticket sales for a private party being held in her home with ms. taylor and some 300 guests. during the event, ms. farris, a former child star and widow of a wealthy industrialist, announced she was giving an additional $1.1 million, figetakis said
funds raised in palm beach will go toward the comprehensive aids program, an organization in west palm beach and belle glade that cares for aids victims
other private dinner parties were being held in the homes of singer julio iglesias, theatrical producer zev bufman and david paul, chief executive officer of centrust bank, among others
with super tuesday behind them, the presidential candidates are looking toward the next big tuesday on the calendar _ june 7, when the california and new jersey primaries offer the last big bloc of delegates to be allocated before the national conventions
there are other big primaries in coming months, including illinois, pennsylvania and new york. but none offers a larger one-day delegate total than final tuesday, as it's been dubbed
montana and new mexico also will hold primaries june 7
for democrats, with massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, jesse jackson and tennessee sen. albert gore bunched in the lead, the late primaries on opposite sides of the country now loom as potentially decisive
on the republican side, where a big super tuesday victory last week made vice president george bush his party's likely choice, the june 7 primaries are expected to be much less crucial
a day after super tuesday, both dukakis and gore announced they would soon make campaign stops in new jersey and california. jackson, too, is building organizations in both states
california democratic party chairman peter kelly says the super tuesday result ``almost guarantees that the race will come down to california, and california will have a say in picking the nominee.''
in new jersey, democratic sen. bill bradley said, ``new jersey takes on real importance. we are, with california, the final two tests.''
california voters will select 205 democratic delegates in the primary, and 109 more will be chosen in post-primary meetings. along with 22 pre-selected ``super delegates,'' the state will send the largest single delegation to the convention with 336 members
new jersey democrats will select 71 delegates in primary voting. they'll join with 38 more picked by party leaders, and nine super delegates for a total of 118
to win the nomination, a democratic candidate will need 2,082 delegates. dukakis now leads the field with 460, followed by jackson with 424 and gore with 353. missouri rep. richard gephardt totals 145 delegates, followed by illinois sen. paul simon with 36
some party leaders say it will be nearly impossible for any of the three leaders to gather enough wins between now and june to win the nomination on the convention's first ballot. dukakis, the front-runner, would need to win more than 60 percent of the delegates remaining available
but final tuesday wins could give any candidate an unchallengable advantage in the final stretch
if you can go into the convention just coming off of (a win in) new jersey, it's momentum,'' said rep. james florio, d-n.j
california independent pollster steve teichner said results from the two primaries also have the potential to sway several hundred uncommitted super delegates from around the nation. those delegates, members of congress and other party leaders, will go to the national convention legally unpledged
in 1984, walter mondale and gary hart battled for the democratic nomination right up until the california and new jersey primaries
hart won in calfornia, but mondale _ who took new jersey and several smaller states that day _ emerged the overall victor. target</head>
red lights don't stop george bush. the vice president's limousine glides along under state police escort, with cars pulling over to make way. traffic signals are ignored; the curious crane their necks
bush is hoping tuesday's illinois primary will be just as smooth a ride
although heavily favored to win the state's republican contest, with 82 delegates at stake, the vice president nonetheless has been spending 12-hour days on the campaign trail
but on the stump his targets are no longer republican rivals like bob dole, the kansas senator he crushed in the primaries of super tuesday. instead, bush is aiming his rhetoric at democrats
i've never seen such a gloomy bunch,'' bush said of the democrats, as he spoke to 500 people at a republican party dinner here. ``everything they said about our country is negative _ midnight in america.''
bush, by contrast, is upbeat. he ought to be _ he's so far ahead of dole that the chicago tribune has quit polling on the republican side
at a stop in a campaign office in libertyville, bush and gov. james r. thompson, who has been accompanying him around the state, made phone calls to try to round up votes
we're putting the hard sell on,'' bush said into the telephone. ``we're at the grass-roots stage now.''
at stop after stop, bush delivers his message _ along with a series of one-liners
he said his success on super tuesday ``gave new meaning to the words southern comfort.'' he tells crowds he's got the support of the ``james gang'' _ thompson, illinois secretary of state jim edgar and cook county sheriff james o'grady
his standard speech includes pledges to trim the deficit in four years through tight spending, and to be tough with the soviets
he says he expects criticism from the democrats over the iran-contra affair _ he got some sunday, from albert gore jr., who said bush had never fully explained his role in the matter
bush, who says he has answered all questions about the matter except his private advice to the president on secret arms sales, said he wasn't worried about democrats harping on iran-contra
they'll raise it,'' he said. ``of course they will. so what?''
the democrats, he said, lack knowledge of foreign affairs
i can't wait to debate any one of those democrats on foreign policy. none of them have had any experience except when they had breakfast at the international house of pancakes,'' he said
he touches on the matter indirectly, perhaps, when he warns voters to expect to find a few warts
i might make a mistake here and there,'' bush said, ``but i've had enough experience i wouldn't do it like yogi berra did. they asked yogi what went wrong when the mets lost a few ball games. he said `we made the wrong mistakes.'''
you've got to think about it,'' bush said. ``anybody's going to make mistakes.''
in the bleachers at st. viator high school in arlington heights, scott bieda, 30, held his 1{-year-old daughter and nodded in agreement
i like what i hear,'' he said. ``those are the issues that are important to me: bargaining from strength and tackling the deficit. but you can say anything now. the proof is in the pudding. we'll see what happens if he gets in.''
a mass resignation of arab policemen has displayed the muscle of the plo and posed a security dilemma for israel and palestinians alike in the west bank and gaza strip
a national police spokesman, yehoshua goldapfel, on sunday said that 450 of the 850 arab police in the occupied territories ``have asked to leave the force.'' he left open the possibility more would depart
the police control crime and direct traffic, but they are not used to quell arab rioting in the occupied lands, now in its fourth month
arab officers in bethlehem said all 70 arab policemen would be off the job today at the city's headquarters office for the southern half of the west bank. as a shift ended at noon sunday, newly retired officers drifted from the station in jeans and jackets into the central manger square. a dozen israeli soldiers in riot gear stood watch beside a phalanx of huge tour buses
i will be left without a job, without income,'' said traffic officer mohammed abu ghayada, who spent 12 of his 36 years on the force. he said he might try driving a taxi
the people have decided, and we go with the decision of the palestinian people,'' said policeman fadl najajri, a 15-year veteran and a father of nine
the walkout was triggered by a communique issued march 10 by the palestine liberation organization and clandestine local leaders of the violent protests against israeli rule of the west bank and gaza strip
the message was driven home for some officers by the march 8 stabbing death of a palestinian policeman in jericho accused of cooperating too closely with israeli authorities
the killing in jericho made me decide very quickly,'' said a 33-year-old policeman who gave his name only as ramis
the national police commissioner, david krauss, told israel radio on sunday: ``there's pressure on them from the outside and a system of threats. but each one of them is organizing his friends, and we'll deal with them.''
he did not specify how
the resignations threaten to open wider cracks in israel's territorial administration, which employs 18,000 arabs and is an important buffer between israelis and the already rebellious palestinians
it is a precedent for many more civil servants to resign,'' said bethlehem mayor elias freij
forty tax collectors in the gaza strip quit last week under pressure from underground organizers
rioters in the village of qabatiyeh on feb. 24 lynched an alleged israeli collaborator who opened fire on a crowd nearing his house and killed a child
authorities punished qatabiyeh by banning visits of family members from abroad and forbidding the town's major export of stone to jordan
authorities also demolished houses of people accused of involvement in attacks on alleged collaborators
such methods will be used against villages and groups we know are involved in attacks on people who are considered to be collaborators or people who are cooperating with authorities,'' said a senior military spokesman
but he also admitted on sunday that israel ``cannot provide 100 percent security'' to all people who work with authorities
police spokesman nahum mendel on sunday termed the police resignations ``a big problem,'' and said authorities discussed offering pay raises to keep veteran officers
several arab officers said israeli superiors had offered to double their pay, now $400 to $500 a month, if they would stay. all said they refused
arab businessmen also are worried by the disappearance of local protectors
the authorities will not bring any israeli police to this area. there will be no law here,'' said rabah abdeen, owner of a plastics factory and a gasoline station in bethlehem
an israeli spokesman in the bethlehem head office said police in ramallah, 10 miles north of jerusalem, were unable to respond to a major traffic accident on sunday
i feel abandoned when out of 80 people at the station, only six of us were left,'' the ramallah district commander, miko bachar, said on israel television. he said all six were israeli officers
freij also said the resignations ``will vastly affect the process of the courts in the west bank,'' which together with those in the gaza strip handle about 200,000 cases a year, mostly traffic-related
the bechtel group, inc., a giant construction company which for years quietly built billion-dollar projects in the middle east, is receiving unwanted attention from a grand jury investigation of attorney general edwin meese's role in a failed mideast pipeline deal
the aborted deal, to build a pipeline from iraqi oilfields to the jordanian port of aqaba, was part of what bechtel president alden p. yates called a ``project development scheme'' to boost business in a bad market
falling oil prices were devastating the international construction business in 1984 when bechtel began to draw up engineering and financing plans for the $1 billion pipeline
it didn't work for geopolitical reasons,'' yates said in a telephone interview from bechtel headquarters in san francisco
independent counsel james c. mckay is focusing on a possible bribery conspiracy involving israeli officials, bruce rappaport, a swiss businessman involved with bechtel in the deal, meese and e. robert wallach, a close friend of meese hired by rappaport to garner administration backing for the project
secretary of state george p. shultz, who was president of bechtel before joining the reagan administration in 1982, recused himself from any role in the pipeline negotiations, opening the way for meese to become the pivotal cabinet official in the deal. former defense secretary caspar weinberger, who served as bechtel's general counsel under shultz, appears to have played no role in the deal
in addition to the unwelcome publicity over the pipeline deal, bechtel continues to have problems of a different nature, the same ones that drove it into the politically risky aqaba pipeline deal
lower oil prices, the dearth of nuclear projects and debt in the developing world have curtailed bechtel's trademark leviathan deals
people characterize us as not willing to take on little projects, but that's not true any more,'' said yates
bechtel's business jumped from $7.6 billion in 1980 to an average of $13 billion annually 1981-83, and back down to $8.6 billion in 1984. it has fallen more gradually since then, forcing the company to seek new markets
bechtel's ``mega projects,'' those costing above $50 million, have dropped from 96 in 1983 to 73 in 1986
yates declined to discuss the specifics of the pipeline case because it is under investigation, but he said it fit into a larger pattern under which bechtel officials sought to spot potential jobs, prepare engineering reports and arrange financing for prospective clients
along these lines, bechtel since 1985 has been studying the possibility of building a second panama canal, said yates
the iraq-jordan pipeline was a `project development scheme,''' said yates. ``in the old days, an oil company would send out a request for a project, and we would do it. now we doing project development, looking at the stuff way upstream.''
in the pipeline deal, bechtel sought out a partner in rappaport, who owns oil refineries and tankers, and asked him to secure promises from israeli officials that they would not attack the pipeline, said company spokesman al donner
wallach, hired by rappaport, wrote a memo to meese on sept. 25, 1985, saying that rappaport had confirmed an arrangement with israel's then-prime minister shimon peres that ``israel will receive somewhere between $65-$70 million a year for 10 years out of the conclusion of the project
what is also indicated to me, and which would be denied everywhere, is that a portion of those funds will go directly to labor,'' wrote wallach, in an apparent reference to peres' labor party
meese and his lawyers deny that the wording referred to a bribe _ the allegation the special prosecutor is investigating
iraqi officials informed bechtel in a letter dated dec. 31, 1985, that they were dissatisfied with security arrangements and that the deal was off, said donner
other deals have gone bad for bechtel. new orders fell from $13 billion in 1980 to $3.5 billion in 1986, the most recent year for which full statistics are available. and the payroll is down from a high of 45,000 to fewer than 18,000, according to company officials. they declined to provide profit figures
the company still prefers massive projects, but has expanded into such new areas as computerized factories, space and weapons technology and toxic waste cleanup, said yates
if you can do a $1 billion job, it is easier than doing ten $100 million jobs,'' he said in a succinct statement of the bechtel credo
bechtel still pulls down its share of big jobs worldwide
its engineers are involved in the $9.6 billion project to build the eurotunnel under the english channel. bechtel also is building a $3.3 billion tunnel project in boston and a $2.7 billion project to develop a new central terminal at new york's kennedy international airport
nine-year-old celeste has big brown eyes and long brown hair. she also has no mother, no father, no little brother and almost no hope
all in all, she's been one of the lucky ones,'' says anita septimus, head of social services at the albert einstein college of medicine, which runs the nation's largest pediatric aids clinic
celeste is among a growing number of children who are victims of congenital aids. they must pay with their future for a parent's past _ a problem that becomes more common as the disease enters the heterosexual population
both of celeste's parents were intravenous drug users who contracted aids; her mother died in 1983, her father died last year. celeste and her brother were infected in the uterus. he died christmas eve
every two weeks, to assist and extend her fragile life, celeste is given treatments of gamma globulin, blood serum that contains a high concentration of antibodies
she is the oldest youngster of more than a dozen treated there. some, less than a year old, are born to die; others face years of battling the disease and the cruel ostracism that often surrounds it. in either case, the prognosis for such children remains invariably pessimistic, specialists say
we have never seen anybody who has beaten the disease,'' einstein's dr. larry bernstein said recently. ``i think you get to a certain point and hope you can stay there, not deteriorate further.''
recent state health department figures indicate the potential number of aids-infected newborns is growing at a startling rate. one in every 61 babies born in new york city last november carried antibodies to the aids virus, which means they had been exposed to the virus
about 40 percent of these children will develop acquired immune deficiency syndrome in some form; 25 percent to 30 percent of those children will be dead before their second birthday. most of them were born to mothers who used drugs intravenously
dr. stephen joseph, the city health commissioner, put the number of children born in the city with aids antibodies last year at about 600; for 1988 the projection is 1,000. between 1980 and 1986, the total was only about 250 children
in fact, aids babies were cited as the reason for the first increase in new york city's infant mortality rate since 1974
one reason for the spurt is the large number of addicts in new york city. intravenous drug abusers make up almost half the city's aids population while in san francisco and most other cities with large aids populations, most sufferers are homosexual
but even in massachusetts, a state not known for large outbreaks of aids, one in 476 child-bearing women tested positive for aids antibodies, according to a study reported recently in the new england journal of medicine
nationwide, there were 865 cases of pediatric aids reported as of feb. 29, with 111 diagnosed in just the first two months of the year. altogether, 518 children are known to have died of aids
the bronx municipal hospital day care center, the nation's first day care facility for aids-infected children, opened in june 1986 to help out; septimus said another is planned for einstein
sixty-five percent of the einstein kids live in foster homes, she said. but some have spent so much time in hospitals, in broken homes or at arm's length from a terrified society that social skills like speaking have not been properly developed
in fact, they say the children remain innocent victims to the end, never realizing they were born without much of a chance
some of the older kids have a sense of it, but even the ones who are older have physical delays _ an 8-year-old with the intelligence of a 5-year-old,'' said bernstein
but we don't have that many older kids, so we don't know.''
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,433.51 points, down 110.22 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on monday
come on everybody _ let's do the conga!'' was the rallying cry for more than 120,000 people who lined up at little havana's calle ocho festival and danced into the record books
about 1.5 million people were jammed along 23 blocks of eighth street (calle ocho in spanish) on sunday when gloria estefan and the miami sound machine set about forming a conga line
is everybody ready? let's conga,'' said ms. estefan as her band began playing their hit ``conga.'' people began to grab the shoulders in front of them and sidestep to the latin beat
there's no way it could fail. as soon as the music plays, we just grab on to somebody and hang on,'' said nuvia valdez, who showed up early to take part in the historic strut
when it was over, anna nicholas of the guinness book of world records confirmed a record line of 119,986 dancers, shattering the old mark of a 10,442-person chain formed last august in canada. the computer-assisted count was made by volunteers at 30 observation posts
it may seem like a conga line is an inane thing, but it represents a lot more,'' ms. estefan said. ``because this community is so diverse, getting along and having a street party of this magnitude really says a lot about our city.''
the festival began as a block party 11 years ago to showcase miami's cuban culture
there are gadget lovers. there are cat lovers. there are people who love home improvement projects. if enough people fall into all three categories, the maker of the electronic cat door is in luck
reilor inc. of horsham, pa. is showing off its product here at the annual national home center show, which started sunday
the cat door comes with a coded collar key so only the owner's cat can enter. the door can be programmed to open from only the inside or only the outside, or from both sides. it's available at pet stores for $120-$150, said shelley daniels, a spokeswoman for the show
an estimated 36,000 retailers are expected to attend the show, sponsored by home center magazine of lincolnshire
the magazine says it did a recent survey of 1,561 homeowners across the country that found 93 percent of those households undertook at least one home improvement project last year
u.s. homeowners seem willing to tackle almost any type of home improvement imaginable,'' said john berry, an official of vance publishing corp., the company producing the show
the reigning drama of 1980 was not so much the carter-reagan campaign but the interminable hostage crisis in tehran. the two became intertwined, and as jimmy carter gave up his presidency, 52 americans were being returned to freedom
the pain's gone; the weight's lifted,'' dorothea morefield exulted as her husband ended 444 days of nerve-wracking captivity
we can all drink to this one,'' ronald reagan said
cut to 1988. another presidential campaign is in high gear and a new set of americans is held captive in the middle east. this time around, the hostages are bound and blindfolded far from the political limelight; the hope is that obscurity will diminish their value
for terry anderson, tuesday will mark three full years as hostage. it has been 1,094 days since anderson, returning from a tennis game, was shoved at gunpoint into a waiting car
anderson is an old friend, your basic boy-next-door, off to see the world in a foreign correspondent's trench coat. he has an enviable talent for finding the story and telling it straight, whether in detroit or johannesburg or beirut
we spent our salad days together in ap's detroit bureau; he filed the state broadcast wire and lived out towards ann arbor with his family and a wonderful collection of japanese etchings. from michigan, he became ap's chief middle east correspondent by way of tours in japan and south africa
in 1984, anderson and i had lunch in washington and he caught me up on the dangers and satisfaction of reporting the complex story of lebanon. i told him we called it ``wartornlebanon'' as if it were one long word. he laughed
now he is a part of the wartornlebanon story, longest held of some two dozen westerners missing in the sad city of beirut
i was out pricing washing machines on saturday, march 16, 1985, when a radio newscast said an american reporter had been kidnapped in beirut. i figured it might be terry anderson, and it was
i figured he might be free by monday, and he wasn't
who would have thought a year would go by, or two, let alone three?
that his baby would be born and he wouldn't know? she would turn one, learn to walk, learn to talk, and he wouldn't know. last spring she turned two. is she a terrible two? is she eating her vegetables? he wouldn't know
the washing machine is three years old and anderson is still the property of shiite kidnappers, currency in a geopolitical ordeal that has killed two american hostages and threatens the remaining eight. terry waite, who negotiated tirelessly for all the western hostages, now shares their fate
in march 1986, we marked the first anderson anniversary in a church on new york avenue. it was an optimistic gathering; perhaps freedom was just around the corner. rarely had a hostage been held so long; we hoped he was holding up
jesse jackson, who knew anderson celebrity-to-reporter, delivered a call for peace and brotherhood and deliverance
hostage relatives expressed frustration, and more
there have been so many times that i was frightened they would do something to them,'' anderson's sister, peggy say, said of the six americans then in captivity. another hostage relative, sue franceschini, said, ``i'm on automatic pilot most of the time, but we made it through the holidays.''
her brother, rev. lawrence martin jenco, would be released in 1986, but for others, more holidays would pass and more americans would be taken
the second anderson anniversary was marked at a second church, up 16th st. from the white house. the iran-contra story was out and it was clear that the hostages were key pawns in a multi-level ``arms for hostages'' intrigue. optimism? not so you could notice
the third anderson anniversary is upon us and wednesday we gather in a third church, this time for a candlelight and olive branch ceremony in georgetown. the pain, not gone. the weight, not lifted
no one knows how anderson will mark the day. he was last heard from in a videotape on christmas eve, day 1,012
jonathan wolman is ap's assistant bureau chief in washington
standing before an only mildly interested crowd at a county fair in florida last week, democratic presidential candidate albert gore jr. introduced himself
i am the only active farmer in this race for president,'' he said, stirring as good an applause as he got for the rest of his speech
the 39-year-old harvard-educated senator from tennessee, perpetually clad in a blue suit, could be accused of stretching it a bit with that statement
true, home is a modest farmhouse hard by the caney fork river at rural carthage, tenn., set amid the gore family farm operation. gore, though, has hardly made his living working its soil
but his statement, often repeated, is emblematic of gore as a man of varying backgrounds and worlds who has so far been able to balance them all
gore made the leap to the top tier of democratic presidential candidates last week in the super tuesday primaries. he won six states, five in the south plus nevada, and accomplished his aim: to use the biggest ever regional primary to jump-start a presidential campaign
he faces the task now of backing up his claim of being more than a regional candidate
while he is competing in the illinois primary tuesday, his hope is to advance as the primaries move across the north, arguing that he is the white alternative to gov. michael dukakis, the delegate leader. he depicts dukakis as a massachusetts liberal who, if nominated, could cause another landslide democratic loss
now that the campaign has moved out of the south, gore can be expected to rely less on his rural background than on his urban background. he has one of each
gore is the son of a veteran tennessee politician. albert gore sr. spent 32 years in congress, first in the house and later in the senate, before losing his seat in 1970
gore jr. was born and educated in washington, d.c., and attended the elite st. albans prep school in washington and then harvard. his wife, mary elizabeth or ``tipper'' as she is better known, was a high school sweetheart in washington
he was the all-american boy: bright, honors student, played basketball and football. he was accustomed to seeing the powerful of washington and can tell stories as a youngster of john kennedy and then-vice president richard nixon
yet like the congressman he would become, gore kept up his ties back home
as his father faced his final battle for re-election, and his opposition to the vietnam war threatened his seat, gore jr. joined the army and was sent to vietnam. he served as an army journalist
he returned to tennessee and a reporter's job at the nashville tennessean, hired by the publisher himself. he entered both divinity school and law school, not completing either. he quit law school after two years when the house seat his father once held came open
returning to washington as a house member himself, in 1976, and as a senator in 1984, gore's eastern background served him well
he was singled out early on by some monied, establishment democrats as a young man on the move, a potential presidential candidate
he was well connected and worked hard. he immersed himself in the arcane, technical ins-and-outs of issues such as arms control, medical technology and the space program
as a campaigner, gore draws on his various backgrounds. in the south he told country-lawyer jokes and talked about hypnotizing chickens _ one of the rural arts he claims to have mastered
but he also won the endorsement of the new republic magazine, whose editor was a former teacher of his at harvard
gore has also moved among nashville's country music crowd. he campaigned with country singer johnny cash, and rubbed elbows with hard-living country rebel hank williams jr. yet his wife tipper has led a campaign against raw lyrics in rock music, a campaign that has stirred opposition from some parts of the entertainment and music industry
the gores have four children, ages 5 through 14, who live and go to school in suburban washington. gore sometimes brings along one or more of his children on campaign trips, without their mother, including 5-year-old albert
gore will turn 40 on march 31. if elected, he would be the youngest president ever, following the oldest. he often makes the comparison to young john kennedy following the elderly dwight eisenhower in 1960
despite a voting record decidedly more liberal than some of tennessee's other representatives, gore won election to the senate overwhelmingly four years ago when republican howard baker declined to run again
whenever a questioner challenge's gore's claim to be a moderate, or his credentials as a son of the south, gore recalls that 1984 election. gore won 61 percent of the vote, running ahead of even ronald reagan, who got 58 percent of tennessee's vote. campaign</head>
to judge from the vitriolic campaign, salvadorans have a choice between thieves and murderers when they cast their ballots in legislative and municipal elections next sunday
tough campaigning has been common in el salvador in the years when civilian politics has prevailed over the exercise of power by force of arms
but this time around the denigration of opposing parties' candidates and institutions has eclipsed most attempts to inform the electorate of proposals for resolving this tiny central american country's tremendous problems
at stake are all 60 seats in the legislative assembly and the mayorships and councils of 262 municipalities nationwide. about 1.9 million of the country's 5 million people are eligible to vote
the governing christian democrats are expected to lose their majority in the assembly and such a defeat would turn president jose napoleon duarte's last year in office into an uphill climb
the election campaign is poisoning the country, deepening resentment and hate and putting even farther off the reconciliation of a divided people,'' said rafael moreno guillen in his column in la prensa grafica, the nation's most widely read paper
monsignor gregorio rosa chavez, auxiliary bishop of san salvador, said in his homily sunday: ``we would like to be able to say that the politicians offer a clear alternative to the violent methods that affect innocent people. but the political forum has likewise been converted into a war of insults.''
the party expected to make the biggest gains is the republican nationalist alliance, or arena, an ultra-rightist group. prominent christian democrats have conceded they have little chance of retaining their majority
adolfo rey prendes, the front-runner for the christian democratic presidential nomination, predicted at a recent news conference that his party would lose eight of its current 33 seats in the assembly. presidential elections are scheduled for next year
rey prendes attributed the decline to ``the natural erosion of support experienced by a party that governs in difficult times.''
el salvador is suffering in its eighth year of a civil war that has killed about 65,000 people, displaced 500,000 and ravaged its economy
the leftist guerrilla alliance battling the u.s.-supported government has denounced the elections as a farce and declared the voting will not be allowed to proceed in the northern and eastern regions under rebel control
el salvador receives more u.s. aid than any country in the western hemisphere. economic and military aid last year was more than $500 million
the military said last week it could guarantee voting in 244 of the 262 municipalities. defense minister gen. carlos vides casanova said 40,000 troops will be deployed to guard against any guerrilla attempts to disrupt the voting
eight parties _ all centrist or rightist _ are presenting candidates, but only three are competing nationwide. left-of-center parties declined to participate, citing lack of security for their candidates
rightist death squads killed several thousand leftist union and political activists in el salvador in the early 1980s. human rights groups say the squads remain intact, and the roman catholic church recently denounced what it said was an increase in the number of politically motivated murders
arena and its founder, retired army maj. roberto d'aubuisson, have been linked to the death squads since the party's formation in 1982
at a recent christian democratic campaign rally in panchimalco, six miles south of san salvador, speakers repeatedly referred to d'aubuisson's group as ``torturers'' and ``killers.''
arena, for its part, calls the pdc _ the christian democratic party's initials in spanish _ the party of the corrupt
arena, which has 13 legislators in the current assembly, is not expected to win an outright majority. but most observers believe it will win almost as many seats as the christian democratic party
that could leave the national conciliation party _ the third group competing nationwide _ with the balance of power
the rightist national conciliation party was formed by the military and governed for nearly 20 years before a 1979 coup. it formed an alliance with arena in the 1985 legislative elections
but the national conciliation party, in an effort to portray itself as moderate, eschewed the alliance this time around. ``against the death squads and the thieves, pcn,'' has been its slogan in this campaign
the farabundo marti national liberation front, which groups five rebel organizations, said in a communique last month:
the country has lost its sovereignty (to the united states) and democracy does not exist. rather there is a new kind of military dictatorship with a civilian facade. without independence, no election is legitimate.''
stocks closed lower and the dollar fell against the japanese yen in tokyo on monday as dealers' expectations for u.s. trade figures due out on thursday grew more pessimistic
the dollar closed at 127.23 yen, down 0.57 yen from friday's close of 127.80 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues closed at 25,433.51 points, down 110.22 points, or 0.43 percent, from friday's close
dealers said the dollar fell due to speculation that figures for the united states' trade deficit for january would be higher than previously expected
traders on the stock market were also waiting for the u.s. trade figures, according to an analyst with a major brokerage who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``trading was not so heavy in the first section, aside from some heavy industrials, steel and electricals,'' the analyst said
the record high subsidies paid out by the agriculture department all went to farmers, right? not quite, says the general accounting office
in the last three fiscal years, according to gao, net cash outlays for farm price and income support programs totaled about $67 billion. of that amount, farmers got about 80 percent, or $53 billion
the gao, an investigative agency of congress, provided a breakdown of recent farm program costs in a report requested by rep. bill alexander, d-ark
the gao divided the record fiscal 1987 cash outlay of more than $25.8 billion into two parts: about $23.5 billion in ``commodity specific'' expenditures such as deficiency payments, loans and storage payments, and $2.36 billion in ``non-commodity specific'' items, including export programs, conservation payments and operating expense
overall, four commodities _ corn, wheat, dairy and cotton _ account for most of the program costs registered by the department's commodity credit corp. in fiscal 1987, for example, when the total was $25.8 billion, corn and other feed grains accounted for $12.2 billion; wheat, $3.44 billion; dairy, $2.34 billion; and cotton, $2.14 billion
the gao report said that of the $25.8 billion total in fiscal 1987, farmers received $20.6 billion
while farmers received most of the support program's outlays, it is unknown how much of those outlays went to individual farmers versus farmers organized under some other business structure,'' the report said. ``farmers organize, operate and receive the support program outlays as any one of various business entities.''
the report added that those entities can include individual proprietorship, partnership, association, cooperative, corporation, trust or estate. moreover, investigators said they were told that usda does not maintain records of farm program outlays by the various types of farm businesses
farmers receive the support program outlays as producers of the supported agricultural commodities regardless of their business structure,'' the report said
about $3.9 billion went to non-farmers in fiscal 1986. those included ``commercial operators engaged in farming-related activities, or to other recipients who may or may not be farmers'' for a variety of reasons, including direct purchases of commodities, storage and handling, transportation, and claims under export guarantee programs
operating expenses and related administrative costs added $2.3 billion to the 1987 total. but the 1987 operation of ccc also include around $1 million in proceeds from sales of commodities, with that amount credited against the other outlays
the census bureau says farmers should remember to return their survey questionnaires describing 1987 operations
although the form was due on feb. 1, the bureau said it recognizes that some may be running late. besides, the law requires it
use your best estimates if you don't have the information in your records,'' the commerce department agency said. ``return your forms to the census bureau even if you did not grow any crops, or have any livestock, poultry or other agricultural products in 1987, so the bureau can correct its records.''
officials said if help is needed, call the census bureau's toll-free number, 1-800-233-6132. indiana residents should call 1-800-233-6135
you may also obtain help from local offices of the cooperative extension service, soil conservation service, agricultural stabilization and conservation service, farmers home administration, and vocational agriculture teachers,'' the agency said
the federal law requiring farmers and ranchers to respond to the census ``also protects the privacy of their reports,'' the bureau said
government trade figures show u.s. agricultural exports in the first three months of the 1988 fiscal year were on target with agriculture department projections
the value of shipments in the first quarter of the year that began oct. 1 was estimated at $8.46 billion, up 10 percent from the pace of a year earlier, according to the department's foreign agricultural service
department officials have forecast 1987-88 exports at $32.5 billion, up from $27.9 billion in 1986-87
the actual volume of shipments in the first quarter was reported at 36.2 million tons, up 11 percent from a year earlier. for the year, those are expected to total about 142.5 million metric tons, up from 129.2 million tons in 1986-87
strong wheat sales to the soviet union and china, strong corn sales to the soviet union, south korea and japan, as well as improved soybean sales to brazil, strengthened export volume,'' the agency said in a recent trade report
some 34.4 million crimes were committed in the united states in 1987, the third straight year of stable crime levels, according to a government survey
since 1980, violent crimes have fallen from 33 per 1,000 u.s. residents to 28, thefts from 83 to 68 per 1,000, and household crimes from 227 to 168, the bureau of justice statistics said in a report sunday
crime levels overall rose a statistically insignificant 0.9 percent last year from 34.1 million in 1986
total crime has remained stable during the last three years'' and remains at a 14-year low, according to bjs director stephen schlesinger
there were 5.5 million violent crimes in 1987, up 0.4 percent from the previous year. thefts totaled 13.45 million last year, up 1.7 percent from 1986. household crimes of burglary, larceny and auto theft totaled 15.4 million, up 0.4 percent from the previous year. only motor vehicle thefts grew significantly, by 15 percent to an estimated 1.6 million
some criminologists had been predicting continued declines in crime levels for a few more years, based on the fact that the most crime-prone age group continues to shrink in size. those researchers predict an increase in crime in the early 1990s as the children of parents born during the post-world war ii baby boom move into the 14- to 24-year-old age bracket in significant numbers. the crime-prone 14- to 24-year-old age group totaled 42.5 million in 1986, down nearly 4 million from the 1979 peak
one factor that could have caused the decline of crime rate in the early 1980s to stabilize may be increased use of serious drugs, said alfred blumstein, dean of the school of urban and public affairs at carnegie-mellon university in pittsburgh
illicit drug use among criminal defendants is high and seems to be on the increase, justice department officials said last month at a news conference
another possibility, blumstein said, may be that people now in their late teen years are disproportionately from a low-income population, which traditionally has shown more involvement in the crimes measured by the national survey
some lawmakers say they think a group of congressional aides used bad judgment in attending a secret meeting in january with palestinian leader yasser arafat
it was very foolish,'' rep. larry smith, d-fla., said last week after the meeting became public. ``that was the wrong thing to do.''
the two-hour meeting with arafat, arranged by the national council on u.s.-arab relations, took place in baghdad, iraq, a few weeks after congress passed legislation closing the palestine liberation organization offices in the united states on the grounds the plo supports terrorism. arafat heads the plo
ronald w. cathell, executive director of the council, said the meeting was constructive because it gave the congressional aides a chance to see arafat in the flesh and conduct a ``candid, forthright'' discussion with him
in response to a question from one capitol hill staff member, arafat told the group the man he admired most in history was saint peter because the disciple of jesus ``conquered rome by winning the hearts'' of f the staffers. he said they could be subjected to reprisals
people with knowledge of the free trip said those who went to iraq worked for sens. mark hatfield, r-ore.; john heinz, r-pa.; j. bennett johnston, d-la., david karnes, r-neb; and reps. edward f. feighan, d-ohio; robert torricelli, d-n.j.; helen bentley, r-md.; douglas bereuter, r-neb.; william clay, d-mo.; james inhofe, r-okla., and robert lagomarsino, r-calif
all but one of the aides on the trip attended the arafat meeting, a state department official said, speaking on condition he remain anonymous
several aides who traveled to iraq refused to talk about what happened in the meeting, and would only discuss the trip if their names were not used. after the arafat meeting, group members realized the significance of their action and made a pact to keep it secret, one said
rep. robert g. torricelli, d-n.j., said he was upset when he learned an aide had seen arafat without his permission
she acted independently, and i had no knowledge of this meeting nor would i have approved it, and i remain very disturbed about it.'' the staffer no longer works for torricelli, but left for personal reasons unrelated to the meeting
feighan, however, was unconcerned. he said his assistant ``was not on any official trip and he was traveling in a personal capacity.''
but several capitol hill staffers who deal exclusively with foreign policy _ the middle east in particular _ said they never would have accepted the invitation in view of u.s. policy
the meeting was ``extremely unwise when as a matter of law american officials are not supposed to negotiate with the plo,'' said michael van dusen, staff director of the house foreign affairs subcommittee on europe and the middle east
the policy _ imposed by congress _ prohibits officials in the executive branch from negotiating with the plo until the group recognizes israel's right to exist
but the policy does not apply to congress, and a few lawmakers as well as staff members have met openly with arafat in the past. rep. nick rahall, d-w.va., for example, saw arafat in a bunker in west beirut in lebanon in 1982
torricelli complained that the u.s. embassy in baghdad failed to advise his aide about u.s. policy on the plo. but a state department official, refusing to be identified by name, said the u.s. ambassador had tried to dissuade the americans from meeting with arafat. no embassy personnel went to the session
the original agenda did not list an arafat meeting. once the group arrived in baghdad, cathell said he learned the plo leader was in town and broached the possibility of a meeting with the congressional aides
the staffers were never pressured to attend the meeting, cathell said. instead they were told, ``it's totally up to you,'' he said
one aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the group was given less than an hour's notice that a face-to-face meeting with arafat had been set
the national council seeks to promote understanding between americans and arabs, and receives its money from grants and private and corporate contributions. with sinatra appearance, quotes; deletes grafs 14-15 pvs, `berniece hourcade ...' to tighten. will stand for ams.</note>
the rat pack is back
frank sinatra, sammy davis jr. and dean martin, reunited for a 29-city, 40-show tour sunday night, brought their unique blend of fun times and good tunes to the old fans who loved 'em way back when and young fans who'd never had the chance
how long have i been on?'' deadpanned martin after walking absent-mindedly onto stage holding a cigarette and a glass of bourbon at the start of the sold-out concert
he then sang ``when you're smiling,'' changing the last word to drinking. to rousing applause and a few shouts of ``louder,'' he then sang ``bourbon from heaven.''
davis, flashing his trademark gold jewelry hanging in chains down his chest, was given a standing ovation for ``i've got to be me,'' his signature song
davis drew applause when he mentioned he'd been in show business 59 years and had been sober for three years
the crowd applauded enthusiastically when he performed songs such as ``candy man'' and ``what kind of fool am i?''
sinatra was the real crowd pleaser, drawing huge ovations from the packed house when he belted out such favorites as ``for once in my life,'' ``mack the knife,'' ``you are the sunshine of my life,'' and ``new york, new york.''
davis and martin rejoined sinatra for the closing finale, which featured a lot of kidding along with medleys of pop favorites from the last four decades
as far as we're concerned,'' said davis to sinatra, ``and i can say this for both of us, you're still the chairman of the board.''
martin added, ``yeah, you're still the chairman, we're still bored.''
the tour's opening show at the sold-out oakland coliseum also marked the 48th anniversary of sinatra's first stage show: a 1940 appearance at new york's paramount theatre with big band leader tommy dorsey
the three of us, we love each other, and we have more fun than the audience,'' martin said when the tour was announced in january
we're going to cities where none of those people have ever, never, seen anything like us.''
the 70-year-old joker vowed to get the audience laughing ``and then they will continue laughing while these guys sing.''
davis and sinatra, age 62 and 72 respectively, first appeared with martin at the sands hotel in las vegas in january 1960. they made frequent guest appearances in each others' shows and made a number of films together, including such box office hits as ``ocean's eleven,'' ``sergeants three,'' and ``robin and the seven hoods.''
alameda county supervisor charles santana and his wife, doris, were among the 14,500 fans at the concert, many of whom decked themselves out in evening and cocktail dresses and sports coats and suits. they said they have been fans of sinatra since the late 40s
mrs. santana said she was so devoted to her idol that ``my mother always said i was the one who made him famous.''
i've seen frank sinatra before, and i grew up listening to his music,'' said lydia cox, 26, of oakland. her 35-year-old brother, charles, said he came to watch the fun
this is a once-in-a-lifetime thing,'' he said. ``if i didn't see them now i'd never get another chance.''
the trio picked up the ``rat pack'' moniker after actor humphrey bogart used that label for a large group of entertainers that lived in the same area of beverly hills
for the last two decades, they've performed mainly in the glitzy showrooms of atlantic city and las vegas. sinatra has joked that the troupers wanted to go on tour so that ``people could see how bad we are.''
the idea of touring surfaced when the three longtime friends gathered at sinatra's house. it became possible because all three are under contract to bally corp
the shows, with top tickets going for $40, will be backed up by a 35-piece orchestra. home box office plans to broadcast a special on the show later
davis, martin and sinatra are among a growing number of aging superstars whose careers only seem stronger with age
comics danny thomas, milton berle and sid caeser recently appeared in a made-for-television movie, ``side by side.'' rodney dangerfield, mort sahl and jackie mason have all found themselves under contract for one-man shows
and then there's george burns, 92, who has a new movie coming out in april. he's booked to play the london paladium when he turns 100
in a recent interview for usa weekend, burns offered a few kind words for the rat pack: ``i'm sure those three kids will make it. i think sinatra has potential. he just has to build some confidence. all three will be big stars if they keep working at it.''
the ``together again'' tour continues in vancouver, b.c., on tuesday, seattle on wednesday, and chicago on friday and saturday
it comes as a small but meaningful reward to peggy say that the people in her hometown are rallying behind her call to remember the hostages in lebanon
there were many times when it seemed people didn't want to hear about how her brother, journalist terry anderson, was still being held. there was the stinging criticism that maybe she was somehow to blame for his prolonged captivity
it's different now. her brother's defiant expression is seen on posters in the stores and restaurants of this rural upstate town 40 miles east of buffalo
the posters say: ``remember terry anderson on the anniversary of his captivity, march 16, 1988. please wear a yellow ribbon and pray for the hostages in lebanon.''
prayer services, a rally and a candlelight march down main street are scheduled to mark the beginning of the fourth year of captivity for the 40-year-old anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press
this is the first time we've gotten this kind of support,'' said mrs. say. ``people just assumed that the government's quiet diplomacy was the answer. now, i think they realize it isn't working.''
many of this week's activities in batavia, where anderson grew up, have been organized by the rev. thomas vickers, pastor and friend of the say family. vickers asked florists to donate ribbon to decorate downtown. while most of the town's seven florists agreed, one shop provided more than 2 miles of yellow ribbon
inside john hamel's flower shop are thousands of yellow bows, hung on garlands, that are being handed out to residents who request them. hamel said that it was ``just a small thing'' he could do to help
a nun at notre dame high school has made a huge greeting card that will be on display at the genesee country mall beginning saturday so that residents can sign it. it will be sent to lebanon
mrs. say's daughter, melody brewington, said the turnout for an observance of the anniversary last year was disappointing. this time the response has been overwhelming, she said
mrs. say will not be here, but at the holy trinity church in washington, d.c., for a service for hostage family members
i wish i could be here, too,'' she said. ``there has been such an outpouring of concern. it would please terry so much to know that people really haven't forgotten him.''
there are 22 foreigners, including nine americans, missing and believed held by moslem fundamentalists in lebanon. anderson has been held the longest
from ex-hostages and other sources, mrs. say has learned that her brother is being held alone in a windowless room, fighting the boredom and loneliness of his solitary existence. he is often blindfolded and has been beaten and harassed
mrs. say has been tireless in calling for more to be done for the hostages
if they (the hostages) are no longer important to the people of america or this administration, then (the captors) will think they have to make a political statement by executing them. that's what waits for them if all of us don't keep them alive in the public eye.''
jesse jackson likes to say he has the ``poor campaign with a rich message,'' but he may have to alter that slogan a bit if his fund-raising trends continue
jackson's mail consultant mal warwick said that while jackson is not in the league of other multi-million-dollar presidential contenders, the response to his mail solicitations is so overwhelming that warwick has had to increase his 12-person money-counting staff to 30 over the past two months
it is too early to tell how jackson's strong showing in the super tuesday states will affect his contributions, warwick said. but he added, ``money has been coming in so far ahead of projections that we are struggling to keep up with it.''
the mail results have grown steadily since last fall, when about $150,000 per month was coming in, said campaign treasurer howard renzi. that increased to about $270,000 in january
and in february, the month when primaries and caucuses began, $400,000 of the $750,000 the campaign raised came in through the mail, renzi said
we're starting to approach the time where we'll have the financial wherewithal to be more competitive,'' he said, adding that a good part of the money raised by mail is going back into the mail program to develop a bigger base of contributors
jackson still has a long way to go to catch up with democratic money leader michael dukakis, who had raised some $15 million by the end of january, including federal matching funds, to jackson's $3.3 million
jackson has made much of the fact that he has done well despite being outspent by as much as 30 times in states where his opponents put on heavy media campaigns
but his sophisticated mail program is producing results that were unheard of in jackson's 1984 campaign, when taking a collection at revival-style rallies was his most frequent fund-raising approach
warwick runs a state-of-the-art direct mail and telemarketing operation, utilizing lists of names purchased from other mail soliciters to determine which categories of people would be most likely to give to jackson
we're using every technique in the book,'' he said, and sending mail to a broad spectrum of progressive democrats. the mail includes everything from postcards to sophisticated packets and questionnaires through first-class mail
in addition to the mail, jackson's campaign chairman willie brown, influential speaker of the california state assembly, said there will be a series of concerts to raise money in the weeks to come. brown, one of the most successful fund-raisers in california politics, also said this week he will try to extract $1 million from the state's ``bleeding hearts'' whom he said should be giving money to jackson
warwick said about one mailing per week goes out, ranging in size from 5,000 pieces to previous contributors, to 400,000 pieces in a search for new donors
the results we are obtaining are as strong as anything i've ever witnessed in all my time of direct mail fund-raising,'' warwick said
warwick's berkeley, calif., firm, changing america, inc., handled direct mail for the presidential campaign of gary hart last year before hart dropped out of the race the first time, and has several liberal organizations as clients
one ``dear fellow american citizen'' letter from jackson was sent to white liberal democratics in affluent west los angeles. in what the industry calls the ``involvement'' approach, it included an ``issues survey'' asking the reader's opinion on jackson's key issues
another mailing that went out after the feb. 8 iowa caucuses highlighted jackson's 8 percent showing in a state with a 1.4 percent black population as evidence that he has support outside the black community, contrary to what ``so called political experts'' had claimed
warwick said that since names on his mailing lists are ``overwhelmingly non-black,'' white people obviously are contributing to jackson
for us to get the results we are getting means he has very substantial support among white mail donors,'' he said
warwick would not be specific on the rate of return for the amount of mail sent out, but said it was ``much better'' than the 1 percent to 1.5 percent return that is typical for so-called prospecting mail, in which new donors are sought out
super tuesday's muddled democratic results could give california and at least one prominent california politician a bigger share of the political spotlight
since democratic contenders jesse jackson, michael dukakis and albert gore jr. emerged from the round of contests on march 8 tightly clustered in the delegate race, more attention is being paid to the late contests, such as california's june 7 primary
and california assembly speaker willie brown, the flamboyant national chairman of jesse jackson's presidential campaign, is waiting in the wings for what could be a key role
the importance and influence of brown, the consummate deal-maker and power broker of the california legislature over the past decade, is growing with the prospect of a brokered democratic convention
if jackson ultimately falls short of winning enough delegates for nomination, every extra delegate he wins increases the chances of a deadlocked convention _ and the chance that jackson and top advisers like brown will have a say in deciding who is the nominee
if it comes to that, democrats will again be facing the quandary of trying to make enough concessions to jackson to keep his supporters while not conceding enough to alienate other constituencies _ creating a situation in which brown's negotiating skills could be especially important
brown has said repeatedly that he isn't maneuvering for a brokered convention, but rather for a jackson victory
the jackson campaign wants the nomination,'' brown told sacramento reporters last week. ``we may well determine the democratic nomination with the california vote. probably jackson is the favorite at the moment (in california).''
but brown's first choice for the nomination was new york gov. mario cuomo, and he signed on with jackson only after cuomo declined to run
brown has repeatedly and heatedly denied speculation that he took the jackson campaign chairmanship to be in a position to deliver jackson votes to cuomo at a deadlocked convention, saying that he is supporting jackson because he believes he is the best candidate and can win
brown isn't the only california politician coming in for attention where the presidential race is concerned. california gov. george deukmejian is frequently mentioned as a possible running mate for the gop nominee
but deukmejian has a democratic lieutenant governor who would take over if he stepped aside. that would diminish the republican support in california he would otherwise be expected to add to a national ticket
deukmejian himself has said he would ``absolutely, unequivocably, not under any circumstances'' accept the nomination
even if offered the opportunity, i would not be able to do it, and i would not,'' he says
deukmejian refuses to speculate publicly on why he keeps being mentioned as vice presidential material when he's made it known he's not interested
one of his advisers, speaking on condition of anonymity, says: ``it's just window-dressing. they all want a westerner on their lists, and he's the biggest name out here. but they all know the situation, and that he's serious when he says he isn't available.''
north dakota democrats have begun a two-week process of picking the delegates who will attend the state convention and eventually cast ballots for president
rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis have maintained the most active campaign offices in the state, said george gaukler, chairman of the state democratic party
democrats in the state hold 53 district conventions, which began sunday and will continue until march 27, to select delegates to the state convention in fargo. convention-goers will cast their ballots for president on april 16, the third day of their four-day convention
delegates to the national convention in atlanta will be chosen based on their presidential preference. straw polls of the presidential race will be taken at each district convention, according to the party
state sen. allen richard, gephardt's state campaign coordinator, said, ``we'll be working hard at creating gephardt preference caucuses at the district conventions.''
we feel his moderate message on agriculture and trade is more in line with the thinking of north dakotans,'' he added
ellen austin, state coordinator of the dukakis campaign, said dukakis volunteers will also attend district conventions
our committee has felt all along that he was leading in this state, and we still feel he's the leader,'' she said. awards</head>
comedian bill cosby won four people's choice awards and the movie ``fatal attraction'' won three from an admiring public that also bestowed honors on cybill shepherd, dolly parton and whitney houston
this is particularly special for me,'' said miss shepherd, named favorite female television performer for her role in abc's ``moonlighting'' despite a shortened role last year due to her pregnancy with twins
when you're out of the limelight, you're pregnant with twins and gain 45 pounds and you go through this enormous change, it always goes through the back of your mind, `are they going to forget?'
it's really nice to know they didn't forget.''
the public chose the winners in the 14th annual people's choice awards, broadcast sunday night by cbs-tv
winners were determined by a gallup poll of 5,000 people older than 12, a statistical representation of nearly 196 million people
cosby was named favorite male tv performer for the fourth-consecutive year and favorite all-around male entertainer for the third. he also won a new award _ all-time favorite tv star _ while his top-rated nbc-tv series, ``the cosby show,'' won its fourth comedy program award
nbc's ``l.a. law'' was the favorite tv dramatic program
three men and a baby'' won for comedy movie and ``fatal attraction'' for dramatic motion picture. its leads, michael douglas and glenn close, were picked top motion picture performers
i want to thank you as my favorite father, and a supporter,'' douglas told his father, kirk douglas, who presented the award
i got so nervous when i got up i didn't thank the people,'' miss close said afterward. ``and that's what makes it so special. it's just a cross section of people who have nothing to do with the industry.''
clint eastwood was chosen all-time favorite movie star, an award presented by jimmy stewart
miss parton won favorite all-around female entertainer, and favorite female performer in a new tv program for abc's ``dolly.''
it's always nice to be recognized,'' she said backstage. ``this has been a hard year and i've been working really hard on this tv show. it's really nice to know the people are on my side.''
kenny rogers won his eighth award as male musical performer, tying with cosby, burt reynolds and barbara mandrell as an eight-time winner of an individual category
in other awards, oprah winfrey dethroned johnny carson as favorite television talk show host, miss houston was the favorite female musical performer, the group bon jovi was chosen favorite rock group, and barbra streisand was the favorite all-time musical star
john ritter was the favorite male performer in a new television program for abc's ``hooperman,'' while kirk cameron of abc's ``growing pains'' and keshia knight-pulliam of ``the cosby show'' tied for favorite young tv performer
the top new tv dramatic program was ``thirtysomething'' on abc, while nbc's ``a different world'' and ``my two dads'' tied in the new tv comedy category
in a new category, the all-time favorite song was ``somewhere my love (lara's theme)'' from the 1965 film, ``dr. zhivago.''
in chatham, a middle-class black neighborhood of brick bungalows and neat lawns, people like clevie williams are pulling for jesse jackson and proud of his democratic presidential bid
you can't talk to nobody in chatham unless it's about jesse,'' said williams, 66, a retired army master sergeant. ``they have a belief they can help him become the democratic nominee for president.''
on the tree-lined streets of chatham on the predominantly black south side, jackson's strong showing in the super tuesday primaries filled many with hope that maybe, just maybe, a black could be elected president of the united states of america
most people who paused to talk about jackson's chances said they would vote for him and his slated convention delegates in tuesday's illinois primary election
every vote counts,'' williams said. ``all i can say is he's got a chance. he's got as good a chance as he'll ever have.''
like many black neighborhoods across the financial spectrum, chatham is jesse jackson country. it's a community of about 40,000 people where the median family income was nearly $19,000 in the 1980 census. most people have jobs and many own their homes, mainly one- and two-story brick bungalows with an average value of $39,200, the census found
i would describe chatham as a rock-solid black middle-income community and one that has been that way for probably 20 years,'' said martin goldsmith, chicago's director of community development planning
jackson's work over the years with operation push, the civil-rights group he founded, and his two presidential campaigns have won the respect of many residents, said housewife jessie blissitt, 50
he's done a lot for black people,'' she said. ``he's someone we look up to. he speaks out for what really concerns black people. we've sort of been shoved aside by all the other candidates
because we are a minority, i don't know if he actually could make it to the presidency,'' ms. blissitt said. ``but i'm glad he's running if for nothing more than to show black kids they can do it, to give them a goal to strive for.''
several people shared her pessimism about whether the nation's white majority would elect a black president
people i talk to say he won't make it, due to the fact of his color,'' said donald crawford, 47, an apartment-building janitor
crawford said he planned to vote for jackson because he likes his background as a preacher and thinks his bid for the presidency shows ``guts.''
one thing about him being black, he wasn't born with a silver spoon in his mouth,'' he added. ``he knows the feeling.''
garrett manuel, also a janitor, paused as he weeded shrubbery in front of an apartment building and grinned as he thought about jackson's super tuesday success
i was surprised, but i really liked that. it made me feel good,'' said manuel, 61. ``most people i've talked to _ they really think he's going to win. and everybody i've talked to said they were going to vote for him.''
but elizabeth jones, 66, a retired tax examiner, said she was torn between jackson and sen. paul simon, the state's other favorite son
both candidates seem honest, straightforward and committed to their principles now, she said, but ``all of them are full of you know what.''
they promise you one thing and do another when they get in,'' she said
jesse jackson made an impressive showing in democratic caucuses in his native south carolina over the weekend and now takes aim at tuesday's primary in his adopted illinois
a record turnout estimated at 45,000 people attended the south carolina precinct caucuses saturday. when the meetings were over, it appeared the greenville native would collect 23 of the state's 48 national convention delegates
fifteen of the delegates apparently will be uncommitted while six will go to tennessee sen. albert gore. the state also has four super delegates which were not at stake in saturday's meetings
we the people have won south carolina,'' jackson told a crowd of about 400 supporters gathered saturday night at greenville technical college. ``this is a campaign of hope. each victory adds another to win.''
on sunday, campaigning in chicago, jackson said he expected his south carolina victory would give him momentum going into the tuesday primary in illinois
the south carolina delegate estimates were based on reports from 93 percent of the state's 1,788 precincts. carol kahre of the state democratic party said it could be a couple of days before all the numbers are in
the problem now becomes the county party priorities are preparing for their county conventions,'' she said. state officials must ``beg a lot'' to get the numbers in, she said
jackson, gore and gephardt all campaigned in the state in the days before the caucuses
clearly jesse jackson and the undecided are the big winners in south carolina,'' gephardt said while campaigning in detroit
gore's state campaign chairman, state rep. bob sheheen, d-kershaw, claimed that gore's finish above dukakis and gephardt ``is a significant victory.''
i thought if we ran neck and neck with the uncommitted that would be a great achievement,'' he said, adding he expects the gephardt campaign to fold before the state convention giving gore a chance to pick up more uncommitted delegates
the state organizer for dukakis, belton zeigler, said the campaign didn't spend much money in the state and ``whatever we get is gravy in the caucus campaign.''
bill prince, the state campaign coordinator for gephardt said ``we're going to make our stand in michigan.''
he expressed hope that a strong showing there later this month would allow the congressman to pick up some uncommitted delegates at the south carolina state convention next month
earl black, a university of south carolina political scientist, said the record turnout was due to jackson's organizing and gore's strong showing on super tuesday
with south carolina jesse jackson's home state, there was a very strong incentive in the black community,'' he said
some of it was due to gore's showing on super tuesday,'' black added. ``some democrats felt there was a candidate out there they could support.''
before super tuesday, gore was way back in polls in the state and he covered a lot of ground in just a few days, black said
but it's hard for him to claim a victory when he comes in behind the undecided,'' black added
the high road to dublin for a 130-member high school band from michigan led through a chicago hospital, where a schoolmate is recovering from bone cancer surgery
the belding high school band members, who raised $1,000 apiece to march in dublin's st. patrick's day parade and celebrate the irish capital's 1,000th anniversary, traveled 200 miles by bus sunday to o'hare international airport. before departing, though, they made a side trip to serenade 17-year-old eddie mikek
their instruments were being packed aboard the plane, so the musicians who gathered in the lobby of the university of chicago's wyler children's hospital and sang
because eddie is fighting cancer, they sang the belding fight song, and because he is their friend, they sang the band's theme song, ``friends.''
eddie's not a band member but he is a good friend,'' said band director bob stiles. ``we just want to remind him that he's one of us and show our love and concern.''
about 95 belding parents also were on hand to surprise eddie as he emerged from an elevator in his wheelchair
there wasn't a dry eye in the whole building,'' said eddie's mother, janice. ``he didn't know they were coming, and it took him a minute or two to figure out what was happening. then he started crying like all the rest of us.''
that's the kind of town belding is,'' she said of the small apple-growing community 30 miles east of grand rapids. ``we know almost everyone there and we consider them all friends.''
eddie was diagnosed as having bone cancer dec. 10, a day after his 17th birthday, mrs. mikek said. before his illness, he had been an active high school junior, too busy helping at his parents' grocery store and working a part-time job at a hardware store to have time for extracurricular activities like athletics or the band
for a while after his diagnosis, he was able to attend school several days a week between chemotherapy treatments, mrs. mikek said, but schoolwork had to stop when he came here for surgery
the family had to sell their store, ``because we knew we wouldn't have time to run it with all the trips to chicago,'' said mrs. mikek in a telephone interview from the ronald mcdonald house, where she stays when she is visiting eddie
everybody was here for the serenade,'' said mrs. mikek. ``my husband, edward, our 18-year-old son, our 7-year-old daughter, our 5-month-old baby and even john and val rayborn, who run the hardware store where eddie worked. seeing them is what really got to him.''
on march 4, doctors at the hospital removed a tumor from eddie's left leg and implanted part of a femur. they also installed a mechanical knee joint. the relatively new surgical technique, called limb salvage, avoids amputation, and should allow eddie to walk normally in the future, mrs. mikek said
he'll be in the hospital about another two weeks, and then will begin physical therapy,'' she said. ``all he wants right now is to be able to walk again, and everything's on hold until he does.''
attorney general edwin meese iii says he still regards as a friend the man whose memos have made him a target of a criminal investigation into a $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline project
meese also denies that he untruthfully played down his involvement in promoting the project with then-israeli prime minister shimon peres
a memo by longtime meese friend e. robert wallach says that on oct. 16, 1985, meese, peres and wallach had a ``three-way discussion'' of the project at the israeli embassy in washington
on sunday, james rocap, one of meese's lawyers, said ``wallach's account totally exaggerates'' the discussion ``in order to impress his client,'' swiss oilman bruce rappaport, a partner in the pipeline project
rocap said it is a ``cheap shot'' and ``stupid'' to suggest that the memo contradicts meese's earlier portrayals of his contacts with peres as limited
in a statement issued feb. 1, meese said that his total involvement with peres on the pipeline consisted of ``only two contacts ... each was brief, limited, and neither was initiated by me.''
meese said that the washington post, which first disclosed the memo in its sunday editions, is ``taking a small fact that's well known and trying to blow it up into a new news story.''
the memo discussing the meeting had not been previously reported prior to the post article
wallach was paid $150,000 by rappaport and when wallach went to meese about the project, the attorney general referred him to the national security council
he is my friend,'' meese said of wallach in remarks sunday on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley.''
mr. wallach has never asked me to do anything that was wrong,'' meese said. he said ``a lot of people are taking a very simple situation'' and ``they're trying to make a big deal out of it.''
independent counsel james mckay is investigating meese's role in the pipeline as a result of a memo written to meese by wallach mentioning planned payments to the israeli labor party in a bid to protect the project in iraq from israeli attack
meese says he doesn't recall the portion of the memo dealing with the planned payments
wallach directed that the $150,000 he received from rappaport be placed in an account under the control of w. franklyn chinn, an investment adviser for both meese and wallach. the $150,000 ended up being pooled with funds from meese in several stock trades
meese's initial $50,000 investment grew to $95,000 with profits from the stock deals, but the attorney general denied in his television appearance that he profited from the $150,000. he said he was not aware at the time of the payment from rappaport to wallach
meese predicted that he would be exonerated in mckay's probe and said ``i shouldn't step aside because if honest public officials can be hounded out of office by partisan political attacks ... then no one as a public official is safe.''
another memo by wallach, also described in sunday's post, recounts a meeting in new york involving peres, wallach, the israeli ambassador to the united states and then-national security council aide david wigg. wallach said the meeting lasted about 15 minutes and that the four discussed two proposed letters for peres to sign, the first committing israel not to disrupt the iraqi pipeline and the second dealing with the possibility of using u.s. foreign aid to israel as insurance
peres has said in the past that he recalls having met wallach only twice, on social occasions with others present
peres eventually signed a later version of the first letter, but he said he could not act on the second letter without additional consultations in israel. the pipeline project collapsed shortly thereafter, for want of an insurance package which the iraqis demanded in the event israel destroyed the pipeline
the justice department saw legal obstacles to using israeli aid money as part of an insurance package
scientists at sandia national laboratories have cast aside a popular theory and developed a new method to dramatically boost the speed of solving complex problems with parallel computers, which work on many parts of a problem at the same time
we have achieved results that most computer scientists thought impossible a couple of years ago,'' said john l. gustafson, a sandia computer scientist
sandia announced sunday that gustafson and other scientists at the lab had broken records for speedups, a measure of the increased speed at which a problem can be solved on a multiprocessor parallel computer, compared with a single processor from the same system
single data processors, like those in home computers, solve problems one step at a time, in sequence, like balancing a checkbook
parallel computers use many processors linked together so they can share the load, each working on a different piece of a problem at the same time, like a lot of people each doing one page of a checkbook
the theory applied to parallel processing had predicted speedups of 50 to 100 times. but the sandia scientists achieved speedups of more than 1,000 times
edwin barsis, director of computer sciences and mathematics at sandia, said in an interview that large-scale parallel computing could be used in such areas as defense work, weather forecasting or solving large economic problems
barsis said the sandia scientists basically ignored a popular belief in computer circles based on a speedup theory dubbed amdahl's law
amdahl's law says that no matter how many processors might be linked in parallel, the problem-solving speed could be increased at most by 50 to 100 times that of a single processor because the increase would be limited by the small portion of any computer program that cannot be chopped up and run in parallel
sandia scientists decided to jump ahead and work with 1,000 or more processors at the same time. ``after you think about it for a while, you think it's obvious,'' barsis said
the idea is that you have to get all the processors to work together,'' barsis said. ``you have to make it so they don't get bogged down in communication (with each other) rather than computing.''
specialists in the field said sandia's findings appeared very significant
all the speedups sound very, very good for me. they sound very significant,'' anoop gupta, professor of computer science at stanford university, said in a telephone interview friday. ``but i would have to know more details. on the whole, however, they sound very good.''
we think it's a very exciting result,'' bill gear, head of the department of computer science at the university of illinois, said saturday
gear is president of the society for industrial and applied mathematics and managing editor of the siam journal of scientific and statistical computing
he read the sandia paper on the breakthrough, submitted for publication in the journal, last week. ``normally, from the time it (a paper) comes in until it appears in print, it may be two years,'' he said. ``we're going to try to publish it in july.''
the sandia scientists developed mathematical and computational methods, or algorithms, tailored to handle large scientific problems
the problems were worked out on a parallel supercomputer called an ncube-ten, made by ncube corp. of beaverton, ore
sandia has the only ncube-ten, which uses 1,024 processors. it is less than 3 feet on a side but is the largest computer in the world in numbers of processors operating in parallel and in the 7.7 billion bytes, or characters, it can move per second, sandia officials said
gustafson, along with fellow sandia scientists robert benner, gary montry and david womble, achieved speedups of 1,020, 1,019 and 1,011 on three full-scale scientific application problems, the officials said
we have come almost all the way to the theoretical limit for a 1,024-processor machine,'' benner said
note holders are balking at accepting less than 50 cents on the dollar as part of a plan to bail out the troubled first city bancorporation of texas inc., federal officials say
the $1.5 billion rescue plan _ which would be the second largest government bank bailout in history _ calls for $970 million in federal assistance, a $500 million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor group headed by chicago banker a. robert abboud, and a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets
but alan whitney, director of communications for the federal deposit insurance corp., said sunday that holders of first city's debt securities are reluctant to go along with the plan. he said it would require the note holders to settle for less than the face value of the notes
the amounts offered to the note holders ranged from 35 cents to 45 cents on the dollar, he said
according to whitney, abboud told federal regulators during weekend meetings in washington that not enough of the note holders have agreed to sell at those prices
the agreement provides that we have to have a 90 percent response to that tender offer, and mr. abboud advised us that that level has not been reached,'' he said
whitney said he didn't know how far the tender offers were from the 90 percent level and added that the note holders have until tuesday afternoon to respond
the fdic is working with mr. abboud and his investor group to handle first city on an alternate basis should the tender not be successful,'' he said
whitney stressed that people with accounts at the bank will be protected. he said fdic will use its powers ``to assure stability in first city banks and in the banking system.''
however, he would not disclose what alternatives would be considered to the abboud plan which first city shareholders approved march 4
whatever alternative way we'll come up with will ensure stability for first city and for the banking system as a whole,'' he said. ``the fdic has statutory authority to handle imminent or potential failed bank situations in various ways. ... we'll deal with that on tuesday, not to say that they'll have an announcement on tuesday.''
the fdic's $970 million pledge to first city is the largest such government rescue of a bank since the 1984 federal bailout of continental illinois bank and trust of chicago
first city grew quickly during the texas oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real estate loan losses when oil prices plummeted. for 1987, the company posted a $1.1 billion loss
it has assets of $11 billion and operates 59 banks in texas and one in south dakota
under the abboud plan, abboud would become chairman of the board and chief executive officer upon consummation of the deal. the proxy statement sent to shareholders before they approved the plan predicted the new company would become profitable almost immediately after spinning off the poorly performing assets
gold opened in london today at a bid price of $441.80 a troy ounce, up from $440.50 late friday
reports that iran may be planning to install silkworm anti-ship missiles on a tiny island in the southern persian gulf add a new element to a much-publicized threat that some u.s. naval officers say has been greatly overrated
military sources in washington said surveillance had detected evidence that crude missile launch pads were being built on abu musa, an outcropping long used as a base for armed speedboat attacks on gulf shipping by iran's revolutionary guards
the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there was still no sign of the missiles being installed. nor did they speculate on what purpose the chinese-built weapons might serve if located there
but missiles on abu musa would extend the so-called ``silkworm envelope'' along iran's coast bordering the strait of hormuz by about 100 miles, ``doubling the arc'' of the present threat, a u.s. source said
it would put the missiles, which have a maximum range of 50 to 60 miles, within easy reach of the main shipping channel leading to and from the hormuz passage, as well as a populated stretch of the arab coast
five of the seven united arab emirates port cities _ dubai, sharjah, ajman, umm al qaiwain and ras al-khaimah _ are 50 miles or less from abu musa
gulf-area diplomats and shipping executives expressed alarm early last year when it was disclosed that tehran was deploying mobile silkworm batteries along the hormuz, the only outlet from the oil-rich gulf to the open sea
iran was said to have successfully test-fired several of the missiles at an old ship's hulk. subsequent reports have said iran possessed as many as 100 silkworms, apparently supplied by china, although beijing has publicly denied the sales
senior american officials made it clear from the outset that any iranian use of the weapon would be met with swift retaliation
then-defense secretary caspar weinberger said that while washington did not contemplate ``pre-emptive strikes,'' even the activation of a silkworm's target-tracking radar would be seen as a hostile act, to which the u.s. navy would respond
iran's subsequent reluctance to even threaten to use the missiles in the strategic hormuz has caused u.s. naval officers to view the threat with increasing skepticism
the convoys of u.s.-flagged kuwaiti tankers continue to have protective air cover while passing through the ``envelope,'' but some warships now sail with crews at less than a full ``battle stations'' alert status, de rigeur when the operation began last july
of course we can't rule the silkworms out as a potential threat, but in my opinion it's been overrated _ right from the start,'' a u.s. navy intelligence officer said several months ago
other american officers have said the silkworms in the hormuz are probably the least of their worries in sailing through the gulf
more imminent concerns include iranian speedboats and most of all, another mistaken iraqi air strike such as that which wrecked the missile frigate stark, killing 37 americans, last may 17
one senior officer said he would not discount the idea of some ``crazies'' firing a silkworm in defiance of orders, but believed the danger from a planned attack was virtually nil
as long as we maintain our retaliatory assets in the arabian sea, that isn't going to occur,'' he said, referring to the u.s. aircraft carrier _ currently the nuclear-powered enterprise _ permanently stationed outside the gulf
the iranians aren't about to fire one of those things (silkworms) at a warship or a ship under navy escort. they know what would happen if they did. they'd be taken out in minutes,'' he said
friday's report of silkworm-related activity on abu musa came just as the only u.s.-flagged ship ever hit by a silkworm was sailing past the island
the 81,283-ton sea isle city, one of the 11 kuwait-owned tankers reflagged with the stars and stripes for protection from iranian attack, was heading out of the gulf in a navy convoy
it was the first trip for the ship since it was devastated by a silkworm last oct. 16 while anchored at kuwait's main offshore oil terminal. that missile, and a handful of others launched from iran-held territory in iraq's faw peninsula, are the only ones that tehran's forces are known to have fired
the silkworm, officially designated hy-2 by the chinese, is a variant of the 30-year-old soviet styx missile. the cumbersome, 20-foot-long projectile flies just above the water at subsonic speed, homing on its target by radar
although the weapon is crude by modern standards, its 1,000-pound warhead can cause severe damage. u.s. naval officials called the hit on the sea isle city a lucky shot, but the tanker was out of service for nearly five months
if military strongman gen. manuel noriega steps down from his post as head of the defense forces, the united states, and not panama's fledgling opposition, will have brought it about
u.s. sanctions freezing panamanian assets have dealt a serious blow to the military regime of noriega, who is indicted in the united states on drug trafficking and other charges
but the opposition has done little to further the process
president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire the general late last month but instead was booted out of office himself and went underground, still recognized by washington as panama's head of state
delvalle's wife, mrs. mariela diaz de delvalle, said last week that her husband was considering asking the united states for military intervention
the opposition grouped under the civic crusade, an assortment of political parties, private groups and businessmen's associations, has tried to stir up a protest movement against noriega but failed to rally enough popular support for large street demonstrations
only those with rifles can overthrow noriega,'' said an opposition businessman who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``those with rifles here (the defense forces) or those with rifles over there (the united states). the opposition has no weapons.''
noriega loyalists in the legislative assembly forced delvalle out on feb. 26, the day after delvalle, encouraged by the united states, tried to dismiss the general
the u.s. determination to force noriega out of office has brought the country to the brink of economic collapse. shortly after delvalle was dismissed the u.s. federal reserve, which provides the dollars panama uses as its currency, withheld shipments of cash to the panamanian central bank
then the united states froze all other panamian government assets in the united states and stopped monthly payments for operations of the panama canal
the result was a money crunch that left the panamanian government unable to pay its employees in cash and forced banks to remain closed for the past 11 days
the government is working out barter deals with supermarkets in an attempt to overcome the crisis, but business has come to a standstill
unless something happens soon, people will have to take to the streets to search for food,'' said winston robles, managing editor of the opposition newspaper la prensa, which the government closed down feb. 25
noriega has been hanging on thanks to the loyalty of his colleagues in the military's top ranks
many of them, like himself, come from middle-class families
in office since 1983, noriega is ideologically and politically an heir to gen. omar torrijos, the officer who rode a crest of panamanian nationalism and concluded the agreement that set a timetable for total panamian control of the panama canal by the year 2000
noriega uses defense forces, the only armed authority in panama, the way a politican would use the party to whip up support in small towns where the soldiers build roads or perform other civic jobs
he has established a very close relationship _ even more than friendship _ between the defense forces and the people,'' said boris moreno, director of the government's national information service. ``the political opposition here cannot overthrow noriega.''
the political opposition is made up of badly organized liberal parties whose leaders spend much time criticizing each other. the best organized party is the christian democrats led by ricardo arias, who is in miami because he was refused entry into panama two weeks ago
the christian democrats led the opposition alliance in 1984 and refused to recognize the election results that put in nicolas ardito barletta as president. they claimed noriega rigged the vote
it was the first election in 16 years in panama. the last popularly elected regime lasted 11 days in 1968. barletta was forced out, following a disagreement with noriega, and delvalle, who was then vice president, took his place. the next presidential elections are scheduled for may 1989
eloy o. aguilar, the mexico city bureau chief, has been covering the region for the past eight years
a star-studded aids benefit led by elizabeth taylor raised $2 million for education and research, and organizers hope the gala will be repeated elsewhere
we've had the most private funds raised (for aids) at this one function than any other place in the country,'' benefit spokesman charles cinnamon said of sunday's ``an extraordinary evening with elizabeth taylor and friends.''
we want it to be the prototype for the rest of the country.''
the series of $2,500-a-plate south florida dinner parties fell short of its $3 million goal, although its ``grand finale'' of champagne and dessert at the fontainebleau hilton hotel was sold out
ms. taylor urged the crowd, which included brooke shields, marlee matlin, margaux hemingway, zsa zsa gabor, ed asner and lynn redgrave, to do more
go out there and get your next-door neighbor involved,'' she said. ``put your money where your mouth is
we're talking about the living who are dying, and it's getting closer to all of us,'' ms. taylor said, likening fear of the disease to the tenacles of an octopus. ``how do you cope with those families who reject their beloveds ... (aids victims) need compassion and understanding. people may say money can't buy compassion, but money can buy health.''
the fund-raiser featured a dozen black-tie parties from palm beach to miami beach, all given in the homes of celebrities or community leaders
before the finale swung into full force with a stream of stars in sparkling jewels and dresses filling the posh beachfront fontainebleau, ms. taylor received $1.1 million from celia lipton farris of palm beach
that's so much money ... i mean that's so incredibly much money and the things that money will do!'' said ms. taylor
ms. taylor, who became involved with aids issues in 1984, chairs the non-profit american foundation for aids research, a research and education group that will share the benefit's proceeds
work at hospitals! be volunteers! ... your lives are not endangered,'' a teary-eyed ms. taylor told her guests. ``i have talked to, kissed and embraced and held in my arms, children, boys and girls, who have died in my arms and i'm still here.''
besides the gift from ms. farris, the total raised was boosted by a $300,000 donation by the wohl family foundation of miami
the community alliance against aids, a fund-raising arm of the university of miami school of medicine, led the benefit and will share the proceeds with ms. taylor's group
celebrities at the parties said they were pleased to join the fight against acquired immune deficiency syndrome
it's really an honor for me to be here,'' actor matt dillon said. ``it's a real problem everywhere, not just in america, but all over the world. anything i can do to help is why i'm here.''
the truth is aids is a problem of all citizens,'' actor eddie albert said. ``i consider it a part of my selfish responsibility to be here. i'm not immune to this thing any more than anyone else.'' crippling storm</head>
snow-clogged roads plagued motorists today from the eastern great lakes region to nebraska and other plains states where road crews were digging out from the region's worst blizzard in decades
the storm fizzled as it moved east, but still left 1{ feet of snow on the ground this morning along the windy wisconsin shore of lake superior and more than 20 inches in michigan's upper peninsula
for all practical purposes, it just kind of died as it moved into canada out of lower michigan,'' said pete reynolds, a forecaster with the national weather service's severe storms forecasting center in kansas city, mo
the only significant snowfall right now is near the lakes due to the lake effect,'' he said early today
three sisters were killed sunday evening south of waunakee, wis., when the car they were riding in collided with a pickup truck on a snow-slick road, authorities said. the accident brought to six the number of deaths blamed on the storm since it hit the midwest on thursday
we have been bombarded with accidents,'' said don olson, a state trooper in detroit, where expressways were glazed with ice sunday night. ``it's very treacherous.''
marquette county in upper michigan had 80 weekend traffic accidents, and all but major roads remained blocked by snow even though crews were working 12-hour shifts, state police sgt. paul numikoski said sunday
four inches of new snow was measured at sawyer air force base near marquette. south of lake erie, a heavy snow warning was posted through today in northeast ohio
cold canadian air pushed south in the wake of the storm. high temperatures today were expected to be much colder than normal for the season from the lower great lakes to the central gulf of mexico coast, and as much as 30 degrees colder than usual in the ohio and tennessee valleys
the storm had closed long sections of major highways in wyoming, the dakotas and nebraska
the last interstate to be reopened was i-90 across western south dakota, which was finally fully cleared late saturday, said todd seaman, a state transportation department engineer in rapid city. at the worst of the storm about 260 miles of it was shut down
fifteen-foot drifts were reported along i-90 in the kadoka area, and seaman said snow had drifted to the top of overpasses
crews in dawes county in northwestern nebraska, where more than 30 inches of snow fell in some areas, were having trouble breaking through snowdrifts up to 10 feet high, and some ranchers couldn't reach their cattle, county commissioner waymann wild said
this is probably the worst we've had since 1949,'' he said. the county was hard-hit last year, ``but nothing like this.''
about 700 snowbound travelers who had crowded the small town of kimball, neb., since thursday were told sunday that roads were still not in good shape but they could leave
to the north, in south dakota's black hills, hungry, snowbound skiers had to dig their cars out of 7 feet of snow to leave terry peak lodge, manager bob ekeren said
two busloads of children who had been snowbound in isolated farmhouses in western nebraska since thursday got home safely saturday afternoon. the 21 children were being driven home from school when the blizzard caught their drivers by surprise, forcing them to seek shelter with farm families
four deaths in wisconsin and two in south dakota were blamed on the storm. policy</head>
in anticipation of israeli prime minsister yitzhak shamir's visit today, more than 3,300 people marched to the white house and rallied near the offices of abc news for two opposing causes
more than 3,000 people carrying palestinian flags and chanting slogans marched to the white house on sunday to protest israeli policies in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
they condemned u.s. policy toward israel, chanting, ``reagan, shultz, you will see _ palestine will be free.''
the demonstrators called on the white house to freeze u.s. aid to israel and asked for a moratorium on military aid to israel until the israeli government supports and participates in the peace process
shamir, who strongly opposes a u.s. peace plan for the middle east, is due to arrive in washington today for talks with president reagan and secretary of state george p. shultz
meanwhile, about 300 pro-israel demonstrators rallied near the offices of abc news to protest the network's coverage of the clashes between israeli soldiers and arabs in the occupied territories
speakers urged the crowd to write or call the network to protest the coverage, while organizers sought signatures on petitions calling upon the media ``to report the entire story.''
a british producer says he has lined up 70 witnesses, including some who served with kurt waldheim in world war ii, to give evidence at a televised ``trial'' of allegations the austrian president was involved in nazi atrocities
the list includes some of waldheim's subordinates and superiors when he was an officer in the german army from 1939 to 1945, says jack saltman, who is producing the show for broadcast on u.s. and overseas television in june
it took a lot of persuasion to get some of them to do it,`` saltman said in a recent interview
the production will be the of result nine days, beginning april 13, of filming lawyers as they examine witnesses as if they were in a court of law, before a panel of retired jurists, including shirley hufstedler, a former u.s. education secretary and federal appeals court judge
the program, which will run four hours, will end with the judges' decision on whether there is probable cause that waldheim acted contrary to the international laws of war. accuracy</head>
rep. les aspin plans to deliver a speech on the floor of the u.s. house today that says the air force is ``part of the problem'' in the guidance system for the mx missile, but the service maintains the weapon is reliable and accurate
the text of the speech by the wisconsin democrat, who is chairman of the house armed services committee, was made available sunday
aspins says his panel's investigation of the 10-warhead weapon shows there are still problems in producing the missile's inertial measurement unit (imu), or guidance system
aspin has previously criticized northrop, which is building the imus at a hawthorne, calif., plant
documents recently received by the house armed services committee show that while northrop is undeniably having its difficulties, the air force is part of the problem,'' according to the congressman's latest criticism of the mx
he says the document, obtained from persons whom he did not identify, show that the service considered accepting one imu without inspecting it, and also protested the use of a process exempting small componentns from testing
an air force spokesman, capt. jay defrank, said, ``we stand by the imu's reliability and accuracy. we've answered many of the charges in his statement. there is nothing new there.''
yasser arafat, chairman of the palestine liberation organization, says the u.s. closing of the plo's observer mission at the united nations would negatively affect american credibility and u.s. interests
arafat, in an hour-long boston globe interview published today, also said the first casualty of the decision by the u.s. congress and the reagan administration to close the mission will be secretary of state george p. shultz's middle east peace plan
arafat, speaking mostly in english, said in the interview sunday that ouster of the plo from the united nations is against international law. he also said it will teach every nation that they ``may face the same treatment if they have a difference of opinion between their country and the american administration.''
the plo leader, wearing a military-style uniform and a winter hat, is in algeria for a two-day meeting with president chadli bendjedid, the newspaper said
the interview came one day before israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir was arriving in washington on a four-day visit. shultz was hoping shamir would agree to attend an international conference to arrange self-rule for palestinian arabs on the west bank and gaza and then an overall settlement
however, shamir was quoted last week as saying the u.s. proposal was ``fraught with danger'' and incapable of bringing peace to the region
the only word i agree with in the u.s. plan is the name shultz,'' shamir said, according to an account friday in the israeli daily newspaper haaretz
arafat said in the interview that shamir was ``giving this hard line because he wants a high price from the american administration'' (and) ``the first item on the list has been offered already,'' referring to the closing of the plo mission
arafat predicted that israel next will demand more weapons, more financial help and ``who knows, more agreements'' before conceding to talk about peace
arafat said he and bendjedid were discussing the algerian leader's call for a summit meeting of arab nations on the middle east peace issue. arafat said he expects the conference to be held the first week in april
asked about palestinian resistance to israel's occupation of the west bank and the gaza strip, arafat said, ``this is one of the most important positive signals in the palestinian revolution. grandfather, father, grandson _ all of them are in a revolution, and we are proud of them.''
here are some quotes from presidential candidates on sunday:

paul simon, on his lack of money for political advertising as some polls show him slipping before tuesday's primary in his home state: ``obviously, not to have paid media hampers me in illinois.''
bob dole, on george bush: ``i'd like george bush to tell us whether (panamanian gen. manuel) noriega was on his payroll when he was cia director.''
michael dukakis, on the prospect of a brokered convention: ``i can't imagine anything worse _ the idea of taking the right of the people to elect their president with their votes and putting it in some backrooms in atlanta.''
jesse jackson, on george bush as chairman of the presidential task force on drugs: ``to that continuous flow of drugs, mrs. reagan says no and george bush says nothing.''
albert gore, on the guilty plea by former white house national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane to misdemeanor charges relating to iran-contra: the reagan-bush administration violated the law in a brazen way.''
richard gephardt, whose campaign is faltering after a poor super tuesday showing: ``they say underdogs do well in michigan and in the united states. i think i'm going to win in michigan
george bush, on the democrats: ``i can't wait to debate any one of those democrats on foreign policy. none of them have had any experience except when they had breakfast at the international house of pancakes.'' selling tickest for up to $300.</note>
frank sinatra, sammy davis jr. and dean martin opened their 29-city ``rat pack'' reunion tour to a sell-out crowd of 14,500, proving they can still doo-be-doo-be-do it with the best
how long have i been on?'' a staggering martin asked the bandleader as the 35-piece orchestra warmed up for the first number, ``when you're drinking,'' a parody of the old ``when you're smiling.''
martin's cocktail lounge manner and slurred one-liners, with trademark cigarette and drink in hand, set the tone for an evening that brought young and old fans to their feet
sunday night's oakland coliseum show was the first of 40 performances on the tour, which is expected to generate $20 million and a home box office cable television special
martin, 70, davis, 62, and sinatra, 72, first appeared together at the sands hotel in las vegas, nev., in january 1960
martin joked his way through sometimes sentimental versions of ``everybody loves somebody (sometime),'' ``that's amore,'' and ``little ole wine drinker me.''
davis provided a powerful contrast to his seemingly sloshed co-star, winning applause when he announced that this is his 59th year in show business and when he told the audience he had been sober for the last three
i gotta tell you the truth. everybody backstage is being very cool,'' he said. ``i wasn't this scared when i lived at 147th street and 8th avenue in new york.''
davis, who recently underwent hip surgery, did not dance but won ovations for ``candy man,'' ``what kind of fool am i?,'' and ``bojangles.''
but it was sinatra who stole the show, opening the second half with a string of the songs that have kept him in superstar ranks for almost a half century
sinatra fans, young and old, went wild as ``old blue eyes'' belted out such favorites as ``what now my love?'' ``maybe this time,'' ``for once in my life,'' ``mack the knife'' and ``new york, new york.''
sinatra was then rejoined by martin and davis, who told sinatra, ``as far as we're concerned, and i can say this for the two of us, you're still the chairman of the board.''
yeah,'' quipped martin. ``you're still the chairman and we're still bored.''
the fans weren't bored, though
i saw frank 15 years ago in vegas and he's better than he's ever been,'' said karen chaix, 38, of alameda. her husband, dan, added, ``i'm sorry we didn't buy tickets for our parents.''
maureen pobuta, 33, of san mateo, said she went through ``heck'' to get her tickets, which sold officially for as much as $40 but were being scalped for up to $300. ``i've loved dean martin and sammy davis jr. ... i thought they looked great. for me, this is a once-in-a-lifetime thing.''
i've been buying their albums since i was a teeny-booper _ since the 40s,'' said tina mendez, who added ``there was no way'' she would have missed the rat pack performance. ``i will not drive without sinatra in the tape player.''
the ``rat pack'' moniker, from humphrey bogart, was given to davis, sinatra, martin, the late peter lawford and other performers who lived in the same area of beverly hills nearly three decades ago
the tour was born when the three longtime friends were gathered at sinatra's house, and became a reality because they are all under contract to the entertainment and casino company bally corp
the three are among a growing number of aging superstars to rekindle their acts. danny thomas, milton berle and sid caeser recently made a television movie, ``side by side.'' rodney dangerfield, jackie mason and mort sahl have all been contracted for one-man shows
the ``together again'' tour continues in vancouver, b.c., on tuesday, seattle on wednesday, and chicago on friday and saturday
later stops include minneapolis, milwaukee, detroit, pittsburgh, cleveland, cincinnati, washington, d.c., providence, r.i., phoenix, ariz., houston, dallas, new orleans, miami, atlanta, philadelphia, secaucus, n.j., uniondale, n.y., boston, richmond, va., buffalo, n.y., st. louis, kansas city, denver, plus cities in southern california
admirers of clarence darrow marked the 50th anniversary of the death of ``the attorney of the damned'' by tossing a wreath into the lagoon where his ashes are scattered and pledging to live by his example
about 100 people huddled together against the snow sunday on a bridge in a park on chicago's south side
darrow, a skeptic on matters of religion and the afterlife, said if there was anything to the spiritual world, he would return at 10 in the morning on each anniversary of his death, according to leon despres, a former alderman of the 5th ward, where darrow lived
for years after darrow's death, magicians and spiritualists gathered at the bridge to conjure up the lawyer's spirit _ but year after year they went away disappointed
those gathered at the bridge departed with a renewed sense of commitment to the ideals darrow stood for: justice and equality
for those of you who question life after death ... clarence is here in spirit today as we commit ourselves to follow the example of his life,'' said u.s. district judge prentice marshall
about a dozen attorneys, politicians, judges and ministers addressed the crowd in jackson park, a few blocks from darrow's home
in his 50 years as a lawyer, darrow defended ``the preconvicted, the powerless, those damned before they had a chance to have a fair trial,'' said herb kraus, a co-chairman of the clarence darrow commemorative committee
one of darrow's most famous clients was tennessee teacher john t. scopes, whom he aided in 1925 in what became known as the ``monkey trial.'' darrow, representing the american civil liberties union, defended the right for evolution to be taught in tennessee schools. though scopes was found guilty, his conviction was later reversed on a technicality
darrow also gained fame during the 1924 chicago murder case of nathan leopold and richard loeb, millionaires' sons accused of the thrill killing of 14-year-old bobby franks. darrow persuaded them to plead guilty and saved them from death sentences
darrow, who was born in kinsman, ohio, but spent most of his legal career in chicago, was one of the first to be called a labor lawyer
he resigned as the attorney for the chicago and northwestern railroad to represent labor's side of an 1893 railroad strike led by eugene debs
for the past 31 years, the commemorative committee has marked darrow's death on march 13, 1938, by throwing a wreath into the lagoon under the darrow bridge
darrow was and is a folk hero,'' said arthur weinberg, who recently published a biography on the lawyer. ``he was always a defender of the damned and a defender of the unpopular.''
a disagreement among supporters of jesse jackson has split the democrat's presidential campaign effort in northern indiana
jackson now has two campaign headquarters, both located in the same block of the same downtown street in gary. and although the campaign workers in each office are working toward the same goal _ the election of jackson in the may 3 primary _ they are functioning under different local campaign directors
the dispute boiled over late last week when jackson's state coordinator, the rev. thomas robinson of anderson, appointed the rev. f. brannan jackson of gary as campaign coordinator for northern indiana
robinson said he made the appointment because the man named by jackson's national campaign office to head the northern indiana effort, carlos tolliver of gary, had refused to communicate with robinson and could not reach out to other elected officials and voters
i did not appoint him and i am not going to unappoint him. but i'm appointing someone to get some things done,'' robinson said, adding that tolliver no longer spoke for the local campaign
however, tolliver insists that robinson has acted beyond his authority, and claims that he is the only authorized jackson representative in gary
top officials of the jackson campaign's national and state offices confirm that tolliver is the authorized head of the campaign in the 1st congressional district
president reagan has labeled federal funding for a planned biotechnology research park in central massachusetts that gov. michael s. dukakis often points to while campaigning for president a prime example of waste
reagan listed the $100,000 for the worcester, mass., project among $1.15 billion in ``pork'' he would have cut out if allowed to single-out projects from last year's massive congressional spending package
but dukakis aides defended the center, which is part of the governor's ``centers of excellence'' program designed to develop technologies of the future like photovoltaics, polymers and biotechnology
the centers of excellence program is another example of an innovative experiment hatched at the state level,'' said dukakis campaign spokesman steve akey. ``for too long washington has turned its back on these innovative approaches.''
in his campaign speeches dukakis has praised the state-supported centers as places where ``the best minds of industry, government and academia are coming together to chart the frontiers of science and technology and spawn new industries and new opportunities for good jobs and economic growth.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis has picked up an endorsement from a top labor figure
douglas fraser, former president of the united auto workers union, said sunday in his announcement that dukakis is the democrats' best hope for winning the november election
dukakis, who was taking the day off from campaigning, said the endorsement will give him momentum heading into the michigan democratic caucuses march 26
his (fraser's) endorsement will give a tremendous boost to my campaign. i think it shows that our campaign is truly a national campaign,'' dukakis said
on saturday, dukakis, the rev. jesse jackson and u.s. rep. richard gephardt made stops in michigan, meeting with plant workers, chatting with the chairman of the party's platform committee, taking a train ride and raising some money
the state department has quietly disbanded the group it set up more than two years ago to sell the reagan administration's widely criticized policy towards south africa
william ``jake`` jacobsen, the most recent director of the working group on south and southern africa, said the office effectively closed at the end of 1987
the decision not to continue the office resulted in part because south africa has waned as an issue attracting daily headlines in the united states, jacobsen said
by 1987 there were other issues,'' he said. ``there was the (persian) gulf, the middle east in general, the controversy involving iran,'' he said
the office, which at one point had a staff of about 20, was created in late 1985 as the administration pursued its policy of ``constructive engagement,'' _ attempting to pressure the white government in pretoria into eliminating racial segregation through diplomacy rather than sanctions
but congress _ against the administration's will _ approved sanctions in 1986, thereby undercutting ``constructive engagement.''
house members are preparing to consider a measure later this month that would impose a full economic embargo on south africa
jacobsen said the working group did a good job explaining the department's south africa policy. ``we got out the message ... people were much better informed in 1987 than in 1985.''
when the group was set up, it was never intended to be a permanent fixture, he said
he said the working group's staff traveled to over 45 states and gave more than 1,000 speeches to civic and business groups and met with reporters and editors from television stations and newspapers
the group was modeled after the department's office of public diplomacy for latin american and the caribbean. that operation was also shut down
irish eyes were smiling a bit more than usual as the city's marching hibernians celebrated st. patrick's day with a inside-joke
dressed in kilts and playing bagpipes, the irish pipers started off the annual parade sunday with a lively tune: ``scotland the brave.''
we do it to fool the guys who think we're scottish,'' said piper john flynn, who marched in a green jacket and gold kilt at the front of the parade
some spectators asked why bagpipes appeared at the irish celebration. piper, patrick o'shea, explained the irish war pipes are an old tradition
unlike the scots, the irish were kept from playing the pipes before most of ireland was freed from british rule, said o'shea, who has played the pipes for 45 years
winter lingered with below-normal temperatures covering most of the nation early today, and snow was predicted in many sections even though spring's only a week away
at 1 a.m. est, freezing temperatures were reported as far south as san angelo, texas, and in fort smith, ark., and crossville, tenn. late-night temperatures were mostly in the single digits and teens from wyoming and colorado across the northern and central plains to the upper great lakes region
snow showers, mostly light, extended sunday night from the upper and middle mississippi valley across the great lakes region and northern sections of the ohio valley to the northern and central appalachians. heavier snow was falling along the shores of lake superior and lake erie
a heavy snow warning was posted through today in northeast ohio. three to 4 inches fell sunday evening at thompson, ohio. an advisory for 1 to 3 inches of snow was in effect this morning over northwest pennsylvania
four inches of new snow fell sunday night near marquette, mich
heavy snow was forecast today over the northern rockies. winter storm watches were posted for this afternoon and tonight over western and central montana and northwest wyoming. up to a foot of snow was possible by tuesday morning in the mountains of montana and wyoming
rain showers fell in southern florida, where a downpour dumped more than an inch of rain on west palm beach in an hour early today
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 4 below zero at bismarck, n.d., to 76 at key west naval air station and fort myers regional airport, fla
the nation's high sunday was 87 degrees at fort lauderdale, north miami beach and west palm beach, fla
for today, snow showers were forecast from the great lakes region and the ohio valley across the northern and central appalachians; rain or snow showers over southern new england; and snowshowers across montana. sunny skies were expected over the nation's southern third, but with scattered showers and thunderstorms in south florida
much of the nation was expected to have highs in the 30s-50s. below-normal temperatures were forecast from the rockies to the atlantic, with highs only in the upper teens and 20s from the dakotas across the upper half of the mississippi valley, the great lakes region and the ohio valley. highs should reach the 60s and 70s over western oregon, california, southwest nevada, southern arizona, southern texas and the florida peninsula, with readings near 80 over parts of the desert southwest and south florida
