religious leaders who were barred from holding an anti-apartheid rally led more than 2,000 people in a defiant church service at a cathedral that was surrounded by police vehicles
the government of south africa has signed its own death warrant,'' said the rev. allan boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches. ``no government can challenge the living god and survive.''
boesak's speech electrified a multiracial crowd at the sunday service and was punctuated by shouts of ``amandla!'' the zulu word for ``power.''
anglican archbishop desmond tutu, winner of the nobel peace prize in 1984 for his fight against south africa's system of racial separation, also spoke to the worshipers who packed the aisles of st. george's anglican cathedral
organizers said many people trying to go to the service were turned back at police roadblocks on highways leading to central cape town
the church service was arranged after police prohibited a rally that had been planned at the nearby university of the western cape
police also banned the 5-day-old committee, whose members included tutu and boesak, that was sponsoring the rally
the cape town service and others in major cities were called to protest government restrictions on opposition groups and the detention of thousands of people without charge during a 21-month national state of emergency
law and order minister adriaan vlok on sunday warned the white-led government would ``take the necessary steps'' against clergymen who took up the cause of 18 black opposition groups banned in a crackdown last month
if teaching the gospel of jesus christ is going to lead me into trouble, tough luck,'' responded tutu
referring to vlok's warning that clergymen should preach the ``true christian message rather than revolution,'' boesak said:
if you had read the bible you would not have spoken such utter nonsense. ... the fight for justice is the christian message.''
in another development, tutu wrote an article in today's editions of the new york times calling on the united states, england and west germany to cut diplomatic ties with south africa unless it meets three demands
first, the state of emergency must be lifted,'' he wrote. ``second, last month's restrictions against our peoples' organizations and leaders must be lifted. third, detainees ... must be tried in open courts or released.''
boesak, who reported receiving two death threats in the past two weeks, told worshipers sunday, ``it does not matter whether they ban us, threaten us, or kill us in jail _ the church of south africa has decided we have work to do
we must tell (president) p.w. botha, `your days are over,' '' he said
tutu told the service, ``if it is revolution to say, `i work for a south africa that is truly democratic, where black, white and yellow and green can walk together hand in hand,' then friends, i am for that.'' conference at 11:30 a.m. est, governor may comment after 1 p.m. est.</note>
the university of minnesota's president has resigned, citing controversy over the $1.5 million renovation of his official residence, eastcliff, and the $200,000 remodeling of his campus office suite
over the past few weeks, you and i have lived with stories about eastcliff renovations and repairs,'' kenneth keller, president for three years, told a news conference sunday night at the 55,000-student big 10 school
the stories have not been good ones,'' he said. ``i bear a key responsibility for it. ... i am profoundly embarrassed and profoundly sorry for it.''
after repeated assertions recently that he planned to stay in office, keller, 53, said he now believes he cannot overcome the controversy. he said he was informing the university's board of regents he would step aside as soon as they arrange for an interim replacement
the regents never gave formal approval for the mansion renovation, which was orginally supposed to cost $400,000, a recent report by the legislative auditor's office said
the report said the involvement of keller and his wife, university attorney bonita sindelir, in the renovation led to some of the additional costs
among the most embarrassing expenditures were those for a mahogany desk and credenza for keller's office that the legislative auditor said cost $17,445. keller has offered to pay for the office furniture
i have said recently that i thought i could learn from the mistakes of eastcliff, improve the management of the university where it's needed, and get on with the important job of completing `commitment to focus,''' keller told the news conference sunday night
commitment to focus'' is keller's controversial $35.2 million plan to improve the quality of the university while reducing undergraduate enrollment
i have also said that if i felt my presence would hurt more than help in accomplishing that task i would step aside,'' he said, adding, ``as painful as it is for me to say, i now believe that to be the case.''
after he read a brief statement, keller left without responding to questions
regent chairman david lebedoff and gov. rudy perpich were expected to comment on keller's announcement today, spokesmen said sunday night
the st. paul pioneer press dispatch, quoting sources it did not name in today's editions, said perpich and keller met privately sunday for about 90 minutes and that perpich had indicated before the meeting that he was prepared to ask keller to step down
perpich spokeswoman patrice vick would confirm only that a meeting occurred
according to the newspaper's sources, perpich was highly irritated when he learned last week that the university had amassed a reserve fund of more than $50 million
keller's critics in the legislature called it a ``slush fund.''
legislative auditors who revealed the existence of the $50 million fund said it was under the control of keller and other top university officials and that some of the money was used on the house renovation without approval of the board of regents
spending on the mansion was revealed in news media reports in early february. keller then went to hawaii on a vacation, angering lawmakers who thought he should have stayed available to answer questions about the remodeling
keller, a new york city native, came to the university in 1964 as an assistant professor in chemical engineering and materials science, and became a department head in 1979. northeastern iran, iranian shelling of southern iraq. trims. no pickup.</note>
iran and iraq fired long-range missiles into each other's capitals today as the so-called ``war of the cities'' flared again after a two-day lull. iran said at least 20 people were killed in tehran
on the battlefield, iran said it attacked mountainous northeast iraq and downed an iraqi warplane. iraq said iran continued shelling border towns
iran's official islamic republic news agency said six rockets exploded in residential areas of tehran today, killing at least 20 people and injuring 50
iran said it fired two missiles today into ``the dens of corruption'' in baghdad. the news agency, monitored in nicosia, said the missiles were aimed at ``military and economic centers'' in baghdad
baghdad radio, also monitored in nicosia, said one iranian missile crashed into a residential district of the city of 5 million around noon, killing some civilians. it gave no figures and made no mention of a second iranian missile
the iranian missile hit as oil and energy ministers from 20 arab countries gathered in the capital of baghdad for the opening of a four-day meeting on improving cooperation in energy and mineral resources. it was not known how far from the conference hall the missile exploded
the iraqis say they have shot seven missiles into tehran since sunday to avenge iranian shelling of iraqi towns over the weekend that killed at least 21 people and wounded 79
the official iraqi news agency said iranian shellfire continued to hit the southern port city of basra, the nearby city of qurnah and the northern city of halbajah today. it reported ``many civilians,'' including women and children, killed or wounded in a barrage that hit schools, houses and stores
iran's islamic republic news agency said revolutionary guards launched a new assault in the northeastern sulaimaniyeh region of iraq early today ``to avenge enemy missile attacks on residential areas.''
quoting a military communique, the agency said the iranians stormed iraqi positions despite bad weather, inflicting ``heavy casualties'' and capturing several peaks in the gerdhelkan range
irna said iranian anti-aircraft gunners shot down an iraqi warplane during the fighting as it attempted to strafe iranian positions
it was the third iranian assault in northeast iraq reported in 24 hours
irna reported earlier that more than 800 iraqis were killed or wounded in attacks in the darbandikhan and khormal regions on sunday when its forces seized 15 square miles of iraqi territory and 12 ``strategic heights'' in the sulaimaniyeh area, 160 miles north of baghdad
the iraqi news agency quoted a military communique as saying iraqi warplanes flew 141 combat missions against iranian troop concentrations and other military targets sunday. it said helicopter gunships flew 85 missions
baghdad radio reported today that an iraqi naval force sank a ``large maritime target along with its occupants'' near the iranian coast on sunday night. it gave no other details
sunday's missile attacks ended an unofficial two-day truce in the war of the cities. hundreds of civilians were killed in tehran, baghdad and other cities in both countries during a 12-day missile duel that had ended friday. tehran is 290 miles from the border, while baghdad is 85 miles away
an air france jumbo jet made an unscheduled landing at the u.s. air base at thule in northern greenland because of a bomb threat, greenland's military command said today
the boeing 747 en route to tokyo landed at thule late sunday night after the paris headquarters of the french national carrier received an anonymous telephone threat saying there was a bomb on board
the 396 passengers were evacuated without incident and given shelter in the base's movie theater
after a four-hour search of the airliner and all the baggage, it was allowed to resume its flight via anchorage, alaska
the death toll from a cyclone earlier this month in mozambique has risen to 100, the national news agency aim reported today
cyclone filao struck march 1 and damaged large parts of the port city of quelimane and surrounding rural areas in zambezia province
the news agency last week reported the cyclone had killed 57 people. it said today the toll rose as more information was received from remote areas
the cyclone destroyed 1,000 homes, leaving an estimated 4,500 people homeless, aim said
a man who embezzled $350,000 from a fertilizer factory in eastern china was executed, an official daily said today
the overseas edition of the people's daily said jiang zhengguo, chief of the finance section of the wujin chemical fertilizer factory in changzhou city, was executed sunday after an court rejected his appeal
the report said jiang embezzled the money from march 1983 to april 1987 by listing false construction expenditures and forging receipts. he was sentenced to death by a lower court last november
the chinese government in january announced tough new rules for punishing economic crimes of corruption and bribery. the rules stated that those who gain more than $13,500 through corruption should be given prison terms of not less than 10 years, and serious offenders should be sentenced to death
there have been at least four reported cases this year of embezzlers being executed, usually by a bullet to the back of the head
high-level talks began today between the united states and south africa on a plan to end fighting in angola and namibia, officials said
the talks between u.s. assistant secretary of state chester crocker and south african foreign minister roelof ``pik'' botha are open-ended and no details will be released until they end, said mari botha, botha's press secretary. it is the first meeting between the leaders in two years
state department spokeswoman anita stockman said saturday in washington that the crocker-botha meeting will provide an opportunity ``to reassess south africa's willingness to proceed toward a settlement involving total cuban troop withdrawal from angola and namibian independence.''
ms. stockman also said the meeting would give the united states a chance to ``register concern'' about recent developments in south africa
the united states has complained about anti-dissent measures in south africa in the past few weeks
she said a state department working group arrived in angola on wednesday to explore the possibility of further talks on getting the estimated 40,000 cuban troops out of the country as part of an overall settlement
on sunday, angola's foreign ministry said angola and cuba presented proposals to the u.s. officials for a southern africa peace accord including a timetable for the withdrawal of cuban troops from southern angola, and an eventual full pullout
since he took office in 1981, crocker has tried to negotiate a withdrawal of cuban troops from angola in return for south african withdrawal from neighboring south-west africa, also known as namibia
the cuban troops have been battling a powerful guerrilla force, the national union for the total independence of angola, or unita. the guerrillas are supported by south africa and the united states
on sunday, unita leader jonas savimbi said south africa has told him it will begin direct talks with the angolan government in a bid to end angola's 13-year-old civil war. he gave no indication when such talks would begin
tens of thousands of skiers remained trapped in three alpine ski resorts today after avalanches killed 10 people and injured at least 20 over the weekend
it was the worst winter-sport death toll for a single weekend in austria in decades
roads to the famed resorts of lech, zuers and stuben were snowed in for a third straight day, and high winds prevented helicopters from reaching the three high-altitude towns
among those stranded in lech were the former dutch queen, princess juliana, and her husband prince bernhard
they were supposed to leave on saturday, but have been stuck here since then,'' said a receptionist reached by telephone at the hotel post, where the dutch royalty were staying
but they are enjoying the winter sports and taking it all with good humor like everyone else here,'' she said, speaking on condition of anonymity
officials said thousands of the skiers, most of them vacationing west germans and scandanavians, could remain stranded until tuesday because of the heavy snows and continued danger of avalanches
it is possible roads will be opened this afternoon, but it is too early to tell,'' eric brumer, a local official, told austrian radio
but it is too early to tell whether the danger (of avalanches) will drop enough,'' he added
the road to st. anton was reopened today after seven people were killed and at least 20 injured in the resort town on sunday
five vacationing swedish skiers and two austrians were killed in st. anton early sunday when two successive avalanches rolled down the steep mountains that tower above the resort and buried several chalets, authorities said
three others were killed in separate avalanches on saturday, bringing austria's weekend winter-sport death toll to 10
the accidents followed the death last weekend of a close friend of britain's prince charles, who was killed in the swiss resort of klosters by a snowslide that narrowly missed charles
the avalanches destroyed four houses, damaged several other buildings and buried the only train tracks leading into the mountainous resort
innsbruck police said authorities would not release the names of victims until their next of kin had been notified
the exact number of those injured in the incident was not clear, but several people were taken by helicopter to hospitals in innsbruck and nearby zams, according to a police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
police said the single road that connects st. anton to the outside world remained closed, but that the train traffic to the resort had been resumed
st. anton, set at 4,118 feet in the arlberg region of western austria, is one of this alpine nation's oldest and best-known ski resorts
scattered shootouts and a bombing left four people dead and eight wounded in beirut, police said today
police identified the slain as two officers from the lebanese forces, the christians' main militia, an officer of druse warlord walid jumblatt's progressive socialist party militia and a palestinian guerrilla
in the latest violence, a shiite moslem attorney was critically wounded today when a time bomb exploded on a window ledge outside the bathroom of his west beirut apartment as he was shaving, police said
nimeh hamieh, a former chairman of lebanon's bar association, was rushed to the barbir hospital by neighbors, police said. they declined to speculate on the motive for the assassination attempt
the two lebanese forces officers were killed sunday by bodyguards of president amin gemayel's 18-year-old son, pierre, in a quarrel in a traffic-jammed street in the christian port of jounieh, 12 miles north of beirut, police said
police said the shooting sharpened tension between the lebanese forces and gemayel's rightist phalange party militia, which controls the metn province in the christian heartland northeast of beirut
the two sides have been vying for dominance of the christian community, whose control of the government, army and parliament triggered the civil war with lebanon's moslem majority that began in 1975
the druse militia officer was killed sunday evening in an ambush by militiamen of justice minister nabih berri's shiite amal movement in the rashaya district in the foothills of mount hermon in south lebanon, police said. they said the druse officer's escorts fired at the ambushers, wounding two of them before syrian troops drove up to stop the shooting
police said a palestinian guerrilla from a syrian-backed group was killed and another wounded in a midnight shootout sunday with supporters of palestine liberation organization chairman yasser arafat in the bourj el-barajneh refugee camp in south beirut
three lebanese army soldiers and a woman were shot and wounded by a drunken gunman sunday as they were lunching at a seaside restaurant in the christian town of halat, 25 miles north of beirut, police said
the syrians maintain 25,000 troops in north and east lebanon under a 1976 arab league peacekeeping mandate
they also have a 7,500-strong force in moslem west beirut seeking to restore law and order after years of militia anarchy
the thieves will celebrate, traffic violators will celebrate, that's what it means.'' _ israeli police minister chaim bar-lev, commenting on the protest resignations of 450 of the 850 arab police officers in the west bank and gaza
god made the world in seven days and we have changed it in seven days.'' _charles a. giansanti, a gallaudet university chemistry professor, on the protests that prompted the appointment of the school for the hearing impaired's first deaf president
the only word i agree with in the u.s. plan is the name shultz.'' _ israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, commenting on the u.s. peace proposal for the middle east
a moderate earthquake shook the soviet republic of kirgizia, the official news agency tass said. it was the third temblor in central asia in less than a month
no injuries were reported in the quake sunday, but older buildings near the epicenter in the kochkork area sustained slight damage, tass said
the earthquake registered 5 points on the soviet scale at its center and 2 points in the republic's capital of frunze, 200 miles northeast of the area hit 12 days ago and 450 miles northeast of the area jolted 24 days ago
on the 12-point soviet scale, a 5-point earthquake is considered capable of shaking buildings, furniture and cracking windows and plaster
the march 2 quake measured 5.5 near its center in the namagan region of uzbekistan, kirgizia's neighboring republic to the southwest. the feb. 20 quake was centered 100 miles east of dushanbe, the capital of tadzhikistan, which borders kirgizia to the south. neither of the earlier quakes caused damage or injuries, according to tass
kirgizia has a population of 3.2 million and is bounded to the east by china. belgrade, changes dateline. pickup 3rd graf pvs ``gorbachev is...'' adds byline.</note>
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev today began a five-day official visit to yugoslavia, a communist nation suffering from high inflation and unemployment and a $20 billion foreign debt
the soviet communist party general secretary, accompanied by his wife, raisa, landed in belgrade in a special aeroflot ilyushin jet that flew directly from moscow
yugoslavia's top party and government leaders were on hand at the airport to greet the gorbachevs
gorbachev is the first soviet leader to visit yugoslavia since the may, 1980 death of josip broz tito, who pulled his nation out of the soviet bloc in 1948 to pursue a non-aligned foreign policy and a once-vaunted system of worker self-management in the economy
that system looks increasingly frail as yugoslavia battles 170 percent inflation and 15 percent unemployment and struggles to repay its foreign debt
last year, yugoslavia's communist leadership faced unprecedented worker unrest, with more than 1,500 strikes adding to the traditional problems of keeping this ethnically diverse nation together
the system of self-management by which workers nominally run yugoslavia's enterprises will be one topic on gorbachev's agenda at meetings today with belgrade's communist leaders, assistant foreign minister ilija djukic of yugoslavia told reporters in belgrade on sunday
asked whether the yugoslavs would discuss recent ethnic tension in the soviet union with gorbachev, djukic said this was moscow's internal affair ``and we shall certainly leave that to their own resources.''
he added, however, that gorbachev would have an opportunity to see for himself how yugoslavia, a diverse nation of six republics and two autonomous regions, deals with ethnic, linguistic and economic differences
gorbachev's drive for more openness on social problems and economic reform in the soviet union has been called into question recently by mass demonstrations by armenians in the southern soviet union
at least 32 people died when ethnic tension between the largely christian armenians and their moslem neighbors, the azeris, boiled over into fighting in the azerbaijan city of sumgait two weeks ago
gorbachev will not be visiting kosovo, the yugoslav region most plagued by ethnic tension between ethnic albanians, and serbian and montenegrin minorities. but he will get a look at the economic diversity of yugoslavia, visiting factories in the relatively flourishing northernmost republic of slovenia and the adriatic port of dubrovnik as well as in belgrade
the visit to slovenia may also give gorbachev a look at the way his country could develop if the kremlin leader's three-year drive for more democracy under communism gains further impetus
slovenia has the most liberal newspapers of yugoslavia's free-wheeling, state-controlled press, and young people there have emulated west european counterparts in pushing strongly for greater ecological concern, a ban on nuclear power and an end to compulsory military conscription
a windshield-washer was in critical condition today after a motorist who did not want his windshield washed cracked the man over the head with a baseball bat
police spokesman sgt. maurice howard said 47-year-old eldred leitzse of the bronx started to wash the windshield on a light green mercedes stopped at the light at about 7 p.m. last night
the driver of the car, one of three men in the car, apparently did not ask for the wash and did not want it, howard said. he stepped from the car and hit leitzse over the head with a bat, howard says
windshield-washers in new york often are poor people who approach cars at stoplights and offer to wash their windows for a small tip. occasionally the washers refuse to stop unless paid
harlem hospital administrator edward titus said leitzse was in critical but stable condition this morning
no one has been arrested and no other details were immediately available
a texas woman who was locked in a custody dispute with her former husband hired a team of retired u.s. army commandos to get her daughter back from jordan, according to a published report
kathy mahoon of dallas was given custody of the girl by a u.s. court when she and her jordanian husband divorced, the philadelphia inquirer said saturday. the husband abducted the girl, lauren mohammed ali bayan, and took her to jordan, the newspaper said
ms. mahoon, unable to get her daughter back through legal channnels, hired a firm of former army commandos to take the girl away from her father, mohammed ali bayan, the newspaper said. bayan claimed legal custody of the child under jordanian law
corporate training unlimited, a firm in fayetteville, n.c., specializing in ``hostage rescue training,'' plotted and carried out the seizure for expenses and a hefty, undisclosed fee, the newspaper said
although company president donald feeney denied the story, other well-placed sources described the company's role, the inquirer said
ms. mahoon now is in hiding with her 7-year-old daughter, while the state department is fielding protests from jordan about americans' role in the dispute, the newspaper said
the rescue attempt began at 8:30 a.m. jan. 28 in jerash, north of amman, sources close to the participants told the newspaper. the abduction began when j.d. roberts, a one-time army delta force hostage rescue specialist, hailed and stopped a school bus by waving a note in arabic
while roberts pinned the shocked driver to his seat, ms. mahoon embraced her child and swept her off the bus, smacking a teacher who tried to block their escape. they fled in a white datsun and switched cars before crossing the border into israeli-controlled territory, the newspaper said
when his daughter first disappeared, bayan said she had been abducted by three americans and published newspaper advertisements seeking information
sameer salem, a jordanian friend of bayan's, told the associated press that bayan had returned to jordan in the fall of 1987 after selling a dallas restaurant called the country skillet. bayan had legal custody of lauren under jordanian law, salem said
the raid embarrassed the u.s. embassy because embassy officials knew about the operation but did not alert jordanian authorities, the inquirer reported
jordanian authorities reached by the ap said the girl left jordan legally because she had an american passport. jerash police accused some u.s. embassy officials of taking part in the operation, but police in amman denied the abduction incident took place
no state department press official was available sunday to comment on the report. there was no listing for corporate training unlimited in fayetteville, and no listing for mahoon in dallas
according to a brochure obtained by the inquirer, corporate training unlimited, consists entirely of ``delta force and special operations qualified personnel.''
its founders left the military in 1983 amid allegations that they had claimed expenses from both the state department and the army for guarding vips at u.s. embassies in central america, the newspaper said
state department investigators now want to know whether credentials issued to the company's founders while in the military were used in the jordanian incident, the newspaper said
the afghanistan peace talks resumed today, one day before a soviet-set target date for a settlement. there were unconfirmed reports pakistan was about to decide whether to sign an agreement with the soviet-backed kabul government
we will announce something today,'' pakistan's chief representative, acting foreign minister zain noorani, told reporters as he arrived for a new meeting with u.n. mediator diego cordovez. he did not elaborate
there was no confirmation of published reports quoting prime minister mohammad khan junejo of pakistan as saying his country will make a final decision today on whether to sign the proposed settlement
the head of the afghan delegation, foreign minister abdul wakil, was scheduled to meet cordovez today in keeping with the pattern of the talks held indirectly because pakistan does not recognize the kabul government
pakistan has been speaking for the guerrillas, which are excluded from the talks and do not formally recognize the u.n.-sponsored peace process
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev said last month that moscow would bring home its estimated 115,000 troops starting in mid-may if a settlement was signed march 15 _ tuesday
but sources close to the negotiations have said they do not consider the date a rigid deadline
soviet troops have been in afghanistan, helping the government fight moslem insurgents, since december 1979
noorani seemed to make plain today that he expected the talks to continue for at least several more days. he said he wanted to ask cordovez what the program would be ``for the next few days to finalize'' the peace package
they are a few points remaining'' before the settlement is ready for signature, he added. details have not been published
the latest round began march 2 and is already the longest since the negotiations began nearly 6 years ago
pakistan's negotiating position is jeopardized by a reported rift in the alliance of seven guerrilla groups over plans to send representatives to geneva if a transitional government will replace the existing one
pakistan argues that only a broad-based government can oversee implementation of the agreements and ensure the safe return of more than 5 million afghan refugees from pakistan and iran
the soviet union and kabul have fiercely rejected that demand, saying the future government was something to be decided by the afghans themselves and was not subject for discussion at geneva
mayor raymond l. flynn headed back to boston from ireland today to be with his sick mother, lillian flynn
flynn arrived in ireland on sunday for a planned week-long stay but was taking the first available flight back, said raymond dooley, city director of administrative services. flynn had planned to celebrate st. patrick's day in dublin
dooley said flynn's brother, dennis, telephoned the mayor in galway to tell him their mother's condition had worsened. dooley said mrs. flynn had been ill for a few months, but he declined to comment on the nature of her illness or her condition
mrs. flynn is in boston city hospital
singer dennis day remained hospitalized in critical condition today after injuring his head in a fall at his home last week, a hospital official said
no change was reported in day's condition during the weekend and he remained in critical and unstable condition today, said a nursing supervisor at st. john's hospital
day, 71, fell at his bel air-area home wednesday and complained of a severe headache in the emergency room. he underwent surgery after tests showed bleeding in the brain
day was diagnosed last july as suffering from amyotropic lateral sclerosis. the progressive nerve disorder, also known as lou gehrig's disease, causes a loss of muscle control
day, who was born eugene denis mcnulty in new york city, began his career with comedian jack benny in 1939. an accomplished irish tenor, day also was known for playing the innocent foil to benny's irascible character on television and radio
the bodies of three irish republican army members killed by british troops in gibraltar were headed to northern ireland today for funeral services and a possible st. patrick's day burial
families members and a roman catholic bishop called for calm at the funerals of the ira members, who british authorities linked to a planned car bombing
police on both sides of the border were expected to mount a huge security operation to prevent paramilitary displays beside the coffins during today's 100-mile journey by road to belfast, and at the funerals later this week
sinn fein, the legal political wing of the ira, said a chartered plane carrying the bodies of mairead farrell, 31, daniel mccann, 30, and sean savage, 24, was to fly today from gibraltar, the british fortress colony in southern spain, to dublin
the cortege was to travel directly from dublin airport to british-ruled northern ireland, police said
sinn fein said the ira members will be buried in belfast's milltown cemetery on wednesday or on saint patrick's day on thursday, when the funeral processions likely would be swollen by hundreds of sympathizers
st. patrick's day, honoring ireland's patron saint, is celebrated by catholics across the island
cahal daly, a roman catholic whose diocese includes belfast, said sunday he hoped both police and mourners will display ``a desire to avoid confrontation.''
in a statement, the families of the three dead men appealed to the security forces ``to permit us the dignity to bury our loved ones in peace.''
the three guerrillas were unarmed when they were shot and killed march 6 by soldiers believed to be members of the special air services, an elite british regiment
the shootings triggered rioting in catholic districts of belfast for much of last week, and provoked protests that the three should instead have been arrested. the british government said the soldiers believed their lives were endangered
two days after the shootings, spanish police discovered a car packed with 145 pounds of czech-made explosives in marbella, 30 miles from gibraltar. britain said the guerrillas intended to blow up the car during a military ceremony in the colony
the ira, outlawed in britain and ireland, is fighting to drive the british out of northern ireland and unite the protestant-dominated province with the catholic irish republic
since the political and sectarian violence erupted in northern ireland in 1969, at least 2,628 people have been killed
ira funerals have in recent years brought bloody clashes between nationalists and massed ranks of police seeking to prevent gunmen firing shots over the coffins, the ira's traditional salute to its dead. the practice is banned
a man who parachuted from a 50-story downtown building is a member of a group that requires such jumps, police said
the parachutist dropped onto a car a week ago and fled before police could collar him
but since then, he was traced through the license number of a getaway car and identified as a canadian, said police sgt. gerald rogers
the man, whose name rogers would not release, belongs to a group called building, antenna, span and earth club, or base. members are required to parachute from a building, antenna, a bridge and a cliff or mountain
they don't live long,'' said rogers. ``it seems utterly crazy that someone needs that much excitement in their life.''
he said it was much safer to parachute from an airplane than from a fixed object
the officer said police traced the license number of the jumper's getaway car to a south side chicago man, who admitted he helped in the escape. rogers also refused to identify the accomplice
rogers said he has not contacted the parachutist, who lives in quebec and is a truck driver. but his accomplice told police that the canadian wants to reimburse the owner of the bmw, musiliu alagbala of chicago, for the several hundred dollars worth of damage to the car, rogers said
alagbala said sunday he was amazed and angered by the incident
i've seen things like that in the movies, but i'd never thought it would happen to me,'' he said
if the parachutist returns to chicago, he may be charged with criminal trespass for being on the roof of the leo burnett building without permission, rogers said. the suspect also may be charged with criminal damages for the dents in the car, he said
we are not going to extradict him. if he doesn't come forward, ultimately we might put a warrant out on him,'' he said. 03-14 0644</first> failing to get on ballot. corrects number of mayoral elections in 10th graf to 1,008, sted 10,008. picks up 12th graf, `barco, in .. .'</note>
a young lawyer, who was once kidnapped because he campaigned against drugs, has been elected mayor of bogota in the first mayoral elections in colombia's history
security at the polls sunday was tight throughout this country racked by violence from extremist political factions and from powerful narcotics traffickers
one of the alleged leaders of colombia's biggest drug organization even tried to run for city council in the town of armenia
but carlos lehder rivas failed because colombian law demands that candidates sign up in person. lehder is in jail in jacksonville, fla., facing drug charges there and in miami
andres pastrana, 34, the son of former president misael pastrana, became bogota's mayor and will be one of the youngest men to take that important political post. several bogota mayors have gone on to become president
pastrana is a rising star in the conservative party, and his election represents a setback for president virgilio barco's governing liberal party
pastrana was the only conservative party candidate for mayor in bogota. the feuding liberal party put up three candidates
voters heeded barco's plea to fight bullets with ballots in the election, which was called as a concession to leftist guerrillas
for the past 169 years, the president, always from either the liberal or conservative parties, had appointed governors who in turn named mayors
there were 1,008 mayors elected sunday. colombians also elected city council, state assemblies and governing bodies for remote territories without sufficient population to become states
in the bogota race, juan caicedo, a former president of the colombian association of businessmen, came in second place. with about 50 percent of the vote in bogota counted, pastrana had 122,107 votes and caicedo had 94,322, the national elections office said in a news release sunday night
by late sunday night the elections office said the liberal party had won 405 of the mayoral races, the conservative party 379 and the leftist patriotic union 13. coalition candidates representing several parties had won 104 mayoral posts, the elctions office said
barco, in a speech televised nationwide saturday night, said voting would be a way to reject the wave of violence that has swept colombia
more than 1,700 people were killed in the past year in fighting between leftist guerrillas and government security forces and by right-wing death squads and drug traffickers
on sunday, soldiers and police guarded voting places and patrolled cities and towns. the campaign was one of the bloodiest ever in colombia, with leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads killing five mayoral candidates and 19 city council candidates. hundreds of other political activists were slain
leftist guerrillas kidnapped 14 mayors in the two weeks before the election. the rebels let them go after warning each to do more for the poor
pastrana, who called for stronger action against the multibillion-dollar cocaine and marijuana trafficking in colombia, was kidnapped by drug traffickers in january. a week later, police acting on a tip, raided a farmhouse where he was held. pastrana had not been harmed
colombian officials sometimes pay with their lives for challenging drug traffickers, who are among the wealthiest men in the nation
one group, the medillin cartel, is said to be responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the united states. lehder is charged in miami with being one of its leaders
in 1984, justice minister rodrigo lara bonilla was killed, and in january attorney general carlos mauro hoyos was gunned down. officials suspect drug traffickers in the deaths because both men fought narcotics. with 2nd execution skedded in louisiana; subs 6th graf pvs, ``darden said xxx, to clarify, note that execution skedded on 7 days notice; note language in 12th graf ``authorities say...'' lead prospects uncertain.</note>
convicted killer willie jasper darden again faces execution this week after outlasting six death warrants and becoming a symbol of the national conflict over capital punishment
his appeal was pending today at the florida supreme court in tallahassee in advance of a scheduled tuesday morning execution at the state prison here
gov. bob martinez, the only official outside the courts who could intervene, said last week he saw no reason to back off the death warrant he signed tuesday
meanwhile, in angola, la., wayne robert felde was scheduled to die shortly after midnight for the murder of a shreveport police officer 10 years ago
felde had claimed he was suffering from post-war stress syndrome as a result of his experiences in vietnam and asked for the death penalty at his trial, implying he would kill again. his lawyer, millard farmer, refused to say if an appeal was being pursued
darden maintained his innocence in an interview published sunday
if i'm executed tuesday, it won't change the facts one bit,'' he told the new york times. ``all that will happen is that i will be an innocent dead person instead of an innocent live person.''
darden said he's convinced his latest execution was scheduled with only seven days' notice ``to keep me from getting too much public attention
since january, i have received close to 2,000 letters from around the world,'' he said in the interview
soviet dissident andrei sakharov and the london-based human rights organization amnesty international are among those who have spoken out in support of darden
backers have said he has been on death row for 14 years because of a racist legal system that denied him a fair trial
but police in three florida counties consider him a suspect in at least five killings in addition to the 1973 death of james turman, for which darden received the death sentence. those cases remain unsolved and darden has never been charged in them
according to a report sunday in the tampa tribune, police in hillsborough, pinellas and polk counties say darden began his spree by beating a woman to death with his hands
authorities say he then strangled a woman with her stocking, battered a woman to death with a tire iron and finally shoot his victims in the face with a short-barreled .38-caliber revolver after they had been forced to perform oral sex on him
all the slayings police suspect darden of occurred in 1973 while he was on furlough from avon park correctional institution, where he was serving a six month to 20 year sentence for breaking into the home of a 70-year-old st. petersburg woman in 1968, beating her and attempting to rape her
the 54-year-old darden has outlasted more death warrants than any other florida inmate, and has been on florida's death row, the nation's largest, longer than all but one inmate
the dispute over his case centers on whether darden has an alibi as a result of statements from a minister and a woman placing him away from the scene of the turman killing. law enforcement authorities say evidence shows the killing occurred an hour too late for darden to have an alibi
in louisiana, felde was scheduled to die shortly after midnight cst
in 1978, after being picked up on a drunkeness charge, felde pulled a gun as he sat in the back seat of a police car and fired it into the back of the driver, police officer glen tompkins
as part of his defense, he claimed he was suffering from post war stress and exposure to agent orange. in his appeals he also claimed he had inadequate defense counsel during his trial
gov.-elect buddy roemer, who was to take office this afternoon, said he had no plans to stop the execution
hilton butler, warden of the state penitentiary at angola, said felde's sisters visited with him sunday and would be back at the death house today where the execution will take place
butler said that felde has asked for pizza, fried shrimp and ginger ale for his final meal
pro-iranian militants marking the third anniversary of a car bombing that killed more than 80 shiite moslems have threatened to launch new terrorist attacks against the united states
we should not forget that america is behind all the massacres and crimes,'' said sheik hassan nasrallah, a senior official of hezbollah, or party of god, at a mass rally in south beirut's bir el-abed district on sunday. excerpts of his speech were published by beirut newspapers today
we have war and we have terrorism to use against america to defend the interests of the moslems and the oppressed,'' nasrallah said. ``we are always ready to teach the wild beasts in the world a lesson.''
the iranian-backed hezbollah has accused the cia of masterminding the march 8, 1985, car bombing in bir el-abed with the help of the army's intelligence branch. it charged that the bombing was aimed at assassinating hezbollah's spiritual guide, sheik mohammed hussein fadlallah
hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella for underground extremists holding many of the 22 foreign hostages in lebanon, including nine americans. the longest held hostage is terry a. anderson, 38, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, who was kidnapped on march 16, 1985
fadlallah also spoke at sunday's rally, charging the device that went off near his residence was ``made in america.''
he declared: ``america, which accuses us of terrorism, is the master of terrorism throughout the universe.''
he vowed that guerrilla warfare against israel will be escalated
we consider our movement a supplement to the palestinian uprising in the occupied territories,'' fadlallah said, referring to three months of rioting by palestinians in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip
hezbollah leads the islamic resistence front, which has claimed responsibility for numerous attacks against israeli troops and their militia allies in israel's self-designated security zone in south lebanon
a robbery suspect who claimed he had aids and threatened to bite the first police officer that came near him was put into a patrol car alone and towed to a police station, a department spokesman said today
richard simmons was taken out of the patrol car by emergency medical service personel wearing protective gear, said sgt. maurice howard
simmons, 27, was taken to roosevelt hospital for psychiatric evaluation and was classified as emotionally disturbed, he said
the incident started sunday morning when simmons, dressed in a wig, makeup, a shirt and jeans, tried to rob a passer-by, the spokesman said
simmons took a small amount of money from the pocket of 19-year-old david murphy, howard said. murphy fought back and two police officers intervened, handcuffing simmons and putting him in the back of a patrol car
after he was in the car, simmons began ``cursing and kicking,'' howard said
he said he had aids, that he was going to die and that he would take them all with him,'' howard said. ``then he threatened to bite the first officer who came near him.''
police locked simmons inside the car and summoned a tow truck, howard said
simmons was charged with one count of attempted robbery
robin hood fans have put an end to a tourism brochure that says their hero and maid marian never met, good-natured little john was a grouch, and robin may have stolen from the rich just to line to his own pockets
i would like to see the authors of this brochure locked in the dungeons of nottingham castle,'' said the sheriff of nottingham, royce young, on sunday. legend says robin hood, the medieval bandit who supposedly stole from the rich to give to the poor, repeatedly outwitted young's ancient predecessor
howls of protest from robin hood fans and deflated tourism boosters led city officials to withdraw the glossy 45-cent brochure. it had been compliled by historians and published by the city council for distribution at a tourist information center
malcolm barker of the robin hood society, who took up the cudgels on the outlaw's behalf, charged: ``the city fathers have done a disservice to their own city.''
barker said he didn't claim that the story, as perpetuated by hollywood, was true. he said he simply objected to being robbed of a legend that also brings tourist riches to nottingham
the brochure took a skeptical academic line on the outlaw who, according to legend, lived in sherwood forest with his merry band of men in the 12th century. city council spokesman tim jones said the brochure put robin hood ``in historical context.''
the brochure said robin hood, in the earliest tales, was a highwayman who robbed travelers in neighboring yorkshire. he was in business strictly for himself
the brochure also says robin's true love, maid marian, was introduced into the legend through a 13th-century french poem, and robin's rotund lieutenant, friar tuck, was probably an amalgam of two characters from different parts of england
nottingham, a city of 290,000 in northern england, can hardly be accused of neglecting the legend. its main beltway is called maid marian way, and two rival consortiums are planning robin hood exhibition centers for the city
in addition, hordes of tourists annually visit the sherwood forest center, where they see displays of medieval lifestyles and gaze at the oak tree where the merry men may or may not have relaxed after a hard day's archery
speakers were heckled with shouts of ``nazi'' and ``traitor'' and shoving matches broke out as rival factions of american jews clashed during a rally to support a peace plan for israel's occupied territories
actor richard dreyfuss was escorted from sunday's roxbury park rally by police after hecklers shouted him down as he tried to speak in favor of a peaceful solution to clashes between israelis and palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip
other speakers included feminist betty friedan, yael dayan, daughter of the late israeli gen. moshe dayan, and several rabbis
despite a number of scuffles, police said there were no injuries or arrests
i was raised in the temple and the jewish community to see the difference between right and wrong,'' dreyfuss said as he tried to address the crowd of about 400, which included many immigrants from israel
if he would spill some of his blood like me and my brothers, then he would have a right to speak out like this,'' countered bobby frankel, a veteran of the 1956 sinai campaign. ``we're against people who don't know what they're talking about.''
the rally was organized on the eve of today's visit to the united states by conservative israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir
shamir has expressed opposition to an american plan for an international conference to arrange self-rule for palestianian arabs on the west bank and gaza, then an overall settlement. israel conquered the territories during the 1967 six-day war against jordan and egypt
sunday's confrontation began as 200 or so counter-demonstrators, whose ranks included orthodox jews and militant jewish defense league leader irv rubin, circled the rally's original group, then crowded around the stage
a good jew is a jew, in my opinion, who sticks to the state of israel through thick and thin,'' rubin said. ``they (the peace plan's supporters) are tearing the jewish community apart. they're using their celebrity status to beg and plead and cajole the prime minister of israel to accept this suicide plan.''
millions of chinese peasants have hit the road in recent weeks to seek their fortunes, creating a transportation crisis along the country's railways, an official report said
armed police have been called out to maintain order at railway stations heaving under the mass of travelers while some passenger trains are carrying more than twice their capacity, china's domestic china news service said in an article appearing in hong kong on monday
some are going to the northwest for construction, some are going to the northeast's daxinganling forest for lumbering, others are going gaungdong province (in the south) to farm and still others are going to large cities as housekeepers,'' the news service said
at the beijing station, the report said, ``people can be found everywhere sleeping in the open.'' in zhengzhou, the capital of central henan province and a railroad hub, more than 10,000 people were said to be waiting at the station for tickets
the news service recounted the woeful tale of one passenger who stood for more than 30 hours on a train trip from anhui province to the far-north city of harbin. at one point he lifted his swollen foot only to find the tiny space immediately seized by a traveler squeezed next to him
nearly 4 million people ride the rails daily, the report said, without saying how much of an increase that represents
most of the travelers are peasants looking for work, the report said. the exodus from rural homes began with the arrival of warmer weather following last month's lunar new year holiday
poor peasants always have sought their fortune in big cities, but the situation has become a problem in recent years because of recent economic reforms that ease travel restrictions and permit labor markets
the railroad situation hits its most critical on the third, sixth and ninth days of each month, which are considered propitious days for travel, the news agency said
although authorities are taking several steps to ease the situation, such as increasing passenger trains, the transportation crisis is expected to continue, the report said
in an earlier report, sichuan radio said march 2 that 100,000 travelers were trying to leave chengdu, the capital of central sichuan province, every day for their hometowns, by rail
a few passengers, heedless of admonitions, have stormed their way onto the trains by breaking the windows,'' the report said. ``at the same time, trains leaving chengdu station for destinations outside sichuan are seriously overloaded to the extend that it is impossible to open the doors or supply drinking water.''
a zoo polar bear injured a man with a history of mental problems who entered its cage, and police shot the bear to death, authorities say
the 28-year-old man, whose identity was not released, was treated at a hospital for a gash on his head and was put under emergency detention by police after the sunday morning incident
police said it was unclear why the man climbed into the bear's cage, but that the man told doctors he did it to ``give his brother strength,'' and that people ``need a show of courage.'' the ``brother'' reference was unexplained
vilas zoo director david hall said the intruder had to scale a wall or climb through a moat to reach the the 7-foot-4, 900-pound bear, named chief
i'd say it's a one in a million chance that you get out of a polar bear's den alive when a polar bear is in it,'' hall said
a jogger who heard shouts flagged down a motorist, who alerted police
the jogger, robert nelson, 47, said the ``bear was standing above the person, licking him, playing around with him. the man wasn't screaming. he wasn't doing anything. i thought he was dead.''
police officer michael puls fatally wounded the bear with a 12-gauge shotgun after yelling at it and firing shots in the air in an attempt to scare it. puls said he shot the animal after it began to drag the man to its cave
hall said chief, the only polar bear at the municipal zoo, was considered one of the largest in captivity. it had been with the zoo for about 13{ years
he was a good show and everyone liked him,'' hall said. ``but you can't compare his to a human life. all of us in the zoo profession know that a human life takes precedent.''
police said the sunday incident was the third time this year that emergency detention procedures had to be used to detain the man. those procedures are used when a person is considered a danger to themselves or others. congressman</head>
a 12-year-old girl's anti-drug poster has brought her praise from first lady nancy reagan and rep. richard ray, d-ga
tomiko womack, a sixth-grader at rigdon road elementary school, got a letter from mrs. reagan on feb. 29, praising her for encouraging fellow students to ``just say no'' to drugs. she received a similar letter from ray on march 4
i was very surprised when i got the letters,'' tomiko, a straight `a' student, said. ``i feel greatly honored and will treasure them forever.''
the letters referred to a poster titled, ``how drugs affect our nation,'' which tomiko entered in the muscogee county social science fair on march 4-5. knowing that both mrs. reagan and ray were active in the fight against drugs, tomiko wrote letters inviting them to attend the fair
after she received mrs. reagan's letter, she added it to her poster, which won first place in the sociology category
i came up with the subject because drug abuse is a nationwide problem, especially for young people, and i want to do something about it,'' tomiko said
a british engineer sentenced to life imprisonment for alleged espionage left libya today for a reunion with his family after his prison term was commuted, the foreign office said
james abra, 59, was freed sunday in tripoli, the libyan capital, after serving almost two years. he was headed for malta to meet family members. it was not known when abra would return to britain
abra was arrested at tripoli airport on june 20, 1985, and accused of passing classified information to his employer, a british electronics company, plessey co. he was convicted of spying in april 1986 and sentenced to life in prison
abra's czech-born wife radislava, 58, died of a heart attack last july after a fire at their home in hitchin, 32 miles north of london
jana, the libyan news agency, has said col. moammar gadhafi has declared an amnesty for jailed foreigners. the foreign office said the italian embassy, which looks after britain's interests in libya, had submitted abra's name for consideration
britain broke diplomatic relations with libya in april 1984 after a london police woman was fatally shot during a libyan dissident demonstration. britain said she was killed by a libyan shooting at demonstrators from inside the embassy
israel and hungary opened diplomatic offices in each other's countries today, but a hungarian official said full ties await resolution of the arab-israeli conflict
hungary isn't a superpower and therefore her ability to negotiate in the dispute is modest,'' visiting hungarian foreign ministry representative jeno jyenis said on israel radio
but we support all efforts to promote a solution to the conflict,'' he said. ``the restoration of full diplomatic ties between israel and hungary depends on a resolution of the conflict between israel and the palestinians.''
the renewal of diplomatic links between the two countries comes 20 years after all soviet bloc countries except romania severed ties with israel to protest its occupation of land in the 1967 middle east war
poland became the first east bloc country to renew low-level ties with israel last october. the soviet union also re-established direct diplomatic contacts with israel and sent a consular delegation there in july
to promote the new ties between hungary and israel, an israeli interest section office was opened in the swiss consulate in budapest, and a hungarian interest section was opened in the swedish consulate in tel aviv
in 1986, trade between the two countries equaled $22 million, according to israeli figures. hungary sells israel money, jam and furniture, while israel exports light bulbs and phosphate to hungary
in addition, about 15,000 israeli tourists visited hungary last year, while about 2,000 hungarians visited israel, according to israeli figures
federico sisneros, the national park service's oldest ranger who spent his life caring for the san gregorio de abo mission, has died at age 93
sisneros died saturday of heart failure
sisneros' family owned the land on which the 17th-century spanish mission stands and donated the property to the state in the late 1930s. it was a state monument for many years and became part of salinas national monument in 1981
sisneros was the mission's caretaker while abo was a state monument and was named a ranger when it became part of the national park system
it'll always be abo on paper, but to the ones who worked with him, it'll always be `fred's place,''' said salinas chief ranger glenn fulfer. ``his father had told him to take care of the mission. it was more or less a legacy given down to fred to take care of abo.''
fulfer said sisneros worked for many years ``for hardly any wages at all.''
fred was the type of fellow that the love of the site outweighed the importance of money,'' he said
sisneros was born in 1894 in a house near the indian ruins at the abo mission. he and his wife, guadalupe, lived in a house a few yards from the ruins
sisneros was honored by the national park service in 1981 with the superior service award for making a significant contribution during most of the 20th century
he received an honor award in 1986 from the national trust for historic preservation at the group's 40th annual meeting
his story drew national attention over the years. he was interviewed by charles kuralt of cbs news and was featured in major newspapers
fulfer said sisneros had asked to be buried at the mission. the national park servce has authorized his grave to be located there. testimony</head>
one member of the senate's iran-contra committee and its chief counsel said today they doubt any ``bombshell'' implicating vice president george bush will emerge from the testimony of former national security adviser robert mcfarlane
nevertheless, sen. george mitchell, d-maine, and counsel arthur liman said they feel the arrangement was correct that led to mcfarlane's plea of guilty on friday to misdemeanor charges that he nad misled congress
mitchell and liman, interviewed on the ``cbs this morning'' program, said they expect mcfarlane's testimony will be helpful in the prosecution and indictment of others involved in sales of u.s. arms to iran and the diversion of profits to the contra rebels fighting the sandinista government in nicaragua
mcfarlane said sunday that even though he has promised to cooperate with independent counsel lawrence walsh, he is unable to provide any new information
in saying i expect to testify, it's neither for nor against really anyone,'' mcfarlane said on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley.'' ``it's to say what i've already said on the record and there's nothing new that i know of to change what's there. and as far as i know that's all there is.''
asked why walsh would want him, mcfarlane responded:
i suppose that he wants to hold everyone who did something wrong accountable and he's ceratainly done that with me, but it isn't a matter of being able to embellish what i've already said.'' but both men say they think indepedent counsel lawrence walsh made the right decision to allow mcfarlane to plead guilty to lesser charges than committing perjury to congress
interviewed today, liman said, ``i think that the mcfarlane plea was an obstacle to be cleared by the independent counsel and i would expect him to take other action soon.''
mitchell, although saying he agreed that mcfarlane's testimony is not likely to produce new information, said that ``his testimony will be useful, i believe, according to the special prosecdutor, in testifying in any future trials that may occur
i think judge walsh really was not seeking so much his cooperation as the principle that there was no justification for lying to or misleading congress in the iran-contra affair,'' added liman
mcfarlane pleaded guilty to the four counts by falsely assuring lawmakers that members of his staff, specifically lt. col. oliver l. north, had not been involved in private efforts to arm the nicarguan rebels during a statutory ban on direct u.s. aid to the contras
each of the four counts carries a maximum penalty of one year in prison and a $1,000 fine
as part of the plea agreement, mcfarlane agreed to cooperate with walsh's inquiry into the secret sale of u.s. arms to iran and the diversion of profits to the contras
mcfarlane, who resigned as president reagan's national security adviser in december 1985, traveled to tehran in may 1986 with north on a mission to deliver spare missile parts and persuade iranian officials to help obtain the release of u.s. hostages in lebanon
the grand jury that walsh impaneled 14 months ago is preparing to return indictments in the next several weeks
south african military forces will not leave angola unless cuban troops also depart, according to a report in today's washington times
the south african forces will remain in angola until the 40,000-member cuban force departs, south african president p. w. botha said in an interview with arnaud de borchgrave, times editor
in the past, south africa has said its forces were operating in angola in order to keep guerrillas out of namibia, a south african controlled area adjacent to angola, the article noted
angolan officials, meanwhile, have reportedly given the united states a timetable for withdrawl of the cuban troops, but made that pullout conditional on departure of the south africans
botha told de borchgrave that he has reasons to believe that the soviet union is ready to cut its losses in africa and is pressuring cuba to withdraw its forces
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev believes his predecessors miscalculated the chances for revolution in africa, botha said. now, he said, the soviets are anxious to cut down on the high cost of arming and propping up poor nations
botha said that he doesn't think the soviet union wants to ``ditch'' angola, but rather is ``shopping for a compromise.''
if he is a wise man, botha said of gorbachev, he will take this opportunity to get out of southern africa
of the united states, meanwhile, botha said the u.s. seems to be playing domestic politics with the economic sanctions it has imposed on his country
the sanctions have thrown thousands of blacks out of work, while forcing his country to become more self-reliant, botha said. he said the end result is merely for the united states to lose what influence it has in his country
a 7-year-old canadian girl who shares a birthday with ronald reagan has learned from the u.s. president that several other important people in history also were born in february
it was wonderful to learn that you and i share a mutual birthday,'' reads a typewritten letter signed by reagan to kaliopi triantafyllakis
february is also the month in which george washington and abraham lincoln were born. i hope you make it a part of your birthday to learn more about these two great presidents who played such important roles in shaping our nation,'' the letter said
the letter was in response to a birthday card the elementary school student sent reagan, who was 77 on feb. 6
the white house response received friday also included a glossy photo of reagan and wife nancy, and a 32-page booklet about the reagan years in the white house
kaliopi said she first heard a couple of years ago that she and reagan, who was born in 1911 in tampico, ill., shared the same birthday
actually, i think it was very nice of him to take the time to write her a letter,'' said kaliopi's mother, kathy
oh mom,'' injected the youngster, ``he didn't write it, his secretary did.'' seven arabs. changes byline.</note>
the army said soldiers shot and wounded seven arabs in a clash today, and arab residents said troops closed one of the west bank's largest food markets as israel stepped up economic sanctions against the occupied territories
arab reports said 150 arab policemen in gaza announced their intention to quit, joining hundreds of officers who have turned in their badges in the west bank. israeli authorities acknowledged some resignations but gave no number
the resignations followed the slaying of a jericho policeman who was accused of collaborating with the israelis. undergound plo leaflets have demanded arabs stop working for israeli occupation authorities
scores of tax collectors resigned earlier
an army spokeswoman said a violent demonstration took place in yamoun, six miles northwest of jenin. she said soldiers fired at the legs of demonstrators because the troops believed their lives were in danger. seven arabs were wounded and the village was placed under curfew, she said
the palestine press service reported 12 arabs were shot in clashes with soldiers, 10 in yamoun and two others in jenin. hospital officials declined comment, citing a newly enforced army ban on speaking to reporters
the united nations says at least 91 palestinians have been killed since anti-israeli rioting began dec. 8 in the occupied territories
in apparent response to the resignation campaign, israel continued its economic sanctions, including a ban on the shipment of gasoline and other fuel to service stations in the west bank
uri hakak of the israeli-owned padesco co., which supplies fuel to 50 west bank gas stations, said drivers were afraid to make deliveries after two tank trucks had been attacked and burned
a truck carrying 20,000 liters (5,000 gallons) of oil is like a napalm bomb. the drivers are afraid to travel,'' he said
soldiers closed the regional fruit and vegetable market in jericho, 22 miles northeast of jerusalem. arab merchants said 70 trucks carrying tomatoes, peppers, cauliflower, lemons, oranges and apples were turned away
we started to sell about 8 a.m. when the soldiers came and forced us to close,'' said one merchant, who was sitting next to crates of fruit covered with tarpaulins and carpets
the merchant said arab farmers drove to other areas of town and tried to set up informal markets. but he said soldiers chased them away
saeb erakat, a najah university political science professor who lives in jericho, said israeli authorities wanted to break the back of the palestinian strike with economic pressure
the military government is trying to tell the people who is boss. they want to hurt the people economically. jericho is an agricultural city. to order the market closed in the morning amounts to killing it economically,'' said erakat
a senior official in the army-run territorial government said there had been a ``shift in focus'' from the disturbances in the streets to civil disobedience
in this context, maybe we are going to take some steps (in response) to the economic steps they take,'' added the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
a dozen heads of arab chambers of commerce from throughout the occupied territories met in jerusalem. they called for a halt to ``all methods of collective punishment and the withdrawal of the israeli army from the cities and population centers.''
they also demanded an end to ``attacks on shopowners and their shops.''
an arab chamber of commerce official who insisted on anonymity said the ban on fuels means palestinianss will have difficulty restocking their heating tanks, that bakeries will have trouble baking bread and that farmers will not have fuel for the irrigation pumps
prime minister yitzhak shamir, meanwhile, arrived in washington for an eight-day visit and said he is ``always open to new and constructive proposals,'' to bring peace to the middle east
shamir, who opposes a u.s. peace plan for the region, said he will give the reagan administration a qualified reply to the american proposal to hold peace talks by may 1
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir said today he is ``always open to new and constructive proposals'' to bring peace to the middle east, but urged the united states to base negotiations on the 1978 camp david agreements
shamir, arriving on an overnight flight from tel aviv, indicated in his statement at andrews air force base that he will give the reagan administration a qualified reply to the u.s. proposal to hold peace talks by may 1
secretary of state george p. shultz escorted shamir to his hotel in downtown washington and talked with him for a half-hour over coffee. defense secretary frank c. carlucci is making a similar courtesy call later in the day
in his arrival statement, shamir appealed for understanding. ``in our search for peace,'' he said, ``the united states has always been helpful, open and indispensable.''
he said ``violence, terrorism and war are endemic'' in the middle east and the area ``is littered with broken agreements.''
shamir said the camp david agreement, which led to a peace treaty between egypt and israel in 1979 but failed to resolve the palestinian issue, ``should serve as our guide'' in the current search for a negotiating formula
he said if past accords were ignored ``future agreements will be meaningless.'' the camp david agreement called for self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who live on the israeli-held west bank and in jordan. jordan and the palestinians did not participate in the talks, which ended in failure in 1981
under that agreement, a temporary arrangement would last five years, setting the stage for negotiations on an overall arab-israeli settlement in which all options, including statehood, would be open
shultz has proposed a three-year interim arrangement, with the final negotiations to begin by the end of this year
we are always open to new and constructive proposdals, with our positive reaction to your useful ideas,'' shamir told his american hosts
the israeli leader made no mention of the international peace conference shultz also proposed. his statement suggested he will attempt, during four days of talks here, to persuade shultz to make some changes in the proposal shultz also has presented to jordan
the u.s. position is that israel should relinquish at least some of the land it captured from jordan and egypt in the 1967 six-day war in exchange for arab recognition
shamir is committed to palestinian autonomy under the 1978 camp david agreement signed by the united states, egypt and israel, but he is reluctant to cede the lands on which 1.5 million palestinian arabs live under israeli control
before leaving for the united states, shamir said sunday that he would not call for a government vote until after his trip
after i come back with a summation of my talks with representatives of the american government, the cabinet will meet immediately and i think we'll have a decision on this subject,'' shamir said on israeli radio. ``it's a matter of about a week.''
shultz urged shamir last week to consider the ``ticking demographic time bomb'' of the rapidly growing palestinian population. at a congressional hearing, shultz suggested israel had much to gain by territorial compromise
he did not say who would take over the land _ the palestinians or jordan, which occupied the west bank from 1950 to 1967. egypt held gaza during the same period
the palestine liberation organization, designated by the arab countries as the palestinians' sole legitimate representative, has vowed to dismantle israel as a jewish state
shultz and defense secretary frank c. carlucci planned separate courtesy calls today on shamir after his overnight flight from israel. the tough bargaining begins tuesday with shultz and continues wednesday with president reagan at the white house
the trip was planned before palestinians on the west bank and in gaza began staging protest demonstrations. as of sunday, 91 had been killed in three months of bloody clashes with israeli forces
shamir wrote shultz in january offering to grant palestinians living in the territories self-rule on all matters except security and foreign affairs. in a letter last week to critical u.s. senators, shamir reaffirmed his commitment to the camp david formula
it provides for negotiations on an overall settlement after five years of palestinian autonomy. all options, including statehood, would be open
we have sought peace relentlessly, but our arab neighbors, except egypt, still have to prove in deeds that they are willing to negotiate peace with us,'' shamir said
shultz proposed his plan for negotiations to shamir and israeli foreign minister shimon peres, to king hussein of jordan, and to presidents hafez assad of syria and hosni mubarak of egypt. so far, none of the governments has responded formally
however, shamir was quoted last week as saying the u.s. proposal was ``fraught with danger'' and incapable of bring peace to the region
the only word i agree with in the u.s. plan is the name shultz,'' shamir said, according to an account friday in the israeli daily newspaper haaretz
shultz has requested a decision by all sides by about mid-march. his ``deadline'' coincided with shamir's visit
israelis supporting and opposing the u.s. plan staged separate demonstrations over the weekend, with an estimated 40,000 turning out to back the american proposal and some 200,000 demonstrating against it
a shelby county judge today ruled that secretary of state evan bayh meets the constitutional five-year residency requirement to be governor
in a 10-page ruling, shelby circuit judge charles d. o'connor concluded the democratic gubernatorial candidate didn't lose his indiana residency when he worked as an attorney in washington, d.c., in 1983 and 1984
republicans had argued that bayh, who leads public opinion polls in the governor's race, lost his indiana residency when he moved to the district of columbia to work for the law firm of hogan and hartson
but o'connor concluded that bayh always intended to return to his home state and never established formal residence elsewhere
personal presence (away) from one's place of domicile is insufficient to change one's domicile,'' o'connor wrote. ``one must move to another place with the intent to make it his home and without the intention of returning to his home as such.''
the judge's decision came after a one-day trial friday on bayh's lawsuit seeking a declaratory judgment that he meets the constitutional requirement to be governor
bayh filed the suit in february after republican gov. robert d. orr instructed the gop-controlled state election board to investigate bayh's eligibility
the election board last week delayed its probe to allow the court to rule. the election board and orr already have called for any lower court decision to be appealed to the state supreme court
o'connor concluded that bayh repeatedly expressed his intent to return to his home state and considered his stint in washington as only a brief episode of professional development
o'connor noted that bayh, the son of former sen. birch e. bayh, voted regularly in indiana and kept his ties to the state democratic organization
bayh, 32, faces opposition from former kokomo mayor stephen j. daily in the may 3 democratic primary
lt. gov. john m. mutz is unopposed for the republican nomination to succeed orr, who is barred by the constitution from seeking a third straight term. bgng ``but a chicago...</note>
democratic presidential hopeful michael dukakis said today the days of brokered conventions ``are gone forever'' as he made his final plea to illinois voters to abandon favorite son paul simon and vote for him
the politics of smoke-filled rooms and selected leaders deciding who our nominee is going to be went out years ago,'' dukakis said on a final day of campaigning before tuesday's illinois primary
the massachusetts governor did not mention simon by name, but his reference was unmistakable. simon, short on cash and far behind in the chase for delegates to the democratic national convention, says he is running in his home state to play a role at a brokered convention in atlanta
dukakis declined to answer directly when a reporter asked him at an early-morning news conference whether a vote for simon was a vote for a brokered convention. he replied by saying he hoped the voters would pick the candidate they believed would make the best democratic nominee
he also said he couldn't think of ``anything worse for our party than to go through weeks and weeks'' after the end of the primary season ``with speculation as to who's dealing with whom, who's negotiating with whom.''
dukakis told reporters he believes he has made ``significant gains'' in recent days in illinois. public opinion polls indicate that simon's support has begun to slip with another favorite son, jesse jackson, challenging him for the lead and with dukakis gaining support as well
dukakis' aides, speaking privately, say they would be pleased if jackson edged out simon for a popular-vote victory, hoping that would persuade the senator to quit his campaign
in the separate election for 187 delegates, dukakis' aides concede he is unlikely to win more than a handful in illinois, if that
dukakis made his comments at a news conference on a cold and windy elevated commuter railroad station. the governor, who prides himself on riding the subway to his statehouse office in boston, greeted commuters and chatted with railroad employees during a 20-minute train ride
dukakis made these same arguments on sunday
this nomination is not going to be decided by six guys sitting in a back room in atlanta,'' he said as he polished off a day of ethnic campaigning at a fund-raiser in a greek restaurant
his comments were a variation on his made-for-illinois television ad which lashes out against a brokered convention
the ad doesn't mention paul simon by name but the reference is clear, since the illinois senator skipped the 21 super tuesday contests last week and says he is remaining in the race so he can participate in a brokered convention
the massachusetts governor set out on his illinois stretch run as polls offered conflicting evidence on the race. an abc news-washington post poll published today in the newspaper gave simon the lead with 39 percent support, jackson 34 percent, dukakis 17 percent
but a chicago tribune poll for publication today gave jackson 32 percent support compared with 29 percent for simon and 20 percent for dukakis. those results suggested that simon's support has begun to slip and jackson and dukakis have begun to edge up
dukakis is the leader in delegates in the democratic nomination race. his strategy in illinois has been to suggest that he has the best chance to win the nomination and a vote for the favorite sons would lead to a brokered convention this summer
some people would like to turn back the clock, to go back to the days when the voters didn't really pick their nominee,'' says the announcer in dukakis' television commercial. ``they say you must turn over that power to them at a brokered convention.''
the continental express plane that crashed near durango on jan. 19, killing nine, was flying a time-saving airport approach over rough terrain that only can be used with federal permission, a safety board official said
the flight pattern is one of many possible causes being considered for the crash, said alan pollock, a national transportation safety board spokesman
we've already looked at the approach,'' pollock said. ``we've ruled nothing out. it's one of the many pieces of the jigsaw puzzle.''
the special approach procedure took the aircraft toward the airport from the northeast, rather than from the southwest as other airlines approach, pollock said
la plata county airport manager ron dent said the approach takes the plane over slightly rougher terrain but saves about 15 to 20 minutes per flight
in this case, their legs from denver to durango would be reduced 30 to 40 miles, saving them quite a bit of flight time, fuel, etc.,'' faa representative david laschinger said in a copyright story broadcast sunday by kmgh-tv
dent said the northeast approach is not published in flight manuals and it is illegal for pilots to use the pattern without federal aviation administration approval
kmgh-tv reporter dave minshall said trans-colorado has had permission to use the special approach at durango for a couple of years. he said representatives of trans-colorado and continental airlines declined to comment about the report
soon after the crash, braniff and american west airlines applied for and received permission to fly the landing approach used by continental express, dent said
pollock said investigators plan to compare that landing pattern with the southwest approach. ``we'll be asking how this pattern differs from the other, if there's anything in this approach that could be a problem and how long trans-colorado has been flying it,'' he said
trans-colorado leases planes and crews to rocky mountain airways, a continental airlines subsidiary that operates in colorado as continental express
continental express flight 2286, carrying 17 people, had been given clearance to land at the durango-la plata county airport when it crashed 10 miles east of durango
the pilot, co-pilot and seven passengers died. many of the eight passengers who survived waded through waist-deep snow to get help
the ntsb released a toxicology report friday showing that pilot steven s. silver had a small amount of cocaine in his bloodstream and urine when he died in the crash
dr. merrit birky, an ntsb chemist at washington, d.c., said it would be inappropriate for him to comment on the significance of the finding. says</head>
iran has been forced to sharply increase imports of refined petroleum products because iraqi air raids have badly damaged some of its refineries, the middle east economic survey reported today
the attacks also have forced iran to ration gasoline for the first time
the weekly oil industry newsletter said west germany's laripax company chartered the 284,298-ton liberian supertanker patria to carry 1.8 million barrels of gas oil to the iranian port of bandar abbas from rotterdam
it said two shipments totalling 900,000 barrels of gas oil were delivered to iran earlier this month. gas oil, a refined fuel heavier than kerosene, is often used as a diesel fuel
iran, a major oil producer, has been importing around 300,000 barrels a day of refined products for 18 months because iraqi air strikes have reduced its refining capacity
the newsletter said that a big refinery on tehran's southern outskirts was badly damaged in an iraqi air raid feb. 27 and its output of 220,000 barrels a day curtailed
that attack triggered a renewed ``war of the cities'' between the two countries, at war for 7{ years, with both sides lobbing long-range missiles into each other capitals
the survey said another refinery in the northwestern city of tabriz was only working at around half its normal capacity of 80,000 barrels a day
iran's refining capacity of around 1.3 million barrels a day is believed to have been slashed by as much as 66 percent since the war began
the iraqi air force has been concentrating on hitting iranian oil industry targets, the mainstay of its economy, since 1984
the newsletter estimated that despite these attacks, iran is producing around 1.9 million barrels a day and exporting around 1.5 million barrels a day through the persian gulf
industry sources said the iranians are driving to expand their refining capacity. the isfahan plant has been upgraded to a capacity of 280,000 barrels a day
the iranians also are moving ahead with plans to build new plants at arak in western iran and bandar abbas on the gulf coast. they would have a combined capacity of more than 250,000 barrels a day that would restore iran's refining self-sufficiency
iran's domestic consumption is estimated at around 700,000 barrels a day. falters</head> updated abc-post poll figures, picking up in 7th graf pvs, barring a; cuts last 3 grafs</note>
paul simon, about even with jesse jackson in new illinois polls, said today ``i have to win and i will win'' in tuesday's home-state primary. the republican contest was looking like another george bush runaway
one poll out today said jackson was pulling ahead of simon in the battle of illinois favorite sons, while another showed simon maintaining his advantage. but the percentages separating them were within the polls' potential margins of sampling error
both showed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in third place, trying to cut into the home state support of his two democratic rivals and claim some of the state's 187 democratic delegates
a poll published today in the chicago tribune said 32 percent of likely democratic voters supported jackson, 29 percent backed simon and 20 percent said they would vote for dukakis. rep. richard gephardt of missouri was the choice of 5 percent and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee had the backing of 4 percent
the poll, conducted by peter hart research associates, interviewed 500 likely voters on friday and saturday and had a margin of error of 5 percentage points
an abc news-washington post poll, conducted saturday and sunday and published today in the newspaper, gave simon the lead with 39 percent support to jackson's 34 percent among very likely democratic voters. dukakis had 17 percent with gore and gephardt far behind. the potential sampling error was plus or minus 6 percentage points
simon, who is counting heavily on a victory on tuesday, said as he campaigned at a commuter-train stop today that he had to win. ``a strong second isn't very strong,'' he said
dukakis, also campaigning in chicago, said today that the days of brokered conventions ``are gone forever.'' he was making his final plea to illinois voters to abandon simon and support his own presidential bid
gore greeted workers during a shift change at a factory in rockford, ill., and said, ``i think we're going to do better than people expect here.''
barring a major upset, bush was expected to pick up the lion's share of the 92 gop delegates at stake on tuesday and deliver another blow to senate minority leader bob dole's fading candidacy. the tribune poll showed bush the choice of 62 percent of gop voters, compared to just 28 percent for dole
as it became more apparent that the vice president was locking up his party's presidential nomination, he became the target of more criticism from republican and democratic rivals
he certainly has a lot of baggage,'' jackson said of bush
i'd like george bush to tell us whether (panamanian gen. manuel) noriega was on his payroll when he was cia director,'' said dole
in a speech at northwestern university law school, gore focused on the iran-contra affair and said, ``we still don't know what george bush's role was.''
presidential politicking was picking up in two other states
gephardt was holding a rally in flint, mich., which holds democratic caucuses on march 26 to choose 138 convention delegates. the missouri congressman, jackson and dukakis all were in the state over the weekend
dukakis was joined in detroit by mayor coleman young who said: ``i am not endorsing anybody but i intend to vote for governor dukakis.'' young was one of the few black elected officials not allied with jackson
in north dakota, democrats began a two-week process of selecting delegates to a state convention in april at which national convention delegates will be allocated
jackson was the big winner saturday in south carolina's democratic caucuses. he received 54 percent of the vote and 23 delegates. gore got 18 percent of the vote and six delegates, while 15 others will be uncommitted
dukakis with 460 and jackson with 423 are the leaders in the democratic delegate race, according to the associated press tally
simon said he was being hurt by the lack of money to buy television time
obviously, not to have paid media hampers me in illinois,'' simon said as he campaigned in the city's chinatown neighborhood. ``but the only way i could have paid media would be to use up the resources and obligate the matching funds that are coming.''
simon insists that no democrat will have the nomination in hand when the party convention convenes in atlanta in july and that he will have as good a chance as anyone to come out a winner at a brokered convention
i think the notion of a brokered convention would be an absolute disaster,'' said dukakis, during a campaign stop in a hispanic neighborhood in chicago
i can't imagine anything worse _ the idea of taking the right of the people to elect their president with their votes and putting it in some back rooms in atlanta,'' he said
simon fired back that dukakis was showing ``a touch of arrogance.''
he said, ``mike has been wrong on other things and he's certainly wrong on that.''
dole was interviewed on the cbs show, ``face the nation,'' and said that regardless of the outcome in illinois he would continue his campaign
sooner or later, the voters in one of these states are going to say, wait a minute, we're about to nominate a candidate who can't win in november,'' he said. ``again.''</note>
i. king jordan said today his appointment as the first hearing-impaired president of gallaudet university, the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf, is a victory for students and the deaf community across the country
what it means to the students, it means to the deaf community at large and that's _ it opens up new horizons for deaf people,'' jordan said on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
jordan, dean of the school's college of arts and sciences, was selected by gallaudet trustees on sunday after what began as an isolated campus protest last week turned into an international forum on deaf rights
students had sought a deaf leader to serve as the school's eighth president, but last week the board of trustees selected elisabeth ann zinser, a hearing woman who did not know sign language
a week of protests shut down the campus as students called for the appointment of a deaf president and the resignation of board of trustees chairwoman jane bassett spilman, who had come under fire for her handling of the crisis. sunday night, seven days after their protest began, the students were victorious on both counts
officials announced the appointment of jordan, 44, to replace zinser, who resigned friday, and the resignation of spilman, who also hears normally and
had chaired the board for six years
she will be replaced by philip w. bravin, one of four deaf members of the board
i took this step willingly,'' spilman said. ``in the minds of some, i've become an obstacle to the future of the university. i am removing that obstacle.''
jordan, who had endorsed zinser's presidency at mid-week but later retracted his backing, today praised the students' efforts
i think that they really honestly believe that they were motivated in a positive way to do positive things, and the outcome has been very positive,'' said the new president. ``it's our responsibility now as administrators, me and phil bravin, to make sure we channel that energy in a positive way.''
jordan, who also appeared on ``cbs this morning,'' said the students realize ``this was something very special. there's not going to be an opportunity for this kind of movement again.''
the battle cry was, `deaf president now;' it has become, `deaf president forever,''' he said
student protest leader jerry covell said sunday that the demonstrators' actions mark ``the first time we've ever shown the world what we want, and that we can get it.''
god made the world in seven days and we have changed it in seven days,'' said charles a. giansanti, a deaf chemistry professor, after the decision was announced
bravin said the board would form a task force to study its own composition in reponse to student demands that deaf people comprise a majority of the 20-member panel. there also will be no reprisals against student protesters, bravin said
gallaudet, which offers undergraduate and graduate degrees in 30 fields, receives 75 percent of its $76 million budget in federal funds. a house education and labor subcommittee plans to conduct hearings tuesday into the school's bylaws governing presidential selection and composition of the board
zinser resigned two days after rep. david bonior., d-mich. and a member of the university's board, hinted that the federal aid could be in jeopardy unless a deaf president were named
deaf groups and schools around the country had supported the students' demands, as had a majority of the gallaudet faculty
jordan, 44, was a finalist for the position when zinser was selected last sunday. before becoming dean in 1986 of gallaudet's largest undergraduate department, jordan served as a psychology professor at the school
after students learned of jordan's appointment, they attempted to put into perspective a struggle that had captured worldwide attention
this is not the end; this is the beginning,'' said bridgetta bourne, a protest leader
this is where we start from now. we have gained this, and we will never have deafness work against us again,'' she said
the only u.s. manufacturer of injectable polio vaccine has stopped shipping the drug to california physicians after learning it was being used as an experimental aids treatment
connaught laboratories' vice president david j. williams said the company would like to cooperate in such a treatment but is prohibited by the u.s. food and drug administration from supplying physicians with the vaccine for anything other than its intended use _ to prevent polio
some doctors in california have been working with aids patients, using our injectable polio product,'' williams said. ``as soon as it came to our attention, we were required to contact the fda to determine if they had all the approvals.''
he said the physicians did not have the required approvals, so connaught halted the shipments
a spokeswoman for the fda said an ``investigational new drug application'' should be submitted to the fda and studied to be sure experiments are conducted properly and that dosages would not adversely affect patients
the risks have to be weighed versus the benefits,'' she said
the old injectable salk vaccine is no longer the preferred polio vaccine in the united states, having been replaced by an oral vaccine. it has shown promise for aids patients, relieving some cancer lesions, herpes infections, swollen lymph nodes and fatigue, a california researcher reported
the old, killed-virus vaccine can only be supplied by connaught
dr. allen allen, a california researcher and co-developer of the experimental treatment, said physicians wonder what will happen now to patients who have shown improvement after receiving the injections for as long as two years
patients with cancers are getting better and doctors can no longer give them treatment. most are close to running out,'' he said friday, adding that the physicians planned to meet to form a plan of action
allen said studies on more than 50 patients have shown the vaccine ``produces clinical benefits after six weeks.''
allen said that it's up to connaught, not the doctors, to submit the necessary applications to the fda, and alleged that the pennsylvania lab has financial reasons for not releasing its vaccine
what they want to provide is a new vaccine which they have a patent for, opposed to the old salk vaccine which is in the publc domain,'' he said
williams said the company did receive a patent in november for an improved injectable polio vaccine for global use, but he insisted connaught is not pushing one over the other for experiments on aids patients
we started working on the new vaccine in 1979-80, probably before aids was a household word,`` he said. 5th graf pvs, gore's campaign</note>
sen. albert gore jr. portrayed himself today as a needed alternative to the three democratic candidates leading him in polls one day before the illinois democratic primary
gore greeted workers during a shift change at a factory in rockford, ill., and said, ``i'm very encouraged'' about tuesday's primary, although he and his aides acknowledged on sunday that he was far behind
i think there are an awful lot of voters here in illinois who want an alternative to the kind of approach offered by michael dukakis and paul simon and jesse jackson. i offer a different kind of approach,'' gore said today
gore on sunday had turned his focus to republican george bush and said the vice president's response to the iran-contra affair amounted to: ``gee whiz, that's great, let's go ahead.''
the tennesseean resumed his illinois campaign after a weekend break, returning to a state where polls show him stuck in single digits far behind favorite sons simon and jackson, and also trailing rival michael dukakis
gore's campaign bought what deputy campaign manager larry harrington called ``a decent or modest amount'' of television airtime in illinois. it was thought to be in the range of $200,000 to $300,000 over the past week. but harrington downplayed expectations, saying gore's only aim was to be ``in the fray'' in illinois
we never put any serious organizational effort into illinois,'' harrington said. he cited jackson's and simon's strength and the timing a week after last week's super tuesday round of primaries that catapulted gore to the top tier of democratic presidential contenders
gore delivered a forceful attack on the vice president and the reagan administration for the iran-contra affair in a long question-and-answer session with students at northwestern university law school
he pointed to the guilty plea by former white house national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane to misdemeanor charges relating to iran-contra as confirming ``the reagan-bush administration violated the law in a brazen way.''
we still don't know what george bush's role was,'' gore said
gore said the administration's sale of arms to iran in a bid to free hostages would have been ``hooted'' down as ``nuts'' if congress was consulted. ``we didn't have that opportunity, but george bush had that opportunity,'' he said
he evidently said, `yeah, gee whiz, that's great, let's go ahead,''' gore said
gore voiced sympathy for simon, the illinois senator whose white house bid is on the ropes in illinois, for a television ad being aired by dukakis. it says a vote for simon is in effect a vote for a confused race and perhaps a brokered convention
gov. dukakis's commercial tries to lump him in with back-room politics of a kind paul simon has not been associated with,'' gore said at a news conference
gore continued to depict himself as a more electable alternative to dukakis and his other rivals but did not dwell on them in a series of speeches in the chicago area. but asked about dukakis by the law students, gore said he would respond ``with relish.''
he repeated his contention that dukakis lacks necessary foreign policy experience and said dukakis has wrongly stated that there is no ``underclass'' in america _ the tennessee senator asserting that children trapped in a cycle of poverty do make up such an underclass. and he faulted dukakis for shortcomings as a campaigner
i think he's not yet found his voice to articulate his message beyond the `massachusetts miracle,''' gore said, referring to dukakis' claim that he helped turn around his state's economy
i don't think he has succeeded in offering a clear vision of what he would do as president,'' gore said
gore said his decision to spend friday night through sunday morning in washington did not reflect an abandonment of his hopes for illinois. he said he spent much of the time raising money by telephone, and said his fund-raisers have collected as much as $150,000 a day since last tuesday
but acknowledging the polls in illinois, gore said: ``there are two favorite sons here; i understand that.''
thousands of nurses at hospitals across britain held strikes, rallies and marches today in a last-minute attempt to get the conservative government to allocate more money to the national health service
bus services were halted or slowed on dozens of routes as crews at some some london transport centers walked out in sympathy, said london regional transport spokesman graham white
in london, where about 500 nurses mounted picket lines at 15 hospitals, nurses delivered a cake with a message to chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson, who will unveil the budget in parliament on tuesday
we hope we will get a bigger slice of the budget,'' said 19-year-old student nurse sue hogg
prime minister margaret thatcher's government, expected to make substantial tax cuts, has ruled out a big increase in the service's $41 billion budget
mrs. thatcher has ordered a review of the service and plans to encourage more britons to take out private health insurance
outside the capital, strikes were ``fairly limited,'' according to the confederation of health service employees, one of two health unions sponsoring the protest
the third major union, the royal college of nurses, has a no-strike code of principle
overall, 515,000 nurses work in britain
in northern ireland, a british province, 10,000 nurses took part in protest marches. in wales, nurses presented a 60,000-signature petition to the health department
outside london, strikes were reported at two hospitals in manchester and one in cheshire, in yorkshire and wakefield, and at st. james general hospital and other hospitals in leeds
pickets or marches were held in brighton, bristol, nottingham, leicester, coventry, birmingham, and coventry
business inventories rose 0.4 percent in january, less than half the pace turned in during the previous month, the government reported today
the commerce department said the gain in inventories pushed them up by $3 billion in january to a seasonally adjusted $705.85 billion
the inventory increase came as total business sales were falling 0.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted $462.78 billion in january, reversing much of the big 1.2 percent december increase in sales
the january gain in inventories held on shelves and backlots followed an even larger 0.9 percent increase in december. the janaury rise was held back by a 1 percent decline in inventories held by retailers
this decrease reflected primarily a 3.3 percent drop in the backlog of unsold cars as dealers offered new incentive programs to spur lagging sales
analysts had worried that a huge rise in unsold inventories during the final three months of the year would force production cutbacks and weak economic growth in the early part of 1988
but economists have recently modified their views somewhat, contending that the slowdown in growth in the early part of this year will not be as severe as they had feared
the 1 percent decline in inventories held at the retail level was accompanied by an increase of 1.6 percent in inventories at the wholesale level and a 0.8 percent rise in manufacturing inventories
the 0.7 percent overall sales decline was led by a 1.7 percent drop in sales by manufacturers and a 0.2 percent decline in sales at the retail level. sales at the wholesale level rose 0.4 percent in january
in an advance report on friday, the government said that retail sales in february had risen by 0.6 percent
the combination of falling sales and rising inventories pushed the inventory-to-sales ratio up from 1.51 in december to 1.53 in january. that means it would take 1.53 months to exhaust inventories at the january sales pace, still a ratio that is not considered abnormally high
company documents reveal that g.d. searle &amp; co. misled doctors and federal officials about safety characteristics of its copper-7 contraceptive device, according to lawyers for the plaintiff in a lawsuit
according to documents released last week by a federal court, searle apparently hid complaints about the copper-7 from the food and drug administration, lawyers said
eventually, an fda task force recommended that a federal grand jury investigate whether any laws were broken by searle's allegedly misleading reports on animal studies for a number of products, including the copper-7. no charges were filed
paul strain, an attorney for searle, said testimony and documents not yet made public will show the company did not mislead anyone
the copper-7 was a popular intrauterine device from 1974 to 1988, when searle withdrew it from the market citing the costs of lawsuits claiming it caused health problems. many american women continue to use copper-7 iuds and searle recently resumed manufacturing the device in order to fill foreign orders
the searle documents, produced for a may 16 trial in st. paul, became public last thursday on order of u.s. district judge robert renner. the judge rejected searle's arguments that the internal company memorandums be kept confidential because of trade secrets and other reasons
these documents can be characterized as the tip of the iceberg,'' said michael ciresi, a minneapolis attorney who represents esther kociemba, a melrose woman who claims to have been made infertile by the copper-7
once all the documents are disclosed (to the public), they will collectively establish without a doubt that the copper-7 causes (infection) and searle knew about it, but did not disclose it to doctors or to women,'' coresi said
nationally, there have been 17 trials over searle's copper-7, 14 of them decided in the company's favor
kociemba's case ``will be the first case tried against searle where the jury will be presented with evidence from searle's files showing what searle knew about the hazards of the iud, when they knew about them and what they did about them _ which was to conceal the information,'' ciresi said
strain said, ``we are confident when a jury hears all the evidence, reviews all the documents and, most importantly, hears from the doctors that they will conclude the copper-7 is a good iud that does not cause infection.''
a major issue will be whether copper-7's withdrawal ``tail'' string was a single strand of polypropylene incapable of transporting infection-causing bacteria into the uterus, as searle contends, or if it was made up of many tiny strands that could act as a tunnel for bacteria, as ciresi contends
one of the searle documents quotes a company official saying for the first time that, although the copper-7 string is considered a single line, it actually is a ``bundle of fused micro-filaments.''
a federal judge today denied for a second time lynette ``squeaky'' fromme's request for a no-contest plea to an escape charge and began calling a jury to hear the case against the manson disciple and would-be presidential assassin
fromme, who said she intends to act as her own lawyer, said she wanted to ``disperse with this case as simply as possible.''
fromme, 39, is serving a life sentence for a 1975 assassination attempt on then-president gerald ford. she escaped dec. 23 from the federal correctional institution at alderson and was recaptured about two miles away on christmas day after a massive manhunt
i admit committing the escape,'' she said. ``i was away for two days.''
fromme told u.s. district judge elizabeth hallanan that the case ``doesn't warrant a jury trial'' and professed herself ``willing to accept whatever sentence you hand down to me.''
but fromme failed today to ask for ``bench trial,'' which would have left the decision in the judge's hands without calling a jury
court officials said 50 potential jurors had been called to be questioned by fromme and assistant u.s. attorney j. kirk brandfess
fromme is a follower of charles manson, a mass murderer serving a life sentence in california
ford was unharmed when a secret service agent grabbed a semi-automatic .45-caliber pistol aimed at him by fromme on sept. 5, 1975
in san francisco 17 days later, ford escaped injury when sara jane moore fired a revolver at him. she eventually pleaded guilty and received a life sentence
in 1979, moore also escaped from the alderson prison, but was recaptured hours later about 25 miles away. she is now in a federal prison in pleasanton, calif. disease</head>
scientists at yale university are planning to transplant brain cells from aborted fetuses into patients with parkinson's disease in an effort to find a treatment for the crippling disease
doctors in mexico and sweden recently performed similar tests but physicians say it is too early to tell if they succeeded in reducing or eliminating the effects of the disease. the procedure has not been attempted in the united states
yale researchers say they are ready to try the procedure on humans after having tested it on monkeys
based upon the technical problems and what we have to do, i think there is a good chance we will be ready to do a human sometime within the year,'' said dr. d. eugene redmond jr., professor of psychiatry at yale and director of the neurobehavior laboratory at yale's school of medicine
redmond said in a recent interview the use of fetal tissue raises many ethical questions
those questions include how tissue should be obtained from aborted fetuses without violating the sanctity of human life, whether the method of abortion should be altered to preserve the tissue and if the technology could foster a new industry geared to the production of human cells for transplant
also at issue is how to obtain permission for transplant from a woman who aborts her fetus, or whether it is needed at all
abortion is a tragedy,'' redmond said. ``but as long as it occurs, i believe it is immoral to let tissue and materials go to waste if it can cure people who are suffering and dying.''
arthur caplan, director of the center for biomedical ethics at the university of minnesota, said only a few major medical centers should conduct brain-cell transplants
brain transplants is an environment in which charlatans, quacks and ripoff artists can flourish,'' caplan said
in his experiments, redmond and his associates have reversed disease-like symptoms in monkeys through grafting of fetal brain cells
parkinson's disease victims suffer from a lack dopamine, which transmits nerve cell messages to the muscles. the disease is often characterized by tremors, rigidity or loss of balance, and afflicts at least 350,000 people in the united states. noriega.</note>
the reagan administration would not say today whether it would try to extradite panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega on drug trafficking charges if he seeks asylum in spain
whatever arrangements he makes with another country are his business,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater. ``we intend to follow the legal process.''
reagan has the legal authority to move to dismiss drug indictments against noriega. or, the united states could press for noriega's extradition and seek to prosecute him. fitzwater refused to clear up which legal course would be pursued
we don't have any comment,'' the spokesman said at a white house news briefing
officials in spain have said that government would be willing to grant asylum to noriega under certain conditions _ including the proviso that the united states would promise not to try to extradite him after he arrived in spain
reagan on friday called for noriega to step down and end his ``illegitimate'' regime. to force noriega's ouster, the administration has applied a series of sanctions against panama, including the withholding of about $6.6 million in payments relating to the operation of the panama canal
a masked man shot and wounded three saudi arabian diplomats in an ambush in the parking lot of lagos hotel, a newspaper said
a fourth diplomat escaped injury and pursued the gunman, the government-owned new nigerian reported. it said the assailant escaped over a nearby wall
the four saudis were fired upon as they left the eko holiday inn in a car at 2 a.m. sunday, the newspaper said. it said the gunmen apparently had been waiting for them
two of the wounded diplomats were in serious condition, while the third suffered a less severe wound, the newspaper said. their names were not made public
both police and the saudi embassy refused to answer questions about the incident
the new nigerian quoted police sources who said witnesses described the gunman as an arab
there was no immediate claim of responsibility for the shootings
a libyan diplomat was shot and killed in lagos in january. police said the diplomat was slain by robbers who were caught. government and police sources said they could not rule out the possibility that the libyan had been killed by chadians
jim bakker has returned to the pulpit for the first time in more than a year, preaching from a small wooden lectern to elderly, suntanned retirees at a trailer park in california
tammy faye bakker introduced her husband to the crowd of 225 campers at a service sunday in niland, calif., according to a report in today's editions of the charlotte observer
the campers were seated on folding metal chairs in a bingo hall that doubles as a chapel, with a folding metal table serving as an altar, the newspaper said
this has been a long, hard year for us,'' mrs. bakker said. ``it hasn't been easy ... i am very happy to introduce to you my husband. i would like to welcome him back to the place where he belongs, in the pulpit, ministering the gospel of jesus christ
jim bakker, defrocked in may after the sex-and-money scandal over ptl, chose the remote corner of the california desert to preach again because his uncle, charles ``lonnie'' irwin, is pastor of the park's lutheran congregation during the winter
curious campers began arriving an hour before the 9 a.m. service. thirty people who couldn't fit inside the building listened through window screens
one regular member of the congregation whispered to a friend: ``it's not just the ordinary congregation. it's just a big show. how many people came to worship, really? how many came to just look.?''
it has been nearly one year since bakker gave up his ministry at ptl, south of charlotte, admitting he had sex with jessica hahn and that money had been promised to keep her silent
bakker preached about friendship for 30 minutes, then grinned and hugged members of the congregation
i've always said over the years if i could give you a gift, the most important gift would be a good friend,'' bakker said during his sermon. ``that's besides jesus.''
bakker quoted again and again from the bible about the value of a good friend and god's commandment to love one's enemies
after bakker ended his sermon with a prayer, the congregation clapped. he and his wife then greeted everyone as they walked out the door. jeannie morgan, 63, of stanford, wash., looked ecstatic after she shook their hands
seeing the real thing and having it here is perfect,'' she said
poland, in an attempt to cash in on the popularity of polish-born pope john paul ii, has struck new gold coins with the papal image and will sell them in the united states for $8,800 apiece
it is the most precious coin issued by the polish national mint since world war ii
the state-run pap news agency said monday the coin is 12.6 ounces of pure gold and has a face value 200,000 zlotys, but will be worth 12 million zlotys
at the black-market exchange rate of 1,360 zlotys to the dollar, 12 million zlotys is about $8,800. pap said the coins would be sold for $8,800 in the united states
poland produced silver coins with the pope's image in 1982, prior to the second visit to his homeland of the former archbishop of krakow, karol wojtyla
the new coins were contracted by a u.s. company, and will be sold through coin dealers in the united states, said zbigniew marski of the national bank of poland. he declined to identify the u.s. company
it will be illegal to buy the coins in poland, even for dollars, pap said
after 18 months of review, the environmental protection agency has decided not to subject a common herbicide to special scrutiny of its cancer-causing potential
subsequent studies have failed to confirm that 2,4-d causes cancer, despite a 1986 finding by the national cancer institute that kansas wheat farmers who mixed their own 2,4-d more than 20 times a year stood an eight-fold greater chance of developing a cancer of the lymphatic system called non-hodgkin's lymphoma, an agency spokesman said
the study said home and garden users were not exposed to enough 2,4-d to cause concern
sold under dozens of trade names, 2,4-d _ short for dichlorophenoxyacetic acid _ is believed the fourth most widely used pesticide in the nation, with more than 39 million pounds of active ingredient sold in 1985
the great bulk of that is believed to be used for broadleaf weed control in wheat fields, though 2,4-d also is widely used on highway rights of way, on lawns and in forests
despite epa's decision, chemlawn inc., a major lawn care company, will not restore 2,4-d to its products until a special national cancer institute study of its employees _ of whom perhaps 3,000 used 2,4-d on 80 or so occasions per year _ is completed, said spokesman steve hardymon in columbus, ohio
hardymon said epa ``probably is right.''
but diane baxter, staff scientist for the national coalition against the misuse of pesticides, said of the decision, ``i think it's outrageous.''
epa, she said, appeared to have given great weight to animal studies showing no cancer-causing potential by 2,4-d
we only do animal studies when we don't have human studies,'' but in this case a good study of humans _ the kansas farmers _ was disregarded, she said
another chemically related herbicide, 2,4,5-t, ``was banned mostly because of birth defects (among humans) in the pacific northwest ... and that (study) is not anywhere near as hard to refute as the study nci did.''
epa spokesman al heier, confirming trade press reports of the agency's decision, said friday, ``it was a tough call.''
in addition to the animal studies that failed to show an effect, ``i think there are quite a few (human) epidemiology studies'' that also fail to confirm the cancer-causing ability of 2,4-d
chemlawn says it knows of at least five human studies that show no cancer effect from 2,4-d. the company did not detail those, but a pair of studies of farm and forest workers in new zealand is frequently cited
the first study found elevated incidence of non-hodgkins lymphoma and another cancer called multiple myeloma, but did not examine exposure to pesticides. the second study, however, found no excess risk of cancer as a result of exposure to chemicals of the 2,4-d class
the herbicide 2,4-d aroused suspicion because it can be contaminated with small amounts of chemicals related to the dioxins, though there are no u.s. reports, and only one abroad, of contamination with the most toxic form of dioxin. that form of dioxin is the most powerful cancer-causing agent ever tested in the laboratory
the contaminants of 2,4-d generally have only about 1 percent of the cancer-causing power of the most toxic dioxin
a u.s.-made f-16 jet fighter crashed into a mountain monday in northern norway during an eight-nation nato exercise, killing its norwegian pilot, the alliance announced
a helicopter-borne rescue team said the pilot, who was alone in the plane, apparently had no time to eject before the crash on hinnoeya island, according to the allied press information center
the weather reportedly was clear at the time, and the cause of the crash was unknown
in neighboring sweden on monday, a swedish air force pilot was killed when his ja-37 viggen fighter crashed during a training flight, the national news agency tt reported
the report said the swedish-made aircraft exploded on impact near frosoke in the southeastern province of smaland. the cause of that accident was under investigation
a vehicle carrying a swiss tv crew toppled down a sand dune in northern chad, killing a journalist and injuring five other people, the chadian embassy reported monday
the accident occurred sunday at bir miski, about 125 miles north of faya largeau
killed was alain doumier, a reporter. suffering minor injuries were cameraman claude pellaud, soundman roger vaucher and three chadians, the embassy said
the crew from television romande had been in the northern african nation less than a week on a trip sponsored by the united nations. it was reporting on development in northern chad, the scene of fighting in recent years pitting government troops against libyans and chadian rebels
the prospect of british soldiers staging war games on the falkland islands is making some islanders a bit uneasy about upsetting argentina, which still claims sovereignty over the tiny archipelago
less than a thousand troops are expected to be flown in thursday for the military exercise, a test of how quickly britain can respond to an island invasion
some islanders say they feel reassured by the 24-day drill, but others fear it unnecessarily provokes the argentines, who lost the war with britain over the islands in 1982
the situation between us and argentina is so delicate that these exercises are bound to be a cause of trouble,'' said islander nicola colbert
i can understand there are excellent possibilities for training down here, but i feel the exercise is not a very good thing from the point of view of our relations with argentina.''
but resident claudette ceballos supports the war games
i think the argentines are being a bit silly,'' she said. ``they are overreacting, as they always do. if they hadn't kicked up such a fuss, i probably wouldn't have given the whole exercise a thought.''
george betts, a boat captain, said argentina has no say in the matter
this place is british, and what happens to it is the problem of the british and us,'' he said. ``it has nothing whatsoever to do with the argentines.''
argentina has led a chorus of latin american protest against operation fire focus, as the exercise is named. britain has denied it is provoking argentina
but after initially refusing to say how many troops would be involved, britain has sought to allay the objections by announcing that only a force of fewer than 1,000 soldiers would be flown in
british authorities want to insulate the troops from the populace. maj. gen. neil carlier, commander of british forces on the islands, says contact will be kept to a minimum
the settlers, however, will be asked to report sightings of soldiers who might be playing the enemy's role during the exercise on the rocky, windswept islands, he told a news conference last week
carlier denied reports that farms would be used as targets of mock attacks, and said wildlife sanctuaries would be avoided
plans reportedly have been made for the half-dozen tourists presently on the islands to be fishing or bird-watching far from the action while operation fire focus is under way
the exercise technically began march 7, with mock intelligence reports being sent to london about enemy troop movements against the islands. it concludes march 31
in 1982, when argentina seized the islands, the absence of a runway capable of taking long-range aircraft meant britain had to respond by sea. it took weeks for a naval task force to make the 8,000-mile voyage
during that time the argentines dug in, and were dislodged only after a 74-day war that claimed the lives of 712 argentine and 258 british servicemen
britain has since spent $690 million on an airport in the islands that can accommodate troop flights in case of another attack
falklanders have grown used to the luxury of an airport that can get them directly to britain, and there have been some grumblings at the disruptions travelers are likely to suffer during the exercise
the communist world gets its first mcdonald's next week, and some people here are wondering whether its american hamburgers will be as popular as the local fast-food treat, pljeskavica
the long-awaited opening of the restaurant on one of belgrade's main downtown squares will take place march 24, the yugoslav news agency tanjug reported, and it will offer big macs, fries and the other specialities familiar to mcdonald's customers in the west
the belgrade media have suggested that the success of the american restaurant depends on its acceptance by yugoslavians who are long accustomed to the hamburger-like pljeskavica
pljeskavica is made of ground pork and onions, and it is served on bread and eaten with the hands. it is sold at fast-food restaurants across the country and costs about a dollar
in fact, this is a clash between the big mac and pljeskavica,'' said an official of genex, yugoslavia's largest state-run enterprise that will operate the mcdonald's
john onoda, a spokesman at mcdonald's oak brook, ill., headquarters, said it was the first of the chain's outlets in a communist country
the next east european mcdonald's is scheduled to be opened in budapest, hungary, by the end of this year, said vesna milosevic, another genex official
negotiations have been going on for years for expanding the fast-food chain to the soviet union, but no agreement has been announced. border</head> inserts three grafs after 6th pvs, ``initial statements xxx, picnickers scattered, comment from mexico</note>
four armed mexican naval personnel who said they were pursuing drug smugglers apparently interrogated a group of american picnickers on a beach more than a half mile north of the u.s.-mexican border, authorities said
the four mexicans were arrested sunday night, said san diego county sheriff's sgt. bob ramirez
the four men, whose names were being withheld, interrogated a group of 10 to 15 u.s. citizens who were picnicking on the beach, said dale cozart, chief agent for the u.s. border patrol in san diego
it's a very serious situation,'' cozart said today. ``our investigation is not complete at this time, but it's possible the americans were being interrogated against their will.''
border patrol agents scanning the area in a helicopter spotted the four men dressed in mexican naval infantry uniforms and armed with fully loaded automatic rifles, cozart said. the weapons were standard military issue, he added
initial statements taken were that they were pursuing narcotics smugglers. but that has not been confirmed and there is no indication that narcotics were being smuggled in the area at the time,'' cozart said
local residents frequently picnic on the beach into the night, but cozart said authorities had not been able to speak to any of the picnickers because they scattered when the helicopter hovered overhead
the mexican men said they had been chasing two suspected drug or arms smugglers up the beach when they were discovered. the mexicans headed south and were intercepted before they could get across the border
in mexico city, spokesmen for the foreign ministry and the mexican navy said they had no information on the incident
the men were being held at the border patrol's san ysidro sector station, solely for investigation of immigration violations, he said
there is no doubt that the individuals knew they were in the united states,'' the agent said
he added that any other allegations, including possible weapons violations, would be considered at a later time
five sheriff's deputies were called to assist in the arrests, which occurred without incident, cozart said
state department officials as well as the mexican consulate in san diego and mexican military officials were notified of the arrests
the plo ambassador to the united nations declared today he will defy a u.s. order to close his mission and said that if his office is closed, israel should be excluded from debates on the middle east
we have the right to stay here, we will stay here and we will stay where we are,'' zehdi labib terzi, the permanent observer of the palestine liberation organization, told a news conference here
the general assembly may reconvene this week in an emergency session to consider the confrontation between the united states and the 159-member world body, u.n. officials said
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar today was drafting a letter to protest the u.s. decision to close the plo's u.n. observer mission under a controversial anti-terrorism law
if somebody tries to kick us out, we will not respond,'' terzi said, adding he had no plans to leave the united states where his mission has operated for the last 13 years
the only way they will make me leave is to put me behind bars and take me away.''
the plo envoy also said that if the plo mission is closed, as ordered by the justice department, then the general assembly should deny israel the right to participate in u.n. debates on the middle east
if the palestinian people are not allowed to be here,'' he said, ``then out of a sense of fairness and justice, the other party to the conflict should not be here _ namely israel.''
terzi was responding to a u.s. justice department statement on friday that it would enforce the law to close the plo's u.n. observer mission by march 21
the united nations has strongly protested the u.s. move to enforce the law. it says the act violates the u.n. charter and the 1947 treaty by which the united states agreed to allow u.n. missions to operate
the plo is an invitee of the united nations
the general assembly convened in an emergency session two weeks ago and urged the united states to comply with international law and allow the mission to operate. it said it would convene again if the united states decided to enforce the act
president reagan demanded today that congress keep his ``star wars'' missile defense system alive, arguing that cutting the high-tech program because of domestic budget pressures would be ``irresponsible in the extreme.''
reagan, kicking off an administration campaign keyed to the program's fifth anniversary, charged that congressional cuts in his strategic defense initiative have ``set the program back one to two years.''
even though reagan has reached the point in his presidency where he has sent his last budget to congress, he pledged in an address to the institute for foreign policy analysis to see the program continued
and he lauded the technological advances that have been made, asserting that the program has ``progressed more rapidly'' than first thought possible
we will continue to research sdi, to develop and test it, and as it becomes ready, we will deploy it,'' reagan vowed
the president restated his belief that without the space-based missile defense, the united states will be left defenseless in the face of an advanced soviet space-weapons program
a recent report by the department of defense called `the soviet space challege' warns that the soviet space program points in one disturbing direction. ... the methodical pursuit of a war-fighting capability in space,'' reagan charged
because congress has made cuts for the past four years in administration sdi requests, ``we would be dangerously undeprepared,'' reagan asserted
there's been a tendency by some in congress to discuss sdi as if its funding could be determined purely by domestic considerations, unconnected to what the soviets are doing,'' reagan said, ``that is, to put it plainly, irresponsible in the extreme.''
the president argued that ``some in the u.s. congress'' have denied additional funds ``because they say sdi won't work. well, it won't if we don't develop it and test it.''
congress should realize that it is no longer a question of whether there will be a sdi program or not. the only question will be whether the soviets are the only ones who have strategic defenses while the united states remains entirely defenseless,'' reagan said
the pro-sdi campaign comes as congress has placed constraints on sdi testing and expenditures, and as soviet arms control negotiators in geneva attempt to crimp the u.s. effort amid negotiations on a u.s.-soviet treaty to slash strategic nuclear weapon arsenals by half
the president has rarely missed a chance to plug the u.s. effort. even at a light-hearted commemorative ceremony last week to honor notre dame's legendary football coach knute rockne, reagan's speech contained a passage referring to the ``dark side'' of the world's technological progress and arguing that his plan would solve the nuclear dilemma
he pointed to the millions of civilians and military killed in world wars i and ii, and said if a third worldwide conflagration occurs in the nuclear age, ``it's estimated that 90 percent of the casualties will be civilian.''
the president said sdi would ``point the way out'' of this problem
it's given us the promise of basing our security in the future on protection rather than the threat of retaliation. sdi offers a chance to reverse not only the nuclear arms build-up, but also to reverse the trend that in effect has put a lower and lower value on human life,'' reagan said
opponents of the program argue that it will cost untold billions and won't work, and that it will only encourage the soviets to abandon arms control efforts and increase their offensive weapons in order to best u.s. defensive systems
in the last fiscal year, the administration sought $5.7 billion for star wars, but congress allowed only $3.6 billion
capitol hill also banned the use of federal funds for any sdi tests that would violate a strict interpretation of the 1972 antiballistic missile treaty. pentagon officials including defense secretary frank carlucci have said no such tests are planned for the near future
while the soviet union has argued that the abm treaty forbids much research, testing and development of an sdi system, the reagan administration has insisted on a so-called ``broad'' interpretation of the treaty that would permit expanded sdi tests and development
reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, at their december summit, in essence agreed to disagree for a time on the issue, saying in a joint communique they would observe the abm treaty ``as signed in 1972, while conducting their research, development and testing as required.''
u.s. and soviet negotiators in geneva have remained at odds over how to address the issue. total, and add redington's arrival, picking up 4th graf, unalakleet xxx</note>
the 70-year-old founder of the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race lost the lead again today when two other teams beat him to the bering sea coast after battling biting wind and drifting snow during the night
martin buser of big lake arrived at this eskimo village at 5:49 a.m. with 13 dogs in harness. defending champion susan butcher pulled in at 5:57 a.m. with 12 dogs
race founder joe redington lost the lead a second time somewhere between kaltag and unalakleet along the frozen yukon river. he arrived in unalakleet at 6:42 a.m. with nine dogs
unalakleet is 889 miles from the race's start in anchorage, and 269 miles from the finish in nome. from unalakleet, the teams run north along the barren, windswept coast. the next checkpoint is shaktoolik, 40 miles farther up the trail
redington had paced the race for more than 400 miles, and then lost the lead to buser on saturday along the yukon river. but in the dark outside kaltag, redington jumped back out front. buser had trailed redington out of kaltag by more than two hours
redington started the race with 15 dogs and had dropped six of them at checkpoints along the trail by sunday. race rules require mushers to arrive in nome with at least five dogs in harness
the race started march 5 in anchorage. the first musher to nome will collect $30,000 of a $150,000 purse; the next 19 finishers will split the rest. three of the 52 teams that started the race have dropped out
following the three leaders out of kaltag on sunday were four-time champion rick swenson, joe garnie of teller in fifth place, and herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref, who for days had held a close second behind redington, fell to sixth
american mushers from outside alaska were paced by robin jacobson of minnetonka, minn., in 15th place. john patten of grand marais, minn., was 22nd; frank teasley, jackson, wyo., 26th; terry adkins, mikado, mich., 34th; dan mceachen, snowmass village, colo., 29th; and stan ferguson, philadelphia, 46th
jacques philip, of thomery, france, led the foreign mushers in 14th place. horst maas, of lenz, austria, was in 23rd; peter thomann of tagish in canada's yukon territory, was 31st; ian mackenzie of bruce mines, ontario, 40th; brian carver of melbourne, australia, 44th; and lesley anne monk of worsthorne, england, 48th
farmers who prayed for rain during a devastating three-year drought have faced nearly four months of almost daily downpours, which threaten to wash away any chance of an agricultural rebound
the rains that began in november have caused widespread flooding in rural areas, swelling rivers, turning streets into streams, and virtually isolating some villages by knocking out phone lines and bridges
it also has severely hampered the recovery of farmers who five months ago were in the throes of drought, the agriculture minstry said monday
last week, eight soldiers drowned while fording a flood-swollen river in the eastern highlands. by the weekend, police said 66 people had been killed by lightning since the first storms broke
we're working all hours and weekends too,'' said temba munyarara, a handyman who works mainly in poor black suburbs. ``it's sad to see the damage that's being done but it's been good for me.''
it is in the countryside, where most of zimbabwe's 8.2 million people live, that floods threaten agricultural recovery after the long drought. about 70 percent of the population depends on agriculture for income
likewise, the bulk of the land-locked nation's export income comes from cash crops such as cotton, coffee, corn, sugar, tea and tobacco
last year, agricultural output fell 18 percent, or $180 million, as a result of drought
business trends, the standard chartered bank's monthly economic analysis, reported that the losses would be recouped with the onset of the regular rains
but the agriculture ministry's most recent crop and livestock report says that in most areas, further widespread rain will ``do more harm than good.''
cotton, peanuts and tobacco are being severely damaged, the report said, but it predicted that if the rains ease off, zimbabwe still can expect bumper harvests
the report also said ample water has been stored underground and in lakes and dams to carry zimbabwe through the coming dry season, which usually lasts from may to october
placido domingo and agnes baltsa are two opera stars who know how to put passion and drama into their singing even when they're not performing in a staged production
the tenor and the mezzo-soprano demonstrated their talents in a gala concert sunday night at the metropolitan opera. the benefit for the met pension fund was sponsored by the metropolitan opera guild and followed by a champagne supper, underwritten by merrill lynch and co
since most operatic love duets are written for tenors and sopranos, domingo and miss baltsa sang three duets of a more confrontational nature. their voices blended beautifully but made the sparks fly
they sang a dramatic scene from verdi's ``aida,'' in which amneris makes one last offer to radames _ take me and save your life. even on that basis, he turns her down
they sang santuzza angrily accusing turiddu of being unfaithful in mascagni's ``cavalleria rusticana'' and turiddu being angry back, lying and denying it
and, building to the most familiar but still the most spine-tingling, they sang don jose pleading with carmen to take him back in act 4 of bizet's ``carmen.'' when she turns him down, he stabs her to death. in that number, the chorus, facing the audience, was too loud. in staged performances, the chorus is behind the ``bullring'' at the back of the stage
domingo has a glorious voice for everything he sang. in a ``luisa miller'' aria, for instance, he was vocally always masculine and strong but could at the same time sound soft and tender in the quiet lines. he was completely equal to the verdi music but never overpowered it
miss baltsa's voice sounds dark in its low tones and light, almost white, in its top. there isn't a break in her register; her voice seems to shade gradually. in her first aria, from rossini's ``the lady of the lake,'' it was a bit disconcerting. then one became used to it. she used that shading and other vocal colors to strong dramatic effect, especially as carmen
she sang the title role in ``carmen'' at the met last season. this season the concert is her only appearance
domingo, who made his met debut in ``cavalleria rusticana,'' is singing in ``the tales of hoffmann'' and ``otello'' at the met this season
nello santi conducted. the orchestra played overtures by rossini and verdi and a mascagni intermezzo and sounded clear and fresh. the chorus, with the women in gowns of their choice, also sounded splendid in verdi's ``anvil chorus'' from ``il trovatore'' and ``va, pensiero'' from ``nabucco.''
an archaeological team has found pottery from a vessel that sank about 2,400 years ago in the mediterranean sea, a spokesman for the group said monday
divers found the wreck site buried in mud and silt in the crater of a submerged volcano near the island of isola panarea off northern sicily, said the spokesman for marine archaeological research for europe
one diver wrote in the team's log that the wreck looks ``as if the gods had been sitting down to a banquet, and then, for some reason, they had to dash off, overturning the tables in their haste and knocking down all the crockery,'' the spokesman said
the cups, plates, jugs, bowls and lamps are made of red clay and painted with a high-quality, black glaze, said the spokeman, who asked not to be identified
all that is visible on the seabed is a spread of pottery,'' he said. ``it is too early to judge with any confidence how much of the wreck survives
rebels derailed and ransacked a passenger train, killing at least five people, a government newspaper reported monday
the islamic information center newspaper focus, however, reported that 30 people died in the uganda people's army attack saturday near nagongera, about 140 miles east of the capital city of kampala
focus said the dead included civilians and eight government soldiers who were disarmed and shot to death by the rebels
the government-owned new vision newspaper said the attack took place on a newly reopened route
an unidentified passenger said the rebels initially asked passengers for money and clothes and left people in their underwear
the rebels are among more than half a dozen groups fighting president yoweri museveni's government. they say they are loyal to peter otai, defense minister under former president milton obote, who ruled from 1980-85
museveni seized power in 1986 after waging a five-year bush war. ^by mary campbell</byline>
