the return of the auto carrier green bay, which was built last year in japan, has complicated efforts by honda to become the first japanese automaker to ship its u.s.-manufactured cars to japan
a spokeswoman for the shipping agent said she had no idea when the vessel would depart again. june ainge, district manager for williams dimond &amp; co. of portland, said repair crews planned to examine the vessel monday
the japanese-built ship left portland last week with 540 accords and 100 honda motorcyles on board. sen. bob packwood, r-ore., and tetsuo chino, president of honda north america inc., participated in a news conference to mark the occasion. chino drove the first car on board
on sunday, the ship slipped in to the swan island drydock
ms. ainge refused to reveal details of the ship's problems or its return
francois l. elmealeh of the port of portland's marine marketing department said he didn't know the details of the ship's problems but that it was of a ``non-life-threatening, non-cargo-threatening nature.''
i think it's an embarrassment more than anything,'' elmealeh said
honda motor co. ltd. had planned a gala reception to welcome the vessel march 22 at narashino port, east of tokyo
the party's postponed, and we're not sure now when it will be held,'' said bret anderson, a honda public relations official in tokyo
