the wife of a convicted smuggler testified monday that she disliked her husband's job with alleged smuggler carlos lehder rivas, but wound up as paymaster for his crew
lehder, 38, is on trial on charges that he and others conspired to smuggling 3.3 tons of cocaine into florida and georgia from colombia via norman's cay in the bahamas from 1978 to 1980
the witness' husband, ed ward, has testified he was the pilot on most of those flights
emilie lassie ward said she met her husband in 1976 and became aware that he was involved in smuggling marijuana before their marriage that summer and confronted him with it
he told me he was smuggling marijuana. i didn't like it. i was very much in love with him and he rationalized it,'' she said
ward took her into his confidence as his ``what if'er.''
as he planned his smuggling operations, ``i would say `what if this happened'?'' she said
all the time, she said she was concerned
i was worried about him getting arrested and worried about him being killed,'' she testified
in 1978, she and her husband discussed lehder's offer to transport cocaine
i didn't like it. it was the fear of cocaine. i didn't know anything about it. it didn't seem like what he was doing was safe,'' she said
she said ward agreed to make 10 cocaine flights for lehder, but she said he quickly became disenchanted
ward, who was very organized, had to deal with uncertain time schedules and that lehder wasn't following the safety measures that ward insisted upon, she said
mrs. ward described her duties in the smuggling organization as counting and handing out the money to ward's crew
lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders in the violent colombian medellin cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise
co-defendant jack carlton reed, 57, of san pedro, calif., is charged only with being a part of the smuggling conspiracy
texas lost another round monday in its battle to keep florida citrus out of the state when a federal judge refused to block those shipments
u.s. district judge filemon vela said he needed more time to study the state's request for a stay of a u.s. department of agriculture decision lifting a ban on florida citrus to other producing states
texas sought the stay until its suit against u.s. secretary of agriculture ricdard e. lyng could be heard. the state sued lyng on wednesday, accusing the usda of violating the adminstrative procedures act when it lifted the 3{-year quarantine on florida citrus
texas contends the usda did not provide an opportunity to comment on the decision as required by law
monday's hearing was the second time since texas sued lyng that vela denied the state's request for a stay of the feb. 11 usda ruling
vela gave texas five days to provide its evidence, from which he will make a ruling
texas officials say they want to keep florida citrus out of the state because they are not convinced an outbreak of bacterial citrus canker has been controlled in florida. the usda quarantined fruit from florida after the disease was discovered there in august 1984
canker, which comes in different strains, can cause defoliation of trees, lesions that make the fruit unmarketable and premature dropping of fruit from trees
assistant u.s. attorney jeanette mercado, representing the usda, argued taht texas has no standing to sue because a quarantine affecting one industry lacks general importance for the state's population as a whole
texas citrus mutual, a growers' organization, has joined the state in its lawsuit
we feel like that if we can get a federal court to address whether the usda violated their own administrative procedures, we think we'll prevail,'' said ray prewett, executive vice president of mcallen-based tcm
bobby mckown of florida citrus mutual said florida suspended shipments of fresh citrus to texas, california, arizona and louisiana on friday, pending the outcome of monday's hearing
we feel much encouraged and we're going to commence shipping today fruit from florida to the citrus producing states,'' mckown said
florida's primary interest in the texas market is in specialty fruits, such as tangeloes and honey tangerines, he said
texas officials are seeking to at least keep the fruit out of the rio grande valley, where the state's $65 million industry is concentrated in the three southernmost counties
last fall, the usda published a proposal to lift the florida quarantine, but on jan. 5 withdrew the proposal after new canker outbreaks were discovered
on feb. 15, four days after usda lifted the quarantine, texas imposed an emergency 30-day quarantine on fresh florida citrus, and set up highway roadblocks
a federal judge in austin overturned the texas quarantine march 1, ruling the federal regulation took precedence
a gulf coast area of florida infested with the aggressive asiatic strain of canker will remain under quarantine
charleston county schools are segregated and local school boundaries hamper integration, an expert witness said monday as the plaintiff's case in the seven-year-old federal desegregation suit neared a close
the schools are racially segregated,'' said william gordon, a professor of education at wright state university in dayton, ohio
gordon, armed with a thick black notebook containing results of a lengthy study of the schools, said the boundaries of eight local districts within the countywide district hamper both integration and good education
gordon took the stand as testimony resumed following a two-month break
the suit centers on a 1967 state law which consolidated the county schools under a countywide
the complaint by the u.s. justice department alleges that control of student and faculty assignments were retained by the local districts for racial reasons
gordon testified on behalf of the legal defense fund which has intervened on behalf of the families of several charleston county school children in the case
the justice department has completed its case and the legal defense fund is expected to wrap up its case by midweek. u.s. district judge sol blatt jr. is hearing the non-jury trial
the complaint asks that blatt find the local district boundaries unconstitutional and order steps to promote integration. blatt has ruled out busing as a possible remedy
gordon testified that about a third of the schools in the county can be identified as black, a third white and a third racially mixed. his guideline for determining a racially identifiable school is whether the black-white student ratio is more than 15 percent different from the black-white mix countywide
gordon said that of 35 schools that opened as identifiably white schools, 17 are still white. of the 20 that opened as identifiably black schools, 17 are still black
the system of local district lines means ``you take away good solid educational choices from those who should be making the decisions,'' gordon said. ``the boundary becomes the decision.''
educators should be making the decisions where children go to school, not boundaries,'' he added
he said adherence to the local boundaries has meant overcrowding in some county schools while others aren't being used to capacity
kansas sen. bob dole, saying he would lose people's trust ``if i cut and run the first bad news we get,'' said monday he has no plans to drop his presidential bid after tuesday's illinois primary even if george bush scores another big victory
i've made a judgment that illinois, whatever happens, we're going to keep going,'' dole said at a news conference
he acknowledged the possibility that a candidate might not understand when to get out
now if you're out there and you've been twisting in the wind for six or eight months and you're starting to smell a little, somebody has to cut the rope,'' he said
still, despite polls showing bush with a lead among illinois republicans of up to 34 points over dole, the senator said, ``we believe the bounce is starting to wear of a bit from super tuesday.''
he referred to the effects of last tuesday when bush won 16 primaries to surge far ahead of the rest of the gop presidential field
i think we've made some inroads,'' said dole when asked about his prospects in illinois. ``i don't think we've had quite enough time. it's a big state.''
he said a ``realistic estimate'' of his prospects would be 40 percent of the 82 delegates to be elected in the primary
dole said that when a decision is made about the future of his candidacy ``it will be made by bob dole.''
to emphasize his determination to fight on, dole planned to campaign tuesday in wisconsin and connecticut, two of the next battlegrounds in the race
hammering away at bush for refusing to participate in a one-on-one debate, dole said, ``why should somebody who's as far ahead as he is be afraid to stand up and debate issues with somebody he indicated doesn't have any leadership ability
i think it's a mark of weakness that he's unwilling with this big, big lead he has, to say, sure i'll take on bob dole any day of the week. why shouldn't he?
i may be a pushover. but i dare him to try it.''
in a speech to the chicago council on foreign relations, dole referred to ``the point where presidential advisers are peddling arms to the ayatollah while others hear no evil, see no evil,'' an obvious reference to bush
when dole was asked why he didn't attack bush more on iran-contra, he said, ``if i hit him, i get ronald reagan first and then they say, oh, oh, he's out there attacking ronald reagan
it's pretty hard to reach bush _ except by telephone.''
part of the stage collapsed at the beginning of an inaugural concert at a theater in southeastern brazil, injuring 55 musicians
about 100 members of the sao paulo symphony orchestra and the americana lyric theater had just begun performing the national anthem when rear tiers of the stage caved in, dropping some musicians nine feet to the floor
the incident occured march 4 in americana, a city 360 miles southwest of rio with a population of 122,000
many of those injured suffered broken arms and legs and dozens of instruments were damaged, the local jornal do brasil newspaper reported
it said the concert was being performed before an audience of 900 in the municipal theater, which had just been completed
another inaugural ceremony will be held thursday, the newspaper said
presidential candidate jesse jackson told hundreds of supporters monday that he would win the illinois primary, and not once did he mention rival sen. paul simon, whose hometown is only six miles away
on the eve of a significant breakthrough in politics in illinois ... with your help, we the people can win illinois,'' jackson told about 1,800 cheering backers, an equal mixture of blacks and whites of all ages
i tell you, we the people will win.''
according to a chicago tribune poll published monday, jackson is in a virtual dead heat with fellow democrat simon
but jackson didn't mention simon in his hour-long speech at southern illinois university at carbondale
instead, he reiterated that his candidacy represents a ``rainbow coalition,'' people of all races and age groups. ``our hope is sweeping the country,'' he said
we're running a poor campaign with a rich message,'' jackson said. ``stop drugs. save jobs. invest in our children. peace in the world.''
jackson told the crowd, on its feet through most of the speech, that the flow of drugs and drug use is the no. 1 problem in the united states
and he said that if elected president, he'd use the armed forces to fight drug trafficking
i don't want communist insurgencies from the left, and drug war lords from the right,'' said jackson, eliciting cries of, ``yes sir,'' and, ``amen.'' ``let's make america better and keep america strong.''
also, the chicago civil rights leader promoted fair prices for farmers, fair wages for workers, justice and peace
and jackson hammered away at u.s. companies that do business overseas, taking advantage of cheap labor while driving up unemployment in this country
jackson touted his managerial skills, noting that on the super tuesday campaign he spent only $100,000 in advertising, compared with his challengers who spent millions
once again, little david versus the financial giants,'' he said
i'm running the most cost-efficient campaign. i'm getting the most return on my investment,'' said jackson
the poll in monday's chicago tribune found 32 percent of the state's democratic voters supported jackson while 29 percent backed simon, and 20 percent favored massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
the poll, taken of 500 democrats likely to vote in tuesday's primary, has an error margin of plus or minus five percentage points _ making the jackson-simon race a dead heat. a sunday tribune poll had simon ahead
jackson reminded the crowd in carbondale of the civil rights struggle in the 1960s, and said a black man could be elected president if he cared about all people, as he said he did
i know just because you're born in the slum doesn't mean the slum is born in you, and you can rise above it,'' he said. ``pull your weight. let your presence be felt tomorrow.''
british agriculture minister john macgregor on monday questioned whether president reagan's administration means to end farm subsidies entirely
the administration has said it wants them phased out internationally by the year 2000. it also favors ``decoupling'' of subsidies from the prices farmers get for crops
macgregor told reporters that while he favored a substantial reduction in subsidies worldwide, removing them altogether ``is i think a debatable question because after all decoupling itself does involve subsidies and decoupling is in the american negotiating position.''
britain is one of the 12 countries in the european economic community, the main u.s. negotiating partner on issues of world farm trade. the other members are west germany, france, italy, ireland, denmark, the netherlands, belgium, luxembourg, spain, portugal and greece
frans andriessen of the netherlands, who is in charge of agriculture for the european community's governing body, the european commission, told reporters recently the eec disagrees with the complete elimnination of subsidies, saying they are needed to preserve small farms. he suggested that congress and u.s. farmers would not stand for complete elimination either
others in the eec have called the u.s. goal unrealistic. macgregor said andriessen both have pointed to recent efforts by the eec to hold down spending on farm supports
according to a study published last friday by fred h. sanderson, formerly in charge of food policy at the state department, in 1986 supporting farm prices cost consumers and taxpayers about $30 billion in this country and $63 billion in 10 of the community countries. spain and portugal are not included in those figures
macgregor said he could not estimate the pace at which these costs could be reduced
secretary of state evan bayh meets a constitutional residency requirement to be governor because he always intended to return to indiana during his temporary absences, a judge ruled monday
circuit judge charles d. o'connor said that bayh has been a lifelong resident of indiana and didn't lose that residency when he worked for a district of columbia law firm in 1983 and 1984
bayh, a 32-year-old democrat who leads public opinion polls in the governor's race, said he was ``gratified but not surprised'' by the decision
but david f. mcnamar, the special counsel for the gop-controlled state election board, said he plans to appeal the ruling to the indiana supreme court
i'm going to go ahead until someone tells me to stop,'' said mcnamar
o'connor accepted the arguments presented during friday's one-day trial by bayh's attorneys, who said bayh's intention to return to his home state meant that he met a five-year residency requirement
mcnamar said he wants to give the supreme court a chance to consider his argument that the framers of the state constitution wanted a potential governor to have been physically present for five uninterrupted years before election
bayh faces active opposition from former kokomo mayor stephen j. daily in the may 3 democratic primary. senate minority leader frank l. o'bannon also has filed for the primary
lt. gov. john m. mutz is unopposed for the republican nomination to succeed gov. robert orr, who is barred by the constitution from seeking a third straight term
a soviet launch of an unmanned spacecraft similar to the u.s. space shuttle could take place this week, with a crew of two possibly heading into orbit six months later, a knowledgeable expert says
nick johnson, an advisory scientist for teledyne brown engineering in colorado springs, colo., quoted unidentified european sources close to the soviet space effort as saying the launch could be thursday or saturday, the huntsville times reported sunday
the soviets have said it is `imminent,''' said johnson, who keeps close tabs on the soviet space program. ``the frequency of reports is climbing very rapidly. it could be late next week. like any new vehicle, problems can crop up.''
johnson has written four books on the soviet program and publishes the annual soviet year in space
analysts say the first soviet reusable shuttle flight will be unmanned, with a totally computerized orbital flight, re-entry and touchdown at a landing strip next to the launch site at the baikonur cosmodrome in central asia, the newspaper said
charles vick, an employee of the space and rocket center in huntsville and a part-time soviet space analyst, said the soviet shuttle will be attached to the new heavy-lift rocket named energia, which underwent its first test flight last october
the soviet shuttle strongly resembles nasa's shuttle, but while the nasa craft has the main liquid fuel engines in the orbiter, the soviet shuttle main engines are attached to the external fuel tank, vick said
he said it has small maneuvering thrusters in the tail as well as four jet engines that give it ``go-around'' capability on landing. the u.s. shuttle glides down without power and must land on the first try
vice president george bush, playing down suggestions that he is closing in on the republican presidential nomination, said monday ``the speculation has gotten ahead of the story.''
bush's imposing lead in delegates, gained in super tuesday primaries a week ago, left his opponents wondering where to turn to revive their campaigns. illinois may not be the place; polls indicate voters in tuesday's primary are strongly pro-bush
i feel the speculation has gotten ahead of the story,'' he told reporters aboard air force ii as he headed for the state capital
bush said he wouldn't get caught up in ``a lot of premature speculation about the future'' and whether his rivals would stay in the race. but asked if he was surprised dole said he would continue his candidacy, bush said, ``i'm not sure i understand what he's doing.''
bush said the aftershock of his super tuesday sweep ``seems to be more persuasive, have a heavier impact than we would have predicted.''
at a rally here, bush said the illinois primary will be a ``national referendum'' on his candidacy
i believe if i win it tomorrow, as i think i can, i really think i will be the next president of the united states of america,'' bush told about 400 supporters in a firehouse at the capital airport in springfield
if i win convincingly, if i win to exceed expectations, you can say that in the firehouse, right here, you met with, hopefully voted for, the next president of the united states.''
recent polls show bush with an overwhelming lead over his two remaining republican rivals, dole and former television evangelist pat robertson. bush told supporters not to take comfort from his standing in the polls because such surveys had been proven wrong before
bush also emphasized his ties to president reagan
this is the presidency,'' he said. ``it is different than anything else. i've stood side by side, through thick and through thin, with a president for whom i have great respect, ronald reagan.''
bush told reporters that he was not concerned about the re-emergence of the iran-contra affair as criminal actions begin. he said it had ``no relevance to what i'm doing.''
scavengers are competing with a pilot recycling program by picking up newspapers and cans put out by residents for special collection, officials say
it's easy pickings for these scavengers to come along and supplement their income,'' says patrick barry, a recycling consultant who designed the new program in chicago's beverly neighborhood
we've got so many people putting (recyclable) material out that it's easy to pick up a ton of newspaper in an hour,'' he said
he estimated the program was losing about $200 every seven days because the scavengers were helping themselves to about four tons of newspaper weekly
barry said the neighborhood program's revenues vary from week-to-week depending on the number of tons collected, hitting a peak of about $1,400 per week. so, he estimated that the loss would represent from 15 percent to 20 percent of weekly revenues
we've got two different recycling systems converging and it's not bad from a recycling point of view,'' barry said. ``but it cuts into the money for the program.''
barry, who also is a spokesman for the greater chicago recycling industry council, an organization of 400 recycling businesses, said scavengers operate all ovr the country
they're called alley entrepreneurs,'' he said. ``some of these people have developed shrewd operations. they're not always street people. some of them are sophisticated business people who are making enough money for a bare living,'' barry said
chicago has an estimated 1,500 scavengers, he said. they make anywhere from $30 to $150 a week sifting aluminimu cans, bottles and newspaperes from the 9,000 tons of garbage produced daily in the city, he said
the city's 20 privately run recycling centers pay an average of 40 cents a pound for aluminum and about 2 cents a pound for newspaper or glass, he said
some of (the scavengers) drive station wagons or pickup trucks on routes to bars and restaurants to collect aluminum cans and bottles,'' barry said
though scavengers work throughout chicago, a group of six to eight alley entrepreneurs is taking advantage of the five-week-old recycling program in beverly on the city's southwest side, he said
the beverly program, a city pilot project and one of seven neighborhood recycling programs, has attracted the most participation from residents _ and the most attention from scavengers, barry said
the resource center, a private, non-profit recycling business that runs the beverly program, says about 60 percent of the neighborhood's residents separate newspapers, aluminum cans and other recyclable material from their garbage and leave it at the curb in special blue boxes
resource center drivers pick up the trash daily, if they get there before the alley entrepreneurs
the scavengers usually raid between 6 a.m. and 8 a.m., said ken dunn, director of the resource center
one gentleman is a minister at a small church that doesn't support him well,'' dunn said. ``so he's devised a system to recycle materials from his congregation and he also, in his free time, collects out on the streets this way to supplement his income.''
dunn said the resource center has hired some of the alley entrepreneurs to drive recycling trucks, but others say the don't want such a formal job
barry said he hopes the city council will adopt a proposed ordinance that would make it illegal for unauthorized persons to take waste set out for special recycling collections. the proposal calls for fining violators from $100 to $500
trash scavenging is going to be a problem in areas with large low-income populations,'' barry said. ``they're trying to make 10 bucks to make it through to tomorrow. you can't fault them for that.''
president reagan on monday wished west german defense minister manfred woerner success in his future post as nato secretary general and thanked him for bonn's contributions to the alliance, a german official said
woerner in july will become nato's first german secretary-general, succeeding britain's lord carrington. he arrived sunday night for two days of meetings with u.s. officials, lawmakers and the media
in addition to white house meetings with reagan and his national security adviser, lt. gen. colin l. powell, woerner lunched with defense secretary frank c. carlucci and also met with secretary of state george p. shultz
reagan and woerner agreed that the north atlantic treaty organization summit at brussels earlier this month was a success and had strengthened the alliance, said a german official who talked to a reporter on condition he not be named
the source also quoted reagan as thanking woerner for the share of the common defense borne by west germany and praising bonn's reliability as a defense partner
before departing for europe late tuesday, woerner planned talks with several members of the senate and meetings with reporters
the pentagon notified congress on monday it had approved the sale of mk-48 torpedoes to canada
assuming there are no congressional objections, canada will be offered 13 of the torpedoes for roughly $16 million, the pentagon said
the ocean systems division of gould inc. in euclid, ohio, will serve as the prime contractor and the u.s. navy will be responsible for overseeing the transaction, the pentagon added
the government of canada needs these torpedoes for its oberon-class submarines,'' the pentagon said. ``these torpedoes can also be used on replacement submarines planned ... for the 1990s.''
the nation's first research center for head injury patients adjusting to their disability will be established at the state university of new york at buffalo, school officials said monday
while four other u.s. centers treat ``traumatic brain injury'' patients in the hospital, university officials said their center is unique because it will deal with the psychological, practical and social problems of returning to normal life
patients go back with their families, even if they didn't live there before. and now what do you do?'' said barry willer, co-director of the center and associate professor of psychiatry
the center will be funded primarily by a five-year, $3 million grant from the u.s. department of education, with $2 million more from funding of ongoing research
recent advances in emergency medical care, stemming from techniques developed largely during the vietnam war, have increased the number of those suffering from severe brain injuries, willer said. years ago people with severe brain injuries would have died
the $5 million grant is part of a national push from the federal government to help traumatic brain-injured patients, school officials said
the injury to white house press secretary james brady, who was shot in the 1981 assassination attempt of preside wouldn't have gone after them,'' hill said of pickens
homestake vice president richard w. stumbo took the bid seriously
you always take him seriously,'' stumbo said, adding he did not know if mesa's withdrawal was the end of its takeover efforts
homestake holds interests in oil and natural gas and mines uranium, silver and gold, as does newmont mining corp., another major gold producer targeted in an earlier, unsuccessful hostile takeover bid by pickens
new york-based newmont was approached last year by ivanhoe partners, a group led by pickens, which made a $2 billion hostile bid for control of the company
a delaware court blocked the move in october when it upheld a ``market sweep'' in which newmont's biggest shareholder, britain's consolidated gold fields plc, grabbed enough shares in a two-day buying spree to raise its holdings to nearly 50 percent of newmont and thwart the hostile bid
pickens' reputation as a corporate raider was made with high-profile bids for several major oil companies in the early 1980s, including gulf corp., phillips petroleum co. and unocal corp
mesa launched hostile takeover attempts, then pocketed millions of dollars in profits when some of the target companies either were bought out by a higher bidder or repurchased their own stock
temperatures typical of the middle of winter covered much of the eastern two-thirds of the nation monday, with record lows across the south, and snow flakes fell as far south as georgia
afternoon temperatures were below freezing as far south as the southern appalachians, kentucky, southern missouri and northern kansas
record lows included 18 at abilene, texas; 19 at albuquerque, n.m.; 26 at dallas-fort worth; 17 at midland, texas; and 20 at san angelo, texas. shreveport, la., tied its record of 29. abilene's former record of 20 had been on the books since 1895
more record low temperatures were expected across the gulf states tuesday and wednesday mornings
a freeze warning was posted overnight across all of georgia, alabama and mississippi, and inland sections of northwestern florida
snow flurries fell as far south as atlanta while sections of the tennessee and ohio valleys received a dusting of snow during the morning
snow flurries also were reported over the appalachians, in parts of virginia and across southern new england
moisture from the great lakes continued to produce lake effect snow squalls across the southern shores of lakes erie, michigan and superior. snow continued to fall over in extreme northern wisconsin, where total accumulation since saturday could reach just over 2 feet along the southern edge of lake superior
during the morning, northeastern ohio reported 4 to 5 inches at the town of conneaut, the national weather service said. five inches of snow fell in sections of western new york
another storm system began gathering strength in canada, just north of western montana. heavy snow began falling during the morning in northwestern montana and a section of northern idaho and snow was expected to spread across much of montana and wyoming by wednesday
elsewhere, showers produced rain over extreme southern sections of florida
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 15 degrees at alpena, mich., to 77 at palm springs, calif. the low for the day was 20 degrees below zero at chadron, neb
for tuesday, snow showers were forecast from the great lakes across the upper ohio valley and the northern and central appalachians to new england. snow also was forecast from northern and central rockies to the western borders of south dakota and nebraska
highs in the 20s or 30s were predicted from the northern and central atlantic coast states across the appalachians, the ohio and tennessee valleys, the great lakes, and the northern halves of the mississippi valley, plains and rockies; in the 60s in southern florida and across most of texas and new mexico; in the 60s or 70s in much of arizona, southern nevada and california; a few 80s in the desert southwest; and in the 40s or 50s elsewhere. up at 3rd graf, ``i've spent''</note>
president and mrs. reagan are hopeful that son michael's book describing a troubled childhood and family problems will help others in similar situations, a white house spokeswoman said monday
michael reagan, 43, has just completed his autobiography, ``on the outside looking in,'' to be published by zebra books. in an interview with people magazine, the adopted son of the president said he grew up resentful and ``didn't feel i belonged in so perfect a family.''
i've spent my life trying to figure out how to make ronald reagan my friend,'' the younger reagan said
the president and first lady read michael's book over the weekend at camp david, md., called him sunday evening to compliment him on it, said mrs. reagan's press secretary, elaine crispen
they thought it was very good, very interesting,'' mrs. crispen said
the couple told michael they hoped it would ``help other children who went through the same situation _ molestation _ and help other children adjust to adoption,'' mrs. crispen quoted mrs. reagan as saying
the first lady was referring to a section of the book in which michael describes how he was molested and photographed in the nude by a day-camp leader when he was seven years old. he had kept the incident secret until last year
the book also contains reports of arguments between michael and his stepmother. asked if the reagans had been concerned that the book might be critical of them, mrs. crispen said that was not the case
they said the book was good, and that if you read it all, it comes out balanced,'' the spokeswoman said
michael reagan was adopted when his father was married to actress jane wyman. the couple also had a daughter, maureen. after divorcing miss wyman, reagan married actress nancy davis and fathered two other children, ron and patti
in his book, michael relates how he set out last year to find out who his biological mother was and that the president helped by calling the governor of california
when my father helped me with this, it was the biggest gift he ever gave me. he set me free,'' people magazine quotes reagan as saying
reagan learned that he was born out of wedlock to irene flaugher lange, who gave him up at birth in los angeles in 1945 and later worked as a movie bit player under the name betty arnold. she married an ohio restaurateur and had a son, barry lange, and died in 1985
reagan's half-brother visited him and brought an album their mother had kept that was full of pictures and clippings of the reagans
it was the most wonderful feeling in the world when i found out she knew all along who i was, and that this mother had kept track of this child,'' reagan said
reagan and his father had a long talk in january in which michael said he told his father of the feelings of abandonment he suffered as he was growing up
he quoted his father as saying, ``my god, i thought just telling you i loved you was all i had to do.''
newborn babies in 30 cities will be checked for aids antibodies in anonymous tests the federal centers for disease control hopes will provide an early and broader look at who is getting the disease
the tests, to be at selected hospitals, are part of a series of surveys designed to eventually test 1.6 million americans a year for acquired immune deficiency syndrome
blood samples from the newborns will be sent without names for testing, cdc spokeswoman gayle lloyd said monday. the study hopes to determine the extent to which aids has penetrated heterosexual women of child-bearing age, thought to be a low-risk group
other programs, some of which are already under way, will test blood samples from sexually transmitted disease clinics, drug clinics, tuberculosis clinics, military recruits, job corps blood donors and others, she said
some tests will be routine and anonymous while others will be voluntary with confidential results, she said
early results are expected next fall, and the findings probably will determine which programs are continued, she said. the cdc is helping finance the programs at a cost of an estimated $47 million for fiscal 1988
some doctors say it violates ethics to test samples from known people without permission and that getting permission would narrow the population being tested
this is the least offensive way of getting a reliable general population sample,'' dr. tim dondero, chief of surveillance and evaluation for the cdc's aids program
others question whether it is ethical not to tell a patient something he or she should know
to simply have the results and not have the ability to do something with the results isn't a completely reasonable position, is it?'' asked dr. wade parks, a pediatrics professor at the miami school of medicine
only about half the babies who test positively carry the virus. the others get a dose of antibody proteins from their infected mothers. a positive antibodies test on a baby proves only that the mother carries the virus
similar tests on 30,000 newborns in massachusetts revealed that one of every 476 women giving birth there was infected. not all who carry the virus eventually develop aids
the newborns will be tested in 20 cities with a high aids incidence. they are atlanta, baltimore, boston, chicago, cleveland, dallas, denver, detroit, houston, jacksonville, fla., los angeles, miami, new orleans, new york, newark, n.j., richmond, va., san francisco, san juan, puerto rico, st. louis, and washington
tests also will be done in the low-incidence cities of albuquerque, n.m., honolulu, kansas city, mo., memphis, tennessee, minneapolis, new haven, conn., phoenix, ariz., rochester, n.y., salt lake city and seattle
acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the body's ability to ward off disease. it is transmitted through sexual contact with an infected person, shared hypodermic needles and blood transfusions, and can be passed from mothers to their offspring. there is no known cure
since june, 1981 there have been 55,167 cases counted in the united states and 30,932 patients have died
university of minnesota officials said monday they hope to quickly name an interim president to replace kenneth keller, who resigned amid controversy about the cost of renovating his official residence and campus office
meanwhile, gov. rudy perpich withdrew his request for an appropriation of $23.1 million to fund keller's program, called ``commitment to focus,'' to raise standards at the university while cutting undergraduate enrollment
perpich said support for the funding had dwindled because of the controversy over the renovations
keller, president of the university for three years, met privately with perpich before calling a news conference late sunday night to announce his departure
at no time did i discuss that he resign, absolutely not,'' perpich told a news conference
however, perpich said he told keller he had two options: ``either leave, or you have a very dramatic plan...to continue with focus and get the university back on track.'''
perpich said the board of regents should consider using a portion of a $53 million reserve fund to meet the immediate needs of the quality-improvement program, which the governor said he continues to support
the existence of the reserve fund was revealed last week as a result of audits ordered after news reports raised questions about the renovations
news reports said that $1.5 million had been spent to renovate eastcliff, the university president's mansion, and $200,000 was spent remodeling keller's campus office suite
the regents never gave formal approval for the mansion renovation, which was orginally supposed to cost $400,000, the legislative auditor's office said
among the most embarrassing expenditures were those for a mahogany desk and credenza for keller's office that the legislative auditor said cost $17,445. keller has offered to pay for the office furniture
the university reportedly met the cost overruns by dipping into the reserve fund, which included profits from book stores, parking lots and temporary investments. the audits released last week did not question the legality of the fund, but criticized accounting and reporting procedures
earlier monday, david lebedoff, chairman of the 12-member board of regents, said he hoped an interim president could be named at a special meeting wednesday. selection of a permanent replacement could take months
lebedoff, who headed a search committee that recommended keller to be president of the 55,000-student school, pledged continued support for commitment to focus
all of my life i will be proud that we selected a president who came up with a plan to make this university even better,'' lebedoff said
some lawmakers had criticizeed the focus program as smacking of elitism, and the $23.1 million proposed by perpich for the program was $12 million less than the university had requested
legedoff said the regents should have demanded an accounting of the remodeling projects, but added that under existing guidelines the spending should have been reported
keller, 53, apologized in his resignation statement sunday
over the past few weeks, you and i have lived with stories about eastcliff renovations and repairs,'' keller said
the stories have not been good ones,'' he said. ``i bear a key responsibility for it. ... i am profoundly embarrassed and profoundly sorry for it.''
the legislative auditor's report said the involvement of keller and his wife, university attorney bonita sindelir, in the renovation led to some of the spending on the mansion was revealed in news media reports in early february. keller annoyed some legislators by going to hawaii on a vacation instead of being available to answer questions about the remodeling
keller, a native of new york city, came to the university in 1964 as an assistant professor in chemical engineering and materials science, and became a department head in 1979
the state board of education is studying a proposal to test students about their understanding of aids prevention, but the legislature is considering action to kill the program
there are states doing innovative things in the area of aids education, but minnesota is the first i've heard about that is trying to mandate assessment this way,'' said katherine fraser, co-director of the aids education project of the national association of state boards of education
it's a good idea because it involves an educational program aimed at changing behavior and that's what is really needed to fight aids,'' she said
fraser commented last week after the state board of education took the first steps toward requiring students in the sixth and 10th grades to be tested on their knowledge of aids prevention
the proposal also would require school districts to teach courses on prevention of aids and other communicable diseases in kindergarten through the senior year of high school
the proposal still faces public hearings and the scrutiny of an administrative law judge before taking effect. department of education officials say the process will take about 10 months to a year and cost $10,000 to $20,000
a bill pending in the legislature which would block board's plan was passed unanimously by the school finance division of the house education committee friday and will be discussed wednesday before the full house education committee
we disagree on mandating. we think school districts in minnesota have good progams in place, and we'd like to continue to help them do that. taking the time and money to develop a rule might upset this progress,'' said state rep. bob mceachern, sponsor of the move to block the board's proposal
fraser says the school boards association backs mandatory aids education because it means local school boards do not have to face as much controversy from people offended by discussion of aids. ``they can just say, `it's the requirement. let's work on how we can meet it,''' she said
according to the minnesota department of education, about 386 minnesota school districts say they have some kind of aids education, but provide no information on what kind. that means about 50 districts still don't have any type of aids education
board member john plocker, who prefers a voluntary approach, said the board still wants local school boards to shape their programs. ``we're just telling them they have to do it. there's still a lot of latitude,'' he said. subs 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``it's not over, with 4 grafs new dole quotes</note>
bob dole declared monday ``it's not over'' for his republican presidential campaign despite indications of a big illinois victory for george bush, but democrat paul simon admitted ``i have no plans beyond tomorrow'' and the home-state primary he needs to win
with five presidential candidates racing around the state in a final day of campaigning, jesse jackson was buoyed by a poll suggesting he may have pulled even with fellow favorite son simon
on the eve of a significant breakthrough ... with your help, we the people can win illinois,'' jackson told a cheering crowd of about 1,800 in carbondale, ill. ``i tell you, we the people will win.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, lying third, sought a good enough showing to keep up some momentum from super tuesday. over and over on monday, dukakis hammered at simon's contention that the democratic convention will be deadlocked
it ``would be a disaster'' for the democrats to end the primary process without a nominee-to-be, dukakis said, with ``negotiating, dealing, people behind closed doors trying to decide who the nominee ought to be.''
the problem for dole was much more immediate than the conventions, months away in the summer. the kansas republican was looking for a way to keep his campaign alive in the face of a string of bush victories
it's not over for bob dole,'' he told the executives club of chicago
later, at a news conference, dole repeated his determination to continue beyond tuesday: ``i've made a judgment that illinois, whatever happens, we're going to keep going.''
the kansas senator said he had ``made some inroads'' against bush in illinois, but that there had not been enough time to stop bush's surge after a 16-state win last tuesday
you want to elect momentum or elect the better candidate?'' he asked the executives club audience. ``maybe it's going to take a couple of weeks for everything to sort of slow down.''
but the illinois outlook for dole was not good
a chicago tribune poll said bush was the choice of 62 percent of the likely gop voters in illinois, with only 28 percent for dole
such a strong showing could give bush a big chunk of the 82 republican delegates at stake in illinois. added to his current total of 705 delegates, it could give him more than 60 percent of the 1,139 needed to win the nomination at the gop national convention in new orleans in august. dole has 165
despite the numbers, bush told a reporter that suggestions he has locked up the nomination are premature
i feel the speculation has gotten ahead of the story,'' bush said as he flew on air force two from chicago to springfield, ill. however, when asked if he were surprised that dole was staying in the race, he replied: ``i'm not sure i understand what he's doing.''
on the democratic side, simon was facing the reality that he has to win the illinois primary to keep even his stripped-down campaign alive until the democratic national convention in july
i have no plans beyond tomorrow,'' he said in chicago. ``i have to win and i will win. but obviously michigan and wisconsin come next.''
and second place isn't good enough
a strong second isn't very strong,'' simon told a reporter. if he does end up in second place in either delegates or the popular vote in illinois, he said, ``i'd have to reevaluate.''
one poll published monday in the chicago tribune suggested simon faces the possibility of a second-place finish
the survey, conducted friday and saturday, said 32 percent of likely democratic voters supported jackson, 29 percent backed simon and 20 percent said they would vote for dukakis. rep. richard gephardt of missouri was the choice of 5 percent and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee had the backing of 4 percent
the poll, conducted by peter hart research associates, interviewed 500 people and had a potential margin of error of 5 percentage points
an abc news-washington post poll, conducted saturday and sunday and published monday in the newspaper, gave simon the lead with 39 percent support to jackson's 34 percent among very likely democratic voters. dukakis had 17 percent with gore and gephardt far behind. the potential sampling error was plus or minus 6 percentage points
going into the illinois primary, dukakis held the lead in the associated press delegate count, with 463 to 424 for jackson. gore had 353 and simon just 36
a total of 173 delegates are at stake on the democratic side in illinois
one dukakis goal is to win some of those delegates, a difficult task given the complicated nature of the state's ballot. voters not only cast ballots for presidential candidates, they also vote directly for delegate candidates. thus, a vote for dukakis in the ``beauty contest'' portion does not necessarily mean a vote for him in the delegate selection process
another goal, dukakis aides said privately, is to narrow the democratic field. mentioning the polls showing dukakis drawing his last-minute support from simon's voters, the governor's aides said they would be delighted to see jackson beat simon, believing it would drive the senator from the race
jack roland murphy was always successful: a violin player with the pittsburgh symphony, a tennis star in college, onetime national surfing champion
later, he became famous as murph the surf: playboy, jewel thief, murderer. now, murphy calls himself a ``frontline christian soldier,'' an ex-convict who has ``dedicated the rest of my life to the lord.''
i've got what they call chain-gang religion, jailhouse religion, and it's easy for people to scoff at it,'' murphy said during a recent interview at the bridge, a prison work-release facility in orlando
murphy, 50, said he has traveled more than 100,000 miles to counsel prisoners and has given his christian testimony at hundreds of schools and churches
he was paroled in november 1986 after 19 years in florida prisons. one of the conditions of his release was that he spend his time helping others by preaching and teaching
many are watching and judging, he knows
they remember that it was murphy who stole the star of india, a 563-carat sapphire, in a spectacular heist from the museum of natural history in new york in 1964, along with a 100-carat ruby and 20 other gems
they remember too that he was convicted of murder in the 1967 slayings of two women whose bludgeoned bodies were found dumped in whiskey creek, a tidal waterway between miami and fort lauderdale. prosecutors said the two women were killed over $488,000 worth of negotiable securities they stole from their employer
there will always be critics or skeptics who don't believe in born-again experiences,'' murphy said. ``but i guarantee it happens and has happened to me.''
those he works with believe in him and his work
his goal is to help prisoners come to christ,'' said the rev. george crossley. ``he wants to help fight crime and wage war on drugs. i believe churchgoers should support jack murphy's ministry.''
vernon rainwater, head of central florida's youth for christ, echoes crossley's statements
i've heard nothing but real good reports on jack murphy since he has been paroled,'' rainwater said. ``he has been a good representative of the christian community.''
murphy said he is just starting
i have a number of mentors who have been down the road before. good christians. prison chaplains. people who care about people
jesus told us to represent him in jerusalem. my jerusalem is in the jails. . . the jails are the places i least want to be. but it's there i believe god wants me to be. it is where he allowed me to grow up.''
murphy married catherine collins, who visited him in prison for 12 years, last december. she frequently travels with him on speaking engagements. he is sometimes paid by groups that ask him to speak. other income comes from the sale of paintings he did while in prison
i don't have wealth. i don't have material things. i go from month to month, but god provides,'' he said. ``i never could have imagined the peace, quality and joy of such a life.''
to those who doubt or scoff, murphy said, ``if you don't believe me, just watch me.''
officials of the soviet communist party met monday with representatives of the nicaraguan government and signed an agreement of cooperation, the tass news agency reported
it did not describe the agreement
the report said the sandinistas stressed their determination to defend their government against u.s.-backed rebels, known as contras, and to seek political settlement of the central american conflicts
tass said the soviets ``declared invariable support for the struggle of nicaragua for freedom and independence, its constructive moves, as well as efforts of the contadora group and other latin american countries aimed at a peaceful settlement of the conflicts in the region, with strict observance of the right of any nation to its own social and political choice.''
the contadora group was formed in january 1983 by mexico, venezuela, colombia and panama at a meeting on panama's contadora island with the aim of resolving armed conflicts in central america
tass said the sandinista delegation met with anatoly f. dobrynin, a secretary of the communist party central committee and a former ambassador to the united states, and karen brutents, deputy head of the central committee's international department
tass said the sandinista delegation was led by bayardo arce, deputy coordinator of the ruling sandinista national liberation front
it gave no other details of the meeting
albert gore jr., campaigning against long odds in illinois' democratic primary, looked ahead monday to the rest of the northern industrial states and said he would ``compete everywhere and look for an opportunity to punch through'' with a victory
the tennessee senator flew around illinois in a final day of campaigning before tuesday's primary, repeatedly describing himself as the alternative to rivals michael dukakis, paul simon and jesse jackson. he said he was encouraged about prospects in the state despite polls showing him stuck in single digits behind the others in illinois
the polls have been wrong quite frequently in this race because the voters are thinking for themselves,'' gore said at an airport news conference in peoria
gore began his day at a factory gate in rockford, ill., where he stood coatless in a light snowfall and greeted workers during a shift change before flying to peoria, springfield and champaign
speaking to reporters aboard his chartered airplane, gore said that regardless of the illinois outcome he saw the race for the democratic nomination as a battle between himself, jackson and dukakis that would be fought out in industrial states during the spring
we've got a whole series of contests between now and june 7,'' gore said. ``we're going to compete in all of them.''
needing a victory to to demonstrate appeal outside his native south, gore said he saw ``a number of opportunities for a win,'' naming connecticut, ohio, pennsylvania, new york and indiana
we're looking at the primary schedule,'' gore said. ``we're going to compete everywhere and look for an opportunity to punch through.''
gore strategist larry harrington said the campaign's aim in illinois was to be ``in the fray.'' he said the campaign had bought ``a decent or modest amount'' of television airtime in illinois, and did not dispute estimates putting the figure in the $200,000 to $300,000 range over the past week
i think we're going to do better than people expect here,'' gore said
i think there are an awful lot of voters here in illinois who want an alternative to the kind of approach offered by michael dukakis and paul simon and jesse jackson,'' gore said. ``i offer a different kind of approach.''
in springfield, he said each of those three rivals represents ``the same old formula'' that has led the democratic party to lose four out of the past five presidential elections
in peoria, home of the caterpillar tractor manufacturing company, gore said the reagan administration ``has not been willing to use the tools'' available under current trade laws to ensure fairness by foreign competitors
he also said that ``a majority of the problems identified in the trade deficit are here at home,'' citing massive federal borrowing and saying there was a need to improve education and economic policy
in springfield, gore toured a small homeless shelter and visited with a mother and her baby who live there, underscoring his call for more federal assistance to the homeless. he said much of the increase in homelessness was due to ``slashes'' in housing programs under the reagan administration
at an american legion post in chicago sunday night and again in peoria on monday, gore, a vietnam veteran, faced questions about men left behind after that war. he drew praise from other vietnam veterans when he promised to ``pursue to the ends of this earth'' any remaining leads on such men
at the university of illinois in champaign, gore stood before a cray super computer and accused the reagan administration of ``the starvation of super computing'' through denial of federal support for civilian computer research
he called for more federal money to support development of computer technology and the linking of super computers _ systems capable of performing millions of computations in an instant _ into a nationwide network
pointing to one of the rare super computers, gore referred to the confused democratic presidential race and said: ``if there's a brokered convention, this is a possibility.''
jesse jackson is within striking distance of leading the democratic race for national convention delegates, but massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, the leader in the field, is planning to pick up delegates from yet uncounted caucuses
jackson, who is favored in some polls to win his home state of illinois in tuesday's primary, could still wind up losing when the delegate prize is divided
dukakis led the democratic presidential field with 462.5 delegates, followed by jackson with 423.55. but dukakis' campaign said he stands to gain at least another 100 delegates when caucus results from texas, washington and minnesota are finally tabulated
meanwhile, jackson's campaign said that the rules in illinois do not favor him in picking up many delegates from his home state
if we get as high a percentage of delegates as we do the popular vote that would be a smashing success,'' said steve cobble, who monitors delegate selection for the jackson campaign
illinois holds a direct-election primary in which slates of delegates are elected from the ballot. presidential candidates are also listed on a ``beauty contest'' section of the ballot, but the results have no effect on picking the delegates
the jackson campaign does not expect to pick up the nearly 40 delegates needed to overtake dukakis in the national count, cobble said. at stake in illinois are 173 delegates
two recent polls show favorite sons, jackson and illinois sen. paul simon, neck-and-neck in the contest. in a chicago tribune poll, jackson edged simon 32 percent to 29 percent, while simon held a slim lead over jackson _ 39 percent to 34 percent _ in an abc news-washington post poll
but the percentages separating them were within the polls' potential margins of sampling error
simon, who needs to win in his home state to keep his political hopes alive, had 35.5 delegates. sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee was third behind dukakis and jackson with 352.8 delegates, while missouri rep. richard gephardt was in fourth place with 145 delegates
uncommitted delegates totaled 275.65 delegates. attack</head>
nisrin's mother, two sisters and three brothers are dead. the 3-year-old and her father, one leg blown away, are all the family left after 25 missiles fell on this town in a storm of explosion and fire
nisrin's head was wrapped in blood-stained bandages monday. her father mohammed amin, 54, also lay in the sulaimaniya hospital in the northern kurdistan province, his right leg missing
both were unconscious as neighbors buried the six family members and nine other people killed by the rain of short-range missiles sunday on darbandikhan. more missiles fell on nearby halabja
the attack marked resumption of the latest round in the ``war of the cities,'' which took hundreds of lives in the 12 days from its beginning feb. 29 until both iran and iraq called it off temporarily last friday
iraq retaliated for the short-range missiles by launching a rocket into tehran like scores of others it had fired into the iranian capital since the duel began
reporters were flown to darbandikhan on a tour organized by the government to publicize the damage caused by the attacks on population centers. thousands of civilians have been killed in the cities since iran and iraq went to war in september 1980
hamad mustafa, a resident, said the town ``enjoyed two quiet nights'' before sunday's barrage. he said the 70,000 people who live there had no time to run to shelters because the missiles came suddenly and continued for an hour
an army officer pointed to a mountain in the distance and said: ``this is the border.'' he said the iranians had set up a new missile position just beyond it
jafer barazanchi, the regional governor, said a ``mass evacuation'' of darbandikhan's population was being considered
mourners demanded revenge, not evacuation. about 10,000 people marched monday behind 15 coffins draped in iraqi flags, chanting slogans against ayatollah ruhollah khomeini, iran's revolutionary patriarch
at the cemetery they shouted ``death to khomeini!'' and waved a banner reading: ``fire more al hussein missiles on the criminals in iran in revenge for our people.''
iraq has given its long-range missiles the name al hussein, for a shiite moslem saint, and claims to have developed them itself. western military analysts say the missiles are soviet-made scud-bs with strap-on boosters enabling them to reach tehran, nearly 300 miles from the border. negative</head>
a study of network evening newscasts from jan. 1 through super tuesday march 8 says democrat jesse jackson got the best television coverage and republican pat robertson got the most negative
the center for media and public affairs, a non-partisan study group, said it studied 532 news items involving the election and found:
_evaluations of every major candidate, based on clearly positive or negative statements from all sources relating to character, job performance, campaign performance or issue stands, became more negative after the new hampshire primary feb. 16
_jackson suffered the least. telecast comments involving him were favorable 74 percent of the time, compared with 90 percent this year before new hampshire. he also nearly tripled his share of the democrats' coverage, from 9 percent before new hampshire to 26 percent in the weeks leading up to super tuesday, the big round of primaries and caucuses
_robertson dropped from 70 percent positive evaluations before new hampshire to 33 percent after it. comments about his prospects also became more negative
_republican george bush got his best attention in the week before the new hampshire primary _ 66 percent of the comments were favorable. since then, his favorable coverage percentage has dropped to 44 percent
the analysts also said there have been four stories on the campaign horse race for every story on policy issues since the feb. 8 iowa caucuses and the issues most frequently mentioned are taxes and trade. documents</head>
the man nominated to head the economic regulatory administration was asked to leave another government agency after providing documents to a friend who was seeking a contract, according to rep. john dingell
dingell, d-mich., chairman of the house energy and commerce committee, has written energy secretary john herrington asking the secretary to relieve the nominee in question, chandler van orman, as acting head of the era and that van orman ``refrain from participating in any sensitive matters of any kind.''
van orman was traveling monday and could not be reached, his office said. enegery department spokesman doug elmets said: ``we support chandler van orman. we feel that he is well qualified and we plan to stand behind him. we do not feel that there are unanswered allegations that would prevent him from getting this job.''
dingell earlier asked the senate energy committee to hold up van orman's confirmation until the general accounting office could report on the circumstances of van orman's replacement of marshall staunton as head of the economic regulatory administration. the era seeks refunds from overcharges when crude oil was under price controls
dingell wrote herrington that the gao investigation was still under way, but gao officials had briefed him that in february 1983, the head of the agency for international development ``asked for and received van orman's resignation.''
van orman, according to dingell's account, had given documents to a friend seeking a $450,000 contract to prepare for an international conference on a new way to cure cholera and related disorders, oral rehydration therapy
the contract was awarded but later terminated ``at some cost to the government,'' dingell wrote herrington
a memo on the stationery of the aid general counsel said it did not appear that van orman helped his friend get the contract, and he had not disclosed any classified information. the memo, which was obtained by the associated press, said the evidence assembled by the aid inspector general ``does not indicate that any statutory violation occurred,'' and van orman had not disclosed classified information, but had provided documents on at least one other occasion
aid declined to take further action after van orman resigned
the aid memo was disclosed in a letter dingell wrote the gao with further questions about van orman
van orman had served as an advance man for trips by vice president bush and president reagan when he was appointed deputy era administrator in august. he was nominated for the administrator's job in september, but did not assume the post as acting administrator until staunton left in december
the court of appeals upheld a lower court ruling monday to extradite to argentina a former major and his wife accused of kidnapping two children born to mothers held during the ``dirty war.''
the couple's lawyer, fatima de bustaller, told reporters he will appeal to the supreme court
the roman catholic radio station caritas said former maj. atilio bianco and his wife nilda susana wehrli face charges filed by the grandmothers of the plaza de mayo group of abducting a boy and girl and falsifying their birth papers during argentina's ``dirty war'' of 1976-83
the children, carolina, 12, and pablo, 10, were quoted this month in the independent daily newspaper hoy as saying they don't want to be separated from the major and his wife
we don't know anything about those supposed parents we have in argentina,'' the children were quoted as saying
the grandmothers group says bianco, a bone doctor at a military hospital in buenos aires, abducted the children shortly after their birth and falsified the attending physician's signature to make them appear to be his and his wife's offspring
neighbors say ms. wehrli was not pregnant at those times
at least 9,000 people suspected of being leftist subversives were abducted by military and paramilitary agents and vanished without a trace during what became known as the ``dirty war'' under military rule in argentina, officials say. human rights group say the number is closer to 30,000
the grandmothers group, an offshoot of the mothers of the plaza de mayo group that includes relatives who lost loved ones in the ``dirty war,'' says 72 of the 182 children taken from their parents were recovered
according to local reports, bianco submitted to a blood test in asuncion last month to determine if he was the father of the two children. results were never announced
the cases of two other couples also accused of having fled to paraguay with children suspected of having been born to mothers held in captivity in argentina are pending, authorities say
raul alfonsin was elected argentina's president in 1983, ending nearly eight years of military rule
julie and guy garner's boat disappeared, but it found its way home the next day
as ms. garner was listening to her emergency radio sunday morning, her ears perked up when she overheard someone on the radio ``call for assistance from a boat named `tradition.'''
seems that ``tradition,'' the garners' 36-foot cabin cruiser, had disappeared the previous evening from a dock in san francisco bay while the couple and friends were having dinner in san francisco. they were afraid that vandals had untied the lines and the boat was heading out to sea
as she listened to the radio the next morning, she said, ``the man aboard was saying something about waking up on the boat and not knowing how he got on board or where he was.''
there was another surprise in store for ms. garner when she turned on a scanning device that can pinpoint the boat's position
it turned out to be in the ocean right near their beachside daly city home, about 10 miles from where it was docked when it disappeared
we looked out and saw our boat sailing about a mile out,'' she said
the coast guard dispatched a crew, which intercepted the boat. san francisco police sgt. jerry senkir said edward thomas james, 26, was taken into custody for investigation of grand theft
residents of this village, settled 131 years ago by irish homesteaders, celebrated st. patrick's day a bit early with their decidedly un-irish tradition: toilet bowl racing
to the cheers of 100 onlookers sunday, two-time champion darrell knish downed a cup of beer and jumped on a bowl perched on plywood and bicycle tires
teammates whisked him down the block toward a second beer sitting on the snow-covered pavement, which he chugged before racing back up the hill ahead of a competitor
his trophy? a toilet seat cover with the names of the winning team members scrawled on the back
kilkenny, population 180, swelled by several hundred sunday as locals and visitors sprayed their hair green, painted shamrocks on buildings, and gulped homemade mulligan stew and beer
if you're going to pick a town to go to, this is it,'' said kevin taaffe of richfield, who has come to the last four st. patrick's day celebrations in kilkenny
if you don't know anybody, you'll know them before you leave town,'' said gene mach, son of the mayor
dana begley, 36, was quick to learn that. she passed through the town a while ago on a trip and liked it so much that she and her children moved here from southern california
kilkenny was all-irish at its founding in 1857, but mobility and marriage have gradually reduced the ranks
there are a few around here who are 100 percent irish, but not many,'' said ann sheridan, 62, one of the 100 percenters. ``but even if the people aren't irish, on st. patrick's day, they're all irish.''
as put by donald kewatt, tapping his foot to the beat in the lions den: ``i'm german, but i help 'em celebrate.''
the sentencing of former presidential aide lyn nofziger was postponed monday from march 25 until april 8 to give defense lawyers more time to study a report being prepared by the federal probation office
u.s. district judge thomas a. flannery granted the defense request to postpone the sentencing. the request was not opposed by independent counsel james c. mckay
nofziger, who was white house political director from 1981 until early 1982, was convicted last month of three counts of illegally lobbying former colleagues in the reagan administration on behalf of private clients
he faces a potential two-year prison term and a $10,000 fine on each count
an asian businessman identified as the drug enforcement agency's no. 1 heroin target has been arrested and charged with importing 1,000 pounds of heroin from southeast asia over three years, authorities said monday
the drug ring run by kon yu-leung kon was much larger than those in such well-known heroin smuggling cases as the french connection or the pizza connection, said robert stutman, head of the dea's new york office
the french connection involved 70 pounds of heroin, the pizza connection about 200, he said
heroin trafficking ``is now controlled by chinese ethnic groups that are bringing in vast amounts to the united states, in amounts far more than any of us who have been professionals in the field ever thought possible,'' stutman said
u.s. attorney andrew maloney said federal authorities lured kon to new york, where he was arrested sunday night in front of the new york hilton hotel. the 44-year-old kon was charged under an indictment handed up in december
maloney refused to give details of the arrest
stutman said that although kon is charged with importing 1,000 pounds of heroin, it is believed he is responsible for bringing in twice that amount
the heroin was smuggled into the country from 1984 to 1987 through various means, including suitcases and shipments of vases, ice buckets, t-shirts and wall plaques, said maloney
couriers then carried millions of dollars in proceeds back to hong kong to be laundered, authorities said. kon allegedly used $20 million to buy commercial real estate in the new york area and san francisco
assistant u.s. attorney catherine palmer said kon, who was born in china and later moved to hong kong, had numerous businesses in asia and the united states, including several fur companies
kon had eluded arrest by becoming ``an international gypsy'' and moving between thailand, taiwan, japan and manila, maloney said. kon had at least six phony passports, palmer said
authorities confiscated 570 pounds of heroin alleged to have been imported by kon's organization in several seizures over the years, stutman said
authorities also arrested john routollo, a former new york city police officer, at his mountclair, n.j., home sunday night
routollo, 50, was allegedly responsible for picking up the heroin in new york, usually at the hilton, for distribution in the united states. he gathered the drug money and arranged its return to hong kong, according to authorities
routollo worked with kon before leaving the force in 1981, authorities said. maloney said routollo supplied weapons to kon's organization through his position in the police department's office of pistols and licenses. uranium plates. deletes now-redundant 10th graf bgng: a defense ..., editing to conform</note>
the army went public on monday with a classified program to improve the armor on its main battle tank, announcing that it was starting to build the m-1a1 abrams with depleted uranium in the armor plating
a defense department official who requested anonymity said army officials were convinced the new uranium-laced plates were so much stronger than conventional steel that they could stop all types of ammunition used by soviet tank guns
the army insisted that the depleted uranium would pose no threat to either the soldiers who operated the tanks or to the production workers who built them because of the manner in which the tanks would be fabricated
the armor design modification to the m-1a1 incorporates steel-encased depleted uranium,'' the army said in a statement. ``sealed within the tank, depleted uranium has a very low level of natural radiation, which is well within the acceptable range established by the nuclear regulatory commission.''
the service said it had begun on monday briefing the roughly 5,000 production workers who assemble the tanks about the new modifications. the abrams is made for the army by the general dynamics corp. at two plants _ in lima, ohio, and detroit, mich
while attempting to alleviate fears about radiation, the army made clear that it attached a high priority to building the new version of the m-1a1. production is starting immediately, the service said, and the new armor ``represents a significant enhancement of u.s. conventional defense capabilities.''
this improvement culminates several years of research and development to meet recent and continuing improvements in warsaw pact anti-armor weapons and will allow the abrams to meet the anticipated threat well into the 1990s,'' the army said
maj. phil soucy, an army spokesman, said the new armor plating now going into production would begin showing up on the tank manufacturing lines early this summer. the first completed tank with the new armor should be delivered in october, the spokesman added
soucy declined to say where the armor plating was being produced or to discuss the extent to which conventional armor plates are strengthened by incorporating depleted uranium
depleted uranium is an inert, heavy metal that is unusually dense. the term ``depleted'' means the uranium does not have sufficient energy to be used for commercial purposes such as in a power plant. the navy, air force and army are already using depleted uranium to fashion certain types of ammunition
in the case of the m-1a1, the army refused to say how much uranium would be incorporated into each tank; where on the tank body the armor with uranium would be located, or how it would produce the new armor
service officials who asked not to be named, however, said the new process involved ``weaving'' a thread mesh of uranium into the regular steel armor plating at the time of casting
while depleted uranium has a low level of natural radiation, our tests have confirmed that this material _ as installed in the abrams _ will involve no appreciable health threat,'' the army said
you would receive less radiation sitting on the surface of the tank than you would receive when flying during a trans-atlantic flight. because of this low exposure, no special precautions are required when near the tank.''
the army has already acquired about 1,500 m-1a1's and they will not be retrofitted with the new armor, the service said. but the remaining 3,000 tanks scheduled for purchase will incorporate the new armor, the army added
the majority of the improved tanks will be stationed in europe where they can most directly contribute to nato defenses,'' the service said. the first should arrive ``late this year.''
senate negotiators on monday called on their house counterparts to drop democratic presidential hopeful richard a. gephardt's heavily debated amendment from their sweeping trade bill
we decided to stick with our own super 301 plan and to oppose the gephardt amendment,'' finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said as he emerged from a meeting of senate conference committee members
the move, which came on a voice vote in the closed-door meeting, could set the stage for the gradual erasure of the gephardt amendment if the house presents a compromise counteroffer to the senate that makes a substantial change in the wording
however, gephardt spokesman mark johnson said that the senate's action represents ``nothing new.''
we've known the senate's bargaining position for eight months,'' he said. ``it in no way reflects a decision by the conference committee. it's merely an opening bargaining position. we're confident that whatever emerges from conference will be new, forceful legislation to open foreign markets. and clearly the gephardt amendment paved the way.''
gephardt's plan would require negotiations to reduce japanese and other nations' ``excess and unwarranted'' trade surpluses with the united states. if that failed, it would prescribe presidential action to cut the surpluses by 10 percent a year
such a move could include tariffs or import quotas on japanese goods imported into the united states. but the president could refuse to act, either to uphold ``national economic security'' or if the other country were wrestling with a serious international debt problem
the reagan administration has criticized the gephardt plan as being likely to hurt consumers, cost more jobs than it would save and invite retaliation against u.s. exports
the administration also has been critical of the ``super 301'' provision that the senate is pushing
super 301,'' named for the section of the trade act calling for retaliation against overseas barriers to u.s. exports, would require the president to act to eliminate all of the unfair foreign trade barriers listed on an inventory to be drawn up by the u.s. trade representative
the senate's offer was not immediately sent to the house
instead, the senators planned to return to the bargaining table on tuesday and fashion additional provisions involving steps to combat ``dumping,'' or selling foreign-made products in world markets at prices lower than those in home markets
they also planned to work on provisions involving countervailing duties, or tariffs that are imposed to offset the price advantage that some foreign-mad products get from export subsidies in their home countries
the senators also eased some of the provisions in the portion of their 1,000-page bill calling for retaliation against foreign unfair trade practices
they moved to expand from seven months to 12 months the time for the president to make a determination as to whether a foreign trade practice should be considered unfair. and they acted to remove some of the specific reasons for retaliation from the bill itself and put them instead in a report that will accompany the legislation. comments. picks up 11th graf pvs, during a ... with minor editing to conform and trim. adds one graf at end soviet comment on yugoslav economic reform.</note>
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev said monday that ethnic minorities stirring unrest in his vast country are raising old grievances but not challenging the authority of the communist government
soon after arriving on monday in yugoslavia, which has a long history of its own nationality problems, gorbachev was asked about recent demonstrations and ethnic riots in the southern soviet republics
show me the country in which there are no such problems,'' the communist party chief replied. ``if you show me, i will travel there right away, without stopping in moscow on return from yugoslavia.''
gorbachev, who is on a five-day visit, is the first soviet leader to visit yugoslavia since the death of president josip broz tito in may 1980
referring to recent demonstrations in yerevan, capital of soviet armenia, and rioting in neighboring azerbaijan between ethnic azerbaijanis and armenians that left more than 30 people dead, gorbachev said the problems had been brewing for a long time
he acknowledged some tensions between ethnic groups have been neglected in his nation of more than 100 nationalities, but said the protesters were not questioning socialist rule or ``challenging our political line.''
the remarks were his first personal comments on the situation in the soviet south, although a statement in his name was read to yerevan demonstrators
gorbachev plans to visit slovenia, yugoslavia's northernmost republic, and the croatian city of dubrovnik
missing from his itinerary is kosovo, which is beset by strife between the albanian majority and slavic minority
late monday, after touring memorials and monuments, gorbachev began talks with president lazar mojsov and bosko krunic, head of yugoslavia's party
yugoslavia's assistant foreign minister, ilija djukic, briefed reporters later. he said national minorities were not raised as a separate topic, but that in a general discussion on social developments, gorbachev stressed the difficulty of resolving ethnic problems
djukic quoted gorbachev as saying, ``there are no problems that could be solved once and for all, that conditions change, that everything requires improvement.''
gorbachev and his wife, raisa, set an informal pace monday as they took their first look at a communist country that has implemented some of the economic reforms gorbachev proposes _ but with mixed results
the soviet leader made an unscheduled stop in a busy downtown square and left his armored limousine to shake hands and chat with pedestrians. a witness said he picked up a child and gave it a kiss
mrs. gorbachev tried to take a walk through downtown belgrade but was nearly overwhelmed by several hundred people pressing for a closer look
the gorbachevs placed a wreath at the tomb of the unknown soldier atop mount avala, just outside belgrade
on the way down the mountain, their limousine made an unannounced stop at a monument in the shape of a broken airplane wing that marks the site of a soviet air disaster. on oct. 19, 1964, a plane carrying former soviet soldiers who helped liberate belgrade 20 years earlier crashed there, killing all aboard
the gorbachevs left two small bouquets
at one point, a reporter asked gorbachev if there was progress at the geneva talks on the afghan conflict. with a smile, he said ``there is,'' and ``there will be,'' but did not elaborate
he has pledged to withdraw all soviet troops from afghanistan _ estimated at 115,000 _ in less than a year if the geneva talks produce a settlement
gorbachev said he came to belgrade to give ``new impulses'' to the friendly relationship between the countries
yugoslav officials have said a principal topic of discussion will be yugoslavia's economic system of ``self-managed, market socialism.''
it also allows for private initiative along lines similar to cooperative enterprises that have sprung up in the soviet union under new laws
the yugoslav system was developed by tito, who broke with the kremlin in 1948 on ideological grounds and pursued his own communist course. while maintaining relations with the soviet union, he was a founder of the non-aligned movement and developed ties with the west
yugoslavia enjoyed a long economic boom, but has encountered hard times in recent years
today, the government and party are struggling with annual inflation of 170 percent, 15 percent unemployment and a $20 billion debt to western creditors
gorbachev is trying to end stagnation in the soviet economy by encouraging more accountability by management and more local control of production
soviet deputy foreign minister vadim loginov told reporters the soviets are studying yugoslav economic reforms
charles e. ``buddy'' roemer iii, a self-styled reformer who toppled a political legend, was inaugurated governor monday and challenged the people of louisiana to help him ``clean up our politics.''
the 44-year-old democrat, who won a runoff concession from gov. edwin edwards on oct. 24, took the oath of office from former sen. russell long, the son of legendary gov. huey long, shortly after noon on the capitol steps
he takes office amid fiscal crisis, with an accumulated budget deficit and cash shortfall of as much as $1.2 billion, much of it due to the oil patch depression
do we have the character to clean up our politics, to free our political leadership from the stranglehold of the special interests?'' asked the former four-term congressman. ``from the governor's mansion to the pardon board, from the legislature to the local government, i say we do.''
i will lead, but i need you to pick me up when i fall,'' said roemer, louisiana's 51st governor. ``i need you to stand beside me when the special interests attack.''
edwards, who served as governor from 1972 to 1980 and returned for a third term in 1984, was occupied for much of his last administration defending himself successfully against federal racketeering charges
roemer, during an inaugural address to some 5,000 people, did not cite the usual litany of louisiana's problems, including high unemployment, teen pregnancies, high school dropouts and nearly-empty state coffers
roemer was interrupted frequently by applause, edwards included
i'm going hunting tomorrow,'' edwards told reporters. ``it's his now.''
the state's unemployment rate hit 12 percent in january, one of the highest in the nation, due primarily to the long downturn in the oil and gas industry
louisiana's schools are under challenge, business interests are demanding an overhaul of the tax system to attract industry and environmental groups are calling for tougher regulations to protect the air and water
roemer campaigned on calls for major reforms in those areas and others, including campaign financing. he said recently that the challenge is unlike that facing any other louisiana governor
i've got to do both to get us out of debt and build _ education development, economic development, better environment. it's going to be a difficult and interesting job,'' roemer said
as solutions for the state's budget problems, edwards had proposed a statewide lottery and casino gambling in new orleans. roemer is opposed to both
we are not going to raise taxes or change taxes until we cut this budget,'' said roemer. ``it is out of control.''
even before his inauguration, roemer won two key victories in the legislature as his candidates for house speaker and senate president were elected during organizational meetings by lawmakers
roemer said earlier that a change in the legislative leadership was needed to give his ambitious programs a fair hearing by lawmakers
before roemer was sworn in, lt. gov. paul hardy, a republican, took the oath from former gov. dave treen. hardy defeated lt. gov. bobby freeman in a runoff last fall. other top state officials, all democrats, also were sworn
roemer, his wife, three children and his parents started inauguration day with a worship service at the first united methodist church
the supreme court by a vote of 7-2 refused monday to postpone the execution of wayne r. felde, who was due to be executed in louisiana tuesday
justices thurgood marshall and william j. brennan, who oppose capital punishment in all circumstances, voted to grant the stay
at the same time, the court refused felde's request for formal consideration of his appeal
felde's claimed he was denied competent representation at his 1980 trial on charges of killing a police officer because his attorney joined him in asking for the death sentence
felde had claimed his experiences in the vietnam war left him subject to flashbacks and unable to tell right from wrong. he described himself as a walking time bomb who would have to be executed to prevent further killings
a young lawyer who is the son of a former president and was kidnapped for campaigning against drugs has won the bogota mayor's office in the first mayoral elections in colombian history
security for sunday's voting was tight throughout colombia, where violence by extremist political factions and powerful narcotics traffickers is common
an alleged leader of the biggest drug organization even tried to run for city council in the town of armenia, but carlos lehder rivas failed because colombian law demands that candidates register in person. lehder is in jail in jacksonville, fla., facing drug charges there and in miami
andres pastrana, 34, son of former president misael pastrana, won the mayoralty election in bogota and will be one of the youngest men to hold the office, which often has been a stepping stone to the presidency
pastrana is a rising star in the conservative party and his election was a setback for president virgilio barco's governing liberals
he was the only conservative running for mayor in bogota, but feuding factions in the liberal party ran a total of three candidates. pastrana got 324,801 votes and juan caicedo, liberal former president of the colombian association of businessmen, finished second with 236,212
voters heeded barco's call to fight bullets with ballots in the first election of mayors. for 169 years the president, always from either the liberal or conservative parties, had appointed governors who in turn chose the mayors
colombians elected 1,008 mayors sunday. they also chose city councils, state legislatures and governing bodies for remote territories with too few people to become states
by late sunday night the elections office said the liberal party had won 405 of the races for mayor, conservatives 379 and the leftist patriotic union 13. coalition candidates representing several parties won 104 of the mayoral contests, the elections office said. results were not yet in from remote areas
barco said in a speech televised saturday night that voting would be a way to reject the violence. more than 1,700 people were killed in the past year in fighting between leftist guerrillas and government security forces and by right-wing death squads and drug traffickers
on sunday, soldiers and police guarded voting places and patrolled cities and towns. the election campaign was one of the bloodiest ever in colombia, with leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads killing five mayoral candidates and 19 city council candidates. hundreds of other political activists were slain
leftist guerrillas kidnapped 14 mayors in the two weeks before the election, then freed them after telling each to do more for the poor
pastrana, who called for stronger action against the multibillion-dollar cocaine and marijuana trade, was kidnapped by drug traffickers in january. a week later, police acting on a tip raided a farmhouse where he was held and rescued him unharmed
one group, the medellin cartel, is said to be responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the united states. lehder is charged in miami with being one of its leaders
the palestine liberation organization observer said monday he will defy washington's decision to shut the plo mission to the united nations, and u.s. officials said they would not try to close it immediately
zehdi labib terzi said american authorities would have to ``put me behind steel bars'' if they wanted to close the mission, which is in a new york city townhouse
we have the right to stay here and we will stay where we are,'' he told a news conference, and added that if the mission is closed the united nations should exclude israel from debates on the middle east
last friday, attorney general edwin meese iii said he would have to close the plo observer mission as required by a new anti-terrorist law
u.n. officials said monday another session of the 159-member general assembly was possible this week in an effort to retaliate or thwart u.s. plans. the plo mission was established 13 years ago
u.s. officials said they would not physically close it by march 21, as stipulated in the law, but would let legal proceedings run their course
the legal situation was confused. terzi said he opposes plo action in u.s. courts because the dispute is between the united states and united nations
unless i am dragged, i see no reason why i should appear in a u.s. court,'' he told reporters. terzi added, however, that a u.s. citizen might sue in an american court to keep the mission open and protect constitutional rights of free speech and association
the united nations recognizes the plo as the sole legitimate representative of the palestinian people and it has non-voting observer status. its representatives have the right to address every u.n. debate on the middle east
the united states considers the plo a terrorist organization
if the mission is forced to close and the plo message cannot be heard, terzi said, the general assembly should decide ``in a sense of fairness and justice'' to exclude israel from middle east debates
the united nations and u.s. state department have said the decision to close the mission violates the international u.n. headquarters treaty under which the united states allows u.n. missions to operate
at a three-day emergency session feb. 29-march 2, the general assembly condemned u.s. plans to close the mission, asked the world court to rule on arbitration and urged the united states to abide by the headquarters treaty
it passed the resolution of condemnation overwhelmingly, with the united states not participating, and decided to reconvene before march 21 to decide what to do if washington decided to press ahead with closing the mission
general assembly resolutions carry moral weight as expressions of world opinion but are not binding, as are those of the security council
many roads in mountainous western austria remained impassable because of snow or avalanches monday, leaving thousands of tourists trapped at ski resorts
in tyrol province, 10 people died under avalanches last weekend. forestry experts and mountain rescue officials predicted new slides of wet snow this week
traffic chaos in the area eased a bit. parts of westernmost vorarlberg province remained isolated, however, and tourists were stranded at the resorts of lech, zuers and stuben and in the kleine walsertal valley along the border with west germany
among those isolated by the masses of snow were former queen juliana of the netherlands and her husband, prince bernhard, who are staying in a hotel at lech am arlberg
the royal guests had planned to leave last saturday. a helicopter flight out of lech also had to be canceled because of bad weather
snowfalls resumed at noon in western austria and supply flights to isolated towns and villages were impossible. local officials said there was no lack of food because emergency supplies had been stored
snow removal and cleanup operations continued at st. anton, the tourist resort in western tyrol hit by avalanche disasters. five swedish vacationers and two local women were killed by two huge avalanches early sunday. damage was estimated in the millions of dollars
experts said wet snow does not settle down unless the ground is frozen. they said recent mild weather, coupled with rising temperatures predicted for tuesday and wednesday, is bound to increase avalanche danger
in st. anton, at least 14 houses, including hotels and guesthouses, were wholly or partially destroyed by avalanches
work teams cleared snow from the approaches of the arlberg tunnel, allowing trains to travel to vorarlberg province
in salzburg province, the main westward rail line was closed for most of monday because of acute avalanche danger. long-distance trains were diverted through regensburg, west germany. missiles fired into tehran and claims of plane and helicopter downed. picks up 6th graf pvs bgng: it said ...</note>
iran and iraq shot missiles at each other's most heavily populated cities and pounded border towns with renewed intensity monday after a weekend truce. scores of civilians were killed and wounded
in a resumption of the ``war of the cities,'' iraq reported it fired eight surface-to-surface missiles into iran's capital of tehran, the last one at 11:27 p.m., and iran said its forces shot two missiles at baghdad, the iraqi capital
the iraqis, declaring an all-out offensive on iranian cities, also launched air raids on ``military and economic targets'' in dezful, kermanshah, shushtar and three other border towns, scoring what it said were ``destructive hits.''
iraqi communiques said the air raids were carried out in a 40-minute period, with all planes returning safely
iraq also claimed its helicopter gunships downed an iranian helicopter
iran, meanwhile, claimed its revolutionary guards and iranian-backed kurdish guerrillas have killed or wounded 1,900 iraqis during ground assaults that began sunday in the mountains of northeast iraq
tehran television reported iran fired nine surface-to-surface missiles into umm qasr, an industrial town near iraq's southern border with kuwait, and said anti-aircraft gunners shot down an iraqi fighter-bomber in the northeastern battles
the official iraqi news agency, monitored in cyprus, said the iraqis fired eight long-range al hussein missiles into tehran monday
it said the barrage was a reprisal for the shelling of iraqi border towns sunday night in which at least 21 civilians were killed and 80 wounded
iraq resumed firing on sunday when it shot a lone ``warning'' missile into tehran, also in retaliation for the shelling of civilian areas
the exchanges shattered the uneasy two-day truce in the war against cities that began friday, bringing a brief respite after a 12-day exchange of missiles, artillery fire and air raids by both sides
iran's official islamic republic news agency, also monitored in cyprus, reported that iraq's missiles on monday exploded in residential sections of the iranian capital, a city of 6 million, killing at least 26 civilians and wounding 50
the news agency, quoting military communiques, said the iranians retaliated by lobbing two missiles at ``military and economic centers'' in baghdad
the iraqis reported that only one missile crashed into a residential area, killing an undisclosed number of civilians
the missile exploded as oil and energy chiefs from 20 arab countries gathered in baghdad for a conference on resources. officials in baghdad said some arab ministers had canceled plans to attend the session, apparently because of the flare-up in the war
both sides in the 7{-year-old persian gulf war vowed to keep pounding each other cities until the other quits
iran will not rest until the blood of our martyrs of iraqi missile and air attacks has been avenged,'' said kamal kharrazi, a member of iran's supreme defense council and head of the war information headquarters in tehran
iraqi news agency quoted an unidentified military spokesman in baghdad as saying that ``iraq has decided to resume its missile attacks and air raids on all iranian cities, not just tehran ... because of iran's new crimes.''
the iraqi agency said that heavy iranian shellfire of the border cities that began sunday was continuing monday, with a ``large number'' of civilians killed or wounded
it said the northern towns of halabja and darbandikhan were badly hit
iraqi communiques said the southern port of basra, heavily bombarded by the iranians in the last 18 months, was hammered by artillery and short-range missiles, with casualties reported to be heavy
the nearby refinery town of zubair and other southern towns also were being shelled, the communiques reported
iraq said it fired 71 missiles into tehran, the holy city of qom and the central city of isfahan, capital of ancient persia, between feb. 29 and march 11
iran said it shot 27 missiles into tehran and two into the northeastern city of mosul in that period. wives'</head>
the judge in the case of seven revolutionaries accused of plotting the overthrow of the government refused a defense request monday to let the three women defendants be tried separately from their husbands
ruling on pretrial motions, u.s. district judge william young also rejected the defendants' request to dismiss the case because of what they claimed was the vagueness of the sedition statute under which they were charged
however, the judge gave the defense a victory when he indicated that witnesses who had been hypnotized to help them recall events related to the case might not be allowed to testify
jury selection was slated to begin tuesday. the trial is expected to last up to a year
the so-called ohio 7 face one count each of seditious conspiracy, racketeering conspiracy and racketeering enterprise. each count carries a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and $20,000 in fines
the indictment accuses defendants raymond luc levasseur and thomas w. manning of nearly 20 bombings and 10 robberies throughout the northeast since 1975 to raise money to finance their radical political aims
two others, jaan k. laaman and richard c. williams, allegedly joined them on later crimes
the wives of three defendants _ patricia h. gros levasseur, carol a. manning and barbara j. curzi laaman _ are accused of harboring their husbands as fugitives, using false identification and taking part in some bombings
ms. levasseur's attorney, william newman, argued monday that prosecutors were trying to ``bury the women'' by tying them to the crimes allegedly committed by their husbands
prosecutors, however, accused the women of taking an equal part in planning the violent crimes, and young denied the women's request for a separate trial
young denied without comment the defendents' motion to dismiss the case because of what they claimed was the vagueness of the sedition statute, enacted during the civil war to punish confederate rebels
he also denied a motion by the government to add to the indictment some of the defendants' convictions on bombing, robbery and other charges. prosecutors had asked that the convictions be included to help prove a conspiracy
the judge agreed monday with the defense team's objection to government witnesses who were hypnotized to help them recall events
before that witness takes the stand, before you even call that witness, you must file a motion detailing explicitly that witness's pre-hypnotic testimony,'' the judge told prosecutors
i am not disposed to let any of these witnesses testify to anything.''
u.s. attorney frank mcnamara said after the hearing that two or three witnesses had been hypnotized. he wouldn't comment on who they were or their potential importance to the prosecution
new york gov. mario cuomo said monday that jesse jackson was electable as a democratic presidential candidate and ``has done extremely well'' at getting out an appealing message
of course he's electable,'' said cuomo during an inpromptu news conference following a speech to new york's county officials. ``if the democrats _ and that's a majority in the country, is it not? _ if the democrats say they want jackson, how can you say he's not electable?''
some political observers have suggested that jackson could not win the general election even if he were the democratic nominee, saying the country is not ready to elect a black man as president
his message is appealing,'' cuomo said of jackson. ``he's saying to the people ... that we have many people who have been left out that we need to educate and house through job training because we can't make it without them. it's not just a matter of compassion, it's a matter of common sense.''
it's an important message,'' said the new york governor. ``and i think people relate to it. i think we need to fashion the most effective message that the democrats can put together.''
cuomo, who announced more than a year ago that he wouldn't seek the democratic presidential nomination, has refused to rule out accepting a draft for the nomination if there were a deadlocked national convention
the new york governor has refused to endorse jackson or any of the other active democratic candidates
cuomo has said he believes jackson stands a good chance of winning new york's important april 19 primary
the national oceanic and atmospheric administration has levied fines totaling $100,000 against three japanese firms whose ships were videotaped apparently fishing illegally in u.s. waters off alaska in early january
the civil fines of $25,000 per vessel involved are the maximum allowed under u.s. law
this underscores how seriously we viewed the violations,'' jim brennan, a deputy general counsel for noaa, said monday. he said the japanese companies can seek an administrative hearing on the fines if they decide to appeal
northwest congressmen, who had criticized the reagan administration's handling of the fishing situation, were pleased with the fines
this action should send a powerful message to any fisherman who is thinking about fishing illegally in our waters,'' said rep. don bonker, d-wash
added rep. john miller, r-wash.: ``if these fines make it dangerous to fish illegally in our waters and if these fines make it expensive for outlaw fishing vessels if they get caught, then i am all for them.''
the fines were based on a review of the videotapes and depositions taken from commercial fishermen who chartered a plane and photographed the vessels with their nets down allegedly 38 miles inside the american fishing zone, said brennan
the investigation was conducted by a noaa lawyer in juneau, alaska, and the fines issued late last week
two of the vessels videotaped are owned and operated by hamaya suisan co., ltd., which was fined a total of $50,000, said brennan. the other two vessels are owned and operated by senkon gyogyo co., ltd., and taisei gyogyo co., ltd., those companies each were fined $25,000
in addition, the owners and operators of two unidentified fishing vessels that were also videotaped were fined a total of $100,000. the identification numbers on the vessels were covered at the time they were photographed
those fines were for illegal fishing and for having their identifying marks obscured
we expect we will get the cooperation of the japanese government in tracking those vessels,'' said brennan
brennan also said noaa was considering denying applications for permits from the three companies to fish in american waters until 1992
foreign vessels are not currently allowed to fish in the 200-mile u.s. zone off alaska, but they are allowed to participate in joint ventures with american firms. brennan said the denial of permits would bar the three japanese firms from participating in joint ventures
american fishermen and the u.s. coast guard have suspected for more than a year that foreign trawlers were slipping into the u.s. zone under cover of darkness or in stormy weather to fish illegally
ed wolfe, the state department's ambassador for oceans and fisheries, said monday he was not aware of the noaa fines and declined comment. brandfass sted brandfess.</note>
a jury monday found manson disciple and would-be presidential assassin lynette ``squeaky'' fromme guilty of escaping from a federal prison after she told the panel: ``you don't have any choice.''
i'm guilty as charged, legally, and without remorse morally, so that's that,'' fromme, acting as her own lawyer, said in closing arguments
fromme, 39, a disciple of mass murderer charles manson, is serving a life sentence for a 1975 assassination attempt against president ford. she escaped dec. 23 from the federal correctional institution at alderson, w.va., and was captured about two miles away on christmas after a manhunt
fromme called only herself as a witness and carefully followed hallanan's instructions that her testimony had to be in the form of questions and answers, questioning herself on the pronunciation of her name and cautioning: ``miss fromme, you talk too much,'' and ``wait a minute, you're getting ahead of yourself.''
the u.s. district court jury returned its verdict after less than 10 minutes of deliberation. judge elizabeth hallanan set an april 28 sentencing date. fromme faces an additional sentence of up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine
fromme has been described as the main member of the ``family'' that congregated around manson, who is serving a life sentence in san quentin prison in california for the 1969 murders of actress sharon tate and eight others
she told the jury monday that she attempted to escape because ``i got word that (manson) had cancer
he needs a relative, somebody to check on him,'' she said of manson, whom she described as ``my husband, my brother, my father, my son, the man who's been my friend.''
she said she decided to escape because ``my access to him is so limited, i've been feeling helpless for years. if love means anything at all it means stop feeling helpless ... (and) take action if necessary.''
assistant u.s. attorney j. kirk brandfass called four prison employees to testify about fromme's disappearance and her capture
fromme cross-examined each government witness on the population of the prison, and each of them indicated the institution _ which has an official capacity of 670 prisoners _ now holds about 1,000,
in her testimony she told the jury that the overcrowding was one of the reasons she tried to escape.``the prison has become more and more crowded, and the institution staff has become more and more tense,'' she said
the judge had twice denied fromme's request for a no-contest plea and entered an innocent plea on her behalf
fromme had told hallanan the case ``doesn't warrant a jury trial'' and said she was ``willing to accept whatever sentence you hand down to me.''
but fromme failed on monday to ask for ``bench trial,'' which would have left the decision in the judge's hands without calling a jury
ford was unharmed when a secret service agent grabbed a semiautomatic .45-caliber pistol aimed at him by fromme on sept. 5, 1975
in san francisco 17 days later, ford escaped injury when sara jane moore, 45, fired a revolver at him. she eventually pleaded guilty and received a life sentence
in 1979, moore also escaped from the alderson prison but was recaptured hours later about 25 miles away. she is now in a federal prison in pleasanton, calif. box</head> last week sted this week.</note>
activists protesting the bank of boston's investment in a paper mill succeeded in depositing a dead fish in a safety deposit box despite pleas from bank officials
the protesters appeared outside the bank building at noon in opposition to what they said are toxic hazards at the international paper co. mill in jay, maine. mill workers on strike since last june have been replaced and in recent weeks, there have beeen three incidents of gas leaks
members of the national toxics campaign and a group from jay, stop toxics against citizens, placed dead fish in safety deposit boxes in several bank of boston branches last week to symbolize what they said are the fish killed in the androscoggin river because of international paper's alleged toxic dumping
bank of boston controls 189,000 shares of international paper and a bank board member, donald mchenry, is on the board of international paper
on monday, three activists entered the bank as some people outside chanted ``bank of boston, they won't tell, holy mackerel, what's that smell?''
as michael stein, representing the protesters, kate o'connor, a national toxics campaign worker, and tina mcdonald, a jay resident, walked to the vault, a coterie of bank security guards scurried after them, banishing press photographers from the premises
one bank official, who declined to give his name, first tried to dissuade the protesters from placing two fish inside the deposit box
i'm just another schlep here,'' he told them. ``i don't know why you want to do this, but i don't think it's a good idea.''
another official, who would only identify himself as ``ronald mcdonald,'' informed stein that he would be allowed to place the two dead fish in his box, but that the bank planned to terminate his contract immediately thereafter
we're asking you to surrender the box,'' said the official. ``we don't want you as a customer any more.''
stein then desposited the fish and was ushered out of the building
wayne taylor, spokesman for the bank of boston, said the protesters' tactics were hypocritical and caused a health issue. ``they're jeopardizing the safety and health of bank employees and customers,'' he said, arguing that the dead fish could attract cockroaches
taylor said the bank has been, and will remain, neutral in the controversy surrounding the paper mill and the strike
members of the united international paperworkers union and the brotherhood of firemen and oilers walked out june 16 in a contract dispute. international paper wanted to eliminate 170 jobs and cut premium pay on sundays
eight workers were sent to the hospital after being exposed to hydrogen sulfide on jan. 28, and a 112,000-gallon chlorine dioxide leak on feb. 5 forced nearly 4,000 residents out of their homes and schools for several hours. a leak on feb. 14 chlorine gas leak injured seven people
following protests from residents, maine gov. john r. mckernan jr. and international paper chairman john a. georges agreed on a full-scale inspection of the plant, at the company's expense, by an outside consultant selected by the state
bill greener, spokesman for international paper in purchase, n.y., said that the maine department of environmental protection last week announced they had found no reason to close down the mill. greener said the three chemical leaks were ``something to be avoided'' and said the company is cooperating with efforts to make the mill as safe as possible. he denied the protesters' claim that the company engages in toxic dumping
a cuban official on monday claimed the united states paid bribes to win support for its effort to have the u.n. human rights commission investigate cuba, the news agency prensa latina reported
the cuban news agency said assistant foreign minister raul roa told the havana newspaper granma that some people at the commission hearings held in geneva received $50,000 in bribes
in the report monitored in mexico city, prensa latina mentioned no names and gave no further details on the bribe allegation
last week, the 43-nation human rights commission accepted president fidel castro's invitation to send a delegation to cuba to investigate allegations of human rights abuses
after that action, the united states withdrew a resolution calling for the u.n. secretary-general to study the human rights situation in cuba and report to the commission
roa, who returned to havana last weekend from geneva, called the commission decision ``the most crushing defeat'' the united states ``has suffered in recent years in an international forum,'' prensa latina said
armando valladares, a former cuban political prisoner who headed the u.s. delegation to the geneva meeting, said last week the two-year u.s. effort to have the commission examine the human rights situation in cuba had forced castro to invite a delegation to his country
a theological conservative was elected president monday of divided southeastern baptist theological seminary and said he will hire as faculty members only those who accept the bible as the literal truth
a moderate on the seminary's board of trustees warned ``there will be no peace'' at the 1,009-student school if drummond makes good on his commitment to carry out the agenda of the board's conservative majority
lewis a. drummond, 61, a professor of evangelism at southern baptist seminary in louisville, ky., takes office april 1 at southeastern, the fourth-largest of six southern baptist seminaries. it was founded in 1950
drummond, an associate of evangelist billy graham, pledged to seek peace among the school's factions and said he he would preserve academic quality and freedom of inquiry at the seminary
however, he also said he will implement the agenda of the conservatives, including hiring as faculty members only those scholars who hold the ``inerrancy'' view that the bible is literally true, even in matters of science and history
theological moderates believe the scriptures were divinely inspired but may contain errors by their human authors. the issue is at the heart of a clash that has divided the nation's biggest protestant denomination for several years. there are 14.6 million southern baptists
drummond succeeds randall lolley, a moderate who announced his resignation in the fall after 14 years. lolley said he could not carry out what he called the conservatives' plan to ``create a fundamentalist seminary.'' four administrators also resigned
it will be my prayer ... that a fresh wind of spiritual renewal could sweep the campus, fostering a spirit of love, harmony and reconciliation and commitment to all that god would accomplish in and through the institution,'' drummond said
despite his conservative orientation, drummond had been described as perhaps the only candidate acceptable to conservatives and moderates because of his academic credentials and what colleagues describe as a tolerant attitude and agreeable personality
the board's vote 21-6 with one abstention to hire drummond after nearly 90 minutes of debate
dr. drummond's view of the bible is one i cannot accept,'' the rev. mark caldwell, a moderate trustee from washington, d.c., said in an interview
caldwell read a statement on behalf of other moderates that accused the conservatives of trying to ``shift radically the theological foundation of the school toward fundamentalism . ... we will not endorse such an erosion of the school's historic character.''
caldwell said a faculty panel that met with drummond gave drummond a less than 50 percent confidence rating. the faculty raised concerns about his his understanding of the moderate-conservative rift, his appreciation of the ``broad baptist constituency'' and his leadership skills, caldwell said
the rev. robert d. crowley, the conservative trustee chairman and a rockville, md., minister, said drummond ``brings to this new job impeccable credentials, an enviable track record and every qualification we could have wanted for a new president.''
richard l. hester, president of the seminary chapter of the american association of university professors, which has fought the conservatives, said the faculty would give drummond a chance to demonstrate his commitment to academic freedom and excellence
but we want to make fully clear that if his dream is the same dream as the trustee majority there will be no peace here,'' hester said
drummond has been administrative director of the billy graham center since 1981 and billy graham professor of evangelism at southern seminary since 1973. he also has taught at spurgeon's theological college in london, england
at a news conference, crowley read from graham's letter of recommendation in which he described drummond as ``an ideal president at southeastern seminary.'' newspaper to yediot ahronot sted yeiot. picks up 5th graf pvs, prime minister ...</note>
troops shut down one of the biggest produce markets in the west bank on monday, turning away 70 trucks of food grown by arab farmers and tightening the economic noose on the occupied territories
soldiers also shot and wounded at least 11 arabs, and a 3-year-old girl was in serious condition after she was hit in the right eye by a rubber bullet, hospital officials said
the army imposed a nightly 10 p.m. to 3 a.m. curfew over the entire gaza strip for the first time since unrest began in the territories dec. 8. a spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the curfew will be in effect indefinitely
israel radio said the curfew was to prevent ``the entrance of violent instigators ... and of written instigation material'' to the gaza strip where about 600,000 palestinians live
all residents will have to stay home while the army seals off entrances to gaza, the radio said
the daily yediot ahronot meanwhile reported that the israeli army will spray rock-hurling protesters with paint from helicopters so they can be identified and arrested
prime minister yitzhak shamir arrived in washington with what he said were new ideas for mideast peace talks
also on monday, another 150 arab policemen in gaza announced they would resign, joining 450 other officers in the occupied territories who quit earlier, according to an arab reporter who watched many turn in their uniforms
israeli authorities acknowledged some police quit but gave no figures. about 850 arab police worked in the occupied territories
the resignations were ordered by the palestine liberation organization two days after the slaying of a jericho policeman accused of collaborating with the israelis
it is clear their resignations were not handed in freely but because they fear for their lives,'' gaza police commander shimon levy said on israel radio. in apparent response to the plo-backed protests and unrest, israel stepped up economic sanctions, including a ban on the shipment of gasoline and other fuel to service stations in the west bank
uri hakak of the israeli-owned padesco co., which supplies fuel to 50 west bank gas stations, said drivers were afraid to make deliveries after two tank trucks were attack and burned
in jericho, 22 miles northeast of jerusalem, soldiers closed the regional fruit and vegetable market, turning away 70 trucks carrying produce, arab merchants said
we started to sell about 8 a.m. when the soldiers came and forced us to close,'' said one merchant who refused to give his name, saying he was being watched by a collaborator
he said arab farmers tried to open informal markets elsewhere, but soldiers chased them away
plo leaflets have ordered jericho shops to open only in the morning. but on monday, merchants said troops told them they could operate only after noon
saeb erakat, a political science professor from an najah university who lives in jericho, said israeli authorities wanted to break the back of the palestinian strike with economic pressure
the military government is trying to tell the people here who is boss. jericho is an agricultural city. to order the market closed in the morning amounts to killing it economically,'' erakat said
at least 91 arabs have been killed during unrest in the occupied territories since rioting began, according to united nations figures
in jenin and the nearby west bank village of yamoun, troops using live ammunition shot and wounded 11 arabs
witnesses in ramallah said troops also shot 3-year-old rasha youssef said in the eye with a rubber bullet in a clash with palestinians protesting alleged harassment by jewish settlers
on the political front, legislators of the right-wing likud bloc said they would try to defeat a u.s. peace plan by forming a new government without the left-of-center labor party, led by foreign minister shimon peres
