a baby born with most of his brain missing clung to life monday at a hospital where doctors hoped to make the doomed infant's organs available for transplant, a hospital spokeswoman said
he shows progressive signs of brain stem deterioriation but has not yet met all the criteria for total brain death,'' said anita rockwell, a spokeswoman for loma linda university medical center
the boy, identified only as baby d, was born at an unidentified southern california hospital march 10 with a fatal birth defect known as anencephaly, in which much of the brain and skull are missing
the newborn's other vital organs are healthy, and his parents asked that their child be considered an organ donor. he was transferred to loma linda
loma linda has developed the nation's first medical guidelines for preserving anencephalics' heart and other vital organs for transplanting into critically ill infants
the baby is the fourth brain-absent newborn accepted at loma linda for possible use as an organ donor
under criteria established by the hospital, baby d was placed on life-support systems for a seven-day period, which ends thursday night
if doctors determine that baby d is brain-dead during that period, the hospital will serve notice that the organs are available for transplant
if the infant is not declared brain-dead within seven days, baby d will be taken off the respirator and will be allowed to die naturally
the guidelines were developed to address ethical questions surrounding use of doomed anencephalics as organ donors
loma linda received nationwide attention and criticism in 1984 when dr. leonard bailey transplanted a baboon's heart into a girl known as baby fae. she died 20{ days later
bailey later transplanted infant hearts successfully. however, a shortage organ donors led loma linda to develop its policy on anencephalic infants. colon, u.s. reinforcements sent to panama. picks up 8th graf: primary and ... inserts 2 grafs after 11th graf pvs, ``alberto soto ... with colon strike, other details; minor editing thruout.</note>
police fired tear gas monday at protesters who blocked traffic in the capital and cried, ``noriega must go!'' work stoppages broke out as employees learned they would not be paid by a government that has run out of money
the government began selling sacks of food, called ``dignity bags,'' to unpaid workers. some schoolteachers, telephone company and panama canal dock workers demanded cash and struck to reinforce their demand
in washington, the pentagon announced it had sent 104 marines and air force military police to panama to reinforce u.s. security units
violence was reported in the port city of colon at the caribbean entrance of the panama canal
nicolas psichoyos, a manager of the rey supermarket chain, said two company stores were attacked by gangs demanding free food for government employees. five supermarket employees were injured in fights with the attackers, one of them seriously, psichoyos said
he said the gangs were supporters of gen. manuel antonio noriega, the nation's strongman
protesters in panama city erected flaming street barricades of trash. others yelled at security forces and were met by volleys of tear gas
for the first time, the disturbances reached into the heart of the capital's business district
riot police used tear gas to disperse about 600 primary and secondary school teachers blocking traffic in front of the ministry of education. ``we want our pay!'' shouted the teachers. ``books yes, arms no!''
as the police, armed with rubber truncheons and tear gas grenades, forcibly removed them, the teachers cried: ``noriega must go!'' no arrests were reported
primary and secondary schools were to have reopened monday following a three-month vacation, but they stayed closed
alberto williams, a secretary of the dock workers union, said about 700 employees walked off their jobs at 9 a.m. at the port of balboa, the pacific ocean entrance to the panama canal, after being told they would not be paid their semi-monthly salaries
this strike is not a political movement,'' said williams, a forklift operator who makes $5.85 an hour. ``all we want is that the workers get their money.''
alberto soto, the port administrator, said the strike would have ``absolutely nothing'' to do with traffic through the 50-mile waterway linking the pacific and atlantic oceans
dock workers also struck at colon 50 miles north of panama city. colon residents told the associated press that in another protest, teachers temporarily blocked the highway that runs parallel to the canal
the u.s. defense department announced that 60 marines and a 44-man air force police unit were flown to panama monday. a pentagon spokesman, cmdr. robert prucha, said, ``this is simply a prudent measure to augment the security personnel who are already in place.''
u.s. officials in washington have said president reagan's decision to withhold a $6.5 million payment due panama on tuesday was aimed at impairing the panamanian government's ability to pay panama's 130,000 public workers this week
withholding the payment was one of a number of economic sanctions the united states has imposed to pressure noriega to step down as chief of the defense forces
nearly one in every five working panamanians is employed by the government. until now, they have supported noriega, at least outwardly
according to panamanian figures, their payroll comes to about $33 million every two weeks. diplomatic sources and private economists, speaking on condition of anonymity, say the nation's treasury is empty
the ``dignity bags'' contained such staples of the panamanian diet as rice, beans, flour, onions, cheese and lard. they were being sold for between $15 and $16 but the government apparently was not demanding immediate payment
horacio rodriguez, director of the ministry of farm and dairy products marketing, said his agency prepared 12,000 of the bags
the nation's new civilian chief executive, manuel solis palma, noriega and other top officials resumed an emergency economic conference monday morning after recessing an earlier session at 2 a.m. without comment
solis palma, installed by the military last month, has been meeting frequently with his chief advisers but sunday's meeting was the first time that noriega had been known to join them
noriega, the power behind the government since 1983, was indicted by two u.s. federal grand juries last month on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering
about 40 employees outside the state-run telephone company's main office told reporters they were striking because they had not been paid
nobody has told us anything,'' said one worker, who refused to identify himself
the 118 local and foreign banks in panama remained closed by government order for the 10th straight day. most had closed their doors earlier because the government was unable to provide them with the cash to cover a run on deposits
the bank run began feb. 26, the day noriega engineered the dismissal of eric arturo delvalle as president. the day before, delvalle had tried to fire noriega. the deposed president has been in hiding for more than two weeks, but is still recognized by the united states as panama's legitimate chief executive. lying, deleting some detail to tighten. corrects spelling of fields, sted field, in 9th graf pvs. no pickup.</note>
a former official in gov. evan mecham's administration, testifying monday at the governor's senate impeachment trial, accused a key prosecution witness of lying about an alleged death threat
max hawkins said the witness, peggy griffith, ``really had it in for lee watkins,'' the man griffith accused of making the threat
in a heated round of questioning, hawkins insisted repeatedly he did not believe a death threat had been made. ``i thought peggy really detested lee watkins,'' said hawkins, former director of the department of administration
asked by sen. carolyn walker whether he was accusing griffith of lying, hawkins said: ``i testified i think she did lie on that.''
watkins, former state prison construction chief, has been accused of threatening donna carlson, a former mecham aide who was testifying at the time before a grand jury investigating mecham's finances
mecham, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, is charged with obstructing an attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat
other impeachment charges against the first-term republican allege he concealed a $350,000 campaign fund and misused $80,000 in a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
mecham has not attended the trial since it began feb. 29
earlier monday, mecham's lawyer, fred craft, accused the state police of intimidating defense witnesses as he moved for a mistrial or dismissal of charges against mecham
mecham sent a letter to acting gov. rose mofford asking that three top state department of public safety officials be placed on leave. mecham sugested that federal authorities be called in to investigate the intimidation claims
a political trial that is difficult at best is made even more difficult when witnesses are subject to these kinds of intimidation and harassment,'' the letter said
there was no immediate response from mrs. mofford's office to the letter requesting that she place dps director ralph milstead and two other officials on leave
arizona supreme court justice frank x. gordon, who is presiding over the impeachment trial, said he would not rule on craft's motion until tuesday
gordon also spent an hour in chambers with attorneys. prosecutors asked for sanctions against craft for trying the case in the news media with a weekend news conference, according to rep. henry evans, a democrat who is a member of the house prosecution team
craft held the news conference to protest the arrest friday of defense witness terri fields on an outstanding warrant. she had testified the day before
dps arrested ms. fields on a january warrant charging that she failed to attend court-ordered alcoholics anonymous meetings following a driving-while-intoxicated conviction. she was released on $1,000 bond
ms. fields testified that a state official who had testified about the alleged threat tended to exaggerate. ms. fields also said she thought there had been no death threat
dps spokesman sgt. allan schmidt has denied that ms. fields' arrest was an attempt to intimidate impeachment trial witnesses
meanwhile, hawkins testified monday that he considered the alleged death threat ``a culmination of comical errors.''
i saw no crime,'' hawkins testified. he denied any attempt to shield watkins
house prosecutor william french, confronting hawkins with his own words in a news release, a newspaper interview and a tape recording of a phone call, suggested hawkins tried to shief watkins and help him pass a lie detector test
hawkins said he was misquoted in the newspaper article and wasn't sure his phone conversation with watkins' attorney was transcribed accurately. he complained bitterly that the conversation with attorney dale anderson was illegal because it was recorded without his knowledge
on the tape, he was quoted as saying: ``i love lee and i want to save his ass. i believe he's being railroaded.'' a transcript also shows hawkins discussing questions that could help watkins pass the polygraph test
outside, some 200 pro-mecham demonstrators protested ms. fields' arrest. they carried placards denouncing the dps and the news media and calling for mecham's reinstatement as governor
a two-thirds vote of the senate is required to convict mecham and remove him from office
mecham contends he has broken no law and is the victim of a political conspiracy. he also faces an april 21 criminal trial on felony counts alleging he concealed the $350,000 loan, and a may 17 recall election
more than 50 independent tv production companies, including johnny carson's ``tonight show,'' appealed to striking scriptwriters for an exemption from the walkout, a union official said monday
brian walton, west coast executive director of the striking writers guild of america, said the union board would consider the special requests to allow scriptwriters to return to work at some companies during the strike
the strike by 9,000 guild members against the 200-member alliance of motion picture and television producers began march 7
walton declined to identify the productions companies seeking special, interim agreements, but ``the tonight show,'' announced it was among them
about 40 percent of the companies that make shows for television are wholly independent. of the rest, about half are considered independent but are affiliated with a major studio
among shows already rejected for an exemption was the academy awards ceremony, which is scheduled for worldwide broadcast april 11
lobell-bergman productions said monday the strike has affected development of five of eight movies on its slate and stopped work on a network comedy series
previously postponed was a revival of ``the smothers brothers comedy hour'' and a new series, ``the dictator,'' starring christopher lloyd
a spokesman for the producers belittled the union's assertion about the number of independents seeking waivers
with the exception of carson, i don't know of any other independent producer looking to make a deal who is also member of the alliance,'' said herb steinberg
no new talks were scheduled in strike. the guild is seeking greater creative control, higher residuals from foreign market distribution, and no adjustment by producers of residuals for hour-long syndicated tv shows. why tung went to trial; subs 9th graf pvs, `two years ...' to add tung is serving 20-year sentence.</note>
a former gang member testified monday that he agreed to the assassination of chinese-american journalist henry liu because he believed it was a patriotic act requested directly by the taiwanese government
tung kuei-sen, the former member of a taiwanese criminal ``bamboo gang,'' has pleaded innocent to the 1984 shooting death of journalist henry liu. he faces a sentence of 27 years to life in prison if convicted of first-degree murder with the use of a handgun
liu, 52, was killed in the garage of his daly city home just south of san francisco on oct. 15, 1984. liu, a columnist for chinese-language newspapers in san francisco, had just finished a biography critical of chiang ching-kuo, taiwan's president from 1978 until his death of a heart attack in january
tung, 35, has admitted the killing but went to trial because the prosecution has not offered a plea bargain and because tung want to tell his story, said defense attorney douglas gray
tung testified in san mateo county superior court that he had never heard of liu or his writings until he was driven to san francisco the day before the killing
speaking through an intepreter, he said he agreed to act as a gunman at the request of chen chi-li, a reputed united bamboo gang leader who told him he received his orders from taiwan's then chief of military intelligence, vice adm. weng hsi-ling
he asked first of all, `am i willing to help my country?''' said tung. ``i said, `yes, of course, because this is everyone's obligation.' and then he showed me he was a member of the intelligence bureau with the id card of the intelligence bureau of the republic of china.''
he said chen told him liu was a traitor who had become a double agent for taiwan and the people's republic of china
tung said he was recruited by chen because they both been united bamboo members before tung moved to the united states to set up an import-export business in august, 1984
two years ago, tung testified about his role in the liu killing while on trial on heroin smuggling charges in new york. he has said that he wanted to testify in order to apologize and possibly lessen his sentence. he received 20 years in prison for conspiracy to smuggle 600 pounds of heroin into the united states
tung described the shooting scene monday. he said he and wu tun rode up to liu's home on bicycles, hiding in the garage until liu came in. he said wu tun shot first. ``i heard a shot and i went forward and i saw this man fall down. at that time, i believed that should be the man i should assassinate. i aimed at his tummy and shot him twice,'' tung said
tung fled the country and was apprehended in rio de janeiro after stops in bangkok, the philippines and singapore
chen chi-li, reputed head of the bamboo gang, and wu tun were convicted in a taipei court and are serving life terms in taiwan. the taiwanese government has refused u.s. attempts to have them extradited for trial here
weng and two of his aides were convicted and given life sentences in the case. chen testified that the admiral and other high-ranking military officers recruited him to kill liu
port-au-prince, haiti (ap) _ the u.s. ambassador personally notified president leslie manigat about the indictment in miami of col. jean-claude paul on narcotics trafficking charges, embassy spokesman jeffrey lite said monday
we have formally notified them, but have not yet revealed the details of the case,'' lite said. ``they will be passed along when they're made available.''
he said ambassador brunson mckinley met with manigat thursday, the same day the miami indictment was unsealed
lite would not say if mckinley discussed the possible extradition of paul or recommended any course of action
the indictment accuses paul, along with his brother and ex-wife, of using a private airstrip to fly a 220-pound cocaine shipment to the bahamas for delivery to miami
paul commands the powerful dessalines battalion that backs up police in this capital city with a population of 1 million
the indictment puts manigat in a precarious situation. the 57-year-old political science professor came to power in a jan. 17 election that many haitians boycotted, foreign observers criticized and rival candidates said was rigged by the army
a decision to act against paul could provoke a coup, and if manigat ignores the indictment it could affect u.s. aid vital to this impoverished caribbean nation and its 6 million people
manigat issued a statement last week through a washington public relations firm calling the incident ``a matter of concern'' that will be handled in haiti by military courts
manigat is in a ``horrible situation,'' said a western diplomat who spoke with the condition he not be identified
paul knows that if he goes (to the united states) he will land in jail. he's not about to let himself be had,'' the diplomat said. ``the solution would be to bring him to trial locally. but how? who would you send to arrest him?'' anaise chavenet, a spokeswoman for the ministry of information, said monday the government has not been officially notified about the indictment
the american government has not notified the haitian government by letter or through normal diplomatic channels _ through the ministry of foreign affairs _ of the indictment of col. paul,'' she said
she added she was not aware of any meeting between manigat and mckinley on the indictment. contest</head>
democratic presidential hopeful rep. richard gephardt brought his tough trade talk to a bastion of organized labor monday night, telling democrats here that america's allies must be prepared to accept u.s.-made products
for gephardt, whose campaign stumbled badly on super tuesday, the march 26 democratic caucuses here are a crucial test. the missouri congressman passed up campaigning in tuesday's illinois primary
gephardt told about 300 supporters that in the past, the threat of tariffs has helped the united states persuade canada to stop dumping wood products and the japanese in dumping microchips on the u.s. market
when we finally lose the timidity and stand up for basic fairness, other countries open up,'' said gephardt, who has made trade issues a campaign centerpiece
gephardt drew scattered groans and catcalls from the audience when he quoted president reagan as saying the trade deficit was a sign of strength
i thought maybe he got his cuecards messed up,'' gephardt said
even as gephardt talked up his stance on trade, lawmakers in washington moved toward to discard the trade amendment the missouri congressman authored
senators are starting to push their house counterparts in earnest to abandon the provision as conferees from the two houses try to hammer out a final version of sweeping trade legislation
gephardt spokesman mark johnson said the senate action represented ``nothing new'' in the trade debate
gephardt planned to remain in michigan through wednesday, then return friday to continue campaigning in advance of the caucuses
michigan attorney general frank kelley, gephardt's state chairman, said the missouri congressman had between $400,000 and $500,000 available for a television advertising blitz over the next 11 days
it's very important that i win in michigan, and we're going to win in michigan,'' gephardt said after the speech
kelley likened gephardt's campaign to that of 1948, when another missourian, harry truman, won an upset victory for the white house
i predict he's going to surprise a lot of people,'' kelley said
earlier monday, gephardt talked to more than 300 members of united auto workers local 569 in flint, where he repeated his call to rebuild america's declining industrial base
in 1948, peter rodino left his native italian neighborhood in newark, n.j., an eager 38-year-old lawyer ready to represent the bustling city in congress
rodino became an institution in the intervening 40 years: fighting for liberal legislation, controlling one of congress' most powerful committees and helping write into history the downfall of a president
on monday, the 78-year-old congressman announced his plans to retire after 20 terms
in those years, newark decayed from the heart of the garden state into the brunt of jokes. rodino's political base eroded, too. his decision not to seek re-election came in the face of mounting pressure from black political leaders, who claim it's now their time to represent the vastly changed area
born in 1909, the son of an italian immigrant toolmaker, rodino seemed awed by responsibility when he was placed in charge of the president nixon's impeachment proceedings in 1974
if fate had been looking for one of the powerhouses of congress, it wouldn't have picked me,'' he told a reporter then
but rodino's steady, judicious handling of the momentous hearings earned him widespread praise and helped produce an overwhelming bipartisan majority in favor of impeachment
rodino said last year he retired to a private office and cried after his committee approved three articles of impeachment, forcing nixon to resign two weeks later
more recently, rodino was again in on the making of history, as a senior member of the house iran-contra committee that investigated the sale of arms to iran and the funneling of profits to the nicaragua contra rebels. he had harsh words for what he called the reagan administration's lack of concern for the constitution
he has continually used the judiciary committee to press for civil rights and what he calls ``the rule of law.''
little in the early years of rodino's career suggested he might climb to the center stage of national political life
a child of the depression, he completed law school in 1937, after 10 years of night classes. he was later decorated for world war ii army service in italy
like many members of congress, rodino relied upon service to his constituents for his electoral success. but he was a strong civil rights advocate, and that served him well as his once-prosperous city became predominantly black by the 1970s
he spoke proudly of his italian heritage, and sponsored legislation that made columbus day part of a three-day annual holiday
peter rodino was an unknown quantity,'' former house speaker thomas p. o'neill, d-mass., once recalled. ``he was a flame under a bushel basket.''
nixon's political demise raised rodino's stock considerably. he made the cover of national news magazines, starred on the dinner circuit, and was even interviewed to be jimmy carter's running mate in 1976
in december 1980, his wife and high-school sweetheart, marianna stango rodino, died after suffering for two years from a brain tumor. rodino had missed many a house session caring for her. he received further blows in 1982 and 1983 when he lost his brother, sister and mother-in-law
rodino focused himself on his work, running for his seat and winning, despite ever-mounting challenges. two years ago, he hinted he would step down as soon as reagan left office
he said then he would concentrate on writing his memoirs
at least 10,000 people marched through la paz monday in a funeral procession for a student who died from a bullet wound he received during a violent protest
later monday, about 5,000 workers demonstrated in the capital against the government's economic policies. at one point, police threw tear gas canisters to disperse protesters about to throw rocks at the u.s. embassy, authorities said
the students and faculty were protesting the death of marco antonio uria, a student at san andres university in la paz who died saturday morning after being hit by a bullet during a confrontation between students and police
the march was peaceful and no arrests were reported
students said police were responsible for uria's death, but the ministry of the interior said the bullet was fired by students
friday's protest was organized to demand an increase in the federal budget for universities. students threw rocks at police, overturned vehicles and threw up roadblocks. police pursued fleeing students onto the campus
a group of students returning from the funeral monday afternoon destroyed a booth in downtown la paz that was selling souvenirs of the pope's visit to bolivia in may, witnesses said
later in the afternoon, at least 5,000 workers marched through la paz to protest the economic policies of the administration of president victor paz estenssoro
the march, organized by the bolivian workers central, was called to pressure the government to increase wages, protect the government social security system and strengthen the public school system
the government is obeying the mandates of the international monetary fund and as a result workers are suffering the consequences with starvation wages,'' said simon reyes, executive of the workers central, during a rally that preceded the march
the shackling of former black panther johnny spain at his murder trial stemming from a 1971 prison breakout attempt was justified by the threat of violence, a prosecutor told an appeals court monday
as the 38-year-old spain, newly released from prison after 21 years, looked on, deputy attorney general ronald niver argued that the judge who presided at the trial ``was confronted with six violent men'' charged with murder
it was reasonable for (the judge) to fear for the safety of those in the courtroom,'' niver told the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals. ``he tried the best way he knew how to protect the safety of the spectators.''
but spain's lawyer, dennis riordan, urged the panel to uphold a lower-court order granting spain a new trial on the grounds that the heavy and painful shackles influenced the jury and deterred spain from testifying
we know that this jury only heard one half the story,'' riordan said. in five years of court proceedings and a 17-month trial, spain wore 25 pounds of chains around his body, arms and legs
the three-judge appeals panel heard more than 90 minutes of arguments and will rule on whether to reinstate spain's two murder convictions
one option raised during the hearing was to return the case to a lower court to find out what spain would say if he had testified and whether it could have affected the verdict. riordan opposed the suggestion
spain, released on $350,000 bail last week, told reporters after the hearing that being free was ``an incredible feeling'' and he wasn't worried about the court sending him back to prison
i probably won't put a down payment on a home, but i can't stop living because of that possibility,'' spain said
spain faces a more immediate threat to his freedom: a vote next week by the state board of prison terms reconsidering a panel's decision to parole him from a life term for a 1966 murder-robbery committed when he was 17
in the unrelated trial known as the san quentin six case, spain was the only prisoner convicted of murder in a 1971 bloodbath that took the lives of militant leader george jackson, two other inmates and three guards
authorities said spain, who was seen running out of a maximum-security unit with jackson, conspired with jackson in the escape attempt. three other prisoners were acquitted, and two were convicted of assault
in his 1986 ruling granting spain a new trial, u.s. district judge thelton henderson said superior court judge henry broderick had failed to consider alternatives to the shackling, such as the warnings used for another of the six defendants
but niver said the appeals court, reviewing the trial years later, should defer to broderick's evident conclusion that he had no safe alternative
circuit judge alex kozinski pressed niver on whether safety could have been maintained with less severe measures _ for example, leaving an arm unchained so spain could write a note to his lawyer without pain
we wouldn't do that to an animal, right?'' kozinski asked
niver replied that spain, even while fully manacled, threw a file folder at the jury and caused other courtroom disruptions. but riordan said the disruptions were caused by the pain of the shackles
primary school teachers across argentina went on strike monday demanding higher wages and forcing cancellation of most classes on the first day of the public school year
officials said only in northeastern corrientes province, where a salary agreement was reached earlier this month, did teachers begin regular classes for pre-schoolers and youngsters in grades one through seven
more than 450,000 members of the ctera teachers' union are demanding a minimum salary of 770 australs a month _ the equivalent of $126
ctera has said grade school teachers in some poorer provinces of this nation of 31 million people receive about 350 australs ($57) a month, requiring many to seek second jobs
it issued a statement saying that except in corrientes, at least 90 percent of the primary school teachers joined monday's walkout
their strike could extend to high school teachers if no agreement is reached by next monday, the opening day of high school classes. university teachers have threatened to boycott classes because of wage conflicts
the government has acknowledged that teachers' salaries are low, but said the wage demands cannot be met because of the country's severe economic problems
education and justice minister jorge sabato described the union decision to disrupt the opening of the school year as abrupt and lamentable
most private schools, many of which are operated by churches, opened as scheduled but a few reported walkouts by teachers sympathetic with their public school collegues
ctera is demanding a uniform minimum salary for teachers in all of argentina, noting differences between wages in districts in and around beunos aires and those in lesser developed regions
the government and provinces have offered to gradually increase salaries by an unspecified amount over several months. that was rejected by ctera, saying the offer was inadequate considering argentina's rampant inflation
inflation registered 189 percent over the past 12 months
a fugitive arrested after he was recognized on the tv game show ``super password'' pleaded guilty monday to collecting $100,000 on a life insurance policy by falsely claiming his wife had been killed in an auto accident
kerry dee ketchem, 36, entered the plea to two counts of mail-fraud indictment. he admitted submitting the false insurance claim while stationed with the air force in england
he faces up to 10 years in prison and a $500,000 fine at sentencing may 2
ketchem, appearing under a pseudonym on ``super password,'' was identified by a tv viewer in alaska and was arrested as he attempted to pick up a record $58,600 in winnings from his appearance on the show
the alaskan banker who spotted ketchem and called authorities claimed ketchem had run up about $25,000 in bills by using fraudulently obtained credit cards
after monday's hearing, ketchem's attorney, jerry newton, said his client also may be indicted in indiana on charges of obtaining a $26,000 bank loan by using a car he didn't own as collateral
a pro-noriega diplomat who was replaced at the panamanian consulate here monday apparently left with official diplomatic seals and important papers, authorities said
consul general joaquin meza left office after panamanian ambassador juan sosa replaced him with robert dominguez, a prominent businessman who fled panama after president eric delvalle was forced from office
sosa supports the ousted delvalle and has replaced 25 other consuls general who had backed panamanian military strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
dominguez said that when he arrived at the consulate monday morning, he found seals and important immigration papers were missing. miami police are investigating, but a spokesman said meza already has left the country
among the papers missing were visa applications filed by dozens of cuban americans who had paid thousands of dollars to visit or pick up relatives living in panama, dominguez said
the central american nation has been in turmoil since noriega was indicted in miami and tampa on drug charges and delvalle called for his ouster
the u.s. state department has said it recognizes delvalle, who is in hiding, as the official leader of panama
dissident miklos haraszti said police detained him for two hours monday and raided the house of another activist on the eve of an official ceremony marking an unsuccessful revolt against austria in 1848
dissidents were planning their own demonstration following the official event scheduled for tuesday morning
haraszti, a writer, told the associated press police picked him up at his house and handcuffed and beat him before taking him to a police station in budapest's 5th district where he was released after being held for two hours
he said he was warned that he and a colleague, tibor philipp, would be held responsible for any ``anti-system moves'' or disturbances if the dissidents hold a demonstration
police also searched the home of philipp, who is associated with the underground inconnu cultural group, according to haraszti
over the past two weeks, police raided the homes of at least seven dissidents including sociologist ottilia solt, writer gyoergy gado and gabor demzsky, who runs the largest underground publishing operation in communist hungary, according to dissident sources
they said police seized hundreds of journals and documents
haraszti said he also was criticized by the police for taking part in a recent two-day conference in bonn, organized by the west german social democrats to discuss detente, and for making a statement on radio free europe. in the broadcast statement, he denied the official claim that police in the earlier house raids found leaflets opposing the consititution and legal order
he said only books and underground papers were confiscated
last friday, several official publications referred to the house searches and said proceedings were under way against six people, but they did not report the type of proceedings
saturday's edition of the communist party daily nepszabadsag said the police announcement of the raids showed that ``the organs responsible for public order had managed to stop irresponsible people from disturbing the march 15 holiday.''
it said that in addition to the official event, ``an opportunity has been offered for other types of commemorations if they are not of dubious intent and do not disturb the peace
