lightning struck the fuselage of a passenger jet over the ukraine, knocking out two of the three engines, but the pilot landed the plane safely, the government newspaper izvestia reported monday
it said the tupolev 154, on a flight from taskhkent to donetsk in the southern ukraine, was hit by lightning sunday about nine miles from donetsk
one engine died and the second stalled but the pilot, identified as s. kharkov, showed ``presence of mind and high skill'' in landing the aircraft at the donetsk airport, the paper said
izvestia did not say how many people were on the plane, which can carry about 160 passengers, and did not mention injuries
the soviet union acknowledged monday it has failed to win support for a security council resolution calling for an end to the deadly missile duel against each other's cities by iran and iraq
the united states viewed the proposal as a maneuver to deflect attention from the u.s. push for a worldwide arms embargo against iran for its refusal to honor the council's july 20 cease-fire resolution and peace plan
it is expected the council now will just issue a statement this week by the council president calling for an end to the missile attacks
soviet ambassador alexander belonogov acknowledged that the soviet bid for a new resolution on the ``war of the cities'' had failed after the council met behind closed doors
our personal preference would be a resolution of the security council,'' he said, but the important thing is ``not the form but the essence'' of the council's action
if the presidential statement has better chances than a resolution to be adopted by the security council, we are all for it,'' he told reporters
belonogov urged the council to do its utmost to end the long-range duel, which he said was poisoning the ``political and psychological'' atomosphere for peace talks centering on the council's july resolution
a weekend truce in the war of the cities began collapsing sunday. by monday, both sides had unleashed missiles on each other's capitals
both iran and iraq are believed to be using soviet-made scud-b missiles in the duel that has killed scores of civilian since feb. 29
u.s. ambassador herbert s. okun said the council does not want to ``proliferate pieces of paper when we have a resolution that we are in the process of implementing.''
the superpowers have been at odds over the july 20 resolution demanding an immediate cease-fire and withdrawal to international boundaries as the first steps in a complex plan for negotiating an end to the 7{-year-old war
america has been trying to gain support since last fall for an arms embargo against iran, which has refused to accept the u.n. resolution. the soviet union is trying to improve its relations with neighboring iran and has been reluctant to suppport an embargo. information</head>
a federal appeals court monday ordered grand jury material concerning u.s. district judge alcee hastings of florida turned over to a house committee considering his impeachment
in a 2-1 ruling, a panel of the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals said the house judiciary committee had demonstrated a ``particularized need'' for the normally secret material
the grand jury had investigated whether hastings tipped off a politician about a fbi wiretap the judge had authorized in 1985. no indictments resulted
hastings, 52, the first black federal judge in florida, was acquitted in an unrelated case in 1983 of charges he conspired to solicit a $150,000 bribe
however, two fellow judges filed a complaint that hastings lied in his defense and was guilty of judicial misconduct. a 27-judge judicial conference last year recommended that the house consider hastings' impeachment
hastings, who was appointed by president jimmy carter in 1979, claims the impeachment proceedings are racially motivated. with response and show speech followed text; inserts 1 graf after 10th graf pvs, bgng: ``in an ..'' to update with shamir also meeting with senators; minor editing to tighten.</note>
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir arrived here monday with what he called new ideas for mideast peace talks and said he would not give a yes-or-no reply to the u.s. blueprint for negotiations with the arabs during his four-day stay
for us, these matters are questions of life and death, of our very existence,'' shamir said monday night in a speech to the united jewish appeal
while he promised to keep an open mind in the talks, shamir took a hard line on israel's retention of the west bank and gaza, at least part of which the reagan administration is calling on israel to surrender
i am astonished at some people's short memory,'' shamir said. ``did we have peace when we did not have these territories? don't they remember that the two most dangerous attempts to destroy us _ in 1948 and in 1967 _ were made when we did not control any of these territories? do they want us to go back to a situation which would inevitably invite another such attempt?''
shamir's speech was well-received by an enthusiastic crowd of about 3,000 people, who gave him several standing ovations
referring to the violence on the west bank and in gaza in which 91 palestinians have perished, shamir said ``it is not a war for a palestinian state in those areas. it is a war against israelis, against the existence of the state of israel.''
shamir's reluctance to respond directly to the u.s. plan did not seem to distress the reagan administration. ``we are not pressing israel,'' a senior u.s. official told reporters at a white house briefing
but the official, who spoke under rules granting anonymity, said ``it is the situation in the area which is pressing israel and all the other parties in the area.''
shamir did not disclose the revisions he will propose to secretary of state george p. shultz, who devised the plan and set this week as a deadline for a reply from the israeli and jordanian governments
the senior u.s. official said ``we are not hung up'' on a specific date for israel's response. but he said the middle east was not stable and ``we feel very strongly that everyone, arabs and israelis, must move forward.''
in an arrival statement, shamir said the 1978 camp david agreements, which called for a five-year trial period of palestinian self-rule, ``should serve as our guide.''
shamir also met monday with three of the 30 senators who had sent him a letter urging him to give up some occupied territory in exchange for peace. the three democrats _ sens. carl levin of michigan, frank lautenberg of new jersey and howard metzenbaum of ohio _ again urged that israel cede land for peace, but shamir did not soften his position
the state department did not indicate whether shultz would be willing to alter his formula for negotiations. spokesman charles e. redman simply called it ``a serious proposal'' that was under ``active consideration'' in israeli and arab capitals
but the senior official said ``we won't let any aspect be eroded or compromised.''
he said the camp david framework was a ``work of`genius,'' but was partly out of date, especially since jordan and the palestinians did not participate in negotiations that fell apart in 1981
shultz is pushing for a three-year interim arrangement on the israeli-held west bank and gaza strip, with negotiations for an overall settlement to open by december. he also is prodding israel to cede territory in exchange for arab recognition
shamir, stepping from a u.s. air force plane at andrews air force base in suburban maryland, said he was ``always open to new and constructive proposals'' to bring peace to the middle east
he said israel wished to live in peace with its neighbors, but that ``violence, terrorism and war are endemic'' to the region
meanwhile, senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., cautioned that for israel ``to continue down the road developing now is a road to disaster.''
byrd told reporters on capitol hill that ``mr. shamir would be well-advised to listen to the viewpoints of the friends of israel in this country,'' including congress and the american jewish community
shamir, after an overnight flight from tel aviv, met with about 30 jewish leaders at kennedy international airport in new york before continuing on to washington. avi pazner, his spokesman, said, shamir told them, ``i have decided not to take any decision right now because people in israel are divided.''
shamir told the group, which including morris b. abram, head of the conference of presidents of major american jewish organizations, that most people in israel want peace
but shamir added that the question was whether it was possible to make peace with the arabs now and also maintain ``our normal lives and our security,'' pazner said
shultz escorted shamir to his hotel in downtown washington on monday morning and talked with him for a half-hour over coffee
shultz reportedly underscored the importance of shamir's visit as well as the ``strong and unshakable'' ties between the united states and israel
in reply, israeli sources said, shamir said he had brought some ``new ideas'' that he would present to shultz in their talks over the next three days
in his arrival statement, shamir appealed for understanding. ``in our search for peace, the united states has always been helpful, open and indispensable,'' he said
he said ``violence, terrorism and war are endemic'' in the middle east and the area ``is littered with broken agreements.''
shamir said the camp david agreement, which led to a peace treaty between egypt and israel in 1979 but failed to resolve the palestinian issue, ``should serve as our guide'' in the current search for a negotiating formula
he said if past accords were ignored ``future agreements will be meaningless.'' the camp david agreement called for self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who live on the west bank and in gaza for five years. jordan and the palestinians did not participate in the talks, which ended in failure in 1981
shultz has proposed a three-year interim arrangement, with talks on an overall settlement of the arab-israeli dispute to begin by december
on sunday, in israel, shamir said ``after i come back with a summation of my talks with representatives of the american government, the cabinet will meet immediately and i think we'll have a decision on this subject.''
meanwhile monday, hanna siniora, a palestinian who met here with shultz in late january, urged the secretary to make room at the negotiating table for the palestine liberation organization
at a news conference, siniora, who is a newspaper editor in jerusalem, said ``so far there has not been a credible effort to seek palestinian representation.''
shultz's plan envisions a joint delegation of jordanians and palestinians, who could participate only with the approval of the plo
but the plo, which shultz and israel have branded a terrorist group, would not take part directly. all the arab governments have endorsed yasser arafat's organization as the only legitimate representative of the palestinians. with disaster proclamation, availability of federal aid; subs 11th graf pvs, `the federal ...' to clarify that aid will be reimbursement of firefighting costs.</note>
a wildfire that charred hundreds of square miles of texas prairie, killing cattle and wildlife, was declared under control monday, but surviving animals faced possible starvation without forage or feed
federal and state officials were organizing a hay donation program for cattle roaming past burned fenceposts through the blackened terrain
officials declared the five-county fire under control monday about noon, said murry fly, the state forest service's head of operations for fire control. but the forecast called for continuing dry, windy weather
damage was so widespread that crews were still trying to assess it five days after flames from burning trash went out of control near abilene
hundreds of firefighters, national guardsmen and state and federal workers contained the blaze after three days. the burned swath covered parts of an area 56 miles long and 24 miles wide
there's been a tremendous amount of forage lost right now,'' fly said
lt. gov. bill hobby issued a disaster proclamation monday, freeing up state money to help the area clean up and recover, said don couch of the governor's emergency management division. gov. bill clements was out of state
bashur said representatives of the state department of emergency services will instruct local officials tuesday on how individuals can apply for relief grants from the federal government
in about 87,000 acres surveyed so far, more than 100 cattle were killed or had to be destroyed, said lawrence winkler, agriculture extension agent in shackelford county, the hardest-hit county with more than 250,000 acres burned. an additional 175 head were injured
wildlife in the area also suffered, he said. a herd of about 20 antelope perished in the flames, according to ranchers who answered questions about damage as they put in requests for hay and feed to keep their livestock alive
there is a two-day supply of donated feed on hand, winkler said. ranchers without winter forage for their herds will have to sell their livestock, haul in hay or feed, or truck the cattle elsewhere, he said
the federal emergency management agency will make disaster aid available to reimburse firefighting costs in the five-county region, said bruce miles, forest service director
if ranchers had to buy feed for all 15,000 cattle affected by the fire, it would require 175 tons a day, at a daily cost of $30,000, said winkler
over the weekend, ranchers from across texas began donating hay. by sunday, tractor-trailers stacked with hay rolls were parked on the courthouse square in albany
at least seven firefighters were treated for minor injuries, said fly. the wildfire at one point threatened the towns of albany, moran and baird. news digest: washington _ pm-us-israel, a0421; jerusalem _ pm-israel, a0443; washington _ pm-anderson anniversary, a0442; washington _ pm-bechtel-pipeline, a0436; new york _ pm-aids-children, a0438; washington _ pm-candidate gore, a0444; galesburg, ill. _ pm-bush, a0431; san salvador, el salvador _ pm-salvador-elections, a0449; tokyo _ pm-japan-infants, a0403, atlanta _ pm-another look-sweet auburn, a0405
