thought for today: ``any movement in history which attempts to perpetuate itself becomes reactionary.'' _ josip broz tito, yugoslavian leader (1892-1980). ^with laserphoto</head>
movie producer robert cooper likes to tell stories about the little guy pursuing a goal despite seemingly insurmountable odds
his first movie in 1979, ``running,'' was about a middle-aged man determined to run in the olympics
the terry fox story,'' a television movie for home box office, told of a youth who ran across canada despite losing a leg to cancer
the simon wiesenthal story: murderers among us'' will follow the story of a man who devoted 40 years of his life to tracking down nazi war criminals
and ``max and helen'' will show a survivor of the holocaust who is finally reunited with the woman he loves, but because of a twist of fate cannot testify against the nazi who brutalized them both
cooper has pursued his own goals against the odds. at 5-foot-4, he describes himself as a little guy out to prove himself. he grew up in montreal, where he abandoned his goal of acting to become a lawyer after his father was threatened by gangsters. he set up a storefront law firm, then became a prosecutor fighting organized crime
he later spent six years as host of a canadian television show called ``ombudsman,'' which looked into complaints of injustice by its viewers
the theme of the little guy against the odds has always appealed to me, not only in my films but in my own life,'' he said. ``i think because of my size i developed an early sensitivity to injustice. it's the david and goliath thing, although some people tell me i use the sling a little too often.''
the simon wiesenthal story'' goes into production for hbo in budapest on may 2. academy award winner ben kingsley (``gandhi'') stars in the title role of the four-hour miniseries
you've got to do something about a man who's been obsessed for 40 years,'' said cooper. ``i told simon i wanted to know why he did what he did when everyone else had come to terms with the holocaust. he had stayed in a time warp in the 1940s. he was the man who found adolph eichmann and (found) the man who arrested anne frank.''
cooper will also film a wiesenthal book called ``max and helen,'' which tells of the only time wiesenthal let a nazi war criminal go. max and the woman he loved, helen, were brutalized in a nazi camp by an ss officer who was found living free in munich. but max refuses to testify
max tells simon to `get in my skin,''' cooper said. ``he tells of how he and helen were in the same camp, but were separated. in 1945 he was able to escape, but was imprisoned another 10 years by the russians. in 1955 he finally found helen in germany
but helen had a son who was the image of the nazi ss officer. he had raped her repeatedly in camp and freed her when she became pregnant. max can't marry her. her son reminds him of the nazi. yet, he won't testify because the son thinks he's jewish and doesn't know who his real father is.''
later, the son grows a beard and moves to canada. max and helen marry, but within a few weeks max kills himself
cooper also has these projects in the works:
_``inspector maigret,'' which is being filmed in europe with richard harris, victoria tennant and patrick o'neal. maigret has been described as a sort of french columbo. the show is for syndication
_``cuba,'' a four-hour miniseries for cbs, tells of an american family living in cuba from 1900 until fidel castro takes over in 1959. cooper hopes to be able to film it in cuba
_an nbc movie about new york model marla hanson, whose face was slashed in a knife attack arranged by her landlord and former makeup man. ``my interest is the fact that she was slashed by her makeup man, whose job was to make her beautiful,'' he said. ``why did he do it? that's what fascinates me. that and the story of a woman who was told all her life she is beautiful _ then loses it.''
elsewhere in television:
so it goes _ linda ellerbee will be the host of a proposed new show that combines reality and comedy. the show is being put together by hearst broadcasting productions and six hearst stations. a pilot is expected to go into production in may. ellerbee, a best-selling author and former nbc correspondent, quit abc after the network canceled her show, ``our world.''
emmy awards _ the 40th annual emmy awards show will be telecast sunday, aug. 28, on fox broadcasting co. for the first time the academy of television arts &amp; sciences will hold its awards program at the shrine auditorium in los angeles. it will be the second year the awards show has been shown on fox
american electronics companies are starved for computer chips. japanese chip makers are raking in windfall profits. and nobody seems quite sure what to do
this is the way of the world in the electronics industry, circa march 1988. it didn't have to be this way
the current worldwide shortage in computer chips is a classic manifestation of the law of unintended consequences, one that has resulted in higher prices of electronic products and even delays in the introduction of some new computers
one big reason for the shortage is unobjectionable: booming sales of personal computers and the retooling for a new generation of memory chips have combined to produce a cyclical squeeze on production capacity
but another reason for the shortage is that a 1986 chip agreement between the united states and japan has backfired in a way that should have been predictable
the accord, intended to benefit u.s. chip makers, was supposed to keep the japanese from ``dumping'' chips at unfairly low prices while giving the americans better access to japan's huge market
what actually came about was the creation of a de facto semiconductor cartel _ a legalized form of collusion that had the effect of setting prices above market levels and carving up markets
the japanese did raise prices of memory chips, mainly by limiting production, but the main beneficiaries were just two u.s. companies, texas instruments inc. of dallas and tiny micron technology inc. of boise, idaho
texas instruments and micron are the only american companies still selling dynamic random access memory chips, or d-rams, and they are earning a windfall
meanwhile, u.s. companies such as digital equipment corp. and hewlett-packard co. are paying more for chips than their foreign rivals pay. the consequences of that over the long term are disquieting
as for u.s. access to the japanese market, it is not happening. it was reported in january that foreigners' share of japan's market had fallen every month since june
in japan, americans are bumping their heads against a concrete ceiling. for one thing, the biggest consumers of chips in japan are also the biggest producers. it is unlikely they will buy from americans when they can take chips right off their own fabrication lines, although pressure on them should be continued
most worrisome in the long run is that the high prices japanese chip makers are fetching under the accord is giving them even more money to pour into their world-leading research and development
in exactly the same way that japanese automakers responded to ``voluntary'' restraints by moving upscale with cars like the honda acura, japanese chip makers are beginning to move upscale with more complex, expensive chips that have been the domain of the americans
so what needs to be done?
the main job, obviously, is to rebuild the american chip industry so it can compete with the japanese without the need for a de facto cartel. the 1986 accord has already been legally challenged by the european economic community
sematech seems to be a step in the right direction. the organization, to be based in austin, texas, is financed by government and industry and will work to improve manufacturing techniques, which are considered the achilles' heel of the u.s. chip makers
a bigger problem is that many of the united states' leading chip makers, such as intel corp. and national semiconductor corp., are only mid-sized companies that lack the deep pockets to compete with japanese giants such as hitachi ltd. and toshiba corp
big u.s. chip buyers such as general electric co. could give the american industry a financial shot in the arm by buying the chip makers, but they have shown little interest in the volatile and expensive business
more mergers of chip companies almost surely lie ahead. the federal government may even serve as matchmaker in some cases
but two of the most worthwhile steps to help the u.s. chip business _ and thus the electronics business _ have nothing to do with integrated circuits per se
step one would be to lower the cost of borrowing for the capital-intensive industry by cutting the federal budget deficit. step two would be to improve the quality of american technical education, on which the industry depends
those are long-term steps, to be sure. but japan did not get where it is by concentrating on the short term
hello dear. you're very handsome. yes you are,'' sir alec guinness coos through the cage at a rhinoceros
you've got a sweet face, very pretty ears,'' the elder statesman of british acting says, as he strolls through berlin's central zoologischen garten
his chat with the animals is almost as engaging as the wonderful characters he has portrayed on stage and screen during five decades as one of the world's finest, most chameleon-like talents
on this particular day, the berlin film festival was awarding the 73-year-old guinness its special ``ehren bear'' (honorary bear) for lifetime achievement in the cinema. the actor, however, elected to avoid the morning crush of screenings and news conferences for a romp in the zoo
i'm not actually that keen on them; i hate to see certain animals caged up,'' he said
but i remember this zoo being small and very imaginatively laid out on the open plan, and i thought it might be amusing to have a second look.'' he last visited the zoologischen garten 14 years ago
images of some of the zoo's reported stock of 10,000 animals have lingered: ``they used to have white rhinoceroses there that were charming. and a great sea lion covered in shrapnel wounds _ an old thing that was like a symbol of berlin; a splendid, great creature.''
this time around, guinness' observations are as keen as ever, whether applied to the varieties of zoo-bound species or the special tributes that have marked his career
in 1980, he received a special academy award to honor a range of work encompassing such portrayals as the sinister fagin in ``oliver twist'' (1948), a comic octet of murder victims in ``kind hearts and coronets'' (1950), the hard-driving colonel nicholson in ``the bridge on the river kwai'' (1957), the aging mystic ben obi-wan kenobi in ``star wars'' (1977) and its sequels
last year, he was twice feted in lavish galas _ in april at new york's lincoln center and in may at the cannes film festival
the occasion in berlin may be less tony, but its significance is no less clear: in the festival's 38 years, guinness is only the second actor to be so honored, following james stewart in 1982
i'm afraid when you get rather elderly, these things seem to come on you rather more than you might wish,'' he says, his brisk gait belying his years, his nose becoming slightly red in the seasonal chill
a signpost draws his attention: ``i think that way may be the pheasantry. do you mind if we go in there?''
somewhere between pheasants and finches, the conversation turns to work. his latest project is ``little dorrit,'' the six-hour film adaptation of charles dickens' novel in which he plays william dorrit, a long-term inmate of a debtor's prison who finds that sudden wealth brings sudden freedom
guinness had not performed dickens since the 1940s, when he both adapted ``great expectations'' for the stage and made his movie debut as herbert pocket in david lean's 1946 film version. he then appeared in ``oliver twist'' in 1948. he considers ``little dorrit'' to be one of dickens' two or three greatest novels
dickens offers great temptations for actors because you can go over the top,'' he said
later this year, he'll be seen as mr. todd in a movie of evelyn waugh's 1934 novel, ``a handful of dust.'' then there's lee blessing's current broadway play, ``a walk in the woods,'' which guinness may do on the london stage. he last trod the west end boards in alan bennett's ``the old country'' in 1977-8
it's a very distinguished piece of writing,'' he says of the play. but guinness acknowledges its pitfalls, as well: ``the amount of learning for a two-hander is horrendous. an actor's great fear is that he won't have the memory.''
on that topic, he is emboldened by the recent return to the stage, after a decade away, of his friend and mentor, sir john gielgud, in the new play ``the best of friends.''
gielgud is 83,'' guinness says matter-of-factly, ``and he got through it (the play) very successfully.''
by now, the sky has clouded over, and rain looks likely. guinness has a lunch date for which he mustn't be late, so he returns to his hotel to find that autograph hunters have arrived
there they are,'' he says, sounding resigned as the anonymity of the walk in the zoo gives way to the fans' ever-ready pens and cameras
but before leaving the zoo, he has one last remark about rhinos: ``we're told they have very nice personalities.''
he takes an inimitable pause. ``but i don't think i'd like to encounter them intimately.''
lavrenti beria
the mere mention of the name stills brings chills to some soviets
in the 1960s, years after his death, people still avoided walking past his drab mansion at 28 kachalov st. in moscow because of the terrible memories it might evoke
now, 34 years after beria's own execution, the mansion houses the tunisian embassy
ambassador abderraouf ounaies of tunisia said there were stories that beria had a dungeon built in the basement and a secret passageway. some areas of the basement could have been used as a dungeon, ounaies said, but he found no evidence of that they actually were used for that, nor was there evidence of a secret passageway
the curse seems to have worn off. people these days walk by, apparently without giving a thought to lavrenti beria, the balding, small georgian who wore pince-nez and is held responsible for the executions of millions during the stalin era
every generation has its horrors,'' said an elderly neighborhood woman, who recalled seeing beria strolling outside the mansion when he lived there
the administration of general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev says it wants the current generation of soviets to know the truth about the past, and is reviving nightmares about beria and the machine of terror he ran in the late 1930s and 1940s as stalin's most ruthless and powerful henchman
press articles and the portrayal of a beria-hitler-like character in the recent georgian movie ``repentance'' are part of gorbachev's attempts to fill in ``blank spots'' in history _ formerly taboo subjects. he believes that extending his policy of glasnost, or openness, to the crimes of the stalin era will help ensure that such mistakes are not repeated
the effort parallels gorbachev's drive to rid soviet society of stalinist policies under which the central government exercised tight control over the economy
sergo a. mikoyan, the son of the late anastas i. mikoyan who had served with beria in the stalin leadership, wrote feb. 21 in the youth newspaper komsomolskaya pravda that it is important to review beria ``to finally free the future from the past.''
beria's legacy is the image of the state security forces as all-powerful and ruthless. in their re-examination of stalin and beria, soviet media have not touched on this image as it pertains to the present-day kgb, successor to beria's nkvd. also conspicuously absent is any criticism of the system that enabled such a pair to take charge and to operate their machine of terror for so long
this is not the first time the official media have focused on beria's reign of terror. he was first exposed during nikita s. khrushchev's de-stalinization drive in the 1950s and 60s. khrushchev, in his memoirs _ published only in the west _ called beria ``a butcher and an assassin,'' a ``beast'' who was ``without the slightest trace of human decency'' and who was ``very skillful at anything that was filthy and treacherous.''
although beria was sharply condemned during khrushchev's years, the early official accounts inacurrately described his relationship with stalin
we refused to believe that stalin himself could have been behind the terror which beria oversaw,'' khrushchev wrote. ``for a while, we gave the party and the people incorrect explanations about what had happened; we blamed everything on beria. he was a convenient figure.''
the truth, khrushchev said, was that ``beria didn't create stalin; stalin created beria.''
only now, under gorbachev, is the official record being corrected, with the help of sergo mikoyan and the sons of other members of stalin's politburo, georgy m. malenkov and khrushchev. andrei g. malenkov and sergei n. khrushchev are quoted in a recent edition of nedelya, a weekly supplement to the literary gazette newspaper. that and the other articles put the blame squarely on stalin
i believe that the roots of beria's evil deeds should be sought in the personality of stalin rather than in beria himself,'' nikolai zhusyenin wrote in nedelya. ``namely the cult, the deviation from leninist norms, resulted in the beria phenomenon. beria was able to guess stalin's wishes, was able to exploit the weaknesses of his master for personal profit and self-glorification.''
zhusyenin said that when he interviewed people, ``their arms began to tremble at the very mention of the name beria.''
the writers of the recent articles said they had trouble researching beria because he did such a good job of covering his tracks, making sure that any evidence that could be used against him was destroyed and witnesses killed
komsomolskaya pravda stated the new evaluation of stalin's relationship with beria in its headline over sergo mikoyan's article: ``the servant.''
stalin tapped beria, a fellow georgian, to be deputy head of the already-dreaded nkvd, as the state security and police force was known at the time, in the summer of 1938. by year's end, beria replaced nkvd chief nikolai yezhov, who had fallen out of favor with stalin and was executed in 1940
the people breathed a sigh of relief, hoping that the years of bloody mass purges were behind them. mass arrests did end, but the terror continued. beria simply made it more selective, playing on stalin's paranoia by identifying and eliminating those deemed to be ``enemies of the people.''
in the meantime, he garnered a staggering amount of power. beria became the first secret police chief elevated to the communist party's ruling politburo. during world war ii, stalin named beria to the committee supervising defense and later put him in charge of developing a soviet atomic bomb. after the war, beria controlled the regular and secret police, the country's labor camps, propaganda and transport, as well as a private empire in his native georgia and surrounding regions
among the horrors western historians link to beria was the massacre of more than 4,000 polish officers in the katyn forest near smolensk by nkvd troops in april 1940. the official soviet version is that the poles were killed by germans
on a personal level, soviet accounts of beria said he interrogated and executed prisoners himself. khrushchev claimed beria raped teen-age girls after having them kidnapped off the streets
beria's intrigues also took a heavy toll on the party itself. nedyelya noted that beria collected files on every government leader, including stalin, for possible use against them. his victims included veteran party members, comrades-in-arms of v.i. lenin and officials of the party youth group komsomol, nedyelya said
even stalin began to fear beria, and by 1946 had taken away all his henchman's security posts. but beria retained unofficial control over the security organs, and planned to use his forces to seize power after stalin's death in march 1953
khrushchev, in his memoirs and in remarks cited feb. 24 in literary gazette, said he was aware of beria's ambitions and suggested privately to the other top leaders in the summer of 1953 that they oust beria. they agreed. the politburo, in beria's presence, met and voted to arrest him. military troops outside beria's control took him to prison. he was put on trial, convicted of being a british agent _ a dubious charge _ and of trying to ``elevate the ministry of internal affairs above the party and government in order to seize power.''
official accounts say he was executed dec. 23, 1953, but some western historians believe he was put to death months earlier
beria, who had been in the limelight for 14 years, quickly became a non-person. the editors of the official soviet encyclopedia, for example, told readers to paste an article about the bering strait over one about beria
this is our last forest,'' said ranger veerawat dheeraprasart, pointing down a deep river valley. ``if the dam is built here, all this will vanish, and nobody will ever be able to replace it.''
veerawat, the chief ranger of this rich wildlife sanctuary astride the border with burma, is among thousands who have joined what unquestionably has become the greatest environmental battle in thailand's history _ a fight to persuade the government not to build a dam in thailand's last virgin forest
in a country that once was jungle-carpeted and teeming with wildlife, it is rare today to see a tract of undisturbed forest, an unpolluted river, white-handed gibbons or free-ranging tigers
anti-dam groups have held rock concerts and demonstrations, some featuring life-like models of crucified animals, in their campaign
newspapers are probing the issue in unprecedented detail. former prime minister kukrit pramoj says the government could face a mass uprising if it approves the nam choan dam
the dam's proponents say nam choam needs to be built, in what is the largest remaining area of protected forest in southeast asia, to increase thailand's energy supply by about 2 percent
the government's electric generating authority of thailand has described the proposed, 580-megawatt dam as the ``last possible exploitable source of hydro power'' in the country. it says it will create a reservoir that would also help irrigate farm land and assure water supplies in times of drought
the projected dam site is still hard to get to: a lurching, nine-hour drive over dirt roads from bangkok, the thai capital, followed by a four-hour jungle trek. when monsoons lash the countryside, a three-day elephant ride offers the only access
but dam opponents claim construction of nam choan, with the necessary approach roads, facilities and ensuing human encroachment, would spell doom for what they say is also the last area in thailand large enough to ensure the survival of a wide variety of wildlife
found in the thung yai and the adjacent huay kha khaeng sanctuary, an area about the size of delaware, are large mammals, such as elephant, gaur, tiger and clouded leopard; some 350 species of birds, and a wide range of plant life. a number of the species are classified as endangered in thailand, some worldwide
foreign conservation groups have written letters expressing concern to the thai government. in december, britain's prince philip, head of the world wildlife fund, urged an independent environmental impact study before a final decision is reached. a similar plea came from more than 1,300 conservationists and scientists at the general assembly in february of the swiss-based international union for conservation of nature and natural resources
the electric generating authority maintains that nam choan would degrade only 4 percent of the area. but ranger veerawat, who has served for 10 years in the sanctuary, contends the 47-mile-long dam reservoir would not only eradicate a biologically vital riverine valley but also disrupt the migration routes of animals, forcing them into smaller habitats
opponents also dispute the 4 percent degradation estimate, saying that in thailand roads built into remote, forested areas have inevitably been followed by massive logging, with collusion between businessmen and corrupt officials circumventing protective legislation
loggers are already felling the rich forests along the park boundary
pisit na patalung, secretary-general of wildlife fund thailand, one of some 30 private organizations opposing the proposal, said the dam issue has raised an environmental awareness among thais. until recent years, the public appeared apathetic as the country's once teeming wildlife was slaughtered and forests that blanketed about 70 percent of the country a generation ago were reduced to around 15 percent of total area today
the dam was first proposed in the early 1970s but plans were shelved in 1983 in wake of protests and charges that environmental impact studies were sloppy and improper
in 1986, the electric generating authority asked that the project be reconsidered and the government appointed a 40-man committee headed by deputy prime minister thienchai sirisamphan to come up with a decision, which is expected soon
some opponents believe government leaders will be impressed by their arguments that thailand now has enough alternate energy sources, including offshore natural gas and lignite, to scrap the dam proposal
others, however, feel that too many key bureaucrats and politicians are still little concerned over environmental problems
another wildlife ranger, sueb nakhasathien, didn't sound optimistic
thais haven't yet put a price on the environment,'' he said. ``they don't realize that trees and water have a price, that wildlife has a price.''
when the farmworkers union failed to persuade civilian officials to remove mario espinal as head of the national agrarian institute, it took its case to the armed forces chief
in going to gen. humberto regalado and the military high command the national association of honduran campesinos made plain its feeling, shared by others, that real power in honduras does not lie with the civilian government of president jose azcono hoyo
the union is seeking espinal's ouster from the cabinet-level post on grounds that he was stalling on agrarian reform
espinal, nevertheless, remains in his post, confirmed once again by azcono hoyo, and so far as is known regalado has not acted
the campesinos' tactic was also used in the past few years by bus drivers, teachers, business leaders and other sectors. it underscores the powerful, even dominant, role still exercised by the armed forces six years after honduras restored civilian government
honduras has a long history of military governments, most recently in the 1972-82 period
the people know where the source of power lies,'' said anibal puerto, vice president of the independent human rights commission and a critic of azcona hoyo's administration. even government supporters acknowledge the imbalance of power
longstanding vices are not gotten rid of from the night to the morning,'' said joaquin luna mejia, president of the honduran council on private enterprise
in an interview with the associated press, he said consolidation of civilian power ``is coming along well.'' but he also observed, ``here, as in all countries, interests are managed according to the real powers. and if those powers are ambitious, we could fall again into old vices.''
no honduran politician is going around saying, `we've got to put the military back in the box,' because here the military never has been in the box,'' said a western diplomat
compared to its neighbors, honduras has enjoyed a degree of stability and peace during a decade of regional conflict. but the civil wars surrounding it have caused big problems
we have become a sanctuary,'' said luna mejia of honduras' tens of thousands of refugees from el salvador, nicaragua and guatemala, all torn by guerrilla wars. ``we are victims of the entry into our country of irregular forces.''
he referred to the contras, who since 1982 have been trying to topple the sandinista government in nicaragua. until last year, a contra force estimated at 6,000 to 12,000 men had waged the better part of the campaign from base camps in honduras along the nicaraguan border. the rebels say most of their forces are now inside nicaragua
by congressional vote, the united states has cut off further military aid, damaging prospects for long-term effectiveness inside nicaragua
there is a great concern that the contras, if defeated, will try to come back here,'' said luna mejia
gen. regalado told journalists in february he hoped the contras would be able to keep up their fight but said if they cannot, they are not welcome back in honduras
we have instructed immigration authorities along the border to ensure that they do not return,'' he said
puerto sees a connection between the contra problem and continued military preponderance in honduran politics. citing honduras' very strong alliance with washington, he said: ``to whom does the honduran army owe its allegiance? everything indicates it owes its allegiance to the united states, and not to its own people.''
he said civilian government and close alignment with the united states had done little to alleviate the poverty of hundreds of thousands in this mainly agricultural country of 4.5 million people
people expected something different from civilian government, but they got more of the same,'' puerto said. ``if things continue like this, people may lose faith in so-called democracy and look for other less desirable forms of struggle.''
azcona hoyo is past the midway point in the four-year term to which he was inaugurated in january 1986. elections are scheduled in november 1989
new discoveries by american archaeologists indicate that humans could have settled on cyprus around 9000 b.c., 1,500 years earlier than previously thought
the finds also indicate that some species of ancient animals survived here at least 1,000 years after they were believed to have become extinct
if proven correct, the discoveries mean that cyprus was one of the earliest human settlements north of africa, along with the island of corsica, also in the mediterranean
if these dates are corroborated, the site will have provided by far the earliest archaeological evidence for island colonization anywhere in the mediterranean,'' dr. stuart swiny, director of the cyprus american archaeological research institute, reported in a recent lecture
scientists had previously dated man's arrival on cyprus around 7500 b.c
but archaelogists digging on a slope near the sprawling british air base at akrotiri on cyprus' south coast recently found pygmy hippopotamus and dwarf elephant bones, some mixed with shells, flint and ash
archaelogists believe the flint, an early cutting tool, was used to slice meat from the animals. the ash indicated cooking fires
carbon dating placed the remains at around 9000 b.c., a millenium after those species of animals were believed to have died out
swiny said that the animals, common to many mediterranean islands thousands of years ago, were wiped out by climatic changes during the last ice age that ended around 12,000 years ago
we thought ... these animals died out because of natural causes _ they couldn't get enough food or enough water,'' swiny said in an interview after the lecture
but now it looks as if man was also responsible for wiping them out.''
the akrotiri excavation is sponsored by the university of nevada and the american schools of oriental research, which sponsors the cyprus american institute. the dig is under the direction of dr. alan simmons, who currently is in nevada
the original discovery was made in 1980 by a british security officer at akrotiri, maj. brian pile, then a lieutenant, while he was training his men to seek out unusual objects
underground excavation at the site, eight miles south of the port city of limassol, started last july and will continue this summer
swiny said the actual age of the site will remain questionable until results of further tests are obtained
the finds are only some of the important discoveries unearthed by american archaeologists in the last few years on cyprus, the center of trade routes between europe and the middle east for centuries
the island is studded with relics of a history that spans more than 10,000 years, during which more than a dozen civilizations, including achaean greeks, egyptians, romans, armenians, venetians and ottoman turks left their imprint
americans are involved in six of the 20 digs currently being made in the greek-controlled southern part of cyprus
the cyprus american institute provides logistical help at one sponsored by brandeis university, of waltham, mass., at the late bronze age town of kalavasos-ayios dhimitrios, 18 miles northeast of limassol
it was one of the biggest bronze age settlements on cyprus and a center for the island's ancient copper trade. cyprus is the phoenician word for copper
last summer archaelogists uncovered the remains of a 13th century b.c. building, covering more than 10,764 square feet and once at least two stories high, that was apparently destroyed by fire
it's the biggest and most important building at the site and one of the biggest of that period in cyprus,'' said dr. alison south todd, the dig's co-director
we also found some inscriptions which are very rare to the period in cypro-minoan script,'' she added
cypro-minoan, which resembles the script used in minoan crete 4,000 years ago, has never been deciphered
the presence of these inscriptions and the huge storage capacity of the building, known as building x, suggest it was either a palace or a town hall
the storage room, more than 60 feet long and 24 feet wide, consists of an outer wall and six stone pillars that once supported the roof
the shards of at least 47 jars, some once as tall as six feet, have been found. all apparently had been smashed in the fire. but six intact jars were later discovered in pits below the floor
todd discovered a tomb, considered one of the richest and best preserved ever found on cyprus, while digging an exploratory trench out from the building
the oval-shaped tomb contained the skeletons of three young women, a child about 3 years old and three infants. they apparently had social status and wealth
the women had been buried with gold and silver jewelry, bronze and bone artifacts, containers of wine with small cups inside and cylindrical ivory cosmetic boxes
abraham d. sofaer says he has been burned and tempered since leaving the federal bench three years ago to become the top lawyer at the state department, a job that keeps him in the heat of the battle over ``star wars,'' the iran-contra affair and other controversies
if it helps to go through fire, i was helped,'' said sofaer
sofaer, 49, says he faces an uncertain future after president reagan leaves office, and is bitter about criticism he received from lawmakers for what is called the ``broad interpretation'' of the anti-ballistic missile treaty
his interpreration, which would have allowed reagan to accelerate the development and testing of missile defenses using lasers and other exotic weapons, provoked angry outcries from members of congress, who voted last year to bar the administration from spending any money that would violate the ``restrictive interpretation.''
i hope that people consider me to be respectable and honorable some day for my work,'' said sofaer. ``but it has been very rough to be attacked the way some people have attacked me,'' he said, referring to sen. sam nunn, d-ga., the chairman of the armed services committee, and sen. joseph biden, d-del., of the foreign relations committee.''
arms control is a very, very emotional subject,'' said sofaer. ``i must say i was not clued in, in a sense, so it was a shock for me to run into that degree of criticism. i feel it was very unfair and unjustified.''
he was also involved in questioning israeli officials in the case of jonathan pollard, who was sentenced to life in prison for spying for israel, and has facilitated contacts between the israeli government and the independent counsel investigating the iran-contra affair
sofaer, interviewed in his office, indicated he might oppose efforts by the iran-contra independent counsel to subpoena testimony from two israelis involved in the clandestine sale of arms to iran, but that no final decision had been reached
as state department legal adviser, sofaer heads a team of about 100 lawyers, and by all accounts has a warm relationship with secretary of state george p. shultz
sofaer was born on may 6, 1938, in bombay to a family of iraqi jews, and came to this country in 1948. after attending law school, he served as clerk to supreme court associate justice william j. brennan in 1966-67, taught law at columbia university from 1969-79, and was u.s. district judge in new york from 1979-85
sofaer gained national prominence as trial judge in the libel case brought by former israeli defense minister ariel sharon against time magazine
in an landmark verdict engineered by sofaer, the jury found that time made a factual error in reporting that a secret israeli report said sharon had discussed revenge with lebanese officials before massacres in two palestinian refugee camps. but the jury said time acted without malice, and was therefore not liable for monetary damages
because of the way i handled the verdict, it turned out to be an important innovation in libel law,'' said sofaer, who proudly points out a sketch of the trial scene hanging on wall of his state department office
i liked being a judge very much,'' said sofaer. ``i particularly liked trials.''
but, he said, ``i don't have any expectation of returning to the bench. no one has invited me. i would certainly prefer that to being unemployed. i don't expect to be unemployed.''
the truth is, he said, ``it's a possibility that i will have a lot of time on my hands'' after reagan leaves office
sofaer bridles at accusations that he devised legal rationales for controversial reagan policies, such as star wars
i have said no to several things, plans, kidnappings, abductions, intrusions into the mail of other nations. there have been lots of things i have opposed successfully,'' he said
sofaer declined to disclose details of the kidnappings and abductions he opposed, but said that none had gone forward. he did support the abduction of fawaz younis, a lebanese suspected in the hijacking of a royal jordanian airliner on june 6, 1985
younis was seized by u.s. agents in international waters off cyprus last sept. 13 and brought to the united states
of all sofaer's actions, he probably will be remembered most for his broad interpretation of the abm treaty
what happened was that senator nunn and others jumped on this issue before we were done with all our work,'' said sofaer. ``the reason we weren't done with our work was because the broad interpretation was announced long before all the work was done, and before any decision to implement was made.'' the interpretation never was implemented
robert c. mcfarlane, then the white house national security adviser, disclosed the broad interpretation on a television news show on oct. 6, 1985
the ensuing controversy has centered on three main issues:
_whether the treaty barred development of space-based or mobile anti-missile weapons based on ``other physical principles''' than those which existed in 1972
_whether remarks made by u.s. officials during ratification hearings in 1972 bound future administrations
_ and whether the subsequent conduct of the superpowers bound them to the restrictive interpretation
sofaer said he was ``not amazed'' by the outcry following mcfarlane's revelations. ``i am not naive. i realize that these people are motivated by their desire to win political battles, not to win legal arguments.''
analysis of the ratification question had been prepared not by sofaer, but by junior attorneys on his staff, and was seized upon by sdi opponents
i had said three times (the ratification analysis) was inadequate and that i would have to come back and redo it. in fact, i was in the midst of redoing it'' when mcfarlane disclosed the broad interpretation
sofaer has completed his review of the abm treaty, and sticks by the broad interpretation, although congress has closed the door for the time being
now would be the time for a real debate on the abm treaty,'' he said. photos and 1 graphic.)</note>
labor relations in the airline industry used to be fairly genteel and mutual accommodation was the rule. then, after deregulation, came a competitive crunch, mergers and cost-cutting, and at many carriers snarl has replaced purr. a reporter surveys today's turbulent scene
the chairman of pan american world airways and several senior executives are fired after a closed-door deal with the airline's labor unions
flight attendants trek to the suburban home of the chairman of trans world airlines to register a protest about a strike that ended nearly two years ago. more than 4,000 of them are still looking to get their jobs back
eastern airlines, expecting a strike, is planning for a small cargo carrier with non-union pilots to fly many of its passenger planes, prompting charges of union busting from eastern pilots and mechanics
it's management and labor hardball, pure and simple
and it has become more frequent since the government eased out of regulating the airline industry in the early 1980s. along with bitter competition among airlines have come increasingly acrimonious relations with labor
in the wars between airline workers and their bosses, the genteel atmosphere of bargaining _ common when the government had its reins on the industry _ seems to have gone the way of the propeller airplane
the hotbed of labor-management combat is at eastern, the miami-based airline that has struggled with huge losses and almost continuous labor turmoil for more than a decade. the company wants major concessions. the unions say they're being pushed into a strike
when word came recently that 26 eastern jets were being leased to a little known cargo operator named orion air, the news unleashed a firestorm among many of eastern's employees
it was no secret that eastern, in the midst of stormy contract talks with its mechanics, intends in event of a strike this summer to have non-union orion air pilots fly the leased planes on eastern's most critical routes
it's an attempt to decimate eastern's cockpit crews,'' says jack bavis, head of the airline's pilots union. there are hints from the parent 40,000-member air line pilots association of a one-day nationwide shutdown of air service if eastern ever uses the orion pilots
thomas matthews, eastern's vice president for human relations, calls the non-union orion pilots ``our insurance coverage.''
corporate hardball
prior to deregulation, for maybe 20 years, there was a posture of accommodation. the unions accepted the companies and the companies accepted the unions. government generally was neutral or slightly on the side of labor,'' says frank cassels, a professor of industrial relations at northwestern university
when labor wanted more money, the airlines often agreed. they knew that the government would pass the increased costs on in the form of higher fares. today, airlines compete vigorously on fares and have argued that one of their biggest problems has been high labor costs. on average, 35 percent of airline operational costs are for labor, according to the air transport association
as a result, there has been ``a stage of outright hostility'' between labor and management in recent years, cassels says
the tiff at eastern may be the latest, but it's hardly the most bitter standoff between labor and management in recent years
it was in september 1983 that frank lorenzo, chairman of texas air corp., the nemesis of airline labor, stopped negotiating with the unions and shut down continental airlines. he declared bankruptcy and shed the existing labor contracts
three days later, continental emerged with pilots flying the same planes, but earning half the salary. pilots and flight attendants saw their strike fizzle
today, continental, which like eastern is owned by texas air corp., is larger than ever, but many of its one-time well-paid pilots are wearing the uniforms of other airlines and have lost much of their seniority and pay
in early 1986 the flight attendants at twa, faced with demands for sharp salary cuts, walked off their jobs and onto the picket lines. today two-thirds of the 6,500 attendants who went on strike are still grounded. while the attendants await a recall from twa, the airline continues to fly with a third fewer attendants who earn less money and work longer hours
would the flight attendants again choose a strike?
victoria frankovich, president of the independent federation of flight attendants, who led the 1986 walkout, mulls the question over before answering. ``i don't think we had a choice,'' she says
attendants at other airlines may not have lost their jobs in recent years, but they have not been able to exert much clout. recently, flight attendants were pushed reluctantly into a settlement at american and thought better of a strike at northwest, where negotiations continue
but labor _ at least in terms of the more-powerful pilots and mechanics unions _ has flexed its muscles as well after several years of back-pedaling and reeling from management demands
consider the fired pan am executives
william t. coleman, with the blessing of fellow members of the pan am board of directors, resigned and sealed the deal with a handshake last january. he then walked into the office of pan am chairman c. edward acker and informed acker and vice chairman martin shugrue they were fired
by the time the bloodletting was over, three senior vice presidents, including raymond grebey, who was in charge of labor relations, also were forced to resign
acker is now in bermuda ``assessing what he's going to do next.'' shugrue recently was hired by texas air corp. to head its continental airlines subsidiary
richard ferris can understand how they feel
a former hotel executive, ferris had a dream of turning united airlines into a broad-based travel company. while at the helm of ual inc., he bought two hotel chains and a rental car company and envisioned one-stop shopping for transportation and lodging for businessmen
the name of ual inc., was changed to allegis corp., to broaden its appeal, but the moniker never caught on among wall street investors. it also served to highlight claims by the pilots that ferris was siphoning money and attention from the airline
one evening last june, the company's board of directors demanded ferris' resignation. the pilots claimed responsibility
although ferris' fall may have been the result of a variety of forces, most industry analysts agree that his empire began to fail when the pilots union launched a $4.5 billion takeover bid, the first effort by a union to buy an entire airline
anyone who thinks that the pilots union or the machinists today are the underdogs in one of these battles is clearly mistaken,'' says clark onstad, a vice president for texas air
indeed, pilots at many airlines have regained the momentum. their salaries are on the upswing. the dual wage scales _ a lower one for newly hired pilots _ imposed by american airlines in 1983 and widely copied by other carriers is showing signs of erosion. new contracts call for a more rapid merging of the two scales
the air line pilots association, caught unprepared and disorganized by the continental bankruptcy, has vowed never to be left so vulnerable again. stiff increases in dues for its 40,000 members have brought $40 million into a war chest that continues to grow
the unions also say they will continue to take their fights into airline board rooms, citing their successes at united, pan am and at twa where the pilots formed an unusual alliance with corporate raider carl icahn two years ago to fend off lorenzo's texas air
ironically, that set the stage for lorenzo to buy eastern, where labor war remains rife. nevertheless, declares alpa president henry duffy, ``labor unions will continue to increase their wall street connections.''
certainly in this day and age you won't get (salary or work rule) givebacks,'' says robert joedicke, airline analyst for shearson lehman bros. but he adds quickly that he wouldn't ``put the unions in the catbird seat'' just yet
nowhere is that more true than at texas air, the houston-based airline whose continental and eastern subsidiaries account for 20 percent of the industry's market and which has led the trend toward lower airline fares
lorenzo made his mark in 1972 when he bought debt-ridden texas international and turned it around by unleashing ``peanut fares'' when business was slow. his low-fare strategy continued with new york air in 1981 and with the newly emerged continental two years later
but to play out the strategy, lorenzo had to cut costs, a direct attack on labor
does frank like unions? that's not the issue,'' says onstad, lorenzo's point man in washington. ``the issue is how does management get the flexibility to deal in a deregulated environment that frank is dealing with.''
onstad says that some members of the machinists union, especially ground workers who haul baggage, are earning salaries _ an average of $43,000 a year with fringes _ that are way too high
when continental emerged with a non-union work force in 1983 it had cut its pilots' pay in half overnight. continental workers in 1986 earned on average $28,200 a year, the lowest in the industry, and better than a third lower than its chief competitors
mechanics at continental earn $16 an hour base salary, $4 an hour lower than new contracts agreed to at united and usair, according to the machinist union
in the third quarter of last year, continental's labor costs were 22 percent of total operating costs, compared to about 35 percent industrywide
but texas air executives argue that low costs are needed if the airline is to survive and continue to provide the low fares that have opened air travel to millions of people
texas air corp., lost $466 million last year and its executives put much of the blame on costs related to absorbing people express and the labor unrest at eastern, where losses were $182 million
eastern president philip bakes has said he wants $490 million in labor concessions at the struggling airline. union leaders countered that they have given back too much already and accuse lorenzo of trying to dismember the airline
jack bavis, the pilot's leader at eastern, says that since lorenzo bought the airline he has:
_sold eastern's valuable computer reservation system to texas air
_cleared the way for continental to fly eastern's profitable latin america routes if lorenzo chooses to
_sold six eastern airbus a-300s and a mcdonnell douglas dc-10 to continental
_tried to spin-off eastern's moneymaking northeast air shuttle operation under a separate subsidiary
he's taking the crown jewels, spinning them off and making them part of texas air,'' says charlie bryan, the chief of the international association of machinists at eastern
onstad suggests the eastern negotations have industrywide implications
we are now the last of the low-cost operators. people focus all of their attention on texas air,'' onstad says. ``if the unions can defeat us, low fares go away and the pressure on wages at other airlines go away.'' photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>
it's been called america's most hidden problem. an estimated one in five adults in the united states can't read beyond the fourth-grade level. but help is available through a growing network of organizations dedicated to stamping out illiteracy. two of the most successful groups are based in syracuse, n.y
joseph everson always feared ``signing away his life.'' even more, he dreaded revealing that he couldn't read
then, about four years ago, everson received a letter from a local hospital saying he owed a big bill for recent treatments. his nightmare had become reality
i told them i had medicaid to take care of it, but they said i had agreed to pay the bill,'' everson says. ``they said i had signed my name on the dotted line.''
fortunately, the 42-year-old everson was able to settle the dispute, but only after admitting to hospital officials that he really didn't know what he had signed because he couldn't read. that was the catalyst everson needed to seek help
no longer would everson have to rely on his wife, children or siblings to explain service applications and contracts to him or read him the newspaper to him. above all, he would be able to do the thing he had longed for most _ to be able to read his bible for the sermons he gave to his church of god in christ congregation at payton memorial temple in syracuse
over the years, family members had read the bible to him
at first it was hard, but after a while i began to know by heart most of the verses i would use in my sermons,'' the minister says. ``i might not know the exact words, but i knew the exact feeling and that was easy to translate.''
everson says it's painful to admit you can't read, ``but it opens a new way of life and you have to admit it to get help.''
living in syracuse, it was easy for everson to find help. the city is the headquarters of two of the most successful organizations in the fight against illiteracy _ laubach literacy international and literacy volunteers of america, both part of a national campaign being conducted by project literacy united states (plus)
laubach is the older of the two groups, founded in 1955 by the late frank c. laubach, a missionary who spent 40 years traveling the globe teaching people how to read and write their native languages. laubach became internationally recognized for his approach to illiteracy, the ``laubach method.'' today, lli has 750 councils in 45 states as well as an international program and publishing division
syracuse housewife ruth colvin was inspired by laubach, who taught at syracuse university in the 1950s, and in 1962 she began a basement organization speaking out against illiteracy and teaching people to read. today, nearly 300 lva community affiliates comprise a network spanning 35 states. the organization has doubled in size in the last three years
together, the two groups are responsible for teaching millions of americans to read. last year alone, both estimated they taught more than 100,000 adults how to read
sadly, that only scratches the surface. the u.s. department of education says 27 million adults in the united states _ one in every five _ can't read beyond a fourth-grade level
in some cases the consequences have been tragic. a new york city mother fed undiluted formula to her nine-day old infant because she couldn't read the directions. the baby died
the government estimates illiteracy costs the united states about $225 billion annually in welfare payments, lost job productivity, unrealized earnings and tax revenues and crime
while illiteracy is predominantly a problem of poor america, its victims include bankers, real estate brokers, firefighters, farmers, laborers and others, according to colvin
don't equate ignorance with illiteracy. people learn to get by,'' she says. ``they contrive ways to work around it because they are too embarrassed to let anyone know. some people have remarkable memories, others fake poor eyesight and have others do their reading.''
however, the demands of today's high-tech society have made it harder
it's a national embarrassment,'' says peter waite, director of american programs for laubach. ``illiteracy is america's most hidden problem, and its most solvable problem given adequate resources. really, there's no good reason people who want to learn how to read and write can't do it. there are a dozen proven programs out there now.''
laubach and literacy volunteers each have their own approach to teaching. both are self-paced individual programs that specialize in mobilizing volunteers to serve as tutors. but laubach teaches reading through a phonics-based system keyed on letter and word sound association, while literacy volunteers use a four-part method that incorporates phonics
the literacy volunteers approach also takes advantage of language experience, using the student's hobbies or interests to draw on as a basis to teach new words
sight words and patterned words are other reading techniques employed by literacy volunteers. sight words are those so basic to reading and encountered so often that they are best learned by sight, not by sounding them out, such as `the,' `have,' and `were.' in the patterned words technique, which concentrates on vowel sounds, words are taught by learning families of words, such as `man,' `can,' `fan
it hasn't been easy, but i don't know why i didn't try and learn sooner,'' says everson, who wants to become an lva tutor as soon as he becomes proficient. ``the longer you wait, the worse it gets as far as dealing with the problem. learning to read is like finding yourself.''
waite and colvin say everson's story is a familiar one
it's interesting if you ask a student whose fault it is they can't read, invariably they will say it's their fault,'' waite says. ``they blame themselves. but there are always extenuating circumstances they can't control. someone else's fault: a teacher, a parent, a school system. they drop behind and then get caught in the cycle.''
in recent years, the federal and local governments, local school systems, libraries, churches, businesses and community groups have entered the endeavor, starting up programs at various levels to assist people in learning how to read
there's no indication the problem is getting any worse,'' waite says. ``however, it doesn't appear to be getting any better.'' photos. colorfoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</note>
a museum in southeastern mexico offers clues to three civilizations that predate the aztecs. among other things, there is evidence that these ancient people probably perceived the earth as round, designed remarkably accurate calendars and had an advanced knowledge of mathematics and astronomy
by isaac a. levi=
huge carved stone heads, tiny clay figures and thousands of other artifacts at a museum here tell a strange story about three civilizations that flourished long before columbus discovered america
it's about the olmecs, totonacas and huaxtecs, who inhabited a long stretch of coast on the gulf of mexico
the fascinating and sometimes gruesome story is told vividly at the museum of xalapa, which specializes in the region's archaeological treasures
a lot is still unknown about the three civilizations. they are believed to have been part of a series of migrations from asia that started about 35,000 years ago across the bering strait, by way of alaska, and lasted several millenia
but, says museum director fernando winfield capitaine, ``as new finds are made and studies of old ones shed new light, the results may rewrite quite a few history books
we don't know what their language was, or what they even called themselves,'' he adds. ``even the names we use for them are false and relatively new. they are `nahuatl' names, the trading language of the aztecs, which didn't even exist at the time.''
only 3,000 of the museum's 29,000 pieces are on display for lack of space. they tell how these people performed human sacrifices, probably perceived the earth as round, designed remarkably accurate calendars and had an advanced knowledge of mathemathics and astronomy, among other things
the artifacts range in size from a tiny olmec carving of a rain god 4 inches high, to huge stone altars. the museum's centerpiece is a monolithic head 9 feet high and weighing 16 tons, carved from andesite rock
now housed in a new $3 million set of modern buildings covering 14,400 square yards and surrounded by eight acres of wooded park, the museum is part of the veracruz state university in xalapa, the state's capital 74 miles northwest of the port of veracruz
the olmecs, totonacas and huaxtecas based their agriculture on corn, frijole beans and squash, supplementing their diets with dog meat, river fish and wild animals and birds, which they seasoned with chili peppers, herbs and other spices
both their weapons and their tools were crude, mostly made out of stone or wood, and no one is sure how they carved such huge stone statues. but their civilizations were surprisingly advanced for its time
in his guidebook ``master works of the xalapa museum,'' mexican anthropolgist alfonso medellin zenil says it's possible the olmecs were the first to make paper out of wood pulp in america
archaeologists believe the political organization was more of a loose coalition of small towns or city-states than one big government entity. but their influence spread far and wide and some of it survives in present-day mexico
they could read and write and knew what a wheel was, but didn't use it, probably because they had no draft animals. their ancestors had hunted them all out of existence, including the ancient american horse and the elephant
they spun and wove fibers, including cotton. they tailored their clothes, wore earrings and jewelry, blackened their teeth with natural tar for cosmetic purposes and made rubber from the rubber tree, which is native to the region
being cross-eyed was considered a sign of beauty
by polishing metallic rock, the olmecs made flat mirrors which they hung over their chests as jewelry, or concave ones, which they used to light fires
they made music on drums, whistles, ocarinas, clay flutes and other instruments. they traveled and traded extensively, as far west as the pacific coast and as far south as el salvador in central america, spreading their cultures and acquiring new ones
as a result, cacao _ the bean from which chocolate is derived and is native to the gulf coast _ became a popular currency for trade throughout pre-columbian mexico
at first, they cremated or simply buried their dead, but later they built little pyramidal rock mounds to mark the sites. later still, they built the monumental pyramids that survive today
they played a ceremonial sport with a rubber ball, which was a combination of soccer and basketball. the winning team was afterwards beheaded as a sacrifice, usually to a sun god, although some authorities claim it was the losers who lost their heads
other victims had their hearts cut out atop some pyramid or other sacred altar. some were skinned alive and priests donned their skins to dance before xipe totec, the ``god of the flayed,'' in a fertility rite to mark the beginning of spring
prisoners of war often had their hands severed so the victors could acquire their strength, skill and magic
worship was centered on the sun, the moon and the planet venus
all three cultures worshipped the jaguar as a sun god and hunting the animal was forbidden, except for its skins, which priests wore during sacred ceremonies. the jaguar was often depicted in partly human form
it was said that in times long past a woman mated with a jaguar, giving birth to a ``were-jaguar.'' archeologists believe this explains the olmecs' morbid fascination with dwarfs, hunchbacks and other human deformations
little is known about venus, usually depicted as the lesser of the three, except that ehecatl quetzalcoatl, god of the hurricane and other winds, and xochiquetzal, goddess of love and the spring, were probably associated with it
the most fascinating of the moon deities was tlasolteotl, the totonaca goddess of confession, protectress of childbirth and advocate of illicit love and passions. she encouraged people to sin so that she could later absolve them
sinners had to confess to her, so that she could devour the ``rubbish or spiritual garbage'' that weighed upon them
but,'' says winfield, ``only one confession was allowed in a lifetime, and people tried to put it off as much as they could, since there was no forgiveness for a second offender.'' photo.)</note>

editor's note _ they are on the radical fringe of the environmental movement, labeled terrorists by some for their practice of ``monkeywrenching,'' sabotaging the equipment of loggers and developers. but earth first! founder david foreman compares his style of civil disobedience with that of mohandas gandhi or dr. martin luther king
from their seats in a juneau conference hall, some 400 people tip their noses toward the rafters and let out a long, high-pitched howl
with scarcely a giggle, they howl their scorn at wilderness-wrecking development, howl their devotion to david foreman's controversial brand of environmentalism
wolf mimicry is among the more benign of foreman's attention-grabbing tricks, which some call criminal, others call visionary
it's the stuff of earth first!, the self-styled radical fringe of environmentalism founded by foreman in 1980 when he decided the movement was boring itself out of existence
since then, earth firsters have been putting themselves on front pages, infuriating loggers and frustrating law enforcement officials with their ``civil disobedience'' protests
they shackle themselves to trees, stage sit-ins before bulldozer blades, pour sand in the engines of earthmovers and pound spikes in tree trunks to mangle loggers' saws
they call the practice monkeywrenching
in the eyes of the alaska loggers association, foreman and his followers are ``terrorists.'' foreman prefers to compare himself to mohandas gandhi and martin luther king jr
he says sabotaging equipment isn't terrorism because it doesn't hurt people
i think that i believe in non-violence, too,'' he says. ``pulling up survey stakes, putting sand in the crank case of a bulldozer, those aren't violent.''
though opponents often link earth first! to an accident in california in which a sawmill worker was hurt by a tree spike that struck a saw blade, foreman says conservationists were not involved
foreman, who makes his home in tucson, ariz., has been arrested several times. dozens of earth first! members were charged with criminal mischief and similar crimes for anti-logging protests in oregon last summer
over the past few years they've blockaded oil wells, occupied uranium mines and joined greenpeace at nuclear test protests in nevada
if people see him going to jail for his cause, foreman says, maybe they'll take environmentalism more seriously
sometimes you've got to put your body on the line,'' foreman says. ``face it. there are a lot of madmen and madwomen out there destroying the earth. why shouldn't we be mad about it? why shouldn't we be passionate?
we need to scare people. it's not our job to come up with the final, politically acceptable solution. we're advocates.''
for all its radical tone, foreman's activism has its underpinnings in conventional political strategy
at a how-to workshop on promoting the environmental cause, he explained he doesn't really expect the general public to adopt all his views. by presenting an extreme, he simply hopes to shift the ultimate compromise his way
there are rational solutions, but others should find them,'' he said. ``i see very few politicians respond to facts. i see politicians respond to votes, to public opinion. we compromise and we sort of water down our opinions before ever speaking them.''
he tells a class how to use self-deprecating jokes _ as politicians do _ to make the audience think they're regular guys
he advises his students not to dread a knowledgeable audience. ``if you relax, you can sound like you know a lot more about something than you do.''
passing out pamphlets? dress up in animal costumes and stage a skit, he says. you'll be harder to ignore
and when you're really in an adversarial position, foreman says, remember ``they can't beat you up quite as much if they're laughing.''
it was foreman's talent for humor and drama that brought him an invitation to speak at the alaska environmental assembly's recent conference in juneau
the assembly got the theater it wanted as he sermonized
first came the doomsday predictions: ``1988 is the greatest biological crisis since evolution began 3{ billion years ago,'' foreman says. ``by the year 2,000 the only large mammals left will be the ones we allow to exist.''
then the promise of salvation: this generation is the most important that ever lived, he says, the generation that can halt environmental destruction
then the underlying moral: biocentrism, foreman says, is the most important philosophy of man. it holds that you can't change one part of the world without affecting every other, that a crab in the mud has as much right to life as a man
and, finally, the call to give up worldly goods, to choose wilderness over drinking more coke, buying more vcrs, figuring the value of something ``by how many greasy bills you can pile up next to it.''
forget about building more highways and bring back the bison instead, foreman says. look beneath skyscrapers and opera houses to see ``a vision of the world the way it could be.''
be an animal, he advises, closing with the howl, 400 voices strong
so how does foreman suggest modernized americans get back to the bison?
i don't have all the answers,'' he says after the speech. ``i think that's one of the problems, that we think we have to have all the answers. but i want to energize people to ask the questions.''
foreman says giving up all modern ways for an ecologically sound stone age is not the idea. he'd settle for a shift toward the primitive side
i believe in compromise and balance. we're protecting something like 3 percent of the land of the united states as wilderness. i don't think that's balance. i would be satisfied with 20 or 30 percent.''
the conservationists who work to reach those compromises sometimes seem unsure how to react to foreman's flamboyance
some juneau environmentalists were titillated. ``did you know you're sitting behind a terrorist?'' one lobbyist stage-whispered a row behind foreman, who was giggling at the furor his visit had stirred
loggers and state natural resources commissioner judy brady boycotted the meeting because of foreman's presence
others mixed admiration with a tinge of embarrassment
bart koehler, a leader of the southeast alaska conservation coalition, was foreman's partner in founding earth first!, but returned to more conventional environmental groups in 1982
though they've been best friends since 1973 and remain so, koehler doesn't like to be reminded of his ties to foreman
foreman isn't offended. being environmentalism's bad boy, he says, has its political purpose
i think we help other environmental groups look mainstream and reasonable _ which they are _ but i think we've helped move them toward taking a stronger position,'' he says. photo.)</note>

editor's note _ many of the stories of the late john steinbeck have become the plot lines for movies, but sometimes the author's artistry has been lost in the translation. now his sons and some of their friends have formed a movie company to try to faithfully adapt their father's works to feature films
a realist in the video age, writer thom steinbeck believes that film offers him the best opportunity to carry on in his famous father's footsteps
the son of the late john steinbeck, one of america's best-known writers, is one of the founders of a new movie company dedicated to faithfully adapating the works of famous authors, starting with steinbeck
sitting in the secluded catskill mountain studio of artist eugene gregan, his film company partner, thom steinbeck explains his plans for steinbeck films inc
our concern is with craftsmanship. steinbeck spent a lot of time on his work,'' says thom, who frequently refers to his father by the family name. ``we're going to spend as much time on his work as he did.''
with dark, combed-back hair, ruddy complexion and piercing blue eyes, the 43-year-old thom resembles the prize-winning author who wrote ``the grapes of wrath,'' ``east of eden'' and other classics of american literature
following years of struggle to make a living as an author, john steinbeck gained national attention in the early 1930s as a writer who could masterfully depict the plight of the disenfranchised and downtrodden. he produced 19 works of fiction, eight of non-fiction and also plays, a documentary and a screenplay
his 1939 book ``the grapes of wrath,'' about the hopeless migration of dust bowl farmers, won a pulitzer prize. it also was one of the many steinbeck stories adapted for film
in 1962, six years before his death at age 66, steinbeck was awarded the nobel prize for literature
steinbeck's two sons, thom and john iv, are writers themselves and now partners in the film venture
we chose steinbeck to work with first because there've been very few accurate interpretations of his work that have been translated into film,'' thom says. ``in many cases, companies have chosen pieces that are far too long for a 125-page script, which is usually standard.''
the results, thom says, have been films which cut the writing of his father and others to fit the filmmaking ``formula.''
on broadway, the author owns the stage. in hollywood, he's lucky if he can get invited to a couple of parties,'' says thom, who recently completed the screenplay of his father's novel, ``in dubious battle'' for a los angeles film company, zupnick enterprises inc
it's not that the senior steinbeck minded seeing his writing adapted for film
steinbeck is not like a lot of authors,'' gregan says, ``because he thought visually and wrote visually. some writers are totally verbal. steinbeck is easy to intepret to film because he saw it that way. he loved movies. all his best friends were involved in movies.''
thom says his father knew and influenced the writers who adapted his stories for film while he was alive. ``it's the films that have taken place since his death that i think he would roll over in his grave about,'' he says
the company plans to make full-length feature films based on ``travels with charley in search of america,'' steinbeck's last book, and ``the moon is down,'' a story about nazi occupation of a norwegian town in world war ii
short stories from ``the long valley'' and ``the pastures of heaven'' are also slated for production, with ``the long valley'' scheduled for release in about a year
we want to stay very close to the novel,'' gregan says, ``so that eventually what people can have is a videotape library of john steinbeck's work.''
if translating books to film is so difficult, then why not leave steinbeck's efforts in their purest form?
because people don't read any more,'' thom says with a laugh. ``and the only way i can start them to read is by doing accurate interpretations of steinbeck's work so that they might be enticed to read it.''
some of steinbeck's work that is already on film shouldn't be duplicated, thom says
who could play tom joad better than fonda?'' thom said of actor henry fonda who starred in ``the grapes of wrath.''
for the last 2{ years, the steinbeck brothers and gregan have talked of starting a film company. thom spent last summer and fall in a cabin near gregan's mountain home and the wheels began to turn
three other partners, whom thom didn't want to identify, are also involved
the firm will have offices in new york city and monterey, calif., where thom makes his home and where his father lived off and on
viking penquin inc. has continued to print steinbeck books in hardbound and paperback editions. the largest printings since 1986 have been 280,000 paperback copies of ``the grapes of wrath'' and 119,500 of ``east of eden.''
professor ted hayashi, president of the international steinbeck society at ball state university in muncie, ind., believes there is an ample market worldwide for the films
whenever somebody makes a film out of steinbeck literature, i want to see it,'' hayashi says, though he concedes that some people have been disappointed in the past when steinbeck stories were adapted for film
`cannery row'' independently was a very enjoyable movie, but if you're serious about comparing movies and literary work, a lot of scholars were disappointed,'' hayashi says. ``film is a very independent art after all.''
the logo of the film company is a haunting sketch of the elder steinbeck, done by gregan. but what would thom say in response to critics who might accuse him of trying to profit off of his father's name?
i make money off my father's name right now,'' he said in a blunt, matter-of-fact tone. ``my name is steinbeck. i also share in the literary estate with my brother and stepmother
it's a little bit like inheriting a grocery store. you've got one of two choices: letting the fruit rot on the shelves and not pay attention to it or you can see it as an ongoing business. certainly a literary estate is an ongoing business.'' photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>

editor's note _ five years after he became conductor of the city of birmingham symphony orchestra at age 25, simon rattle thought it could become britain's best. at 33, he hasn't changed his mind. rattle, who is attracting a lot of attention in the world of music, is now bringing the orchestra to america to show it off in 11 cities
britain's simon rattle, who has become known as one of the world's most exciting young conductors, is introducing his city of birmingham symphony orchestra to american audiences for the first time
the orchestra, which rattle believes is ``well on the way'' to becoming britain's finest, will tour 11 u.s. cities from march 29 to april 17
rattle has made his mark in the music world without joining the baton-wielding jet set or accepting a top job with a prestigious orchestra. in fact, he regularly turns down offers to appear as guest conductor
the 33-year-old native of liverpool, england, prefers to concentrate on his job as conductor of the birmingham orchestra and his work as principal guest of the los angeles philharmonic
the curly haired, bright-eyed rattle took over the birmingham orchestra in 1980, at age 25. he plans to stay a while, already making plans for the orchestra into the next century
before he went to birmingham, rattle was the no. 2 conductor with the royal liverpool philharmonic and the bbc scottish symphony and did a lot of guest conducting. ``in some ways,'' he says, ``i was following a more conventional career pattern than i seem to be now.''
rattle is not without his fans in the united states
in the words of critic andrew porter in the new yorker magazine, rattle is considered a first-rate conductor who ``inspires players and elates audiences.''
just before rattle conducted the los angeles philharmonic in his 1985 new york debut, critic nicholas kenyon wrote in the new york times: ``the biggest surprise about this debut by the most brilliantly successful conductor of the younger generation in britain _ the perception, power and clarity of whose work has been acclaimed internationally _ is not the age at which it is occurring but the fact that it did not happen long ago. mr. rattle has been invited to the metropolitan opera and he has been invited to the new york philharmonic. he has turned both down.''
during a recent stopover in new york, rattle was asked if an offer from a prestigious orchestra would lure him away from birmingham
i've been given enough offers that haven't,'' he answers, declining to elaborate. it is known that in 1984 he rejected an invitation from the los angeles philharmonic to become its music director
the work in birmingham is so satisfying,'' he says. ``and it is also unfinished. now we're planning a festival. starting in 1991, we'll do spring festivals, each year concentrating on the music of one decade of 20th century music
in 2000 we'll just about have caught up with ourselves. in 1999, when we're dealing with the music of the '90s, we will surely be playing music by people who now are schoolchildren.''
rattle said in 1985 that he thought the birmingham symphony could become the best in britain
i think they're well on the way,'' he says now
my wife tells me i always refer to the city of birmingham symphony orchestra as `us,' which is true,'' he says. ``we consider that we've been able to grow together. they play beautifully as a unit. there's a degree of listening to each other as an ensemble, like chamber music playing, that is unique in britain.''
though he has made a lot of music documentaries for television, surveying trends or about a particular composer's work, rattle says he isn't a tv ``natural'' like andre previn
andre created an extraordinary new audience in england for music. he can talk to the camera as though it was his best friend. it's something i admire enormously. i can't do that.''
rattle's father briefly led a jazz band. while he appreciates jazz, the younger rattle knew from the time he entered the royal academy of music at age 16 that he would conduct. he thought he'd have to be an instrumentalist _ he was a percussionist _ first, whose conducting career would only be beginning ``about now.''
conducting happened sooner because rattle won a conetst. ``i went in simply because if you got in the final 10, there was a chance to work with the bournemouth symphony,'' he says. ``i was 19 and i'd never conducted a professional orchestra
i still think i only won because it never occurred to me that i might win and i had no anxiety. the final piece i conducted was strauss' `don juan,' which takes 17 minutes. there were 20 minutes to rehearse it. at that age, it was probably just as well. i didn't have time to get up the noses of the musicians.''
studying conducting, rattle says, he learned that ``there's as much connection with what your baton does to the orchestra as to what a violinist's bow does to the strings. all motions a conductor makes affect the orchestra, even if you don't want them to
the reason a conductor begins to get halfway competent around 50 or 60 is that he probably has had as much time in front of an orchestra then as the average 20-year-old violinist has had playing his instrument
at a certain point, to be able to communicate what you know, you have to know your musicians. that's the reason i went down the road of working very hard with one orchestra.''
one of the reasons rattle limits his guest conducting is that he and his american wife, soprano elise ross, and 4-year-old son alexander, known as sasha, like to spend time together
i'm not one of those musicians who wants to live a life which is entirely the musician part,'' he says. ``i'd like to be able to explore the richness of life. there is enough else going on in the world to put music in perspective.'' photo.)</note>
when the time came for president lincoln's secretary of war to point out gen. robert e. lee's route into pennsylvania, he had to seek help from a private
we were filming a scene and we couldn't find the place on the map,'' says sam waterston, who portrays abraham lincoln in the nbc miniseries ``gore vidal's lincoln.'' ``the only person who knew the route was a private.''
the private was one of the civil war re-enactors who served as union and confederate soldiers for the four-hour adaptation of vidal's book about life inside the white house
`they were just an enormous resource in helping the rest of us, who were just pretending, to feel authentic,'' says waterston. ``i remember riding down a street and there were small groups of union soldiers along the way. they came to attention as i passed. they did it according to civil war drill
they were immensely supportive of the rest of us. they saved us more than once when we needed information, like with lee's route.''
lincoln,'' which will be televised on sunday and monday, also stars mary tyler moore as mary todd lincoln, john houseman as gen. winfield scott, richard mulligan as secretary of state william seward, john mcmartin as ohio sen. salmon p. chase, who hopes to become president, and deborah adair as chase's overly ambitious daughter, kate
in an ironic twist on history, the washington scenes were filmed in richmond, va., the capital of the confederacy. the confederate home for needy women, built as a replica of the original white house, was used as the executive mansion. petersburg, where lee put up his last defense before surrendering at appomattox, was also used for some washington scenes
the side benefit of that was that everyone had an enormous interest in the civil war,'' waterston says. ``one man came up to me and said, `if you were the man you're pretending to be i'd want to shoot you.' we got into quite a discussion.''
waterston says he had not seen any lincoln portrayals in a long time and had purposely avoided looking at any
henry fonda seems to me to be the closest to what i imagine he was really like,'' waterston says. fonda appeared in ``young mr. lincoln'' in 1939. ``but i didn't see anything. the danger is that you'll be influenced. in college a friend was doing `richard iii' and made the fatal mistake of seeing laurence olivier's film about five days before we opened. he couldn't put it out of his head.''
waterston says he read a lot of books on lincoln, including one by william safire, one-time speech writer for president richard m. nixon
if safire meddles with the facts, he tells you how,'' waterston says. ``if he's interpreting, he tells you the opposing views so you don't have to read 17 different books to get all the viewpoints.''
waterston says when he read vidal's book he thought it would make good television. ``it's the civil war as seen from the white house, which is different from the usual way of looking in from the outside. it shows how lincoln responded to the pressure of events. i think what's most extraordinary was that he was not perfectly attuned to every situation
but when the chips were down he was up to the occasion. that's what people have found remarkable about him _ how could a man of his background find the skills to manage a war on a scale that no one had ever imagined. his law partner once described him as a man who read less and thought more than anyone he had ever known.''
waterston also spent time trying to understand the man. ``edwin stanton called him `the illinois gorilla,''' he says. ``it certainly takes a breadth of mind to hire that same man as your secretary of war.''
waterston, who is somewhat lincolnesque in build and looks, says he has wanted to portray lincoln for a long time
there ought to be some reward for looking like this,'' he says. ``i thought he was a fascinating man. you can't help but be in awe of this combination of high principle and amazing public skills.''
it was waterston's third opportunity to work with mary tyler moore. previously, they were in ``finnegan begin again'' and ``just between friends.'' he says he found her portrayal of mrs. lincoln as a woman on the edge ``very bold and interesting.''
waterson is currently starring with robert prosky in the new york play ``a walk in the woods.'' playwright lee blessing based it on a real incident in which two arms negotiators, one american and one soviet, worked out a deal during a walk in the woods in geneva, switzerland
this is one of the rare tv appearances for waterston, who was nominated for an academy award for ``the killing fields,'' although he did star in a series six years ago, ``q.e.d.'' photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>
carole shorenstein hays put her own money, some $850,000, where her convictions were and brought ``fences'' to broadway. tony awards, a pulitzer prize and a lucrative film sale were her reward
smart money was against the play, hays' first solo producing venture
listen kid, it ain't commercial,'' hays deadpans, mimicking the advice she got from seasoned theater professionals. they cautioned against bringing to new york the august wilson drama about the upheavals of a black family during the late 1950s
it was important for me to do `fences' because i believed in it,'' the producer said the other day, between coos to her infant son, wally, in a fifth avenue hotel suite. ``it was very important for me to send out the word to young emerging american playwrights that broadway is a place where their dreams could be fulfilled. you don't have to go to london or hollywood.''
besides ``fences,'' wally, born aug. 16, was hays' other big production last year
when hays, wearing a maternity evening gown, clambered to the stage of the mark hellinger theater last june to accept a tony as producer of the best play of the season, she exclaimed, ``i think i'm going to give birth right now.''
she didn't. little walter hays actually arrived some two months later, but, according to hays, ``he knows `fences' inside and out.''
the baby made his broadway stage debut _ at age 8 weeks _ in the show. wrapped in a blanket, he was carried on stage by james earl jones, who usually cradles a doll. wally had to be kept covered, though. he was playing a little black girl
i don't believe i did that,'' hays laughs. ``i'm a real stage mother.''
hays first saw ``fences'' in january 1986 at chicago's goodman theater, while it was making the circuit of various regional theaters. by intermission, she knew she wanted to produce the play
she met with director lloyd richards, who had first done the show at the yale repertory theater in connecticut, with author wilson and jones
it was all very simple,'' she recalls. ``i said, `i want to do this. it will be done. i have a theater in san francisco.'''
hays actually runs three theaters there _ the curran, the golden gate and the orpheum _ all owned by her family. her father is walter h. shorenstein, a california real estate mogul. three years ago, forbes magazine estimated the family fortune at some $300 million
hays always was stage-struck. theater-going was the big family activity. she remembers as a child putting on her party dress and white gloves and going to the theater
when her family got into theater real estate, hays got into the theater business
i started at the bottom of the top,'' she recalls, learning what it takes to put on a play. until ``fences,'' though, she had never produced a show on her own
i think the easiest thing is to find other investors,'' hays says. ``you can twist arms. i always sold the most camp fire girl cookies and girl scout cookies
that's the point of my being `fence's' sole investor. it was about doing it right and having that control. i think when you produce you must be a benevolent dictator. you must have the power to make a decision, to say `no' or `yes.'''
before new york, hays staged ``fences'' at one of her theaters in san francisco and the reviews were mixed. changes needed to be made, particularly in clarifying the play's final scene, and hays saw that they were
it was a tryout and we went through the process of trying different things,'' she recalls. ``ultimately, it worked, but it could have gone the other way.''
now the future of ``fences'' seems secure. the play, now starring billy dee williams, has started its second year at broadway's 46th street theater. its fortunes were boosted last april after the drama won the pulitzer prize, last june when it won four tony awards and then later in the year when paramount pictures paid some $500,000 for the film rights as a possible vehicle for the super hot eddie murphy
i never did the play strictly as a commercial venture,'' hays says. ``i'm a broadway baby. i believe in broadway as being the pinnacle of american theater
the first day of rehearsals for `fences' i said to everyone, `we do not know what's going to happen to this play, but we know that we will all do our very, very best,''' she recalls. ```and i want all of you to know that as a producer, you have my word that this show isn't going to open and close. no matter what. we're going to try and keep it running.'''
so far, hays hasn't had any trouble keeping her promise
the tangled, complicated and close relationship between the united states and israel is underscored by developments in the iran-contra affair and the iraqi oil pipeline deal, which converged in november 1985
by coincidence, that mont also saw a serious rift in u.s.-israeli relations when jonathan jay pollard, a counterterrorism expert at the naval investigative service was arrested as a spy for israel
an examination of what led up to the events of november 1985 provides insight into the relationship between israel and the united states and the interaction between officials from the two countries
two independent counsels, james mckay and lawrence walsh, are investigating the iraqi pipeline proposal and the iran-contra affair, respectively. they have begun to share information in a search for links between the cases
what is clear is that at least two of the same people dealt with both cases; private citizens used their friendships with government officials to make money, and international policy was affected by business interests
at the same time that israelis were shipping u.s.-made weapons to iran in an effort to free american hostages in lebanon, businessmen were enlisting friends at the highest levels of both governments to guarantee the safety of a proposed iraq oil pipeline from israeli bombing attacks
late in the year, the israelis gave white house aide oliver l. north free rein over $850,000 in excess profit from the iranian arms sales. most of that money went to the nicaraguan contras, according to a congressional report
here is a loose chronology:
on november 21, 1985, north worked frantically in his national security council office to sort out foul-ups in the plan to have israel ship 80 hawk missiles to iran as part of a deal to release six american hostages held by pro-iranian groups in lebanon
desperate for help, he called his boss, robert c. mcfarlane, then national security adviser, the state department and the cia
the israelis had flown the first batch of u.s.-made weapons to tehran in late august, leading to freedom for hostage benjamin weir in september. details for future shipments were ironed out by north and amiram nir, an aide to shimon peres, then israel's prime minister
handling operational details on the israeli side was adolph schwimmer, an arms dealer, founder of israel aircraft industries and one of peres' closest friends
president reagan had given his blessing to the project
on nov. 22, an iranian middleman transferred $24 million _ payment for 80 hawks _ into swiss bank accounts controlled by an israeli intermediary
north had ordered schwimmer to place $1 million in a lake resources account run by private businessmen working with north. the money was to cover transportation costs of flying the missiles from israel to iran
ultimately, only 18 of the 80 hawks were flown to tehran on nov. 24. shipments were halted because the iranians complained they had been cheated on the kind of missiles sent to them; no hostages were released
because only 18 hawks were delivered, more than $800,000 remained in bank accounts under north's supervision. that money was spent on the nicaraguan contras _ the first diversion of money to the rebels, and it appears to derive from israeli funds, a congressional report on the iran-contra affair says
north testified that in early 1986 he told the israelis that the money had been used `for the purpose of the contras' and they acquiesced,'' the report said. the israelis said north told them dec. 6, 1985, that he intended to use proceeds from the iran arms sales to help the contras
american investigators have been unable to question israeli officials face-to-face about the iran-contra case. yossi gal, a spokesman at the israeli embassy, did not return telephone calls asking about the diversion
the israelis gave the congressional iran-contra committees written chronologies, but no one was interviewed in person. walsh has not been able to question israelis, either
about the time the missiles were en route to iran, another project that involved israel and the united states came to a boil: the proposal by the bechtel group inc. and swiss businessman bruce rappaport to build a $1 billion, 540-mile pipeline to run from iraq's kirkuk oil fields to the jordanian port of aqaba. the route ran near the israeli border
rappaport, who has a relationship with peres that goes back 45 years, had hired as his attorney, e. robert wallach, a san franciscan with close ties to attorney general edwin meese
on sept. 19, 1985, four days after hostage weir was freed, peres wrote meese asking the attorney general to advise secretary of state george p. shultz about israel's interest in the pipeline
promoters of the project planned to pay israel to keep jerusalem from bombing the pipeline in the territory of its enemy, iraq
a week later, wallach wrote meese about rappaport's purported arrangement to pay israel _ and peres' labor party
the debt apparently involved israel's role in freeing weir, the memo said. rappaport ``indicates that peres emphatically indicated that the release of weir was a result of the state of israel, and no one else,'' wallach wrote
in his memo, wallach says ``there is a feeling that the u.s. `owes' and that the accomplishment of this project, as outlined in my memo, is appropriate.''
peres has denied he or his party received bribes; he has called the idea ``nonsense.'' the israeli government supported the project, however, he said
on oct. 7, meese recommended that peres discuss the pipeline with mcfarlane who is ``thoroughly familiar with the subject.'' mcfarlane had assigned nsc aide david wigg to quarterback u.s. involvement in the pipeline
when peres visited the united states oct. 16-oct. 12, he met with mcfarlene and wigg about the pipeline, according to sources quoted by the washington post
on nov. 20, peres sent mcfarlane a letter saying the israeli government was prepared to ``extend guarantees'' that the pipeline would not be touched
within weeks, a proposal surfaced which called for the pentagon to make secret payments to israel to prevent a pipeline bombing
mcfarlane's successor, john m. poindexter, eventually ended the nsc involvement in the pipeline at year's end. it was never built
meanwhile, the justice department continues to investigate the unrelated pollard case
michael ledeen, a former nsc consultant, said he thinks the pollard case may have encouraged red-faced israelis to keep pushing the iran initiative on the assumption it would lead to release of more american hostages in lebanon, thus pleasing the united states
an israeli source with access to top officials in his government says peres indicated that jerusalem thought it could earn forgiveness for the pollard affair if hostages were freed. the source spoke on condition he remain anonymous
peres publicly apologized to the united states on dec. 1, 1985
pollard pleaded guilty to charges he sold secret military documents to israel and was sentenced to life imprisonment. his wife, anne henderson-pollard, was sentenced to five years for being an accessory
israeli air force brig. gen. aviem sella was indicted, and three other israelis were named as co-conspirators in the espionage network operating inside the united states
hollywood's pursuit of the here-and-now has created a glossy, mostly superficial quality to the product coming out of the major studios. nowadays it's european filmmakers who indulge in remembrance of things past
two commendable examples are candidates for this year's academy award as best foreign language film: ``au revoir les enfants'' from france and ``the family'' from italy
louis malle, after working for a decade in the united states, returned to his homeland for the most personal film in his distinguished career, ``au revoir les enfants'' (``goodbye, children''). he wrote and directed the film from his own bitter memories as a schoolboy in occupied france during world war ii
the story begins with a tearful 12-year-old, julien quentin, leaving his mother in paris to attend a catholic boys school in fontainebleau. there he encounters the taunts of the older boys, the privations of wartime and the strict discipline of the priests. julien forms a grudging friendship with a bright, aloof fellow student, jean bonnet, whose background is a mystery
jean, it turns out, is a jew whose identity is hidden by the sympathetic priests. but jean is betrayed by someone inside the school, and both he, two other boys and the head priest are taken off to concentration camps
a brief synopsis cannot convey the rich texture malle contributes to the melancholy tale, nor the deep humanity. he is fortunate in his choice of two gifted young performers: gaspard manesse (julien) and raphael fejto (jean)
in ``the family,'' ettore scola traces the 80-year history of a roman family through the recollections of the central figure, carlo. the entire film takes place within the family's apartment, with views of the hallway signifying the change of eras
the turbulent events from 1906 to 1986 provide the backdrop for the family history. the central theme is carlo's divided affection between the sister he marries and the sister he really loves
scola is the master of such wide-sweeping stories, and his depiction of the temperament and humor of the italians is delightful. he chose three actors to depict carlo at different ages: young emmanuele lamaro, the rising star andrea occhipinto as carlo from 20 to 40, and vittorio gassman thereafter. all three are superb
au revoir les enfants,'' an orion classics release, is rated pg and runs 103 minutes. in french with english subtitles
the family'' is a vestron pictures release, rated pg, running time: 127 minutes. in italian with english subtitles
motion picture association of america rating definitions:
g _ general audiences. all ages admitted
pg _ parental guidance suggested. some material may not be suitable for children
pg-13 _ special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. some material may be inappropriate for young children
r _ restricted. under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian
x _ no one under 17 admitted. some states may have higher age restrictions
sidney poitier was recently asked why he took a 10-year absence from film acting. in explaining why, in a roundabout way, he reminisced warmly about his boyhood on cat island in the bahamas:
i started work when i was seven. my father was a tomato farmer, and i was the youngest of the (family) group. it was not traditional to leave a child of seven, because a child of seven was able to work. there was no one to leave me with. so i went to the fields, for the practical value of contributing to the family by working
i remember we took our breakfast at home, and then we walked to the fields, which were three to four miles from the house. we would all walk because there was no form of transportation except for the donkey, which my mother would ride. it was a very important time when i would be allowed to ride the donkey for brief periods
we worked in the fields until the sun was mid-sky. about that time, my mother would quit work, build a wood fire, take utensils out of a bag, and she would cook for the family in the fields. we used leaves of plants for plates. interesting. we didn't know what we were doing, but they were biodegradable
my job was to find the leaves, which were usually what we call a sea grape in the bahamas. my mother would fashion them into a plate, very easily done. of course we didn't have knives and forks, so we would twist one of these leaves into a spoon. after lunch we worked until the light began to fade, then we would go back to the house, where my mother would have to prepare a fire and cook dinner.''
the poitier farm went bust when the united states banned tomato imports from the islands, and the family moved to nassau. a husky lad, sidney poitier at 12{ became a ditch digger and water boy for a construction project
and i've been working ever since,'' he declared
this, he admitted with a laugh, was a long way around to answering the question. but then, poitier has always been a man to choose his words with thoughtful care, never flinging pat answers to oft-asked questions
when he reached 50, he continued, he faced the situation of many people in mid-life:
you somehow develop through the years work habits. more than that, one becomes psychologically habituated to the process of work as the gauge for your life. we work and we take a certain amount of time off every year _ two weeks or three or four if we're fortunate. the rest of the time we're doing the nine-to-five. even if you have the awareness of other lifestyles, you don't have the wherewithal to investigate them
at 50 i decided to see what life was really like outside of the narrow corridor of work.''
what is it like?
it's wonderful,'' he said. ``it's a little scary, because most of the wonderful things have nothing to do with making a buck. the world is filled with wonderful things; a remarkable diversity exists in the world.''
poitier, who is now 61, fulfilled a long-held desire to study astronomy. he began work on a novel. he and his wife, joanna shimkus, and their two daughters (he has four grown daughters as well) traveled a great deal. he also looked into individuals and organizations who in a quiet sort of way _ poitier style _ try to improve the world around them
he stopped acting after ``a piece of the action'' in 1977, but not filmmaking. he directed ``stir crazy,'' ``hanky panky'' and ``fast forward.'' about 18 months ago, david puttnam, then head of columbia, sent poitier a script about an fbi man who enlists an 18-year-old to catch a pair of soviet spies _ the boy's own parents. the result: ``little nikita,'' starring poitier and river phoenix
then disney submitted ``shoot to kill,'' with poitier as an fbi agent chasing a killer through the wilds. the film was released before ``little nikita'' and has reasserted the star's box-office power
it may seem a curious coincidence that poitier would play fbi men in his two returning films, but he maintains it's not surprising
that seems to be a trend in motion pictures. many of our top actors, and i don't place myself among them, play law enforcement officers. (clint) eastwood. (sylvester) stallone. eddie murphy. (al) pacino. kevin costner. nick nolte. why?
i have a feeling that filmmaking is so much a business that we tend to search for formulas more than we are willing to admit. cops are almost always good guys, however one-dimensional they are drawn. criminals are the bad guys. so we don't have to deal with real issues. we can deal with surface entertainment and a lot of razzle-dazzle, action, dangerous activity and gunplay.''
joseph beuys, west germany's answer to the late pop artist andy warhol, once said the berlin wall should be raised 10 centimeters for aesthetic reasons. the comment did little to endear him to his countrymen
for most of his career, beuys was better known in the united states than at home. but now, two years after his death, germans have suddenly become fans of the avant-garde artist
prices for his works are skyrocketing. critics are singing his praises. and record numbers of visitors are flocking to see the first-ever major exhibition of his sketches and sculptures in west germany at one of the nation's leading museums
in east berlin, a smaller exhibit of beuys' early drawings also is attracting crowds to the communist capital
the overhaul of beuys' reputation has been speedy. less than a year ago, cleaners at the duesseldorf art academy accidentally threw out a beuys sculpture made of wood, butter and animal fat. the cleaners thought the creation was, literally, garbage
i often wonder what beuys himself would think of all this,'' said a bemused heiner bastian, who served as the artist's assistant for 12 years. ``he was used to criticizing society, but not to being toasted by it.''
beuys specialized in sculptures made out of everyday items or cast-off objects: empty boxes and tin cans, scraps of wood, stones, shoes, blackboards or pieces of furniture. felt and fat were his favorite materials
in one creation, a single egg sits atop a wooden bench. in another, a pair of battered boots dangles on a string above two empty crates
a 1977 sculpture entitled ``in memory of my youth in the mountains'' consists of three large, white boulders inscribed with the same words of the title
beuys believed art had to be puzzling to be good, and there is no denying that he is puzzling,'' said bastian, who organized the 120-piece exhibition in west berlin's martin-gropius-bau museum
the 10-week show, which opened feb. 20, drew an unexpected 9,000 visitors in its first five days, an unofficial record for an exhibit in west germany
with his jaunty and battered felt hat, vest and rumpled trenchcoat, beuys never looked like he fit in among the prosperous and serious west germans
his sense of humor was also atypically german. he was fired from his job as administrator at the duesseldorf art academy in 1972, after announcing he would hire only applicants who had failed a formal art program
he was dismissed by an angry johannes rau, then the economics minister for the state of north rhine-westphalia, beuys' birthplace and lifelong home
but rau and other politicians have since changed their tune
now the north rhine-westphalian governor, rau traveled to east berlin last month to open the city's first beuys exhibition and lavish praise on his former employee
meanwhile, volker hassemer, west berlin's culture chief, claimed beuys for berliners
it is only fitting that the best-known contemporary german artist be shown first in berlin,'' hassemer told reporters at the bueys exhibit's gala opening
bastian is at a loss to explain the boost in bueys' popularity, and says it caught him by surprise
throughout the history of art, there have been artists who have become popular only after their deaths,'' he said. ``that has been particularly true for modern art. no one can say why this is so.''
in a recent issue of der spiegel, west germany's largest news weekly, the entire letters column was devoted to beuys. opinion was running decidedly against the artist
you recently ran pictures of beuys works,'' wrote immo kayser-eichberg, a lawyer from the town of meerbusch. ``you do not seriously consider these things works of art, do you?''
visitors to the west berlin beuys exhibition were more tactful
no i do not understand it,'' said ulrike nagel, gazing at a beuys object that appeared to be little more than several empty blackboards scattered on the floor. ``but that does not mean i do not automatically dislike it.''
jan hammer had one thing in common with the cocaine dealers on ``miami vice'': he was fleeing sonny crockett and rico tubbs. unlike those villains, the man behind the ``vice'' music got away
after three years of scoring the show, hammer has stepped down from handling the weekly music chores for ``miami vice.'' and he's released a new album, aptly titled ``escape from television.''
it was very autobiographical when the name was coined,'' hammer said recently in an interview at his manager's manhattan office. ``we went through many different titles, and then i came up with `escape from television,' because i was definitely leaving the show.''
the decision to leave, hammer said, was not too difficult to make
there's other things i want to do _ like living without this sword hanging over your head,'' said hammer, 39, who scored the first 69 ``vice'' episodes, delivering a half-hour of music for each show. ``every week there's a new deadline. ... it's not healthy living.''
it also forced hammer, who came to the united states from his native czechoslovakia in 1968, to pass on several projects. for example, hammer said it pained him to turn down the chance to score ``lethal weapon,'' the mel gibson-danny glover movie
i really like mel gibson. that would have been fun,'' hammer said with regret
but he has few regrets about ``miami vice,'' which created such opportunities and produced hammer's lone no. 1 single with the tv show's theme song. now, hammer says, he's ready to return to his solo career and continue his collaborative efforts with guitar virtuoso jeff beck
i have some sketches for songs, so we're going to get together and see what they sound like. just write and record, just the two of us, and see what happens,'' said hammer, who works in a studio on his upstate new york estate. ``jeff is like second nature to me.''
hammer's initial collaborations with beck followed the 1973 break-up of his acclaimed fusion band, mahavishnu orchestra, which featured guitarist jon mclaughlin. these days, hammer said, the idea of a band doesn't appeal to him any more
those days are over for me. ... all through the '70s, i always had a band. i kept people on salaries year-round,'' said hammer, who toured about eight months a year back then. ``can you imagine the drain? the overhead? i don't feel the need for that, and it just doesn't make sense.''
there are a few other things hammer finds do not make sense: american radio and music videos
it's a machinery, and it force-feeds people,'' he said of radio. ``through the whole top 40 format, it just force-feeds: `you're now going to dig these 40 songs, and only these 40 songs. you're not going to hear anything else
it's just this chunk of 40 songs being jammed down people's throats. ... these things are prechewed, you know?''
as for videos, hammer said, ``to tell you the truth, i'm sick and tired of them. i still like music-music, as opposed to music-pictures. i think that's what i object to _ that everybody has a video, and it's always the same.''
and what does he mean by always the same?
a run-of-the-mill boys playing guitars on the rooftops, boys playing guitars in the desert, and boys playing guitars underground,'' hammer explained. ``and the funniest thing is these really ugly guys have these gorgeous women just climbing over them
they wouldn't do it unless they were paid a lot of money. it's just so unreal.''
after getting together with beck, hammer plans to make his first live appearances in the united states since a 1983 benefit tour. he hopes to release another solo album, score some films and doesn't rule out a return to television work. he'd also be content just hanging around the house playing the piano
i really don't have any mountains to climb. i've been so lucky in my life _ it's staggering,'' said hammer. ``i don't want to analyze it, because i might disturb something. i've been able to be successful, and to do what i love. it's great.'' fiction</head>
pierre salinger has worn so many hats in his lively career that it's not surprising he's helped create a fictional hero with an identity crisis
investigative reporter andre kohl returns to his supersnooping in ``mortal games'' (doubleday, $17.95), the second espionage novel written by salinger and leonard gross
the two authors first introduced the character a few years back in ``the dossier,'' in which the star news correspondent prevented a world war ii nazi collaborator from coming to power in france. in ``mortal games,'' kohl is forced to stage his own death and resume another identity as he ferrets out a rogue cia network that has inked up with similar rebel operations within the kgb and elsewhere
salinger, who has been a reporter for the san francisco chronicle, press secretary to president john f. kennedy, u.s. senator, and chief foreign correspondent for abc news, said in a recent interview that writing fiction serves an important function for him
fiction appeals to me because i can say all kinds of things that i can't say in non-fiction. i can deal with stories that interest me, have my charact's coming.''
she said the message is ``be careful about pointing the finger. you've got three more pointing at yourself.''

one mind'' (global pacific records) _ joaquin lievano

joaquin lievano gives special thanks to zen master rama on the back of ``one mind,'' his new record. if you buy this record, you may wish to enlist mr. rama's assistance in learning the patience you'll need to get through it
one mind'' is simple-minded. it starts at the beginning and never wanders far beyond, winding back and forth upon itself with no apparent direction
lievano plays a variety of instruments, including guitars, synthesizers and drums. he is assisted by steve smith on drums, steve kindler on violin and issac epps on hand percussion. the musicianship is proficient and the production is excellent. the players turn in a nice riff here or a soft phrase there and, if you like this sort of technical mastery of the soul, the record delivers. for this reviewer, though, the overall effect was less than zero
this record has its roots in the 1970s. it is derivative of chick corea's ``return to forever'' and kindler's playing sounds suspiciously like that of jean luc ponty, who rocketed out of france in the '70s on a bow and an electric violin and has been laying down the same tracks ever since
with apologies to mr. rama, an ancient greek philospher once said, ``you can't step in the same river twice.'' but joaquin lievano is sure trying
_ by james reindl, associated press writer

if my heart had windows'' (mca) _ patty loveless

patty loveless' new album consists of 10 songs, and the writing credit is different on each. but loveless' singing and the production of emory gordy jr. and tony brown make the album into a cohesive set that's as country as grits
if my heart had windows'' includes a honky-tonk waltz (the title cut, by dallas frazier); country swing (hank williams' ``i can't get you off of my mind''); and plenty of ballads. loveless' full-throated alto really hits its stride on side 2, climaxing on john and johanna hall's ``fly away,'' which lives up to its name with a soaring chorus reminiscent of the halls' defunct pop group, orleans
the arrangements, built around the solid rhythm section of leland sklar and eddie bayers, include such nice touches as a steel and fiddle playing in unison on the break of ``i can't get you off of my mind.'' the material occasionally sags, but most of the album contains strong and honest performances
by steven wine, associated press writer.  03-14 0858</first> moved feb. 22</head> painting, ``warm colors ... personal preferences.'' ^by andy lang</byline>
you've heard it before and you'll hear it again: the success of your paint job will depend on how much time and effort you put into the preparation
it's nice to see the paint transform your lackluster walls and ceilings into gleaming brightness or unblemished freshness, but the pleasure will disappear quickly if you haven't prepared the surfaces properly
proper preparation means freeing the interior of loose dirt, peeling paint, oil and grease. it also means spackling all cracks and holes with spackling compound or patching plaster. the patches should be primed before the final coat of paint goes on, but read the label on the paint can to determine the manner of treatment
some professionals and many do-it-yourselfers apply a primer even when no patching has been done
it is especially important that any gloss be removed from the surfaces, since new paint does not adhere well to slick or shiny walls and ceilings. the gloss can be steel-wooled, sanded or given a coat of a special liquid that dulls the shine. unlike a few years ago, oil and latex paints can be used fairly well over each other, but a primer will insure an excellent result. the assumption is that you will be using a good paint, since it is poor economy to choose a low-quality paint when it is your own ``elbow grease'' that is being utilized. latex paints have little or no odor and make it easier to clean up after the job is completed
follow the rule-of-thumb that a high gloss paint usually is more washable, resists moisture and wears well, which is why it is preferred in kitchens and bathrooms. flat paints are the choice in most living rooms and bedrooms, being easier on the eyes. a semi-gloss paint is what the name implies, about halfway between the gloss and flat
the ideal way to prepare a room for painting is to remove everything from it, but this may be impractical. at least take out the lighter objects, moving the heavier pieces to the center of the room and covering them with a dropcloth or whatever is handy
all electrical switch plates, doorknobs, etc., can be taken off, but be extra careful about exposing any electric wires. ceiling fixtures can be dropped slightly to make the painting easier
in a casual room, you might want to try unusual effects. there are special rollers to give you offbeat results. you can do the same thing by dragging or swirling brushes, whisk brooms, sponges and rags across the paint while it is still wet, keeping in mind that easy does it if you want to avoid a mess. to find out what kind of results these gimmicky styles of painting will produce, try practicing on something like a piece of scrap wallboard
when you have estimated the amount of paint you will need, it's a good idea to buy an extra amount. for one thing, you always find something more you want to paint to blend in with the room. it may be only a bookcase or two, but if you have it on hand, it can be used at some later time for a touch-up job
buying the same kind of paint at a future time does not always assure that the shade will be identical with the original
some people just don't order enough the first time because they don't want to pay for unused paint. but many paint dealers will take back an unopened can if too much time hasn't elapsed. should you think that might be a problem, ask the dealer about the possibility
you may want to get on with the painting and not worry about whether you are trying to make a room seem larger or smaller, but if the latter concerns you, the proper color is the answer. want to make something in a room ``disappear''? paint it the same color as the room itself. want to make it stand out? paint it a contrasting color
if a room is long and narrow and you want it to seem a bit shorter, using white paint on two of the walls and a soft warm color on the two end walls will do the trick. when a side wall is painted white or a cool color, the room will appear to be wider. in the same way, a hallway that is too narrow can be made to seem wider if a side wall is painted white or cool
warm colors _ red, yellow, red-orange, yellow-orange and variations of red _ make a room warm. cool colors _ blue, green and their many shades _ make it cool. thus, theoretically, rooms which get very little sunlight are best painted warm colors, those with lots of sunlight cool colors. in actuality, other factors, including the shapes of the rooms and their decorative features, usually affect the choice of colors, not to mention personal preferences.   03-14 0201</first>
