internal documents indicate that g.d. searle &amp; co. may have misled doctors and a federal regulatory agency about safety characteristics of its copper-7 contraceptive, according to an attorney representing a woman who claims the device made her sterile
wall street reacted monday by knocking the stock of monsanto co., searle's parent, down $3.12{ a share to $83.37{
according to the documents, searle apparently hid complaints about the copper-7 from the u.s. food and drug administration, the attorney said
an fda task force recommended that a federal grand jury investigate whether any laws were broken by searle's allegedly misleading reports on animal studies for a number of products, including the copper-7. no charges were filed
the searle documents, produced for a trial set to start may 16 in st. paul, became public last week on order of u.s. district judge robert renner. the judge rejected searle's arguments that the memorandums be kept confidential to protect trade secrets
michael ciresi, a minneapolis attorney who represent esther kociemba, a melrose woman who claims to have been made infertile by the copper-7, said: ``these documents can be characterized as the tip of the iceberg. once all the documents are disclosed (to the public), they will collectively establish without a doubt that the copper-7 causes (infection) and searle knew about it, but did not disclose it to doctors or to women.''
nationally, there have been 17 trials involving searle's copper-7, 14 of them decided in the company's favor
kociemba's case ``will be the first case tried against searle where the jury will be presented with evidence from searle's files showing what searle knew about the hazards of the iud, when they knew about them and what they did about them _ which was to conceal the information,'' ciresi said
paul strain of baltimore, an attorney for searle, said, ``we are confident when a jury hears all the evidence, reviews all the documents and, most importantly, hears from the doctors that they will conclude the copper-7 is a good iud that does not cause infection.''
he said that documents not yet released and defense testimony will show that the company did not mislead anyone
a major issue in the suit will be whether the copper-7 tail string was a single strand of polypropylene incapable of transporting infection-causing bacteria into the uterus, as searle contends, or if it was made up of many tiny strands that could act as a tunnel for bacteria, as ciresi contends
one of the searle documents quotes a company official saying for the first time that the copper-7 string is a ``bundle of fused micro-filaments.''
the copper-7 was a popular intrauterine device from 1974 to 1988, when searle withdrew it from the market citing litigation costs. many american women continue to use copper-7 iuds and searle recently resumed manufacturing the device in order to fill foreign orders
the dollar turned in a mixed performance against other major currencies monday as traders bided their time in advance of thursday's report on the january merchandise trade deficit. gold prices edged higher
republic national bank of new york said gold was bid at $441.90 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from $441.25 an ounce late friday
traders in europe said the dollar's immediate future was closely tied to the british pound, which has gained 10 cents against the dollar in the past month
traders were cautious about the dollar-sterling rate on the eve of tuesday's british budget statement
also in the offing were a commerce department report tuesday on the united states' fourth-quarter balance in the current account, the broadest measure of trade, and thursday's merchandise trade figures
currency traders in new york have largely been reacting to developments overseas in the last two weeks, ever since the big run-up in the british pound, said keiichi udagawa, chief trader for the bank of tokyo in new york
now it's going to be a calm before the storm, before the trade figures,'' said zlatko glamuzina, chief currency dealer for the banco di sicilia in new york
in london, the british pound edged upward to $1.8575 from $1.8535 friday. but later in new york, the pound finished the trading day at $1.8540, down from $1.8562 late friday
