soybean futures prices soared as much as 13{ cents a bushel monday after a private crop analyst predicted only a slight increase in soybean planting this year. grain futures also closed higher
on other markets, crude oil futures tumbled well below $16 a barrel; livestock and meat futures advanced sharply; precious metals posted slight gains; and stock-index futures advanced
prices for delivery of new-crop soybeans _ those to be harvested this fall as opposed to those already in storage _ posted the greatest gains on the chicago board of trade in reaction talk about estimates issued monday morning by sparks commodities inc., a private analytical firm based in memphis, tenn
sparks reportedly pegged 1988 u.s. soybean plantings at 57.5 million acres, just slightly above last year's 57.4 million acres. the report followed an estimate of about 60 million acres made last week by refco inc., a large commodities trading firm
earlier trade estimates have been as high as 64 million acres. the agriculture department will release its first 1988 crop acreage estimates on march 31
sparks would not comment on the figures, which it supplies only to its subscribers
that's not the gospel, but it's the closest thing we've got for the time being,'' victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc., said of the reported sparks estimate
mickey luth, chicago-based soybean analyst for shearson lehman hutton inc., said the sparks estimate merely gave the soybean market an excuse to reclaim the losses it sustained last week
you were oversold, you were in a hole,'' luth said. ``with an excuse to rally, that's exactly what the market did.''
luth said he expected 1988 soybean planting to total 58.4 million acres
sparks also reportedly predicted 1988 corn plantings at 66.8 million acres compared to last year's 65.7 million. the estimate was seen as slightly bullish for corn prices
wheat settled 2} cents to 4 cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $2.95\ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 2{ cents higher with march at $1.98\ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2 cents higher with march at $1.90 a bushel; soybeans were 7{ cents to 13{ cents higher with march at $6.14} a bushel
oil prices fell sharply to below $16 on the new york mercantile exchange in reaction to reports that saudi arabia, opec's largest producer, had rejected calls for new restrictions on production
crude prices had moved above $16 late last week after members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries called for a meeting of the cartel's pricing committee to stabilize market prices
prices for future delivery of refined products also tumbled
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 63 cents to 70 cents lower with april at $15.59 cents a barrel; heating oil was 1.30 cents to 1.38 cents lower with april at 43.34 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.23 cents to 1.33 cents lower with april at 44.36 cents a gallon
livestock and meat futures posted sharp gains on the chicago mercantile exchange in response to stronger demand for cattle and tighter supplies of hogs, resulting in higher cash prices for both
weather worries also helped boost the livestock futures, analysts said. a winter storm moving out of the rocky mountains could slow the movement of animals to market in the northern great plains states, said tom o'hare, an analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
live cattle settled .70 cent to 1.18 cents higher with april at 74 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .38 cent to 1.42 cents higher with march at 82.85 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to 1.50 cents higher with april at 45.22 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.40 cents to 1.90 cents higher with march at 53.57 cents a pound
silver futures advanced slightly while gold finished nearly unchanged on the commodity exchange in new york
gold settled unchanged to 50 cents higher with april at $443.10 a troy ounce; silver was 5.9 cents to 6.2 cents higher with march at $6.24 a troy ounce
stock-index futures gained on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled .90 point higher at 266.40. the underlying spot index gained 1.43 points, closing at 266.37.  
american telephone &amp; telegraph co. is urging shareholders to reject a resolution from a white supremacist organization calling on the company to phase out its affirmative action program
the resolution is included in the proxy materials for the company's annual meeting, to be held in denver on april 20
the national alliance of arlington, va., argues that affirmative action programs ``may contribute towards discrimination against white people'' and ``may contribute to a decline in the quality of a company's work force.''
at&amp;t responds that affirmative action plans are necessary to qualify for government business, are a ``sound and fair business practice'' and have improved employee morale and performance, spokeswoman luann gardner said monday
the national alliance is described in the encyclopedia of associations as an organization dedicated to creating racial and cultural pride among whites and ``building a new order in american life.''
oilman t. boone pickens said monday the petroleum industry will recover soon, but never to the heights reached during its boom days in the early 1980s
pickens, chairman of mesa limited parnership of amarillo, said oil should reach at least $18 a barrel by the end of the year, far below its highs near $40 a barrel in 1982
pickens told delegates to the 111th texas and southwestern cattle raisers convention that the state needs to continue its trend of economic diversification
sometime, oil production in texas won't be too important. taxes from the oil industry are consistently going down,'' pickens said
to believe that the oil industry is going to lead the state of the doldrums we're in i don't believe it will be the case,'' he said. ``i do believe the industry will get better over a period of time, but it will never be the leader that we had been in the past.''
pickens said the oil and gas rig count would never reach its peak of nearly 5,000 in 1981
i don't believe in my lifetime that i will see 2,000 rigs operating in the united states,'' pickens said
pickens said that consumers should not fear the long lines at the pumps such as those during the arab oil embargo of 1973 and 1974
opec is going to provide the floor price for you. just give them a little time and they'll get their act in order and they'll give you an $18 floor,'' he said
pickens said he opposed an oil import fee because it would spark government control
investor a. robert abboud said monday he is confident debt holders of first city bancorporation of texas inc. will surrender their notes to the bank for less than face value
on march 4, more than 71 percent of the houston-based bank holding company's 37 million shareholders approved a $1.5 billion federal bailout plan
the plan _ which would be the second largest government bank bailout _ calls for $970 million in federal assistance, a $500 million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor group headed by abboud, and a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets
first city, the fourth-largest bank firm in texas, grew quickly during the texas oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real estate losses when oil prices plummeted. for 1987, the company posted a $1.1 billion loss
under a buyout plan that was made a condition of the bailout, holders of first city's debt securities would be paid less than the face value of their notes, said alan whitney, director of communications for the federal deposit insurance corp
the amounts offered to note holders ranged from 35 cents to 45 cents on the dollar, he said
but abboud, who would head the bank under the plan, told federal regulators in washington this weekend that not enough of the note holders have agreed to sell at those prices. the agreement provides that 90 percent of the debt holders turn over their notes by a 4 p.m. cst tuesday deadline
during a monday afternoon news conference in houston, abboud would not say how many debt holders had submitted their notes, but expressed confidence the deal can be closed by month's end
there's a high degree of confidence and enthusiasm as presently structured,'' said abboud, who was wearing a ``yes we can! first city'' button on his lapel
i would ask the other debt holders who have not yet tendered to cooperate with us and submit their securities. we're prepared to close if conditions are fully satisfied,'' he added
abboud said debt holders are getting more than if the bank were liquidated
the offer on the table is basically the offer until tuesday afternoon,'' he said. ``there is no intent on anybody's part to make any material changes in the monetary terms of the offering.''
last week, first city bonds were trading well above the prices being offered under the bailout plan. analysts said this indicated that some investors were gambling that federal regulators would come up with a higher price for the first city debt
the investors are betting that the fdic, in its eagerness to wrap up the first city deal, will either sweeten the offer or reduce the percentage of shares that need to be tendered
still other analysts said last week that the fdic could refuse to raise the offer for fear of setting a precedent for future bank bailouts
other options available to the fdic, the analysts said, include cancelling the abboud deal and reopening bidding for the bank, or a move by the fdic to itself take over first city, as it did with continental illinois bank and trust of chicago in 1984
first city has assets of $11 billion and operates 59 banks in texas and one in south dakota
the united auto workers union and mazda motor manufacturing corp. in usa reached tentative agreement monday on an initial contract covering workers at the automaker's only u.s manufacturing facility
details of the agreement, covering more than 2,000 members of uaw local 3000 at mazda's plant near flat rock, mich., were withheld pending a ratification vote thursday, the union and mazda said
black &amp; decker corp. on monday disclosed previously confidential information received from american standard inc. that showed the takeover target expected sales and earnings to rise substantially by 1992
american standard had shared the information as part of its negotiating strategy with black &amp; decker, a tool and appliance company that has been pursuing the plumbing and air conditioning maker since late january
black &amp; decker has an outstanding offer of $73 a share, or $2.27 billion, to acquire american standard
it wasn't clear whether the information would influence black &amp; decker's next move. american standard said sunday it was considering other bids from undisclosed suitors, including one worth $75 a share or $2.35 billion, and gave black &amp; decker until wednesday to make another offer
as quoted by black &amp; decker, the information received from american standard included its secret five-year plan with sales and cash flow figures and the basic economic assumptions underlying them
they showed american standard expected sales to rise from $3.8 billion this year to more than $4.7 billion by the end of 1992, and earnings to double to $304 million
both companies said the disclosure was required by federal securities laws because it could have a bearing on whether black &amp; decker changed its position in the takeover battle. but securities analysts said it was highly unusual that the information was released
black &amp; decker is involved in a ``contentious battle,'' said william h. miller, who follows the company for legg, mason, wood, walker in baltimore. ``if the information works to discourage another bidder, that works in black &amp; decker's interest,'' he said. if the returns look crummy, it could discourage someone else.''
stanley fishman, analyst for fahnestock &amp; co., in new york, said ``i've never heard of that before. confidential means confidential where i was brought up
if it is not unique, it's nearly unique,'' said fishman. ``we (analysts) can't even get five-year forecasts.''
share prices closed slightly higher in thin trading monday in what traders said was cautious optimism ahead of tuesday's release of the british budget
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index closed up 7.9 points at 1,819.5. the index had been up by 9.0 points at mid-afternoon after a wall street slightly higher than friday's close
volume fell to 337.1 million shares from 688.2 million on friday
traders said many participants stayed on the sidelines ahead of chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson's budget speech to parliament on tuesday
economists are forecasting personal tax cuts amounting to 3 billion to 4 billion pounds _ about $5.5 billion to $7.4 billion at current exxchange rates _ and a fiscal 1989 budget that is balanced or slightly in surplus
also boosting shares were better-than-expected results from glaxo holdings, the giant pharmaceuticals concern, traders said. glaxo announced its pre-tax profit rose 5.6 percent to 397 million pounds in the six months ended dec. 31, exceeding market expectations
glaxo finished up 27 pence at 10.82 pounds a share
newspaper and television station operator media general inc. said monday it sued unwanted suitor burt sugarman, the los angeles-based investor and tv producer, accusing him of making statements designed to create speculation in media general's stock
the suit filed in federal court in richmond, va., where media general is based, seeks an injunction barring sugarman from such actions and requiring sugarman to sell the 10 percent of the company's stock he has acquired
the suit also seeks unspecified monetary damages
at the same time, media general said its board had ``carefully considered'' sugarman's $61.50 per share, or $1.58 billion, offer for the 90 percent of the company he doesn't already own and decided not to pursue it
sugarman was out of the office and not available for comment, a receptionist said
the suit accuses sugarman of making ``inaccurate and incomplete'' statements to the press and in securities and exchange commission filings `designed to create speculation concerning media general stock and to help him in a possible proxy contest.''
the suit also claims sugarman has, in effect, begun seeking proxies through his statements in the press without filing required sec documents in advance
media general's stock closed monday at $47.25, down 37{ cents
the suit is the latest salvo in two-week-old tug of war between sugarman and the family of media general's chairman, d. tennant bryan, which controls a majority of the company's voting power
if sugarman succeeds in putting his proposal before shareholders, the company said, the tennant family will vote against it
the tennant family owns 71 percent of the company's class b common stock. although there are only 559,168 class b shares, they have the voting power to elect seven of the company's 10 directors
media general has 28 million class a shares, which have one vote each and elect three directors
sugarman, who owns 10 percent of the company's class a stock and none of the class b, has argued that the disproportionate voting rule doesn't apply if a holder of more than 10 percent of the company's stock proposes a merger
media general says its counsel disagrees
media general, based in richmond, owns a number of daily newspapers, including the richmond (va.) times-dispatch and news leader, the winston-salem (n.c.) journal and the tampa (fla.) tribune, plus 32 weeklies in southern california and a 40 percent interest in garden state newspapers inc. that owns 18 dailies and four weeklies in eight states
it also owns television stations, including wcbd-tv in charleston, s.c., wjks-tv in jacksonville, fla., and wxfl-tv in tampa, fla
sugarman is making the takeover offer through two companies he controls _ barris industries inc., the maker of successful televison programs such as ``the dating game'' and ``the gong show,'' and giant group ltd., the parent of keystone cement co. and giant cement co. order. picks up 9th graf, federated stock...</note>
federated department stores inc. on monday agreed to a sweetened friendly merger with r.h. macy &amp; co., which upped its initial bid by $200 million in cash to $6.3 billion, giving it an edge over hostile competitor campeau corp
under terms of the amended merger agreement unanimously approved by the federated board, macy will offer $77.35 a share in cash for 80 percent of federated's stock, up from $74.50 per share for the same portion in its original offer
macy plans to swap shares in a new company _ macy's-federated inc. _ and issue convertible debt securities for the remaining 20 percent of federated shares. the offer expires on april 4
meanwhile, toronto-based campeau indicated it had no immediate intention of revising its rival bid. the company late monday extended its $6.18 billion tender offer through friday in advance of a court hearing over suits filed by both sides to challenge each other's bids
u.s. district judge leonard sand indicated at the lengthy evening hearing that he would not rule before wednesday either on macy's request to force campeau to extend its tender offer past friday or on campeau's challenge to federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense
sand said he was seeking an opinion from the securities and exchange commission on macy's contention that campeau's latest tender offer _ which was revised from a previous, lower bid _ constitutes a brand-new offer that must remain open past its scheduled expiration. macy hopes that by forcing campeau to extend its offer it will ease the pressure on federated stockholders to accept the canadian company's bid
the judge said he would not get the sec opinion before wednesday and would not rule on either suit before then
however, sand stated that both buyout offers would have to remain in effect for at least three business days after he ruled on the poison pill issue, effectively extending campeau's offer through next week
federated stock closed unchanged at $66 a share on the new york stock exchange
in consideration for the sweetened offer from macy, federated granted macy a ``lockup'' option to purchase its bullock's-bullock's wilshire and i. magnin retail divisions if the merger is not successful. federated said the divisions would sell for at least $800 million and $150 million, respectively
campeau has valued those divisions at a total of about $1.25 billion
additionally, macy granted federated's board ``sole discretion'' over whether to maintain its ``poison pill,'' or shareholder-rights plan, which makes unwanted takeovers prohibitively expensive. under its previous agreement, cincinnati-based federated would have rescinded the plan in a merger with macy
in recommending shareholders tender their stock to macy, federated called the new offer ``substantially more favorable to federated stockholders than macy's previous offer and the coercive campeau two-tier offer.''
campeau on monday extended its hostile offer to buy 70.5 million of federated's stock, or 80 percent, at $75 a share from tuesday until friday to take pressure off the federal judge who was to preside over the courtroom battle
campeau said the remaining 20 percent of federated stock would be acquired later for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger, giving the deal an aggregate value of $68 per share
shortly after campeau's move was announced, federated urged its shareholders to hold onto their stock, reversing an unusual recommendation issued sunday, when federated ``reluctantly'' advised shareholders to tender their shares
although federated is opposed to merging with campeau, the retailer intended to make sure its shareholders got the higher price offered in the first stage of campeau's two-tier buyout bid
federated said later monday that its board again might advise shareholders to tender to campeau ``to avoid the risk of being relegated'' to the $44-a-share ``backend.''
if campeau were to succeed in its bid, federated vowed to go to court, and urged shareholders to do the same rather than ``accepting the grossly inadequate price which campeau has proposed for its backend merger.''
federated owns department store chains including bloomingdale's, burdine's, filene's, foley's, rich's and bullock's. campeau has indicated that if successful in acquiring federated it planned to sell filene's and foley's to may department stores co. for about $1.5 billion
macy has nearly 100 department and specialty stores, while campeau owns allied stores corp
campeau said it expects to obtain all the necessary financing to complete its buyout by the march 18 expiration date, but federated repeatedly has challenged that claim
a continental airlines advertisement designed to catch readers' attention has caught some flak from the new york city consumer affairs department
the department said monday it had cited the airline for a march 10 ad in the new york times that it claims gave the false impression that the u.s. internal revenue service was involved with the airline's promotion
the ad in question stated: ``fly continental to be out of the country on april 15 and the irs will allow you an automatic filing extension.''
angelo aponte, commissioner of consumer affairs, said the ad falsely implied a sponsorship by the irs and falsely asserted that consumers must leave the country in order to get the automatic extension to file
aponte also said the ad failed to give important information concerning the filing of extensions
bruce hicks, a spokesman at continental's houston headquarters, said an irs official indicated last week there were no problems with the ad and that it was straightforward and accurate
we're mostly very puzzled that the department would insinuate itself into an issue where there is no argument,'' hicks said. ``the irs has stated that it has no problems whatsoever with the advertisement.''
gary walker, a spokesman for the consumer affairs department, said continental was cited friday and sent a notice via overnight mail to its headquarters. continental was directed to send a representative to the department on march 25 and pay fines of up to $500 for each violation
hicks said no one at the airline's headquarters had seen the notice, but the airline's representatives would attempt to clear up the issue with the consumer affairs department
